*Key: HE-F--HE-fragmentation; S-C--shaped-charge; I- illumination; S-- 
smoke; L--leaflet; In--incendiary 


  Service rounds are made up of shells for various 
purposes: high explosive, fragmentation, HE-fragmentation, armor 
piercing, shaped-charge, incendiary, special (illumination, 
smoke, leaflet) and proof and testing. 
  High explosive, fragmentation and HE fragmentation 
shells make up the bulk of ammunition in units of fire of 
artillery pieces and are intended for engaging personnel and 
combat vehicles and demolishing light, field-type shelters. 
  A shell's blast effect consists of its deep penetration into 
an obstacle and its burst within the obstacle (or soil). 
  A shell's fragmentation effect consists of its instantaneous 
burst on contacting an obstacle (or the soil). 
  A shell's blast-fragmentation effect consists of its burst 
at 
a certain depth in the obstacle (soil). 
  Armor-piercing shells are intended for engaging 
enemy armored targets. 
  The effect of armor-piercing shells consists of the 
penetration of armor and injury of personnel behind the armor by 
core fragments. 
  In contrast to armor-piercing shells, shaped 
charge shells penetrate armor not through kinetic energy of 
the shells, but thanks to the concentrated, directed effect of a 
burster charge with a shaped-charge cavity. Damage behind the 
armor is accomplished by fragments of the armor and gases from 
the burster charge. 
  Incendiary shells are used for firing against 
wooden structures, fuel and ammunition depots and other highly 
flammable targets and are intended for creating centers of fire 
and injuring personnel. 
  Illumination shells are used for illuminating 
terrain in the vicinity of a target at night (or placing marker 
lights). 
  Smoke shells are intended for laying smoke 
screens, registering and signaling. 
  Leaflet shells are used for delivering leaflets, 
official statements, appeals and so on to the enemy disposition 
to exert an ideological and political effect on him. 
  Fire missions of artillery subunits in engaging a 
target may be annihilation, destruction, neutralization or 
harassment, depending on the nature and importance of the target 
and combat situation conditions. 
  Annihilation of a target consists of inflicting 
such losses (damage) on it that it completely loses combat 
effectiveness. The individual- target kill probability is 
0.7-0.9 or the mathematical expectation of the number of targets 
damaged in the makeup of a group target is 50-60 percent. 
  Destruction of a target consists of putting it in 
an unserviceable condition. 
  Neutralization of a target consists of inflicting 
such losses on it and creating such conditions by fire under 
which it is temporarily deprived of combat effectiveness, its 
maneuver is limited (prohibited) or C[.sup]2[/] is disrupted. 
The mathematical expectation of the number of damaged targets 
will be around 30 percent. 
  Harassment consists of a moral-psychological 
effect on enemy personnel by the conduct of harassing fire by a 
limited number of guns (mortars) and a limited amount of 
ammunition for a prescribed time. 
  Artillery subunits employ the following types of 
fire (Fig. 1) in fire damage of the enemy: fire against a 
single target, concentrated fire, a single-line standing 
barrier, single-line rolling barrier, successive fire 
concentration, and rolling barrage. In addition, they 
participate in massed fire. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-09A>      Fig. 1. Types of fire employed by an artillery battalion (battery): </FIG>

  Fire against a single target is the fire of a 
battery, platoon or gun (mortar, fighting vehicle, ATGM 
launcher) conducted independently from an indirect firing 
position or by direct fire [ogon pryamoy navodkoy]. 
  Concentrated fire is fire conducted by several 
batteries simultaneously against one target. 
  A standing barrier is a continuous curtain of fire 
created ahead of the frontage of an assaulting 
(counterattacking) enemy. A single-line standing barrier is used 
to repel assaults (counterattacks) by enemy infantry. 
  The width of a standing barrier sector is set figuring no 
more than 50 m per piece. 
  Standing barrier lines are codenamed for names of trees such 
as Klen [Maple], Bereza [Birch] and so on. 
  Fire is conducted by HE-fragmentation shells with impact 
fuze 
set for fragmentation effect, by shells with proximity fuzes, 
and by shells with time fuze at one range setting. 
  In conducting single-line standing barrier fire, fire 
commences at the moment infantry and tanks approach the standing 
barrier line and is conducted until the infantry is cut off from 
the tanks and stops the assault (counterattack). If the enemy 
infantry has gone to ground, it is engaged by concentrated fire. 
  A rolling barrier is a continuous curtain of fire 
created at one line on the path of movement of enemy tanks, 
IFV's and APC's and shifted successively to designated lines as 
the bulk of tanks (IFV's, APC's) exits the zone of fire. The 
rolling barrier is prepared at several lines located on the path 
of movement of enemy tanks (IFV's, APC's). The distance between 
rolling barrier lines can be 400-600 m depending on their rate 
of movement. The width of a battery (battalion) rolling barrier 
sector is set figuring no more than 25 m per piece. Lines are 
given a common name of predatory animals such as Lev [Lion], 
Tigr [Tiger] and so on, and each line beginning with the far 
line is given its own serial number such as Lev-1, Lev-2 and so 
on. 
  Barrier-fire lines are assigned on terrain sectors 
observable 
from ground observation posts [OP's]. A battalion is assigned a 
sector on a barrier line which is divided into battery sectors. 
Each battery's place in the division sector is established in 
advance by the battalion commander. 
  A successive fire concentration is used during 
fire support of the assault. Successive fire concentration lines 
are assigned 300-1,000 m from each other with consideration of 
the enemy defense alignment. Successive fire concentration lines 
are codenamed for predatory animals such as Lev [Lion], Tigr 
[Tiger] and so on, and lines are numbered in the order of the 
sequence of conducting fire against them beginning with the near 
line. A battalion is assigned one group target or two or three 
single targets on a successive fire concentration line. The 
group target area should not exceed 9 hectares. A battery 
conducts fire as part of the battalion or independently. With 
independent conduct of fire, a battery is assigned a target 
whose size should not exceed 3 hectares for a 6-gun battery or 4 
hectares for an 8-gun battery. 
  The rolling barrage is used in fire support of the 
assault and is conducted against primary and intermediate lines. 
Primary barrage lines are assigned 300-1,000 m from each other 
and intermediate barrage lines every 100- 300 m between primary 
ones. Primary barrage lines are codenamed for predatory animals 
such as Bars [Snow Leopard], Lisa [Fox] and so on, and lines are 
numbered in the order of the sequence of conducting fire against 
them beginning with the near line. Intermediate lines are 
numbered separately from primary lines and are called first 
intermediate, second intermediate and so on. A battalion is 
assigned one sector on a barrage line, which is divided into 
battery sectors. The areas of battalion and battery sectors are 
determined figuring 25 m per gun and 15 m per mortar. 
  Massed fire is conducted simultaneously by all or 
the bulk of artillery against an enemy grouping with the mission 
of decisive damage of one or more important objectives (targets) 
in a short time. 
  Procedure for engaging different enemy targets 
(objectives). As a rule stationary, unobserved (visually 
from ground OP's), unarmored targets in the open are 
annihilated, while covered and armored targets are neutralized 
or annihilated. No less than a battery is used for firing on 
such targets. 
  Artillery and mortar batteries and platoons (sections) as 
well as individual pieces are engaged at firing positions. 
  SP gun batteries (platoons) usually are annihilated, while 
SP 
mortar platoons are neutralized. 
  As a rule, SP gun batteries (platoons) are engaged 
immediately on detection by fire assaults conducted by rapid 
fire. 
  Personnel and weapons in the open usually are annihilated. 
  Sheltered personnel and weapons usually are neutralized. 
  Enemy AT weapons (ATGM launchers and AT guns) and subunits 
of 
these weapons are annihilated or neutralized depending on the 
situation. Subunits of unarmored and lightly armored AT weapons 
in disposition (concentration) areas as well as single, 
unsheltered, unarmored AT weapons disposed at positions as a 
rule are annihilated. 
  Enemy platoon strongpoints, mortar platoons, command 
observation posts [COP's], radars, and companies in 
concentration areas [rayon sosredotocheniya] and on the march 
usually are objectives and targets for engagement by artillery 
fire. 
  Fire capabilities of artillery to engage enemy objectives by 
fire from indirect firing positions are determined by the nature 
of the targets, shell density used, number of available guns and 
mortars, amount and quality of ammunition issued, and the time 
in which missions must be accomplished. 
  The number of shells and mortar rounds which can be fired in 
this time is determined for each artillery system depending on 
the number of guns and mortars which a battery has, the duration 
of fire preparation and the method of fire. By dividing this 
amount by the average ammunition expenditure norm we obtain the 
number of objectives which can be neutralized (annihilated) 
during artillery preparation of the assault. 
  The following indicators are used in calculating fire 
capabilities of artillery firing from indirect positions against 
personnel and weapons in the open: 50 m per gun and mortar for 
placing a standing barrier; 25 m per gun and mortar for placing 
a rolling barrier; and 15 m per gun up to and including 100-mm 
caliber and mortars of all calibers, and 25 m for guns over 
100-mm caliber for conducting a rolling barrage. For a 
successive fire concentration based on the size of battalion 
sectors on one line: 6 hectares for battalions armed with guns 
up to and including 100-mm caliber and with mortars of all 
calibers; and 9 hectares for battalions armed with guns over 
100-mm caliber. 
  Methodology for calculating subunit capabilities to 
combat enemy armored targets and other targets by direct 
fire. The calculation methodology is based on use of combat 
effectiveness factors, which are given in Table 2. To calculate 
capabilities, multiply the number of AT weapons by their factor. 


