  The following are considered initial data for calculating 
capabilities for a maneuver of forces and assets by a company 
(battalion): content and depth of the maneuver; rates of subunit 
movement along roads and cross-country routes with consideration 
of terrain accessibility; type of column; norms of time required 
by forces and assets to leave areas (positions, lines), close up 
into columns and extend them; time for a column to pull into a 
new area, deploy into battle formation and prepare to perform a 
mission. 
  The procedure for calculating the time for executing a 
maneuver of forces and assets on the terrain can be as follows: 

  -  analyze the goal and content of the maneuver; determine 
from a map the depth of the maneuver with consideration of 
corrections for terrain relief and map scale; break the route 
into 5-10 km segments and determine rate of movement along 
sectors with different trafficability. In breaking up routes 
into 5-10 km segments, make corrections for each segment; 
  -  figure the time for crossing each sector (divide sector 
length 
by movement rate), preparing for movement (leaving disposition 
areas, closing up and extending columns), deploying in the new 
area and preparing to execute the mission (using tabular data); 
  -  determine overall time for executing the maneuver by adding 
up 
the indicators obtained. 


    In calculating time for forward movement, take into account 
the following: have mixed columns move at average speeds of 
20-25 km/hr; move up to the line of departure at a speed of 
15-20 km/hr. 
  The time for subunits to concentrate in (pull into) an area 
is figured from the formula 
  T[.sub]pull-in[/]=D[.sub]col[/]D[.sub]area[/]/s, 
  where 


------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|D[.sub]col[/]                       |--depth of march column;              | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|D[.sub]area[/]                      |--depth of area;                      | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|s                                     |--rate of concentration (equal to one-| 
|                                      |half of march speed, i.e., 10- 12 km/-| 
|                                      |hr).                                  | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  Example 1. Figure the time for commitment of a 
second-echelon battalion which is 6 km from the commitment line. 
  Solution. The battalion will arrive at the line 
for deployment into platoon columns in 16.5 minutes (5x1.1=5.5 
km); (5.5x6020=16.5 minutes). The battalion will move from 
the line of deployment into platoon columns to the commitment 
line in 3 minutes (1x6020). Deployment of companies into 
battle formation during the day will take 4 minutes. Twenty- 
four minutes are required for commitment. The battalion 
commander and staff will require up to 20 minutes for 
decisionmaking and assigning (updating) missions to companies. 
Thus, a regiment's second echelon battalion can be committed in 
44 minutes (16.5+3+4+20) after the combat mission has been 
updated for it (assigned to it) by the senior commander. 
  The maneuver of company (battalion) forces and assets when 
operating in a tactical airborne assault force includes company 
(battalion) movement up to the concentration area, boarding and 
loading, flight to the landing area and the landing. 
  The following are initial data for calculating the time for 
executing a maneuver by air: rates of forward movement of 
landing forces and assets under their own power; norms of time 
required for boarding (loading) and disembarking (unloading); 
distance of boarding sites from drop zones; and type and flight 
speeds of air assault assets. 
  The procedure for calculating time for landing of a tactical 
airborne assault force requires the following: determine flight 
distance from a map; calculate flight time of the assault force; 
determine the time for forward movement of landing forces and 
assets to concentration areas and time for boarding; establish 
the time for disembarking (unloading) after landing; determine 
overall time by adding up the indicators obtained. 
  Based on exercise experience, a reinforced MRC will take 
20-25 minutes and an MRB will take 45-50 minutes to board 
(disembark). 
  Consideration of moral-political attitude of subunits 
in assessing their combat capabilities. Firepower, striking 
power and maneuverability represent the potential capabilities 
of a company (battalion). As we already established, material 
resources are the basis of combat power inasmuch as the sides' 
mutual damage is the basic content of battle and is accomplished 
by material resources, above all by fire from all kinds of 
weapons. Consequently, the outcome of battle is decided by 
weapons, but weapons do not operate of themselves. The outcome 
of battle depends largely on what kind of moral-fighting 
qualities a person possesses. 
  The moral-fighting qualities of personnel are understood to 
mean the aggregate of the most important qualities of people 
determining their behavior in battle. This includes both 
individual as well as collective qualities of people. Individual 
qualities usually are subdivided into political, moral, 
psychological and professional. 
  People's moral qualities are the basic regulator of behavior 
in all spheres of their activity, including in battle. Moral 
qualities are characterized by such categories as a sense of 
duty, responsibility, conscience, honor and dignity. The entire 
set of moral-fighting qualities of personnel in battle is 
realized and materialized through professional qualities, and 
all qualities form and are manifested under the influence of 
political views. This must not be forgotten and must be taken 
into account in determining combat capabilities of the company 
and battalion in modern battle. 
  Constant consideration and use of the moral-political and 
psychological factor in the interests of performing an assigned 
mission are the most important condition for achieving success 
in battle. This is achieved by constant, profound knowledge of 
the personnel's political-moral and psychological state, by 
organization and conduct of active political work to strengthen 
such a state, by a systematic study of the enemy's 
moral-political qualities, by identification of his strong and 
weak points, and by creation of active opposition to his 
ideological subversion in propaganda. 
  In estimating the enemy, the company (battalion) commander 
takes the following into account: Subunit organization and 
strength level, combat experience and traditions; level of 
personnel's professional training; ethnic-psychological features 
of personnel; level of discipline and relationships between 
commanders and subordinates and among soldiers of different 
nationalities, and the attitude toward allied armies; system of 
brainwashing personnel and its effectiveness; servicemen's 
attitude toward socialism and war as a whole; and measures which 
must be carried out to undermine and weaken the morale of enemy 
troops. 
  In estimating the state of morale of friendly troops, the 
company (battalion) commander proceeds from the fact that our 
social system is a source of soldiers' high morale. Moral forces 
are not a constant value; they depend on the level of political 
and military education. Therefore in estimating the state of 
morale of friendly subunits the following always must be taken 
into account in addition to other questions of political work: 
state of ideological-educational work to strengthen military 
discipline, efficiency and order; the personnel's state of 
supply of necessary material resources for battle. 
  As a result, a conclusion is drawn about the extent to which 
the moral factor contributes (or does not contribute) to 
performance of combat missions and what measures must be taken 
to change the personnel's moral political attitude. 
<H5>  Chapter III - Command and Control of Subunits </H5>
<H5>  1. Principles of Command and Control of Subunits </H5>
  C[.sup]2[/] of subunits is the purposeful activity of the 
company (battalion) commander, his deputies and the battalion 
staff to maintain subunits' constant combat readiness, prepare 
them for battle and lead them in performing assigned missions. 
  C[.sup]2[/] of subunits includes the following: organizing 
and accomplishing measures to improve or maintain their combat 
readiness and ensure or restore their combat effectiveness; 
maintaining high morale, psychological stability, firm military 
discipline, efficiency and constant combat readiness in the 
subunits; continuously collecting, gathering, generalizing, 
analyzing and assessing situation data; making decisions; 
assigning missions to subordinate subunits; organizing and 
maintaining continuous coordination; organizing and fulfilling 
measures for political work and comprehensive support; and 
organizing C[.sup]2[/]. In addition, the commander and staff 
carry out practical work in subordinate subunits to direct their 
immediate preparation for battle, organize the performance of 
assigned missions in the course of battle, and perform other 
measures. 
  It is common knowledge that C[.sup]2[/] theory and 
practice also developed and changed along with the development 
of armed forces. Thus, before the appearance of mass armies 
C[.sup]2[/] was exercised directly by the commander (field 
general), since at that time he could observe the actions of all 
his troops and could issue necessary orders and command the 
troops personally or through adjutants, orderlies and messengers 
without the help of a special entity (a staff). 
  With the appearance of mass armies and consequently also 
with 
the increased scope of combat operations and changed conditions 
of preparing and conducting battle, it became more and more 
difficult for one commander to lead the troops and he could no 
longer cope with this mission alone. The need arose to establish 
a permanent, special C[.sup]2[/] entity. A Military Council 
under the commander in chief was introduced for this initially, 
then the army staff was established in the middle of the 18th 
century, and in the early 19th century staffs appeared in 
divisions, regiments and battalions. The staffs developed and 
were perfected and improved all the while, becoming the 
commander's irreplaceable assistants in C[.sup]2[/] both in 
peace as well as wartime. 
  New combat arms and special troops, which began to take part 
in battle, appeared in the course of further evolution of the 
armed forces of many states. This led to a further expansion in 
the circle of appointed persons used for leadership of 
formations, units and subunits. Chiefs of these combat arms and 
special troops appeared in the organizational structure of 
troops. 
  The basic content of C[.sup]2[/] of subunits consists of 
maintaining high political attitude and morale and the constant 
combat readiness of subunits; collecting and studying situation 
data and discovering enemy intentions; making decisions; 
communicating missions to subordinates; organizing and 
maintaining coordination among subunits of the battalion and 
other combat arms participating in battle; comprehensively 
supporting battle and monitoring its preparation and subunits' 
performance of assigned missions. 
  Timely, well organized, uninterrupted C[.sup]2[/] of 
subunits facilitates seizing and holding the initiative, 
covertness in preparing for battle, surprise in delivering 
attacks against the enemy, swift exploitation of results of 
nuclear and fire damage of the enemy, and timely accomplishment 
of measures for protecting subunits against mass destruction 
weapons. In addition, it permits more effective use of the 
combat capabilities of all forces and assets involved in the 
battle. 
  Conditions for C[.sup]2[/] of subunits. 
Conditions for C[.sup]2[/] of subunits have become 
substantially more complicated in modern battle compared with 
the Great Patriotic War. In the past war C[.sup]2[/] of 
subunits was exercised in a situation where the battle developed 
relatively slowly and its outcome depended chiefly on rifle 
subunits, sometimes reinforced by tanks and artillery fire. 
  As a rule, company and battalion COP's were disposed in 
battle formations of subunits, usually being in one and the same 
place for a lengthy time (especially in a defense). 
  The modern MRC and MRB became highly mobile and 
maneuverable. 
While a company (battalion) of the Great Patriotic War period 
had a rate of advance of 4- 5 km/hr, now it can march at an 
average speed of 20-25 km/hr. Under present conditions, if the 
enemy uses nuclear weapons the commander will have to control 
his subunits fighting in areas of contamination, destructive 
damage, fires and flooding. Now the combat situation on the 
battlefield may change often and substantially, which will 
necessitate updating a decision or organizing it anew. 
  The growth in spatial scope of battle, both defensive as 
well 
as offensive, and of its tempo of conduct leads to a more 
frequent change in locations of C[.sup]2[/] facilities and 
will force a commander to exercise control of subunits on the 
move. As we know, this hampers C[.sup]2[/] of subunits and 
complicates their protection and protection of the means of 
C[.sup]2[/] against nuclear and precision weapons, air and 
artillery strikes, and actions by enemy raiding parties, which 
as a rule will have the mission of knocking out command posts. 
  Changes which occurred in organization and technical 
outfitting of our own and enemy troops led to substantial 
changes in the content and nature of modern combined arms 
battle, in methods of its organization and conduct and in 
methods of C[.sup]2[/] of subunits. Battle became decisive, 
dynamic, maneuverable and fast-moving. The spatial scope of 
battle increased substantially compared with the Great Patriotic 
War period. Thus, a modern MRB may attack a deliberate enemy 
defense in a frontage up to 2 km and defend an area with a 
frontage of 3-5 km. 
  Under such conditions the company (battalion) commander will 
control subunits over radio communications equipment, as a rule 
in movement or from short halts. The volume of information on 
the enemy which the company (battalion) commander must quickly 
collect, generalize, study, analyze, make a decision on and 
report to the senior commander has grown substantially. 
  In modern battle the company (battalion) commander will be 
forced to make or update a decision at least 3-4 times in the 
course of a 24 hour period, in less time than was the case in 
the Great Patriotic War, and often under conditions where the 
COP will be in movement for a considerable time. Therefore the 
factor of time now has a deciding effect on all C[.sup]2[/] 
processes. Under these conditions the company (battalion) 
commander must think out and determine well the location of his 
COP and the organization of communications from it with 
subunits, adjacent subunits and the senior commander. 
  The company (battalion) commander's place should be a place 
from which he can confidently lead subordinates and exert an 
effective influence on them in preparing for and conducting 
battle. The presence of communications equipment (especially 
radio equipment) in the company and battalion gives the 
commander great mobility in choosing his location, but the 
commander's attachment to communications equipment should not 
contribute to his rejection of contact with subordinate, 
attached and supporting subunits. 
  The experience of the past war shows that a company 
(battalion) commander should have a good view from his COP of 
his subunit's battle formation and of the enemy whom he is 
fighting. 
<H5>  2. Requirements Placed on C </H5>[.sup]2[/] of Subunits 
  The highly maneuverable nature of combat operations as well 
as frequent, abrupt situation changes demand of a company 
(battalion) commander that C[.sup]2[/] be stable, 
continuous, efficient and concealed, and accomplished so 
the necessary degree of centralization of C[.sup]2[/] is 
combined with granting of initiative to subordinate commanders 
in determining methods of performing assigned missions. 
  Stability of C[.sup]2[/] of the company 
(battalion) is manifested in the constant influence of the 
commander and staff (in the battalion) on operations of subunits 
participating in the battle in the interests of their successful 
performance of assigned mission under any combat situation 
conditions. Great Patriotic War experience indicates that even a 
temporary loss of C[.sup]2[/] of subunits leads to 
nonperformance of the combat mission and in some cases also to 
defeat. 
  Stability of C[.sup]2[/] is achieved by knowing the combat 
situation which actually has taken shape and the combat mission 
received, making the decision promptly and assigning missions 
precisely to subordinate subunits; maintaining stable 
communications with subordinate, attached and coordinating units 
(subunits) and with the senior commander (chief), and ensuring 
reliability of its operation; and making comprehensive use of 
all C[.sup]3[/] equipment at the disposal of the company 
(battalion). In addition, back when organizing the battle 
measures are taken to protect friendly organic radio equipment 
and electronic C[.sup]2[/] systems and oppose enemy technical 
reconnaissance assets. 
  Continuity of C[.sup]2[/] consists of the 
commander's constant influence on the course of battle by word, 
action and means at his disposal in the interests of subunits' 
successful performance of the assigned mission. In battle the 
company (battalion) commander is obligated to carefully follow 
the course of battle and continuously conduct reconnaissance and 
know the enemy's actions and intentions. He must promptly assign 
or update missions to platoons (companies) and to attached and 
supporting subunits. Constant knowledge and analysis of the 
battlefield situation both within one's own boundaries as well 
as ahead of adjacent subunits, and foresight of the most 
important changes are necessary conditions for achieving 
continuity of C[.sup]2[/]. This will permit the commander to 
employ all organic and attached weapons skillfully in the course 
of battle and effectively exploit results of nuclear and fire 
damage of the enemy. 
  To achieve continuity of C[.sup]2[/] it is very important 
to select the site of one's COP, dispose it covertly and 
displace it promptly, especially when conducting battle at night 
and on rough terrain. The company (battalion) commander must be 
on the most important axis at a given point in time and exert 
timely influence on the course of battle with all forces and 
assets at his disposal. The commander must lead subunits in 
difficult moments of battle by personal example, showing 
boldness, initiative, resourcefulness and unshakable resolve, 
and perform the combat mission regardless of any difficulty or 
even a threat to life itself, instilling this resolve in all 
subordinates. 
  Back while organizing for battle the commander should 
appoint 
deputies for himself in addition to authorized ones and issue an 
order on them. The battalion commander and staff immediately 
take steps to restore C[.sup]2[/] disrupted in the course of 
battle. 
  Efficiency of C[.sup]2[/] consists of timely, 
swift accomplishment of all measures connected with leading 
company (battalion) subunits in preparation for and in the 
course of battle; constant knowledge of the situation and swift 
reaction to its changes; timely updating of a decision and of 
missions assigned to subunits; and the company (battalion) 
commander's ability to use the most effective work methods in a 
given situation and perform assigned missions within time 
periods ensuring preemption of the enemy in operations. In 
addition, great importance is attached to the ability of 
commanders at all levels in the company (battalion) to operate 
organic battalion communications equipment and conduct 
conversations briefly and using formatted documents. 
  Especially high efficiency is needed in the company 
(battalion) commander's work in organizing for battle in a short 
time and in the dynamics of battle, when it will be necessary to 
update a decision or organize anew. 
  For example, if company (battalion) subunits attack at a 
rate 
of 3-4 km/hr and a combat mission based on a new situation is 
communicated to them in 20 minutes, then during this time they 
will move forward 1 1.3 km, and may cover up to 2.6 km in 
pursuing the enemy at a rate of 8 km/hr. Therefore if a 
commander's reaction to the development of events is delayed, 
his orders (instructions) will be late and will not correspond 
to the actual situation. 
  A rapid situation estimate, timely decisionmaking and its 
timely communication to subunits are of decisive importance for 
maintaining C[.sup]2[/] efficiency. 
  Concealment of C[.sup]2[/] is achieved by 
following established rules and procedures for conversations 
over technical communications equipment; strictly fulfilling 
rules of secure C[.sup]2[/]; strictly complying with measures 
of maskirovka and of concealed placement of C[.sup]2[/] 
facilities; involving a strictly limited number of appointed 
persons for carrying out measures connected with preparation of 
battle and keeping the measures in strictest secrecy; using 
various ciphers and codes, tables of callsigns and signals, 
prearranged message codes and coded maps; prohibiting 
conversations in the clear; reliable maskirovka of COP's; and 
keeping all conversations concerning preparation and conduct of 
battle secret. 
  Concealment of C[.sup]2[/] was of great importance in 
C[.sup]2[/] of subunits in past wars. Under present 
conditions it is given even greater attention in connection with 
the increased role of surprise of enemy operations, increased 
capabilities of enemy reconnaissance, and use of nuclear, 
precision and other kinds of weapons. Therefore keeping all 
measures connected with preparation and conduct of battle secret 
is a very important condition for concealment of C[.sup]2[/]. 
  Role of the commander and staff in C[.sup]2[/] of 
subunits. It is common knowledge that the commander's 
decision is the basis of C[.sup]2[/]. The company (battalion) 
commander bears full personal responsibility for his subordinate 
subunits' combat readiness and preparation for battle, their 
proper employment and their successful performance of combat 
missions within prescribed time periods. In addition, he is 
responsible for political work, indoctrination, military 
discipline, psychological preparation and political attitude and 
morale of personnel. 
  The company (battalion) commander exercises C[.sup]2[/] of 
subordinate and attached subunits by issuing verbal operation 
orders and instructions and by commands and various prearranged 
signals. 
  The place and time of deployment of the company (battalion) 
COP and procedure for its displacement are specified in the 
order. 
  The company (battalion) COP should not lag behind or break 
away from subunits, especially in an attack at night and in the 
fog. The company (battalion) commander must observe the 
battlefield, receive timely situation reports and react 
immediately to situation changes. The battalion COP usually was 
disposed up to 300 m and that of the company up to 200 m from 
first echelon subunits in the attack, and up to 2 km and 800 m 
respectively in the defense. 
  When the battalion COP is disposed together with the COP of 
an attached artillery battalion, it may occupy an area up to 0.2 
hectares and vehicles are placed 30-50 m from each other. 
  For mutual recognition and for determining the affiliation 
and location of subunits, a recognition and identification point 
(post) [punkt (post) oboznacheniya] is assigned from a squad or 
crew specially trained for this purpose in each first echelon 
company (battalion) in direct contact with the enemy or 
conducting battle or reconnaissance in the enemy rear. 
  Subunits are located by activating visual and technical 
means 
of recognition from the recognition and identification point 
(post) at a command of the company (battalion) commander or 
battalion chief of staff in accordance with directions of the 
higher staff. 
  Usually no more than three persons, an NCO and two privates, 
are assigned to a company (battalion) recognition and 
identification point (post). It is supplied with observation 
devices (binoculars, stereoscopic telescopes) and a large-scale 
map or diagram of the terrain. In addition, a control log, 
compass, watch, flashlight, communications equipment (telephone 
or radio) and means of giving recognition, identification and 
warning signals are allocated for the point (post). Technical 
means of recognition and identification usually are set up near 
the battalion COP. 
  The point (post) makeup, location, observation sectors, and 
the recognition, identification and warning signals usually are 
indicated when a mission is assigned to a point (post). 
  C[.sup]2[/] of company (battalion) subunits in the course 
of conducting battle means above all the commander's continuous 
influence on the course of battle and direction of their efforts 
toward performing the assigned mission within prescribed time 
periods. 
  A battle is a two-sided process in which each side strives 
to 
achieve set objectives with forces and assets at its disposal. 
Therefore one should not get the idea that an attack that has 
begun, for example, will develop in full conformity with the 
outlined commander's concept. Enemy opposition by various means, 
by stubborn holding of strongpoints and lines and by 
counterattacks of reserves not only will hamper performance of 
assigned missions, but also fundamentally alter the situation 
and the nature of combat operations. 
  Depending on this, the need may arise for the company 
(battalion) commander to further detail the decision and update 
it in different stages of performing a combat mission. 
  The experience of the Great Patriotic War and field training 
exercises shows that in the course of battle the company 
(battalion) commander is required to have the ability to quickly 
collect data on the situation and on the nature of operations of 
enemy and friendly troops so as to immediately issue necessary 
instructions to subordinates. This is achieved by the company 
(battalion) commander constantly observing changes in the 
situation and assessing it. The extent to which this is 
important is apparent from the following example. In the course 
of artillery preparation of an assault in the Belorussian 
Operation (June 1944), B. Fedorov, commander of a rifle 
battalion of 61st Guards Rifle Regiment, 19th Guards Rifle 
Division, determined that the enemy had begun withdrawing from 
the first trench 30 minutes before preparation fire ended. He 
immediately reported this through channels. As a result the 
decision was updated, in accordance with which artillery fire 
was shifted into the depth and the battalion with tanks was 
committed into the fire corridor which formed. Such updating of 
the decision led to rapid capture of a crossing over the Luchesa 
River and performance of the assigned mission ahead of the 
prescribed time and with minimum losses.[.sup]1[/] 
  The commander must be on the most important axis and exert 
timely influence on the course of battle in its decisive moments 
in the course of an assault on the enemy defense, in repelling 
counterattacks, and in an enemy assault on a company strongpoint 
(defense area). 
  A battalion commander not only controls battalion subunits 
personally, but also through deputies and his staff. The 
battalion staff is the principal entity ensuring C[.sup]2[/] 
of battalion subunits. As a rule, the staff arranges all its 
work of organizing and preparing battle based on the battalion 
commander's decision and instructions, and also instructions of 
the regimental staff. 
  Such an entity in the company is the command group, which 
includes the deputy company commander for political affairs, 
senior technician (in his place in the TC is the deputy company 
commander for weapons), company first sergeant and medical party 
NCOIC. 
  The battalion chief of staff is the battalion commander's 
first deputy, and only he has the right to issue orders and 
instructions to subordinates on behalf of the battalion 
commander. He is fully responsible for organization and 
maintenance of continuous C[.sup]2[/] of subunits, their 
combat readiness, and combat support to battalion operations in 
all situation conditions. The battalion staff (and in the 
company the command group) organizes systematic collection and 
study of situation data; helps prepare necessary calculations 
and suggestions for the company (battalion) commander for 
employment of weapons, tactical employment of organic, attached 
and supporting subunits and for the decision as a whole; issues 
warning orders to platoons (companies) and plans battle in 
accordance with the commander's decision. In addition, by 
direction of the battalion commander the chief of staff 
communicates missions to subordinates, organizes reconnaissance 
and carries out other kinds of combat support. Special attention 
here is given to organizing communications with combat subunits 
and adjacent subunits and protecting communications against 
enemy ECM. 
  The battalion chief of staff is obligated to sign operation 
orders and instructions issued by the battalion commander to 
subunits and monitor their fulfillment. He must constantly keep 
an eye on the subunits' state of supply of everything necessary 
for fighting the battle, especially availability of ammunition, 
and promptly deliver it to subunits. 
  The battalion chief of staff must constantly organize 
reconnaissance both of the ground as well as the air enemy. To 
this end he is obligated to assign reconnaissance missions not 
only to the battalion reconnaissance platoon, but also to 
commanders of MRC's and separate platoons of the battalion, 
monitor their fulfillment, and through them communicate to 
subunits the methods and signals for recognition of friendly and 
enemy aircraft (helicopters). 
<H5>  3. Forces and Assets for C </H5>[.sup]2[/] of the Company and 
Battalion in Battle 
  Communications is organized in the company (battalion) in 
accordance with the commander's decision and with directions of 
the battalion (regimental) chief of staff. The company commander 
is responsible in the company and the battalion chief of staff 
is responsible in the battalion for the organization and status 
of communications. The battalion chief of communications (signal 
platoon commander) directly organizes communications and is 
responsible for its stable, precise operation. 
  There is a signal platoon to support C[.sup]2[/] in the 
MRB; it includes two control squads and a radio squad. 
  The signal platoon in a BMP-equipped battalion has 2 BMP-1K 
command vehicles and in a BTR-equipped battalion it has 2 
BTR-70K's. The radio squad is authorized 7 R-107M (R-159) 
radios, 15 R-157 (R-158) radios, a P-193M telephone switchboard, 
8 km of P-274 field telephone cable and 15 TA-57 telephones. 
  In addition, the headquarters platoon in a mortar battery 
has 
a signal squad with 4 R-107M (R-159) radios, 4 km of P-274 field 
telephone cable and 5 TA-57 telephones. 
  The TB signal platoon consists of the commander's tank, a 
control squad and a radio squad. 
  The battalion chief of staff's BMP-1K command vehicle is in 
the control squad. The radio squad has 3 R-159 (R-107M) radios, 
a P-193M telephone switchboard, 4 km of field cable and 5 TA-57 
telephones. The radio squad is accommodated in a BMP. 
  The BMP-1K command vehicle set has 2 R-123 radios, a TA-57 
telephone, R-124 tank intercom for five subscribers, ASh-4 
antenna, and combination whip antenna on an 11-meter mast. 
  The makeup of communications equipment in the BMP 
1K permits accomplishing the following: 

  -  telephone communications among officers and crew members 
within the vehicle; 
  -  radiotelephone communications on two VHF 
radio nets or links. 


    Two workstations for battalion staff officers are equipped 
in 
the vehicle. 
  The BTR-70K set has two R-123 radios and the R-124 tank 
intercom. 
  Communications equipment, other equipment and combat 
capabilities of the BTR- 70K are completely similar to the 
BMP-1K. 
  The commander's tank is equipped with R-123M and R-130M 
radios, R-124 tank intercom for four subscribers and ASh-4 
antenna. 
  Communications equipment of the battalion commander's tank 
supports telephone communications between commander and crew 
members within the tank, radio telephone communications over VHF 
and HF radio nets, and sound telegraph communications over the 
HF radio net. 
  Radios. The R-123M low-power VHF radio installed 
in BTR's, BMP's, tanks and maintenance vehicles is intended for 
supporting telephone communications among armored vehicles and 
control of subunits during battle. R-107M, R-157, R-158 and 
R-159 portable VHF radios serve to provide radiotelephone 
communications among subunits. 
  The R-130M low-power HF radio serves for telephone and sound 
telegraph communications. It is used in the TB for communicating 
with the regimental commander. 
  Wire communications equipment. The MRB has the P 
193M switchboard, P-274 field cable and TA-57 telephone sets. 
They are intended for setting up wire telephone communications 
at the battalion COP with subordinate subunits and for remote 
control of portable radios. 
  The P193M switchboard is intended for preparing a 
lowcapacity 
telephone exchange at the battalion COP. Switchboard capacity is 
10 numbers. Time for deploying the switchboard is 3-4 minutes. 
  Organization of C[.sup]3[/]. Radio, wire, 
mobile and signaling means of communications are employed in the 
company (battalion) for supporting C[.sup]2[/]. All 
C[.sup]2[/] activity of the company and battalion commander 
in battle is accomplished from the COP. 
  The company COP may include the company commander, deputy 
company commander for political affairs, senior technician (in 
the TC the deputy company commander for weapons), company first 
sergeant and medical party NCOIC. Technical equipment may 
include the company commander's BTR (BMP) or tank. A radio net 
is set up in each company made up of radios of all company 
fighting vehicles and radios of company and platoon commanders. 
Portable radios are used for maintaining communications when 
commanders are outside the fighting vehicles and for 
communicating with MRP's operating in dismounted formation. 
  In defensive battle, radios of attached tanks located in the 
company strongpoint may be included in the MRC radio net. Other 
subunits attached to the company also are included in this same 
radio net. 
  The commander of the artillery subunit attached to the 
company as a rule is with the company commander. During movement 
of COP's, communications between them is maintained by 
connecting the radio net of the commander of an attached or 
supporting subunit into the company commander's radio net. 
  Wire communications with the MRC (TC) usually is organized 
by 
the battalion commander in the defense, when the battalion is 
disposed at the halt, and in the assembly area [iskhodnyy rayon]. 
  Communications by mobile means in the company is used in all 
kinds of battle and also on the march and when disposed at the 
halt. Motor vehicles, BTR's, BMP's, foot messengers, and 
sometimes also tanks may be used as mobile means. 
  A group of couriers sent out from organic and attached 
subunits may be established in the company and sometimes also in 
the MRB; they usually are at the company (battalion) COP. 
  Communications signaling devices may be used in the company 
(battalion) in all kinds of battle for transmitting commands, 
reports, and warning, control and coordination signals. 
  Visual and audible means usually are used for giving 
signals. 
Signals must be simple, easy to memorize and permit sharp 
distinction of one signal from another. An observer with 
necessary means (binoculars, signal flags, pyrotechnic flares, 
flashlights, pointers and so on) is assigned in advance in each 
subunit for giving and receiving signals. All subunit personnel 
must know the warning signals. 
  Coordination communications between adjacent subunits in the 
battalion usually is organized from right to left and 
accomplished by wire and mobile means of the neighbor on the 
right. 
  The battalion COP includes the battalion commander, deputy 
battalion commander for political affairs, deputy battalion 
commander for weapons, chief of staff, deputy chief of staff and 
battalion chief of communications. 
  The battalion communications equipment at its COP usually is 
combined organizationally and technically into a communications 
center, which is considered one of the important elements of the 
battalion COP. It is intended for accomplishing reliable 
communications with the regimental command post (with the 
regimental commander and chief of staff) and with COP's of 
subordinate, attached, supporting and coordinating subunits. It 
usually includes a BMP-1K command vehicle, individual radios, a 
telephone exchange and a group of couriers. 
  The BMP-1K command vehicle is considered the basic element 
of 
the MRB (TB) COP communications center. 
  The telephone exchange is intended for providing 
communications over wire lines and remote control of radios. It 
consists of the P 193M switchboard and subscriber telephones. 
The switchboard usually is installed in the signal platoon BTR 
or a shelter. It includes cable lines laid from COP's of 
companies and attached subunits, the commander's BMP-1K and the 
battalion chief of staff's BTR, and also wire from the 
communications center of the regimental CP and the supporting 
(attached) artillery battalion. 
  As a rule, two radio nets are organized to provide reliable 
control of subordinate and attached subunits in the battalion: 
the battalion commander's net and chief of staff's net. 
  The battalion commander's radio net usually includes radios 
of the battalion commander and chief of staff and of commanders 
of MRC's, the mortar battery, support platoon and servicing and 
maintenance platoon. Radios of the commander of the ATP, 
reconnaissance platoon and GLP, and the BMP (BTR) radio net made 
up of R-123M (R-173) radios of all battalion BTR's (BMP's) also 
may be included in this net. Centralized control of companies, 
platoons and squads usually is accomplished over this radio net 
when making a march and fighting in BMP's (BTR's). 
  Radios of the reconnaissance patrol, if it is sent out, may 
be included in this radio net. 
  Control of tanks attached to the battalion is exercised over 
the radio net of the attached tanks. It usually includes the 
R-123 radio of the battalion commander and chief of staff. The 
commander of the artillery subunit attached to the battalion is 
at the battalion COP. When the COP is in movement, 
communications between them is maintained by including the 
artillery subunit commander in the battalion commander's radio 
net. 
  Communications with the regimental commander and staff is 
maintained over two radio nets: regimental commander's and chief 
of staff's. 
  Communications with the regimental rear control post and aid 
station is established over the rear radio net by having one of 
the battalion radios enter this net. 
  For C[.sup]2[/] in the defense, wire communications is 
organized between the battalion COP and COP's of subordinate 
subunits over cable lines run and serviced by signal platoon 
personnel. Wire communications lines are run to the MRC's 
(mortar battery) by links; communications with the ATP is 
maintained over a line run to the MRC or through the commander 
of the company with which they operate together in battle. 
  In the mortar battery a cable line is run from the COP to 
the 
battery firing position. 
  Features of organization of communications in the 
TB. The TB COP is approximately the very same in makeup as 
that of the MRB. Its communications center consists of the 
commander's tank, a command vehicle, individual radios, and 
sometimes also (in the defense) a team of couriers. In battle 
the TB commander controls subunits from the tank. The tank 
commander's R-130M radio is used for communicating with the 
regimental commander. The R- 123 radio usually is used for 
C[.sup]2[/] with subordinate subunits. 
  The BMP-1K command vehicle is the basic element of the 
communications center. Using the radios installed in it, 
communications is maintained with the regimental staff, with 
motorized rifle and artillery subunits operating together with 
it, and with the battalion's subordinate subunits. 
  The R-123M radio of the signal platoon BMP can be used for 
communicating with those radios not included in the radio net of 
the commander's tank or the BMP- 1K. 
  In organizing radio communications it is advisable to set up 
three radio nets in the battalion for continuous C[.sup]2[/] 
of subunits with any situation changes and with transition from 
one kind of battle to another. This will allow maintaining 
reliable communications both during battalion operations at full 
strength as well as during operations of TC's with MRB's. 
  When the TB is fighting at full strength, subunits are 
controlled over the battalion commander's radio net, which 
consists of radios of the battalion commander, chief of staff, 
and commanders of the TC's, platoons, line tanks, support 
platoon and servicing and maintenance platoon. 
  If TC's are attached to MRB's, the radios of all company 
tanks are switched into the radio net of the MRB commander and 
staff. The number of such radio nets may be according to the 
number of MRB's. 
  When a TB (less TC) is attached to an MRB, C[.sup]2[/] of 
them is exercised by the TB commander over his own radio net. 
  In addition, a technical observation post and a repair and 
recovery team are set up in the battalion and headed by the 
deputy battalion commander for weapons. The technical 
observation post usually is located together with the COP, and 
one of the communications center radios must be included in the 
regimental technical support radio net. Communications is 
accomplished over this radio net with the deputy regimental 
commander for weapons, with repair and recovery teams and with 
maintenance companies. Tanks and BMP's (BTR's) needing 
evacuation or technical assistance switch their radios into this 
same radio net. 
<H5>  4. Work of the Company (Battalion) Commander in Organizing </H5>
for Battle 
  The continuous development and upgrading of means of warfare 
inevitably leads to a change in the nature of battle and 
substantially affects the content and methodology of the work of 
the commander and staff to organize it. 
  The scope of tasks which a commander must perform in 
organizing for battle has grown considerably under present 
conditions, and time for performing this work has been reduced 
sharply at the same time. The time factor now has a deciding 
influence on all C[.sup]2[/] processes. While a battalion 
commander had several days to organize for battle in the Great 
Patriotic War, this work has to be done in a shorter time in 
modern war. 
  Making an advisable decision in a short time, when the 
commander assumes responsibility for the fate of the people 
entrusted to him, is a very important moment in his work. 
  The fact is that, like any other process in which a person 
takes part, the decisionmaking process has two sides--objective 
and subjective. 
  The objective side includes the combat mission and situation 
elements existing outside of our awareness and independent of 
our will and desire; the subjective side includes the commander, 
who possesses certain knowledge, experience and intellectual 
features. 
  In connection with the fact that something objective is 
reflected differently in the awareness of each person, a 
decision made by two commanders based on a study of one and the 
same situation elements also may differ in content. 
  A decision can be advisable only if the situation elements 
and other factors independent of the commander's will are 
grasped by him as precisely as possible. Therefore in order to 
make an advisable decision the commander must possess high 
command qualities and professional expertise, have detailed 
knowledge of the theory of modern combined arms battle and the 
organization and operating tactics of probable enemies, and be 
able to get his bearings quickly in a complicated, abruptly 
changing situation. 
  Those times have passed when a decision for battle could be 
made only on the basis of intuition and natural talent alone. 
Science, a scientific approach to military phenomena, precise 
calculations and substantiated conclusions now are the basis of 
military art. A correct decision is the result of the 
commander's painstaking mental work in studying situation 
conditions and his knowing to perfection military affairs and 
the laws and principles of conducting modern war. 
  At the same time, in order to be able to make a decision 
quickly and implement it boldly and firmly, in addition to 
knowledge a commander must possess such command qualities as 
decisiveness and determination, independence and high 
exactingness, bravery and purposefulness. 
  A commander without such qualities vacillates long and 
agonizingly in making a decision. He spends so much time on this 
that in the final account he is late in making a decision and, 
having made it but not having displayed proper determination and 
resolve, he cannot always achieve success even with superiority 
over the enemy. 
  Content and sequence of a company (battalion) 
commander's work of organizing for battle. Organization for 
battle includes a large set of measures taken by the commander 
and staff from the moment the combat mission is received until 
the moment subordinate commanders report subunit readiness to 
execute it. 
  The content and sequence of the company (battalion) 
commander's work of organizing for battle depend on the combat 
mission received, availability of time and situation conditions. 
  As a rule, the company (battalion) commander begins the work 
of organizing for battle on receiving an operation order 
(operational instructions, warning order) or after the battalion 
(regimental) commander has announced his decision for battle. 
  The battalion commander's work sequence may be as follows. 
On 
receiving a warning order (Fig. 2) he analyzes the mission; 
determines measures which must be taken immediately for swiftest 
preparation of subunits to perform the assigned mission; 
performs a time calculation (or approves a calculation offered 
by the chief of staff); orients his deputies on upcoming 
operations; issues directions to the chief of staff on preparing 
battalion subunits to perform the combat mission, on organizing 
reconnaissance, and on the time and procedure of work on the 
terrain; estimates the situation; determines his commander's 
concept and reports it to the senior commander (chief). Then he 
familiarizes his deputies with it, issues verbal warning orders 
to subunit commanders and gives instructions on organizing 
coordination, comprehensive support of battle, C[.sup]2[/] 
and political work. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-23A>      Fig. 2. Sequence of company (battalion) commander's work in organizing for battle on </FIG>


  On receiving the operation order the company (battalion) 
commander completes decisionmaking, performs ground 
reconnaissance, issues a verbal operation order and organizes 
coordination. Then he directs immediate preparation of subunits 
for battle and, within the prescribed time, reports company 
(battalion) readiness for performing the combat mission to the 
senior commander. 
  On receiving an operation order or operational instructions 
(Fig. 3), the work of the company (battalion) commander is done 
in the same sequence as on receiving a warning order, the only 
difference being that after the situation estimate, a decision 
is made to the full extent, which then is briefed to the senior 
chief (commander). After its approval the company (battalion) 
commander performs ground reconnaissance and issues the 
operation order. 
  The company (battalion) commander's work sequence also may 
be 
different depending on the situation and availability of time. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-24A>      Fig. 3. Sequence of battalion (company) commander's work in organizing for battle on receiving </FIG>


  Methodology of company (battalion) commander's 
decisionmaking for battle. The decision for battle is 
understood to mean a finally chosen plan of action of the 
commander for performing the assigned mission, which specifies 
in basic outlines the procedure for using available forces and 
assets in the upcoming battle. 
  The decision is a volitional act of the commander. It 
answers 
questions about what is to be done where, when, how, and by whom 
so as to perform the assigned mission with least expenditure of 
forces and assets. It contains important initial data for 
conducting all basic measures connected with organization for 
battle and with C[.sup]2[/] of subunits in the course of 
battle. 
  The content of the commander's decision for battle is 
spelled 
out by the "Boyevoy ustav Sukhoputnykh voysk" [Ground Troops 
Field Manual]. The company (battalion) commander makes the 
decision personally based on his analysis of the mission 
received and on a situation estimate. In the decision 
the company (battalion) commander specifies the commander's 
concept, combat missions for subunits, basic questions of 
coordination, and organization of C[.sup]2[/]. In addition, 
the decision may specify missions for kinds of support and for 
political work. 
  Decisionmaking is a very complex, important process in the 
commander's work requiring him to have not only a detailed 
knowledge of the theory and organization of modern combined arms 
battle and of combat capabilities of friendly and enemy troops, 
but also mastery of this work methodology developed by many 
years of experience of subunit commanders' activity and 
incorporated in the Manual. 
  As a rule, the company (battalion) commander performs the 
work of organizing for battle on the terrain. In those cases 
where the situation does not permit traveling onto the terrain 
(little time for organizing battle, open terrain), the company 
(battalion) commander performs this work from a terrain map 
(model). But even in this case he has to find time to travel out 
on the terrain to update missions for subordinates and organize 
coordination. 
  In all cases the commander must perform the work of 
organizing for battle so as to ensure continuous C[.sup]2[/] 
of subunits, timely decisionmaking and assignment of missions; a 
large part of the allotted time must be given to subordinate 
subunits for preparation and performance of the mission. 
  Analysis of the mission begins the company 
(battalion) commander's decisionmaking work. Company (battalion) 
efforts can be directed properly toward performing the combat 
mission only on condition that the commander has a clear picture 
of the goal of upcoming operations, the senior commander's 
concept, his own mission, his place in the battle formation and 
the role of his company (battalion) in performing the senior 
chief's mission. 
  In modern war knowing the senior commander's concept also is 
necessary to ensure greater independence in the company 
(battalion) commander's actions when communications with the 
battalion (regimental) commander is lost. By knowing the senior 
chief's concept the company (battalion) commander will be able 
to assume control if necessary. He can learn the content of the 
concept from the senior commander's order (operational 
instructions). 
  On receiving a mission personally from the battalion 
(regimental) commander, the company (battalion) commander 
usually analyzes it on the spot and while returning to his own 
COP (to the battalion staff). 
  Correctly understanding the senior chief's concept means 
firmly learning what enemy he intends to rout where and in what 
sequence; where he is delivering the main attack (concentrating 
main efforts); how he is exploiting results of nuclear and 
precision weapon strikes delivered by the senior commander, and 
how he is using conventional weapons, especially on the axis of 
company (battalion) operations; what kind of grouping of forces 
and assets the senior commander is establishing; and what kind 
of maneuver he envisages executing in the course of battle. 
  The role of the company (battalion) is determined by the 
nature and degree of its involvement in performing the mission 
assigned to the senior commander. Therefore in order to 
correctly understand the role of the company (battalion) in 
performing the mission assigned to the battalion (regiment), it 
is necessary to firmly learn the content of the company 
(battalion) combat mission, as part of what element of the 
battalion (regimental) battle formation it is fighting, what 
enemy grouping it must rout and what line to take (what 
strongpoint to hold), the depth of the combat mission, how much 
time is allotted for performing the combat mission, and 
readiness time. 
  Based on an analysis of the combat mission, the company 
(battalion) commander draws conclusions in which he determines 
the axis for concentrating main efforts (if not specified by the 
senior chief), combat missions for subunits, nature of the 
maneuver, alignment of the battle formation, rate of advance and 
other matters. In addition, the commander determines measures 
which must be taken immediately for preparing the company 
(battalion) and the calculation of time for organizing for 
battle. 
  Having analyzed the mission and drawn appropriate 
conclusions, the company (battalion) commander can 
determine measures which must be taken immediately. 
They can be divided into two groups: on preparing company 
(battalion) subunits for performing the combat mission and on 
the work of deputies (the staff) connected with decisionmaking 
and preparation for battle. The first group usually includes 
measures concerned with preparing vehicles and personnel, 
replenishing supplies, evacuating sick and wounded, taking 
immediate measures for protecting subunits against mass 
destruction weapons, providing replacements for subunits, 
repairing vehicles and weapons and so on. 
  The second group can include measures on organization of 
reconnaissance, on preparation of data for decisionmaking, on 
the time and procedure of work on the terrain and so on. 
  The time calculation is one of the most important 
conclusions made from analyzing the combat mission. The company 
(battalion) commander usually performs the calculation of time 
for organizing for battle himself. The following are initial 
data for calculating time for organizing for battle: time of 
receipt of the combat mission and company (battalion) readiness 
for executing it; time of briefing the decision to the senior 
commander; time periods for the commander's participation in 
measures conducted by the senior commander in organizing for 
battle on the terrain. 
  In performing the time calculation the company (battalion) 
commander first determines the presence of overall time 
available for preparing for battle and determines the length of 
daylight. Then he determines the following: how much time 
(including daylight) to give subordinate commanders for 
organizing for battle and to allot to himself for 
decisionmaking, assigning combat missions, performing ground 
reconnaissance, updating the decision, issuing the operation 
order, listening to and approving subordinate commanders' 
decisions, and organizing coordination; in what time periods to 
prepare subunits for performing the mission and to give them 
necessary assistance; and when to report readiness for 
performance of the combat mission to the senior chief. 
  In calculating time, its bulk should be given to 
subordinates. 
  Situation estimate. The situation estimate is 
understood to mean the aggregate of all objective conditions in 
which a company (battalion) has to perform the combat mission. 
In this stage conditions of the assigned combat mission usually 
are studied and factors are identified which will facilitate or 
hamper its performance. In other words, the situation estimate 
is where the commander comes to understand objective conditions 
of upcoming battle and finds the most correct ways of taking 
advantage of these conditions for successful performance of the 
assigned mission. 
  The enemy, friendly troops, adjacent subunits, terrain, and 
the NBC situation usually are elements of the situation 
estimate. In addition, the state of weather, time of year and 
day and their effect on preparing and conducting battle are 
taken into account. 
  The situation elements enumerated above have a varying 
effect 
in deciding one and the same question. In connection with this 
the conclusions at which a commander arrives as a result of 
their estimate also are not only different, but even 
contradictory. The greatest influence will be exerted in one 
instance by the status or position of enemy troops, in another 
instance by the status and position of friendly troops, in a 
third instance by features of the combat operations area, and in 
a fourth instance by time of year or day, visibility conditions 
and so on. But the enemy is the most important and dynamic 
situation element of all. He is the objective of combat effect. 
Actions of friendly troops largely depend on his actions. 
Therefore it is recommended that a situation estimate begin with 
an estimate of the enemy. 
  Enemy estimate. Destruction of the enemy in the 
attack (defense) frontage is the content of the company 
(battalion) combat mission. Success in accomplishing it 
naturally depends fully on a correct understanding of this 
enemy's makeup, position, intentions and capabilities. 
  The battalion commander estimates the enemy on the axis of 
attack of the battalion and adjacent subunits to the depth of 
disposition of the enemy brigade, and in greatest detail to the 
depth of the battalion combat mission. The company commander 
estimates the enemy to the depth of the battalion defense and in 
greater detail to the depth of the company combat mission. In 
the defense he estimates that enemy grouping which may launch an 
attack on the axis of company (battalion) defense and on the 
flanks. 
  As a rule, data on the enemy always will be insufficient and 
some may be unreliable, contradictory, obsolete and even false. 
But the company (battalion) commander must be able to compare 
available information on the enemy, take into account his 
tactics, troop organization, and possible nature of actions, and 
draw correct conclusions on the basis of this. 
  It is recommended that the enemy estimate be conducted in 
the 
following sequence: initially study and analyze the general 
nature of operations and the position, makeup, status and degree 
of protection of the enemy grouping in the zone of advance (in 
the defense sector) of the battalion (regiment); then estimate 
that part of his grouping which must be routed in performing the 
assigned mission, i.e., in the company (battalion) attack 
frontage; finally, relying on a knowledge of enemy tactics and 
knowing the degree of protection and the system of 
fortifications, fire and obstacles and having determined the 
enemy's strong and weak points, the commander uncovers the 
probable nature (concept) of his operations as the company 
(battalion) performs the mission. 
  The company (battalion) commander draws conclusions based on 
a detailed, comprehensive analysis of the enemy and the probable 
nature of his operations: what enemy is ahead of the company 
(battalion) and the probable nature of his operations; where the 
main body of the enemy grouping is whose destruction will 
sharply degrade his combat capabilities; the enemy's strong and 
weak points. 
  These conclusions enable the company (battalion) commander 
to 
determine the axis for concentrating main efforts (terrain 
sectors on whose holding the stability of the defense depends); 
what enemy to rout by what method and in what sequence; 
procedure for engaging the enemy by fire of organic and attached 
weapons; company (battalion) battle formation; combat missions 
for subunits; principal questions of coordination and the 
procedure for comprehensive support of battle; and on what to 
perform final reconnaissance and by what time. 
  In addition, the commander determines tasks for political 
work based on the enemy estimate. 
  The company (battalion) commander formalizes results of the 
enemy estimate on his working map. On it are plotted the 
position of mechanized infantry and tank subunits down to 
platoon (platoon strongpoints), artillery firing positions, 
command posts and other elements of the enemy battle formation 
and also possible directions and lines of counterattacks and 
commitment of follow- on forces in the defense, makeup and time 
periods for moving to them, and locations of radars, individual 
weapons and AT weapons (tanks, ATGM's, machineguns and so on). 
  Estimate of friendly subunits. Friendly subunits 
are understood to mean organic, attached and supporting subunits. 
  Like that of the enemy, a correct estimate of friendly 
troops 
is of great importance for decisionmaking, since its primary 
purpose is to determine combat capabilities of organic and 
attached company (battalion) subunits, determine their political 
attitude and morale, and find the best ways of using them to 
perform the assigned mission. 
  The company (battalion) commander as a rule will have 
exhaustive data on his own subunits. 
  According to requirements of manuals, in estimating friendly 
troops the company (battalion) commander studies the makeup, 
position, status, capabilities, degree of protection and state 
of supply of his own, attached and supporting subunits. 
  The company (battalion) commander draws individual 
conclusions in studying each element of the estimate of friendly 
subunits. For example, in studying the strength level, the 
battalion commander concludes that one of the companies suffered 
the greatest losses in battle and must be brought up to strength 
or moved to the second echelon. 
  The company (battalion) commander usually estimates friendly 
troops in the following sequence: initially he analyzes the 
position of organic and attached subunits, then studies their 
makeup and finally determines their combat capabilities for 
performing upcoming missions. 
  In estimating the position of friendly troops the company 
(battalion) commander studies the position of company 
(battalion) subunits with respect to the enemy and the nature of 
their actions (attacking, defending, located in an area, on the 
march); distance of subunits from the planned line of departure 
(defense area) and time needed for their forward movement; 
location, nature of actions, and time and areas of arrival of 
attached subunits, and time for changing the areas (positions) 
they occupy. 
  In the process of estimating the makeup and status of 
friendly subunits the commander analyzes the table of 
organization structure of the company (battalion), whether or 
not all organic subunits are present and, if not, where they are 
now and when they will arrive; makeup of attached subunits; 
political attitude, morale and physical condition of personnel 
and the condition of weapons and combat vehicles; training level 
and combat experience of subunits; and organizing abilities of 
subunit commanders. 
  In estimating the state of supply of friendly troops the 
commander determines the company (battalion) state of supply of 
material resources and time periods for establishing their 
reserves in subunits; norms of expenditure of material resources 
and requirements for them for performing the combat mission; 
organization of delivery and evacuation; and technical and 
logistic support. 
  In estimating combat capabilities of friendly subunits the 
company (battalion) commander determines artillery capabilities 
for engaging enemy objectives from indirect firing positions and 
for destroying tanks, ATGM's and other weapons; capabilities of 
air defense weapons for combating airborne targets; and 
capabilities of motorized rifle and tank subunits for 
establishing a superiority over the enemy in penetrating his 
defense (repelling assaults ahead of the FEBA). 
  Based on the estimate of the enemy and friendly troops, the 
company (battalion) commander performs a 
quantitative-qualitative analysis of their makeup, political 
attitude, morale and combat capabilities, and with consideration 
of this determines the absolute and quantitative-qualitative 
status of the sides' forces. 
  A comprehensive estimate of friendly troops permits the 
company (battalion) commander to draw conclusions about the 
general status, degree of protection and combat effectiveness of 
subordinate subunits; whether or not their position conforms to 
the nature of the combat mission received, whether or not a 
regrouping is necessary and time required for this; where to 
concentrate main company (battalion) efforts; how to align the 
battle formation and distribute forces and assets; what combat 
missions to assign subunits based on their capabilities; what 
main questions of organizing coordination and of comprehensive 
support of battle to plan; and how to organize C[.sup]2[/]. 
  Estimate of adjacent subunits. Adjacent subunits 
customarily are understood to mean subunits operating on flanks 
(on the right, on the left) and in front, or which are in the 
rear, but operate on the company (battalion) axis in the course 
of battle. 
  The main goal of estimating adjacent subunits is to 
determine 
their influence on company (battalion) performance of the 
assigned mission and to detail the procedure for joint 
operations with them to rout the enemy. 
  In estimating adjacent subunits the company (battalion) 
commander studies the makeup, position, and nature of actions of 
adjacent subunits and conditions of coordination with them. In 
estimating the nature of their actions the commander determines 
what they are doing as of the moment he makes the decision for 
battle and what maneuver they will execute in preparing to 
perform assigned combat missions. 
  In estimating conditions of coordination with adjacent 
subunits the commander determines how those subunits will 
contribute to routing the enemy; what assistance must be given 
them in performing combat missions; what maneuver of forces and 
assets to execute to exploit possible success of adjacent 
subunits; what measures to take to secure flanks; and what 
procedure of coordination with adjacent subunits to provide for 
in routing the enemy. 
  The company (battalion) commander can draw the following 
conclusions from the estimate of adjacent subunits: how actions 
of adjacent subunits influence performance of missions; where it 
is advisable to concentrate main efforts and what enemy must be 
routed in coordination with adjacent subunits; what enemy 
targets (objectives) to engage by company (battalion) weapons on 
flanks with adjacent subunits; alignment of the battle 
formation; with which adjacent subunits coordination should be 
organized most closely in routing which enemy and on what 
questions; what assistance to give adjacent subunits in joint 
destruction of the enemy; what maneuver of forces and assets to 
provide for to exploit possible success of adjacent subunits; 
what data must be additionally received from adjacent subunits 
and what questions must be coordinated in the interests of 
maintaining coordination and communications with them in the 
course of battle; how to support commitment of the second 
echelon and coordinate actions with it; and the procedure for 
passing company (battalion) subunits through battle formations 
of subunits operating in front. 
  Terrain estimate. The company (battalion) 
commander studies the terrain to determine its influence on 
combat employment of friendly and enemy troops. As a result of 
its study he determines the extent to which terrain helps the 
enemy organize and conduct a defense and helps our attack. 
  In estimating the situation it is necessary to study the 
nature of terrain and its influence on subunit operations and 
also to study the most likely axes of operations of enemy 
aircraft and helicopters and other airborne targets flying at 
low and extremely low altitudes. 
  The following methodology for studying terrain has been 
developed in troop practice. Initially terrain is estimated in 
the enemy disposition, then in the friendly troop disposition. 
Before beginning the terrain estimate the company (battalion) 
commander carefully studies changes which occurred on the 
terrain compared with the map as a result of the opposing sides' 
use of nuclear weapons. 
  Then the terrain usually is estimated in the following 
sequence: general nature of terrain; conditions for observation, 
fire, maskirovka and disposition; conditions of trafficability 
and protective features; and changes which may occur as a result 
of the use of nuclear weapons and in the course of battle. 
  In studying the general nature of terrain the battalion 
commander identifies the following: type of relief, local 
features, hydrography, and degree of ruggedness and 
observability; favorable lines for enemy defense and lines whose 
taking creates conditions for successful development of the 
attack by our troops. 
  In estimating conditions of observation, fire, maskirovka 
and 
disposition the company (battalion) commander determines the 
following: commanding heights and other places for observation; 
natural screens, cover, and favorable areas for disposing 
elements of the battle formation, C[.sup]2[/] facilities and 
rear subunits; favorable lines for deployment, departure, 
repulse (delivery) of counterattacks, and remote minelaying; 
conditions of maskirovka; probable axes of operations of enemy 
aircraft, helicopters and other airborne targets at low and 
extremely low altitudes, and so on. 
  In studying trafficability conditions and protective 
features 
of terrain, the commander determines the following: presence and 
status of roads and maneuver, supply and evacuation routes; 
nature of soil and off-road terrain passability; nature of 
natural obstacles; presence of water obstacles and engineering 
structures on them whose destruction can hamper operations of 
company (battalion) subunits, and so on. 
  In studying the terrain the commander forecasts changes 
which 
may occur as a result of the use of nuclear and incendiary 
weapons, destruction of dams, fires, flooding, torrential rains, 
snowstorms and so on. 
  As a result of the terrain estimate the company (battalion) 
commander determines the following: how the terrain influences 
employment of different combat arms and performance of the 
combat mission; most accessible axes for operations of friendly 
and enemy troops and where, based on this, it would be advisable 
to concentrate main efforts (and on the defense in addition, he 
determines terrain areas on whose holding stability of the 
defense depends); enemy objectives for engagement by fire of 
conventional weapons (artillery from indirect firing positions, 
tanks, ATGM's, AT weapons, grenade launchers and machineguns); 
how to align the battle formation and where to place its 
elements, support subunits and COP, and the direction of COP 
displacement; lines of immediate and subsequent missions of 
subunits (in the defense, locations of company and platoon 
strongpoints); second echelon commitment lines (in the defense, 
lines of firing positions, axes and lines of deployment for 
counterattacks); and sectors for forcing water obstacles. He 
also draws conclusions relating to questions of coordination, 
comprehensive support of battle and organization of political 
work. 
  NBC situation estimate. The NBC situation is 
understood to mean the situation which has arisen with use of 
mass destruction weapons as a result of contamination of 
terrain, air, personnel, equipment and various installations by 
radioactive substances, chemical agents and bacteriological 
warfare agents. The NBC situation estimate is made to identify 
its effect on subunits' combat effectiveness and determine 
advisable directions and methods of their operations, and to 
outline basic measures for protecting personnel against mass 
destruction weapons. 
  The NBC situation estimate is made on the basis of 
reconnaissance, forecasting and radiological monitoring data. 
Results of a forecast of the radiological and chemical situation 
in the area of operations usually are announced to the battalion 
commander by the regimental staff. 
  In estimating the scale and nature of NBC contamination of 
terrain, the company (battalion) commander determines the 
following: kinds, time, method and means of contamination of the 
company (battalion) disposition area and axis of attack; 
boundaries and nature of zones of radioactive contamination and 
how they can change by the beginning of company (battalion) 
subunit operations in them; type of chemical agents, boundaries 
of areas, duration of contamination, and depth of spread of 
contaminated air; kind of contagious disease pathogens; 
boundaries of contaminated areas; what subunits have entered 
(will enter) the zone of contamination and destructive damage; 
and levels of contamination. 
  In estimating the nature of the effect of contamination on 
company (battalion) subunits and possible consequences, the 
commander determines the following: possible radiation doses of 
personnel from radioactive substances (counting those received 
previously); possible degree of personnel injury by chemical and 
bacterial warfare agents; degree of contamination of 
communications equipment, weapons, supplies and water; possible 
personnel losses from contamination; and the need for performing 
decontamination (partial and complete). 
  As a result of the NBC situation estimate the company 
(battalion) commander usually draws the following conclusions: 
how the NBC situation can affect subunits' combat effectiveness 
and performance of the combat mission; measures for mopping up 
in the aftermath of enemy use of mass destruction weapons and 
for restoring subunit combat effectiveness; what instructions on 
protection must be issued in the given situation and to whom; 
the safest axis (area) for subunit operations and, in connection 
with this, where it is advisable to specify the axis for 
concentrating main efforts (in the defense in addition, also 
terrain sectors on whose holding stability of the defense 
depends); what enemy to rout, by what method and in what 
sequence based on the existing NBC situation; procedure for 
engaging the enemy by fire of organic and attached weapons; what 
battle formation to have and where to place it; and combat 
missions of subunits. He also outlines the main questions of 
coordination and the procedure for comprehensive support of 
battle, and determines organization of C[.sup]2[/], the 
method of crossing a contaminated area and tasks for political 
work. 
  In addition, in the situation estimate the company 
(battalion) commander takes into account the state of weather 
and time of year and day, since these factors have a very great 
influence on troop combat operations, especially with an abrupt 
change of weather, without knowledge and consideration of which 
it is impossible to make a substantiated decision. 
  Making the decision. The essence of the company 
(battalion) commander's work in this stage of decisionmaking 
consists of comparing conclusions drawn from individual elements 
(questions) of the decision (in the course of analyzing the 
mission, estimating the situation and making tactical 
calculations) for the purpose of final determination and 
formulation of component elements of the decision. The decision 
should not only conform to the real situation, but also contain 
elements of creativeness, aggressiveness, reasonable risk and 
use of operating methods unknown to the enemy, i.e., everything 
that ensures routing the enemy with a minimum expenditure of 
forces and in the shortest possible time. 
  The company (battalion) commander usually begins making and 
formulating the decision by determining the commander's concept. 
In the course of analyzing the mission and estimating the 
situation, he draws appropriate conclusions for each element of 
the commander's concept. Conclusions drawn from analyzing the 
mission and estimating the situation may be identical for some 
elements of the concept. Consequently, the commander could 
determine these elements of the concept once and for all back in 
the process of estimating the situation. Conclusions may be 
contradictory for other elements of the concept. For final 
determination of these elements the commander needs to compare 
the conclusions he drew previously and choose the most advisable 
one. 
  Thus, final determination of all or some elements of the 
decision is the concluding stage of the commander's work of 
decisionmaking. 
  Formalization of the decision. As the decision is 
made, the battalion commander together with the chief of staff 
(and the company commander independently) plots everything on 
the map that can be depicted graphically. As a rule, the 
following is plotted on the map: enemy battle formation; axis 
for concentrating main efforts (in the defense in addition, 
terrain sectors on whose holding the stability of the defense 
depends); company (battalion) missions, missions of adjacent 
subunits and boundary with them, and weapon missions to be 
performed by forces and assets of senior chiefs; missions of 
subordinate subunits and the methods and time periods for their 
performance; COP locations of battalion and companies and 
directions of their displacement. In addition, basic questions 
of coordination, C[.sup]2[/] and support of battle are 
reflected on the map. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-30A>      Figure </FIG>



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-31A>      Figure </FIG>


  In addition to the graphic part, tables are drawn up on the 
working map which may show means of reinforcement, distribution 
and ratio of forces and assets, their densities and other 
matters. 
  Thus, by the moment decisionmaking work is done the 
commander 
has a plan of company (battalion) actions which has formed in 
his mind once and for all and is graphically displayed on the 
map. Now he can brief his decision to the senior commander, 
announce it to deputies and staff officers (subordinate 
commanders), and perform ground reconnaissance, issue the 
operation order and organize coordination. 
  Assignment of combat missions to subordinates is 
done by various methods depending on specific situation 
conditions. If sufficient time is available the company 
(battalion) commander issues a verbal operation order. Combat 
missions as a rule are communicated by verbal operational 
instructions or warning orders in organizing for battle in a 
short time, especially in the course of battle. 
  The battalion commander's verbal operation order must be 
entered in a workbook by the battalion chief of staff or his 
deputy. The order is not duplicated. 
  In operational instructions the company 
(battalion) commander indicates the following: conclusions from 
the enemy estimate; objectives to be engaged by the senior 
commander's weapons in support of the platoon (company); the 
combat mission and readiness time for executing it. If necessary 
the operational instructions may indicate missions of adjacent 
subunits and other data. 
  In a warning order the company (battalion) 
commander usually indicates the following: information on the 
enemy; objectives to be engaged by the senior commander's 
weapons in support of the platoon (company); the combat mission 
with a degree of detailing corresponding to the decision made by 
the senior commander as of the time the warning order was 
issued; readiness time and basic measures of preparing for 
battle; time and methods of communicating missions, and other 
data. 
  Organization of coordination is an important 
measure taken by the company (battalion) commander in organizing 
for battle. Coordination is organized by missions, time, place 
and possible options of operations. 
  The company (battalion) commander organizes coordination 
with 
the participation of his deputies and the commanders of platoons 
(companies) and attached subunits. As a rule, it is organized on 
the terrain to the depth of visibility, or on a terrain model 
(map) to the full depth of the combat mission received. 
  Coordination may be organized by two methods: by the method 
of reports by subordinate subunit commanders on the procedure 
for their subunits' operations in performing assigned missions, 
with a run-through of the main tactical episodes; and by the 
method of commander's instructions. This method usually is used 
when battle is being organized in an extremely limited time. 
  In organizing coordination the company (battalion) commander 
has to coordinate efforts of organic, attached and supporting 
subunits in performing the assigned mission; achieve uniform 
understanding by all commanders of the goal of battle, combat 
missions and methods of their performance; and outline and 
coordinate options of subunit operations and measures for 
deceiving the enemy which take account of the possible nature of 
enemy operations. The company (battalion) commander also is 
obligated to indicate warning, control, coordination, mutual 
recognition and target designation signals. During battle 
coordination is accomplished continuously, is constantly 
updated, and is organized anew with abrupt situation changes and 
when a new decision is being made. 
  In organizing C[.sup]2[/], the company 
(battalion) commander indicates the following: places and time 
of deployment of COP's of the company (battalion) and attached 
subunits and the procedure for their displacement in the course 
of battle; procedure for maintaining communications and radio 
traffic, and methods and time periods for submitting reports; 
degree of engineer preparation of COP's and procedure for their 
security. 
Footnotes 
  1. See N. Alekseyev, "Oskolkom oborvannaya zhizn" [A Life 
Cut 
Short by a Fragment], Moscow, Politizdat, 1978, pp 72-74. 
<H5>  Chapter IV - The Defense </H5>
<H5>  1. Principles of Defensive Battle </H5>
  As one of the basic kinds of battle, the defense arose 
simultaneously with the offense. Upgrading of existing weapons 
and appearance of new ones, a change of troop organization, and 
defenders' use of new means of warfare increase subunit combat 
capabilities, give the defense new features, make it more stable 
and active, and change the kinds of defense and methods of 
operations of subunits and units. On the other hand, an 
attacking enemy also uses modern weapons and combat vehicles 
permitting him to deliver powerful, precise strikes to a 
considerable depth and create breaches in the defense in a short 
time. In developing new and upgrading existing methods of 
attack, the enemy pays special attention to achieving surprise, 
creating a decisive superiority in forces and assets, and 
delivering massed strikes. Reliance is placed above all on 
precision weapon systems, by which it is proposed to inflict 
damage on defending subunits and units in a short time to the 
full depth of their battle formation. For timely exploitation of 
results of fire damage, the enemy envisages decisive operations 
of attacking subunits and units from the front in combination 
with wide use of aviation, airborne assault forces and EW assets. 
  Under present conditions defenders will have to repel 
assaults of an enemy who has a superiority of 5-6 times in 
personnel and combat vehicles. As a result, the defense must 
successfully withstand a powerful enemy attack and support the 
repulse of massed air and precision weapon strikes and the 
assaults of his tanks and mechanized infantry. 
  A defense may be occupied on a deliberate or forced basis to 
perform these missions. Subunits or units shift to the defense 
deliberately when more active (offensive), decisive operations 
are inadvisable, and on a forced basis as a result of a 
situation that has shaped up unfavorably. In addition, it may be 
prepared in advance before the beginning of combat operations or 
organized in the course of battle. At the beginning of a war the 
defense will be the most prevalent kind of battle. 
  Inasmuch as defenders are inferior to the attacking enemy in 
forces and assets, the possibility of repelling his attack 
largely is determined by the ability of subunit and unit 
commanders to take advantage of strong aspects of the defense. 
  Defending subunits above all must skillfully use the 
terrain's protective features, since they choose the place of 
battle. For this it is important that positions, trenches and 
strongpoints be disposed where possible behind natural barriers, 
on slopes, on commanding heights and in other terrain sectors 
affording a good field of view and fire toward the enemy to 
maximum range of their weapons. Natural barriers in themselves 
hamper operations not only of mechanized infantry, but also of 
tanks. 
  Occupation of lines favorable for defense, use of the 
terrain's protective features and its skillful engineer 
preparation also considerably reduce the effectiveness of enemy 
employment of nuclear and conventional weapons, including 
precision weapons. For example, just the simplest foxholes 
reduce subunit losses from nuclear weapons by approximately 
three times, and losses from artillery fire by seven or more 
times. 
  Weapons possess comparatively greater capabilities in the 
defense than in the offense. For example, in the war years 
neutralizing an enemy battalion attacking in dismounted 
formation and inflicting 20-30 percent losses on it (forcing it 
to give up the attack) required using three artillery battalions 
and expending 0.3-0.4 unit of fire, but inflicting the very same 
losses on a battalion in the defense with engineer preparation 
required at least nine artillery battalions and their 
expenditure of the entire unit of fire. 
  Having modern weapons, defending subunits and units are 
capable of delivering preemptive strikes against the most 
important enemy objectives in concentration areas, on routes of 
advance and on lines of deployment for an assault. This permits 
inflicting considerable losses on him even before he arrives at 
the FEBA and deprives him of an opportunity for a simultaneous 
assault. 
  The possibility of wide, advance use of various obstacles, 
especially minefields, is an important advantage of defenders 
over attackers. They permit holding up or reducing the rate of 
forward movement, deployment and assault of tanks, IFV's and 
APC's and thereby increasing the effectiveness both of AT 
weapons as well as of artillery fire by several times. In 
addition, in crossing minefields the enemy will suffer losses 
not only in vehicles, but also in personnel. 
  Subunit maskirovka capabilities increase in the defense. By 
concealing the true and showing a false trace of trenches and 
the location of strongpoints, firing and other positions, and 
COP's, subunits force the enemy to deliver strikes against empty 
places or secondary objectives and expend a considerable number 
of artillery and mortar rounds and missiles. 
  Being on defense, subunit and unit personnel can study the 
terrain in detail, create a system of trenches, strongpoints and 
firing positions both at the first position as well as in the 
depth, and thoroughly organize fire. Commanders can provide for 
the maneuver of forces and assets, prepare routes of advance for 
counterattacks and lines of firing positions, create a flexible 
C[.sup]2[/] system, supply subunits with an additional amount 
of ammunition, and carry out maskirovka measures. Thus, 
defending subunits are capable of destroying a comparatively 
large amount of enemy personnel, tanks and other armored 
vehicles and repelling his assaults with fewer forces. 
  The principal goal of the defense is to repel an attack by 
superior enemy forces, inflict maximum losses in personnel, 
weapons and vehicles, hold important terrain areas (objectives) 
and thereby create favorable conditions for launching an attack. 
  Ways of achieving the goal of defense can be as 
follows. 
  First of all, by engaging above all the main enemy 
grouping by fire of all weapons (combat helicopters, artillery, 
mortars, tanks, BMP's, small arms) both during forward movement, 
deployment and the assault on the FEBA as well as when he 
penetrates into the depth of the defense. 
  Thus, a battalion can engage the enemy by mortar fire 5-6 km 
from the FEBA and conduct a successful fight against armored 
vehicles at distances of 3 km from the FEBA by the fire of 
tanks, BMP's (BTR's) and ATGM's. 
  Secondly, the goal of the defense is achieved by a 
broad maneuver of fire, forces and assets. War experience showed 
that the defender countered an attack by an enemy of superior 
strength not only by stubborn resistance at occupied positions, 
but also by a broad maneuver of fire, forces and assets. 
  For example, in the Battle of Kursk on 7 July 1943 the 
Germans concentrated up to two infantry battalions and six tanks 
for the next assault in front of the center of the sector of 
151st Rifle Regiment, 8th Rifle Division. Executing a maneuver 
of trajectories, subunits of 476th Mortar Regiment and a guards 
rocket launcher battalion disrupted the enemy's intentions with 
massed fire and his assault did not take place.[.sup]1[/] 
  Thirdly, the goal of the defense is achieved by 
firmly holding important terrain areas, among which are areas 
which include tactically favorable sectors with natural barriers 
intercepting probable axes of enemy attack. Without a tenacious 
defense of such areas it is impossible to ensure effective fire 
against the enemy and execution of a bold, swift maneuver. 
Meanwhile, holding such terrain sectors permits immobilizing the 
attacker and creating favorable conditions for engaging the 
enemy by fire of all weapons and destroying him by a 
counterattack. 
  And fourthly and finally, the goal of the defense 
is achieved by skillful destruction of an enemy who has wedged 
into its depth. 
  Based on this, the essence of the defense lies in repelling 
the attack of superior enemy forces by inflicting damage on him 
by air strikes and fire of all weapons, with wide use of 
obstacles ahead of the FEBA and in the depth in combination with 
a maneuver of fire, forces and assets and decisive 
counterattacks, with the simultaneous tenacious holding of 
important (key) positions and terrain areas, thereby creating 
favorable conditions for launching an attack. 
  Subunits may shift to the defense under different situation 
conditions. The latter should be understood to mean the 
aggregate of factors of the combat situation in which the 
defense is prepared and a transition is made to it. Such factors 
are the position, the status and nature of terrain, time of year 
and day, state of weather and so on. 
  The position of subunits with respect to the enemy is a 
deciding condition for shifting to the defense. Depending on 
this and the mission received, a company (battalion) may shift 
to the defense in advance before the beginning of combat 
operations or the shift may be organized in the course of 
battle, out of contact with the enemy or in direct contact with 
him. An advance shift of subunits to the defense may be carried 
out both in peacetime as well as wartime. A shift to the defense 
in peacetime will be accomplished to cover border areas and 
repel an enemy invasion. 
  For example, subunits of 715th Rifle Regiment, 122nd Rifle 
Division shifted to the defense to cover our country's northern 
border in one of its sectors. They cut two roads leading from 
Kotala and Kelloselka to Kuola-Yarvi several days before 
the 
beginning of the war.[.sup]2[/] This permitted completing 
construction of the main defensive zone by the beginning of the 
enemy attack. 
  An advance shift to the defense in the course of war may 
occur where an attack is inadvisable or impossible for a number 
of reasons and situation conditions (on secondary and 
hard-to-reach axes, on a seacoast, on islands and in other 
cases). Under the given conditions subunits shift to a defense 
out of direct contact with the enemy. Subunits which are part of 
followon forces of units and formations in the deep rear of 
defending troops also may shift to the defense out of contact 
with him. 
  Under such conditions in particular subunits of 1075th Rifle 
Regiment, 316th Rifle Division shifted to the defense in the 
decisive period of the Battle of Moscow. Not having direct 
contact with the enemy, they prepared the occupied areas for 
four days beginning on 12 October 1941.[.sup]3[/] 
  The possibility of shifting to the defense out of contact 
with the enemy even in the course of an attack is not precluded. 
For example, on 26 October 1944 17th Rifle Division was 
successfully attacking in East Prussia. On the evening of that 
same day reconnaissance reported an imminent counterstrike by 
enemy reserves. To mislead him and create favorable conditions 
for the division main body to shift to the defense, the division 
commander ordered one company of each battalion to continue the 
attack and the main body to shift to the defense on a favorable 
line.[.sup]4[/] 
  As Great Patriotic War experience shows, subunits' shift to 
the defense in direct contact with the enemy will occur most 
often in the course of an attack when repelling counterattacks 
of superior enemy forces, consolidating captured lines, securing 
flanks of attacking troops, or with an unsuccessful outcome of a 
meeting battle. 
  Thus, in November 1943 the enemy tried for two days to halt 
an attack by subunits of 1147th Rifle Regiment, 353rd Rifle 
Division southwest of Dnepropetrovsk by counterattacks. All 
enemy counterattacks were successfully repelled, but on 5 
November the power of the enemy counterattacks rose and subunits 
shifted to the defense to repel them.[.sup]5[/] 
  The shift of subunits to the defense also is possible with 
an 
unsuccessful outcome of a meeting battle. This also is shown by 
the past war's experience. Thus, on 1 August 1944 a meeting 
battle occurred in the vicinity of Iodzhimyay during which 
subunits of 729th Rifle Regiment, 145th Rifle Division routed up 
to an enemy battalion and took the populated point. But during 
subsequent attacks they encountered strong resistance of the 
enemy, who counterattacked 729th Rifle Regiment subunits with 
forces of up to two battalions with 12 tanks and supported by 
the fire of three artillery battalions. By this time four 
infantry battalions already were operating against the regiment. 
The subunits were forced to hold up the attack and shift to the 
defense.[.sup]6[/] 
  In the course of an attack subunits and units often will 
have 
to force water obstacles and seize and hold bridgeheads. Great 
Patriotic War experience showed that battles for bridgeheads 
were characterized by high activeness on the enemy's part. 
  Thus, after forcing the Tisza River in the vicinity of 
Mehesz 
on the night of 27/28 October 1944, 4th Rifle Company of 795th 
Regiment took up a defense 200- 300 m from the water obstacle. 
The enemy repeatedly assaulted the defending subunit with forces 
of up to two infantry companies supported by artillery and 
mortar fire, but all his attempts to eliminate the bridgehead 
failed.[.sup]7[/] 
  Shifting to the defense in direct contact with the enemy is 
exceptionally difficult. This is determined by the fact that as 
a rule the defense will be organized under enemy fire in a short 
time, not always on a favorable line and as a rule on a line 
without engineer preparation. Subunits will have to perform 
several missions simultaneously: conduct a fire fight with a 
defending or counterattacking enemy, repel his air strikes, take 
steps to mop up in the aftermath of enemy use of nuclear, 
chemical and precision weapons and of fire strikes, reorganize 
the battle formation, replenish reserves of ammunition, fuel and 
other supplies, and organize the battle, the system of fire, and 
engineer preparation of occupied positions and strongpoints. 
  In addition, the situation also will be complicated by being 
understrength in personnel, weapons, vehicles and supplies 
caused by losses in the course of the attack. 
  Often it will be necessary to improve subunits' positions by 
battle or shift to the defense at the line which has been 
reached. In the first instance the need arises to destroy the 
opposing enemy by an attack, capture the line indicated for 
defense, consolidate on it, then shift to the defense. In some 
cases subunits will be forced to withdraw to the most favorable 
line. 
  In shifting to the defense out of contact with the enemy, 
subunits may have greater time for preparing the defense and 
better conditions for studying terrain ahead of the FEBA and in 
the depth of their defense, selecting more favorable positions 
and strongpoints with consideration of natural barriers, 
aligning the battle formation, organizing the system of fire and 
maneuver, and making wide use of engineer vehicles and 
improvised materials for preparing positions. 
  Meanwhile, absence of direct contact with the enemy does not 
preclude the possibility of his exerting an effect on subunits 
shifting to the defense by means of artillery, MLRS, aviation, 
raiding and reconnaissance parties, and precision weapons. This 
in turn requires taking measures for preparing the defense with 
observance of measures of maskirovka, security and protection. 
  Combat experience shows it is very difficult to shift to the 
defense during the day, especially in direct contact with the 
enemy. In this case the subunits' success is determined by the 
speed of their actions in taking the indicated line, timely 
assignment of missions to subordinates, organization of 
observation, a system of fire and engineer preparation, and 
skillful use of terrain relief and smoke in combination with 
fire damage of the enemy. In this period special attention 
should be given to destroying enemy AT weapons, helicopters and 
aircraft, and steps should be taken for protection against 
nuclear and fire strikes, including by precision weapons. 
  The most favorable conditions are created when shifting to 
the defense at night, under other conditions of limited 
visibility, and on terrain offering concealment. The nighttime 
and limited visibility (snowfall, fog, heavy rain and so on) 
reduce activeness of operations by enemy ground troops and 
aviation; in addition, at night the depth to which he conducts 
reconnaissance by observation and the effectiveness of fire is 
reduced considerably and conditions improve for performing 
engineer work. At the same time, selection of terrain sectors 
suitable for the defense is hampered, which necessitates 
updating positions and strongpoints with the arrival of dawn and 
updating conditions for organizing the system of fire. 
  The influence of these and other conditions should be taken 
into account by the subunit commander in organizing and 
conducting defensive battle. In launching an attack, the enemy 
may employ nuclear, chemical and precision weapons, airborne 
assault forces, airmobile and raiding and reconnaissance 
subunits, a large number of tanks, IFV's, APC's and aircraft 
(helicopters), and the massed fire of artillery, mortars and 
other weapons; he may remotely mine terrain to a considerable 
depth; and finally, he may assault swiftly with superior forces. 
In order to withstand the strikes of all these kinds of enemy 
weapons, repel his massed assaults and hold occupied areas 
(lines), the defense must be impregnable. Impregnable means 
stable and active, capable of withstanding strikes by all kinds 
of weapons and an assault by large masses of enemy tanks and 
infantry and conducting an active fight against his airborne 
assault forces and airmobile and raiding and reconnaissance 
parties. In addition, the defense must be antitank, antiaircraft 
and antilanding, deeply echeloned, and ready for lengthy battle 
under conditions of enemy use of mass destruction and precision 
weapons and EW assets. 
  Impregnability of the defense is achieved by tenacity, 
staunchness, determination and high morale of defending troops; 
continuous reconnaissance of the enemy and timely discovery of 
his preparation for an attack and of possible axes of attack; 
thorough maskirovka of the battle formation and misleading the 
enemy regarding the defense alignment and the concept of 
operations; skillful, varied defense alignment; skillful use of 
favorable terrain conditions and its engineer preparation; 
creation of a carefully organized system of fire, especially AT 
fire, in combination with systems of engineer obstacles, 
strongpoints and firing positions; reliable air defense; a 
timely maneuver of units (subunits), weapons and fire to 
threatened axes; immediate destruction of an enemy who has 
penetrated the defense and of his assault forces which have 
landed; use of unexpected tactics in the defense that are 
capable of stunning the enemy, placing him in a difficult 
situation and imposing one's will and initiative on him; 
constant fulfillment of measures for protection against enemy 
mass destruction and precision weapons; and tenacious, lengthy 
holding of defense areas (strongpoints) in combination with 
participation in conducting counterattacks. 
  Counterattacks are conducted under favorable conditions to 
destroy an enemy who has penetrated the defense or to take a 
line favorable for defense. Stability should be understood to 
mean the capability of withstanding powerful enemy strikes by 
all kinds of weapons, repelling an attack by his superior 
forces, holding occupied positions, strongpoints and important 
terrain areas and destroying the enemy in case he penetrates. 
Subunits must defend occupied positions tenaciously and hold 
them under all circumstances, even out of tactical contact with 
adjacent subunits and under conditions of total encirclement. A 
tenacious defense is a matter of the defenders' honor. They do 
not have the right to leave occupied positions and withdraw 
without an order of the senior commander. Successful performance 
of this mission depends on the subunit personnel's morale and 
fighting qualities, staunchness and determination, efficiency 
and firm military discipline, excellent combat proficiency and 
the desire to perform the assigned mission no matter what 
without sparing themselves. A deep alignment of the battle 
formation; a skillfully created system of fire, especially AT 
fire, in combination with obstacles; skillful engineer 
preparation of occupied positions, strongpoints and areas; and a 
ground-based air defense--all this also contributes to tenacious 
holding of defended positions. 
  Impregnability of a defense is inconceivable without its 
activeness. The defense will be active when the 
attacking enemy is constantly engaged by fire of all weapons on 
distant approaches to it during forward movement, deployment, 
and ahead of the FEBA, in the course of repelling an assault, 
and also in the depth of the defense in case the enemy 
penetrates. A maneuver of forces, assets and fire is the basis 
of activeness of the defense. A maneuver executed covertly, 
suddenly and swiftly permits placing friendly subunits in the 
most favorable position and inflicting decisive damage on a 
numerically superior enemy with fewer forces. It stands to 
reason that activeness of the defense is impossible without 
firmly holding defended positions. 
  Consequently, activeness of the defense consists of 
continuous engagement of the enemy by all available means, 
imposing one's will on him, creating unfavorable conditions for 
the attack, and conducting a broad maneuver of fire in all 
stages of battle. 
  It is common knowledge that nuclear weapons possess the 
greatest destructive properties. Therefore the defense must be 
stable in the antinuclear sense, i.e., possess the capability of 
withstanding nuclear weapon strikes and preserve the necessary 
number of forces and assets for repelling enemy assaults. This 
problem is solved in subunits basically by dispersal of elements 
of the battle formation, skilled use of terrain and its engineer 
preparation. 
  In the course of an attack the enemy also will employ tanks 
en masse for penetrating the defense. Great Patriotic War 
experience also attests to this. 
  Based on experience of the past war and local wars, the 
fight 
against tanks and other armored vehicles in the defense today 
acquires priority importance. Therefore it also has to be an 
antitank defense, capable of withstanding massed tank assaults 
and destroying them both ahead of the FEBA as well as in the 
depth of the subunits' defense. This is achieved by skillful use 
of the terrain's protective properties and its engineer 
preparation, skilled alignment of the defense, skillful 
organization of fire, especially of AT weapons, and creation of 
a system of obstacles in combination with natural barriers. 
  The defense can be positional or mobile 
depending on the mission received, combat capabilities of 
subunits and units, nature of terrain and extent of its engineer 
preparation, and the selected method of conducting battle. 
  The positional defense is the basic kind of 
defense. It most fully meets the principal objective of the 
defense and is conducted by inflicting maximum losses on the 
enemy ahead of the FEBA and in its depth. A positional defense 
is based on holding a number of defensive positions established 
by subunits within limits of occupied areas for a certain time, 
making maximum use of subunits' fire capabilities, and fullest 
possible engineer preparation of terrain. 
  The basic method of conducting a positional defense is to 
destroy the enemy by fire of all weapons as he approaches the 
FEBA and stubbornly hold tactically favorable terrain areas 
prepared for defense. A positional defense is used on the 
majority of axes, above all where loss of territory is 
impermissible. 
  The mobile defense is conducted to inflict losses 
on the enemy, gain time and preserve friendly forces by 
successive defensive battles at preplanned lines echeloned in 
depth in combination with brief counterattacks, wide use of fire 
ambushes, and organization of obstacles and the demolition of 
important installations. 
  It should be noted that as a rule a battalion conducts a 
positional defense. In individual cases it may participate in a 
mobile defense or may conduct it independently when assigned to 
defend a security zone. 
  The mobile defense allows abandoning certain areas of the 
territory and can be used for repelling an enemy invasion and 
when conducting battle in a security zone. 
  At each line the battalion occupies a defense area in which 
separate company and platoon strongpoints are established 
intercepting the most likely axes of enemy advance and helping 
to hold favorable terrain sectors. In the course of such a 
defense the battalion forces the enemy to advance in a direction 
in which a stable positional defense is prepared, or the enemy 
is drawn into an area providing favorable conditions for routing 
him by counterattacks. 
  As a rule a company (battalion) defends as part of the 
battalion (regiment) in coordination with adjacent subunits and 
with support of the senior commander's assets. A company 
(battalion) may occupy any place in the battalion (regimental) 
battle formation and perform various missions in the course of 
battle. 
  Based on this, a company (battalion) may be in the first or 
second echelon. When defending in the first echelon, depending 
on the mission received, a company (battalion) may defend on one 
of the flanks or in the center of the battle formation on the 
axis of concentration of battalion (regimental) main efforts. 
  In addition, a battalion (company) may make up a combined 
arms reserve or be in an antilanding reserve. A battalion 
(company) may receive a mission to operate in a security zone or 
at a forward position. During disengagement and withdrawal a 
battalion may be assigned to a rear guard and a company may be 
assigned to a rear (flank) security element or for operations as 
a covering- force subunit. 
  The company (battalion) role in the defense will depend on 
the place it occupies in the battle formation of the 
battalion (regiment) and the mission the company (battalion) is 
performing. The role of subunits will change constantly in the 
course of a defensive battle. Thus, in repelling an enemy 
assault ahead of the FEBA, a company (battalion) defending in 
the first echelon on the axis of concentration of battalion 
(regimental) main efforts will play the principal role in 
performing missions of the defense, since it will have to repel 
the assault of superior enemy forces, inflict significant losses 
on the enemy and hold the occupied area. 
  At the same time, a second echelon company (battalion) 
disposed in the depth of the defense is in readiness to perform 
assigned missions. Its role in this period primarily will be 
secondary. The company (battalion) begins to perform the primary 
role in case the enemy penetrates into the depth of the defense, 
since stability of defense not only of the battalion, but also 
of the regiment, depends on successful operations. 
  The content of missions to be performed and makeup of means 
of reinforcement are determined for a subunit depending on its 
role and place in the defense. 
  Thus, a mortar (artillery) battery, TP, AT subunit, grenade 
launcher subunit and combat engineer subunit may be attached to 
an MRC defending in the first echelon; an artillery battery, 
motorized rifle subunit and combat engineer subunit may be 
attached to a TC. 
  An artillery battery (an artillery battalion on the axis of 
concentration of main efforts) may be attached to the MRB (TB). 
In addition, a battalion may receive a TC (MRC), combat engineer 
platoon, AT subunit and air defense subunit as reinforcement. 
  In addition, a company (battalion) may be supported by an 
artillery battalion (battery) in the course of a defensive 
battle. 
  A first echelon company of the battalion defends a 
strongpoint in the first and second trenches with the mission of 
inflicting damage on the enemy by fire of all weapons and not 
permitting his penetration of the FEBA. 
  A first echelon battalion defends an area with the 
mission of repelling an enemy attack, destroying him ahead of 
the FEBA and when he has penetrated the defense at the first 
position, and also holding an important terrain area and 
creating favorable conditions for routing the enemy. 
  The tank battalion of an MRR as a rule is used for 
reinforcing the MRB's, and some of its forces are used in the 
combined arms reserve. It also may be in the second echelon. 
  The MRB of a TR as a rule is used for reinforcing the TB's. 
It also may operate independently, occupying a defense at the 
first position or in the security zone (at a forward position). 
  A second echelon company of the battalion has the 
mission of halting and under favorable conditions also 
destroying by counterattack enemy subunits which have penetrated 
the first and second trenches. A TC (BMP- equipped MRC) in 
addition may perform the mission of destroying enemy tanks by 
fire from lines of firing positions. 
  A second echelon battalion of the regiment 
occupies a defense at the second position, as a rule on an 
important axis. Its mission is to hold the occupied area firmly, 
reinforce (replace) first echelon subunits in case they lose 
combat effectiveness, execute counterattacks, and also destroy 
enemy airborne assault forces and airmobile subunits. A TB and 
BMP-equipped MRB in addition perform missions of repelling enemy 
tank assaults from lines of firing positions (by fire from in 
place). 
  A battalion making up the combined arms reserve 
occupies the indicated concentration area (defense area) and is 
in readiness to perform opportunity missions or to reinforce 
(replace) first echelon subunits in case they lose combat 
effectiveness. 
  A battalion assigned for defense in a security 
zone, operating as a forward detachment, has the mission of 
misleading the enemy regarding alignment of the first position, 
delaying the advance of his superior forces, forcing them to 
deploy prematurely and advance in a direction unfavorable for 
him, inflicting losses on him and winning time for preparing the 
defense. 
  A company (battalion) may defend at a forward position in 
case a security zone is not established. Such a position is 
established 4-6 km from the FEBA by decision of the senior 
commander to mislead the enemy regarding the trace of the 
forward edge and the defense alignment, prevent an enemy 
surprise attack on first echelon subunits, repel his 
reconnaissance in force and force him to deploy his main body 
prematurely. 
<H5>  2. Defense Alignment </H5>
  The company and battalion defense alignment (Diagram 2) 
includes the battle formation, system of strongpoints and firing 
positions, system of fire and system of engineer obstacles. All 
these elements represent a single whole and are mutually 
dependent. 
  In each specific case the defense alignment should conform 
to 
the commander's concept and take into account the nature of 
terrain and enemy operations. It should mislead the enemy 
regarding the trace and alignment of positions, battle formation 
and disposition of weapons, hamper his selection of targets of 
fire strikes, and thereby force him to deliver strikes against 
dummy, weakly occupied or unoccupied sectors. 
  The defense alignment as a whole should support growing 
opposition permitting prevention of enemy penetration of the 
defense area (strongpoint) and create conditions for his 
destruction. 
  The battle formation is the alignment of subunits 
for battle. it should correspond to the mission and concept of 
upcoming battle and ensure the following: defense stability and 
activeness; successful conduct of defensive battle both using 
only conventional weapons as well as using nuclear and other 
weapons; fullest use of subunits' combat capabilities for 
engaging the enemy during forward movement, deployment, and when 
launching an assault (or in the attack position [iskhodnoye 
polozheniye dlya nastupleniya]), when repelling an assault by 
his tanks and infantry ahead of the FEBA and destroying them 
during penetration of the defense area (strongpoint); least 
vulnerability of subunits to strikes by all kinds of weapons; 
maneuver of fire and subunits in the course of battle; maximum 
use of favorable and concealing properties of terrain; 
possibility of repelling enemy air strikes and destroying his 
airmobile and raiding and reconnaissance parties; and 
maintenance of continuous coordination and C[.sup]2[/] of 
subunits. 
  The company (battalion) battle formation basically depends 
on 
its mission, importance of the defended axis, strength level of 
subunits, makeup of attached assets, size of the strongpoint 
(defense area), expected force and axes of enemy assaults, and 
nature of terrain. 
  The battle formation of the MRC (TC) is formed in one or two 
echelons (Diagram 3). 
  The company first echelon consists of MRP's (TP's) 
with means of reinforcement. It is intended for inflicting 
maximum damage on the enemy by fire of all weapons ahead of the 
FEBA and tenaciously holding important terrain sectors 
(objectives) on the FEBA. With a single echelon alignment of the 
company battle formation, it includes all MRP's (TP's) with 
means of reinforcement, and with its two-echelon alignment two 
platoons are assigned to the first echelon and one to the second. 
  The company second echelon is intended chiefly for 
firmly holding a strongpoint in the depth of the defense (in the 
second trench) and destroying an enemy who has penetrated. 
  Depending on the nature of terrain, platoons in a company 
strongpoint may be disposed in a reverse wedge or have an 
echelon or other disposition which provides best organization of 
the system of fire ahead of the front and on the strongpoint 
flanks. First echelon platoons are disposed at the first trench 
and the second echelon platoon at the second trench. 
  A battalion battle formation may be formed in two echelons 
or 
one echelon (Diagram 4). It consists of first echelon subunits, 
a second echelon or reserve, and weapons and subunits of 
reinforcement remaining directly subordinate to the battalion 
commander. In a single-echelon alignment of the battle formation 
a reserve is assigned made up of at least a platoon. Such an 
alignment usually is used with a shortage of forces and assets, 
on terrain difficult of access for enemy operations, in a 
defense in the second echelon or on another axis, and during 
battle in the security zone. 
  A battalion may have a varying disposition of companies 
depending on the mission to be performed and nature of terrain. 
One company may be moved forward or backward, forming a fire 
sack, and on open terrain be disposed in an echelon [left or 
right]. In all cases company strongpoints should be disposed so 
they intercept probable enemy axes of advance. 
  The first echelon of an MRB (TB) consists of MRC's 
(TC's) reinforced by tank (motorized rifle) subunits, ATGM's and 
combat engineer subunits. It is intended for destroying the 
enemy ahead of the FEBA and when he penetrates into its depth, 
firmly holding important terrain sectors and preventing a 
breakthrough of the occupied defense area. 
  With a single-echelon alignment of the battle formation, the 
first echelon may include all MRC's with their means of 
reinforcement, and with a two-echelon alignment it may include 
two companies. First echelon companies defend strongpoints at 
the first and second trenches. 
  The battalion second echelon is intended for 
defending a strongpoint in the depth of the defense with the 
mission of halting and under favorable conditions also 
destroying by counterattack an enemy who has penetrated the 
first and second trenches. A company usually is assigned to the 
second echelon; it defends a strongpoint at the third and 
sometimes also the fourth trench. 
  The battalion reserve (at least a platoon) 
occupies a concentration area in which it prepares a strongpoint 
for defense and is in readiness to perform opportunity missions. 
  The mortar (artillery) battery and grenade launcher subunit 
usually remain subordinate to the battalion commander and as a 
rule are employed at full strength for supporting the battle of 
first echelon MRC's. Sometimes the GLP is attached to first 
echelon companies by squads or attached at full strength to an 
MRC defending on the axis of concentration of battalion main 
efforts. 
  The AT subunit of the battalion (a platoon) usually remains 
subordinate to the battalion commander, occupies a concentration 
area and as a rule is used at full strength on a likely avenue 
of tank approach to repel assaults by enemy tanks and other 
armored vehicles, cover an exposed flank and support a 
counterattack. On terrain affording concealment and on rugged 
terrain it may be attached to first echelon companies. The AT 
subunit performs its missions from firing positions or from 
lines, the number of which is determined by the battalion 
commander. 
  As a rule, air defense subunits remain directly subordinate 
to the battalion commander and are disposed in company 
strongpoints and in the vicinity of the battalion COP so as to 
provide reliable cover of subunits against air strikes. 
  An armored group and fire ambushes may be part of the 
company 
(battalion) battle formation depending on the situation. 
  The company (battalion) armored group is established to 
increase activeness of the defense, promptly reinforce its 
stability on the most threatened axes, and close breaches which 
have formed as a result of enemy fire strikes. In addition, it 
is established to perform other missions as well which require 
swift, mobile operations and effective fire damage of the enemy 
and also to make more complete use of combat capabilities of 
tanks, BMP's and BTR's. The armored group makeup may include 
several tanks, BMP's or BTR's (usually without a mounted force) 
assigned from first and second echelon subunits defending 
outside of axes of concentration of main efforts. 
  With occupation of a defense by the company (battalion), 
tanks and BMP's (BTR's) intended for operating as part of an 
armored group usually are disposed and make ready for battle in 
their own platoon strongpoints. Then at the prescribed time they 
concentrate in an area with reliable protective and concealing 
features of terrain (in ravines, on reverse hillslopes, in the 
forest and in other sheltered places), carefully conceal 
themselves and prepare to perform missions assigned to the 
armored group or to occupy a defense in their own platoon 
strongpoints. 
  One of the deputy platoon commanders may be appointed 
commander of a company armored group and one of the platoon 
commanders of a second echelon company may be appointed 
commander of a battalion armored group. 
  A fire ambush is organized to inflict maximum damage on the 
enemy by direct fire commenced suddenly, by surprise close-range 
concentrated fire, and by use of minefields. 
  A platoon (squad, tank) reinforced by flamethrower operators 
and combat engineers may be assigned to a fire ambush. 
  A system of strongpoints and firing positions is 
established for performing defense missions in a company 
(battalion) in accordance with the commander's decision, combat 
capabilities of subunits, time available and nature of terrain. 
It includes the following: combat security outpost position (in 
the battalion); strongpoints of platoons and companies 
consolidated into a battalion defense area; firing positions of 
tanks, BMP's (BTR's), ATGM systems and other organic and 
attached weapons; trenches and communication trenches. 
  The combat security outpost position is established to 
prevent an enemy surprise attack and his conduct of ground 
reconnaissance. A reinforced platoon usually is sent out as a 
combat security outpost from a first echelon battalion to a 
distance up to 2 km. The platoon is assigned a position up to 
500 m in frontage which is prepared for a perimeter defense. 
Obstacles are arranged ahead of the platoon position and on the 
flanks. 
  A combat security outpost is not sent out when in direct 
contact with the enemy. In this case its missions are assigned 
to subunits occupying the first trench. 
  Battalion defense areas, which unite company strongpoints, 
are the basis of each defensive position. 
  A company strongpoint (battalion defense area) is a terrain 
sector (area) of specific size with engineer preparation in 
accordance with the commander's decision, adapted for a 
perimeter defense and occupied by a subunit. 
  A company defends a strongpoint 1-1.5 km in frontage and up 
to 1,000 m deep. An MRC strongpoint is prepared as two trenches 
or one trench and consists of strongpoints of MRP's and 
positions of weapons of the company and attached subunits 
interconnected by a unified system of fire, obstacles and 
communication trenches within limits of the company strongpoint. 
A TC strongpoint consists of the strongpoints of TP's and 
positions of attached subunits. 
  Tanks attached to an MRC occupy a defense in its strongpoint 
and reinforce its capabilities to combat enemy armored targets, 
and motorized rifle subunits attached to a TC usually occupy 
positions ahead of the tanks and also in gaps between TP's and 
on flanks. 
  Communication trenches must be used widely for a perimeter 
defense of a company strongpoint, platoons must be assigned 
secondary sectors of fire, and alternate firing positions are 
prepared for weapons with consideration for conducting fire 
toward flanks and to the rear. Some weapons should be disposed 
in the depth of the defense. Obstacles are arranged on flanks, 
in gaps between platoons and in the rear of the strongpoint. 
  Gaps between company strongpoints may reach 1,000 m and must 
not fail to be under continuous observation; covered by 
flanking, oblique and cross fire of all weapons, especially AT 
weapons; and also covered by fire ambushes, artillery fire and 
obstacles. Trenches and alternate positions are prepared in gaps 
between platoon (company) strongpoints. 
  A battalion defends an area 3-5 km in frontage and 2-2.5 km 
in depth. It builds the defense within one position and prepares 
3-4 trenches. A battalion defense area consists of company 
strongpoints and the positions of organic and attached weapons 
interconnected by a unified system of fire, obstacles and 
communication trenches. 
  The width and depth of a battalion defense area and the 
distance between trenches, subunits and weapons are not constant 
values. In each specific case they must ensure repulse of enemy 
tank and mechanized infantry assaults ahead of the FEBA and 
their destruction when wedged into the defense; convenience of 
situating elements of the battle formation; dispersal of 
subunits for least vulnerability to enemy nuclear strikes, 
artillery fire and precision weapons; and an opportunity to 
execute a maneuver of fire and subunits. For example, the 
battalion defense frontage may be greater on terrain that is not 
accessible everywhere for operations of attacking troops and 
also when defending in a security zone. 
  Company strongpoints are disposed in a battalion area so 
they 
intercept the most likely axes of enemy attack by their 
disposition and fire, preclude stereotype in aligning the 
defense, and ensure stability of defending subunits. 
  Firing positions are prepared within the subunit battle 
formation to perform fire missions and improve survivability of 
weapons. A firing position is a place with or without engineer 
preparation occupied or intended for occupation by a tank, BMP 
(BTR) or other weapons. Skillful selection of firing positions 
is an important condition for successful performance of assigned 
missions. 
  Firing positions must be selected so they provide a good all 
around view of terrain and the conduct of fire in primary and 
secondary sectors of fire, possibility of firing to maximum 
range in given directions, engagement of the enemy by 
concentrated fire, reliable maskirovka and shelter of weapons 
against various enemy weapons, a concealed passage from the 
primary to an alternate position, a convenient move into a 
counterattack or a withdrawal, and an opportunity for mutual 
fire support and conduct of fire into gaps, from behind flanks 
and over the heads of friendly subunits. 
  Firing positions are subdivided according to 
purpose into primary, temporary, alternate and dummy. 
  Primary firing positions are intended for 
performing assigned missions in the course of battle. They are 
prepared for BMP's (BTR's), tanks, ATGM launchers, machineguns, 
grenade launchers and other weapons. 
  Temporary firing positions are prepared for duty 
weapons, BMP's (BTR's) and tanks and are intended for performing 
individual missions and misleading the enemy regarding the true 
alignment of the system of fire. Fire is conducted from these 
positions to destroy an enemy attempting to perform 
reconnaissance, breach obstacles or penetrate into the depth of 
the defense. After performing assigned missions, weapons occupy 
primary firing positions by direction of the company (battalion) 
commander. 
  Alternate firing positions are intended for 
executing a maneuver in the course of a defensive battle, and 
also in case it is impossible to perform the assigned mission 
from the primary position. It is advisable to designate one or 
two alternate positions for each kind of weapon. The transfer to 
and occupation of alternate positions is done only by order of 
the commander. 
  Dummy firing positions are established to mislead 
the enemy regarding the true position of weapons. For fighting 
vehicles these positions (emplacements) usually are prepared 
10-15 m from the primary firing position with simulation of the 
main revealing signs. 
  Depending on the degree of cover against ground observation, 
firing positions may be direct fire or indirect fire positions. 
Tanks, BMP's (BTR's), AT weapons and machineguns occupy and 
conduct fire from direct fire positions. 
  Firing positions should be established in such a way as to 
ensure dispersed placement that is not in a straight line. 
  Trenches and communication trenches should provide 
convenience in conducting fire, especially flanking, oblique and 
cross fire, sheltered disposition of subunits and weapons, and 
their swift, concealed maneuver laterally and into the depth, 
and also hamper the enemy in discovering the battle formation 
and system of fire. 
  The first trench of the first position is the 
forward edge, which is designated by the senior commander. 
Antitank and antipersonnel obstacles are established ahead of 
the first trench. It is selected where possible behind natural 
antitank barriers and should provide good observation of the 
enemy and best conditions for creating continuous fire of all 
kinds ahead of the FEBA, on flanks, in gaps and from the depth 
of the defense. Terrain ahead of the FEBA should hamper enemy 
observation and his choice of sheltered areas for concentrating 
tanks and infantry and concealed approaches to the FEBA. 
  The second trench is prepared 300-600 m from the 
first so its defending subunits could destroy an enemy on 
approaches to the FEBA by their fire, cover obstacles in front 
of the FEBA and support subunits located in the first trench. 
  The third (fourth) trench is prepared 600-1,000 m 
from the second (third) trench. It should allow its defending 
subunits to conduct fire in the belt between the second and 
third (fourth) trenches, and in some sectors also ahead of the 
FEBA, and use it to maneuver to threatened axes. 
  Communication trenches are used for fighting an enemy who 
has 
penetrated the defense, for concealed maneuver of subunits, and 
for evacuating wounded and delivering ammunition and food. At 
least one communication trench is dug for each platoon from the 
first to the second trench and at least one communication trench 
is prepared for each company from the second to the third 
(fourth) trench. This will permit organizing a perimeter defense 
in a short time if necessary. Trenches and communication 
trenches should be dug full profile and in some sectors 
strengthened by revetments to reduce losses from the effect of 
enemy nuclear weapons, artillery fire and air strikes. Covered 
sectors, dugouts [blindazh] and bunkers [ubezhishche] are made 
for personnel in trenches and communication trenches, and niches 
and small excavations are made for ammunition and other supplies. 
  Trenches and communication trenches are used for personnel 
movement to platoon, company and battalion assembly areas [rayon 
sbora] when disengaging and withdrawing. 
  Fire is the basic means of destroying the enemy in the 
defense. To perform this mission the company (battalion) has 
diverse weapons (assault rifles, machineguns, RPG's, BMP's 
(BTR's), tanks, ATGM's, automatic grenade launchers, mortars, 
air defense weapons) differing both in range and effectiveness 
as well as in type of targets engaged and degree of protection. 
To ensure the most effective fire, it must be organized in a 
unified system corresponding to the concept of upcoming battle. 
In addition, the defense is organized as a rule to fight an 
enemy considerably superior in forces. Consequently, the enemy's 
quantitative superiority in tanks and mechanized infantry must 
be countered by quality of fire, which is reflected in a 
specific system of the disposition and use of available weapons. 
  The system of fire should be understood to mean 
the disposition of weapons organized under a unified plan and 
the combination and distribution of their fire missions by 
targets, place and time with consideration of maximum use of 
their fire capabilities in accordance with the commander's 
decision for engaging the enemy on his approach to the FEBA, his 
deployment and his launching of an assault; and repelling an 
assault by enemy tanks and mechanized infantry ahead of the 
FEBA, on flanks, and with penetration of the strongpoint. 
  Considering the great importance of the system of fire in 
performing defense missions, the subunit commander builds it 
with consideration of fire capabilities of all kinds of weapons 
at his disposal and their close interworking in combination with 
engineer obstacles and natural barriers. 
  The system of fire must ensure creation of a zone of fire of 
AT weapons and continuous, multilayered fire of all kinds ahead 
of the FEBA, in gaps, on flanks and in the depth of the 
strongpoint (battalion defense area), and a rapid transfer, 
distribution and concentration of fire on any threatened axis or 
sector. 
  The company (battalion) system of fire includes the 
following: sectors of concentrated fire and defensive fire lines 
of artillery and mortars prepared on approaches to the defense, 
ahead of the FEBA, on flanks, in gaps between company 
strongpoints and in the depth of the defense; zones of fire of 
AT weapons and continuous, multilayered fire of all kinds of 
weapons ahead of the FEBA, in gaps, on flanks and in the depth 
of the defense above all for destroying enemy tanks and other 
armored vehicles; and a prepared maneuver of fire to concentrate 
it on any threatened axis or sector in a short time. The basis 
of the company system of fire is the fire of tanks and BMP's; 
the basis of the battalion system of fire is the AT fire of 
companies, organic and attached AT weapons and direct fire of 
artillery, with consideration for employing the regiment's AT 
reserve and mobile obstacle detachment on a likely avenue of 
tank approach. 
  Thorough organization of AT fire is a very important 
obligation of all subunit commanders. Weapons must be disposed 
covertly in the company strongpoint (battalion defense area) 
with consideration of terrain relief. Their disposition must 
ensure conduct of fire to maximum range and engagement of the 
enemy by flanking, cross and surprise close-range concentrated 
fire, they must have fire coordination with each other and they 
must create fire sacks. 
  To keep the enemy from uncovering the system of fire, 
weapons 
must be carefully camouflaged and a broad network of alternate, 
temporary and dummy positions and of roving tanks, guns and 
BMP's must be established. Linear disposition of weapons is 
impermissible. 
  To combat enemy tanks and other armored vehicles the 
battalion (company) commander specifies the zone of AT weapon 
fire. It represents a terrain sector ahead of the subunit 
forward edge, on flanks, in gaps between strongpoints and in the 
depth of the defense against which fire is prepared in advance 
and conducted from tanks, ATGM's, BMP's and other AT weapons. 
  In modern battle the enemy will attempt to take advantage of 
the gun fire of tanks and BMP's (BTR's) at maximum grazing range 
during an assault and, if the vehicles have launchers for firing 
ATGM's, to destroy the defenders' armored weapons. Based on 
this, the above enemy weapons should be expected to commence 
fire when they come to a line 2-3 km from the FEBA. 
  The depth of the AT fire zone should ensure engagement of 
enemy tanks and BMP's (BTR's) when they move into the impact 
zone of defenders' AT weapons. The far boundary is specified 
(established) depending on the range of effective fire of the 
weapon being used with consideration of terrain conditions ahead 
of the FEBA, on flanks and in the depth of the defense. The 
range of effective fire of a weapon (subunit) is the range at 
which a target is killed with a single round (volley) with a 
probability of 0.5. For example, it is 2-2.5 km for modern tanks. 
  A zone of continuous, multilayered fire of all kinds of 
weapons is created to repel enemy massed tank and infantry 
assaults. It represents a terrain sector (area) in which each 
terrain point is under effective fire. Within this zone small 
arms fire is reinforced by fire of machineguns mounted on BMP's 
(BTR's), and fire of AT weapons is reinforced by RPG's. 
  In each specific instance the depth of the zone of 
continuous, multilayered fire is determined by the nature of 
terrain and range of effective fire of weapons involved and may 
be up to 400 m. 
  Establishing zones of fire gives a defense a monolithic 
nature with respect to fire. Lines for commencing fire from 
various weapons are designated in these zones for organized 
engagement of the enemy. When the enemy moves to these lines 
fire is commenced by ATGM launchers, tanks, BMP's (BTR's) and 
small arms. 
  Special attention in organizing a system of fire should be 
given to creating fire sacks. A fire sack is a terrain sector 
ahead of the FEBA or in the depth of the defense against which 
high density fire of all or the bulk of subunit weapons is 
prepared from flanks and from the front to inflict maximum 
damage (loss) on the enemy in a short time. It is created by 
skillfully disposing platoon (company) strongpoints and weapons 
with consideration of terrain conditions so the terrain within 
its limits is covered by cross, flanking and frontal fire of all 
weapons. Fire sacks may be created by a maneuver of fire, 
weapons and subunits in the course of a defensive battle. 
  Minefields are laid and artillery, mortar and concentrated 
small arms fire is prepared within the fire sack. 
  The size of a fire sack can be 900-1,000 m in frontage and 
up 
to 1,000 m in depth when created ahead of the FEBA, and 500-800 
m in frontage and up to 1,000 m in depth when created in the 
depth of the defense area (strongpoint). 
  Concentrated and defensive fire of artillery (mortars) and 
concentrated fire of tanks, BMP's and small arms is prepared for 
engaging the enemy on possible forward movement routes, 
deployment lines, and axes of his attack and penetration. 
  Concentrated fire is conducted against a precisely detected 
target or group of targets by several tanks, BMP's (BTR's), 
machineguns, assault rifles and other weapons as well as by one 
or more of the company subunits. In some cases prepared 
concentrated fire may be conducted for neutralization, 
annihilation or prevention of enemy advance. Neutralizing a 
target consists of inflicting such damages (losses) on it which 
temporarily deprive it of combat effectiveness, restrict its 
maneuver or disrupt C[.sup]2[/]. 
  Annihilation of a target consists of inflicting such damage 
(losses) on it that it completely loses combat effectiveness. 
  Concentrated fire is conducted at the following ranges: 
2,000 
m from the KPVT [14.5 mm Vladimirov heavy machinegun], 1,000 m 
from the PKT [Kalashnikov tank machinegun], and 800 m from 
machineguns and assault rifles. When concentrated fire is 
conducted by subunits, this range increases and is 2.5 km for a 
BMP- equipped MRP, 3.5 km for a TP, 4 km for a BMP-equipped MRC 
and 5 km for a TC. 
  Fire concentration sectors usually are designated against 
road junctions, crossings, defiles, forest openings and other 
terrain sectors constraining enemy actions or compacting his 
battle formation. 
  The size of fire concentration sectors in frontage and depth 
are determined by subunit fire capabilities. It should 
correspond in width to the size of the fragmentation effect zone 
of a shell and be 40 m per gun for tanks and 25 m for BMP's. The 
width of fire concentration sectors should correspond to the 
amount of shell dispersion and be 100 m for tank guns and 50 m 
for BMP's. Based on this, fire concentration sectors can be 120 
m in frontage and 100 m in depth for the TP and up to 75 m in 
frontage and up to 50 m in depth for the BMP platoon. The width 
of a fire concentration sector when firing small arms is 
designated with consideration of ensuring a fire density of 
10-12 bullets per meter of frontage and depends on the number of 
weapons in subunits and involved in the battle. With subunits at 
authorized strength, the fire concentration sector can be up to 
150 m for a platoon and up to 300 m for a company. 
  Firing data are prepared with the help of the longitudinal 
level and traverse indicator to support conduct of tank and BMP 
fire against a fire concentration sector at night or under 
conditions of poor visibility. 
  The method of conducting concentrated BMP and tank fire can 
vary: systematic fire, rapid fire and salvos. In conducting 
systematic fire, the firing BMP's (tanks) fire rounds in a 
certain sequence at set time intervals. Such fire is used during 
registration and to ensure observation of results of fire when 
shifting to fire for effect. 
  Rapid fire is conducted when BMP's (tanks) are ready for the 
next round, and at the maximum rate. It is used during fire for 
effect. 
  In conducting salvo fire, all firing BMP's (tanks) fire 
rounds simultaneously at the subunit commander's command. 
  Frontal fire, flanking fire, cross fire and surprise, close 
range concentrated [kinzhalnyy] fire is prepared to 
increase the effectiveness of engaging the enemy. 
  Frontal fire is fire directed perpendicular to 
target frontage; it is more effective in engaging deep targets. 
  Fire conducted against the enemy (target) flank is called 
flanking fire and is most suitable in firing on 
targets operating across a wide front. Cross fire is 
fire conducted against a target from two or more directions. 
Fire commenced suddenly from close range in one direction is 
called surprise close-range concentrated fire. It is 
prepared at distances not exceeding grazing range for 
head-shoulders chest figure targets and is conducted from 
carefully camouflaged positions at maximum intensity until total 
annihilation of the enemy or interdiction of his attempts to 
advance in a given direction. 
  The company (battalion) commander organizes the system of 
fire when assigning missions and organizing coordination. Zones 
(sectors) of fire, secondary sectors of fire and fire 
concentration sectors are assigned to subunits (weapons). 
  A subunit zone of fire should be at least the width of the 
strongpoint (defense area) in frontage and is indicated on the 
terrain (map, diagram) by four reference points: first on the 
right, then on the left into the depth. The depth of the zone of 
fire is determined by the range of effective fire of subunit 
weapons. To cover boundaries and gaps between subunits by fire, 
the zones of fire of adjacent subunits must overlap at distances 
of 400-500 m from the FEBA. 
  Sectors of fire are indicated for BMP's (BTR's), tanks, 
machineguns and other weapons. Fire of RPG's is prepared in the 
zones of their own squads. 
  Readiness of the system of fire is determined by occupation 
of positions by weapons, preparation of firing data, and 
availability of missiles and ammunition. 
  An important element of the defense alignment is the system 
of engineer obstacles being created by decision of the commander 
to the full depth of defense to inflict damage (losses) on an 
enemy, delay his advance, hamper (constrain) maneuver or force 
him to advance in a direction favorable for the defenders and 
thereby contribute to his destruction by fire and counterattacks. 
  The system of engineer obstacles includes 
minefields, mine clusters, integrated obstacle complexes, 
abatis, other antitank and antipersonnel barriers, and 
installations prepared for demolition (mining) created ahead of 
the combat security outpost position, ahead of the FEBA, in gaps 
and on flanks of the battalion (company) to the full depth of 
the battalion defense area. It is created in accordance with the 
commander's concept in combination with the system of fire with 
consideration of natural barriers and the maneuver of subunits 
(your own and adjacent ones). 
  Minefields emplaced by combat engineer subunits are the 
basis 
of the obstacle system. The procedure for demolishing 
installations in the depth of the defense is determined by the 
senior commander. 
<H5>  3. Preparation of the Defense </H5>
  Preparation of the defense represents an entire set of 
measures taken by the company (battalion) commander for 
successful performance of assigned missions. It begins with 
receipt of the combat mission from the senior commander and 
includes the following: organization for battle (decisionmaking, 
assignment of combat missions to subunits, ground 
reconnaissance, organization of coordination and a system of 
fire, comprehensive support to battle and C[.sup]2[/]); 
development of a diagram of the company strongpoint (battalion 
defense area); preparation of the company (battalion) for 
performing the combat mission; occupation of the defense; 
creation of the battle formation and system of fire; engineer 
preparation of the strongpoint (defense area); organization and 
conduct of political work; practical work of the company 
(battalion) commander, his deputies and staff in subordinate 
subunits; and other measures. 
  The duration and procedure of the commander's work of 
organizing the defense depend on conditions for 
shifting to the defense, mission received, how far away the 
enemy is and the nature of his operations, nature of terrain and 
time available. With time available, the defense is organized 
with measures carried out to the full extent; if time is 
lacking, then it is done in a short time with measures carried 
out to an abbreviated extent. In all cases it should not delay 
subunits in taking up a defense and creating a system of fire. 
  When shifting to the defense out of contact with the 
enemy the commander usually arranges his work in the 
following order: analyzes the mission; determines measures which 
must be carried out immediately for most rapid preparation of 
subunits to perform the assigned mission; makes or approves a 
time calculation; gives instructions to commanders of 
subordinate and attached subunits for preparing to perform the 
combat mission and on the time and procedure of work on the 
terrain; estimates the situation; makes the decision and briefs 
it to the senior commander; communicates the decision to his 
deputies and subunit commanders; performs ground reconnaissance, 
during which he updates his decision; issues the operation 
order; and organizes coordination, a system of fire, 
comprehensive support of battle and C[.sup]2[/]. 
  Then he moves the company (battalion) to the indicated 
strongpoint (defense area), organizes its engineer preparation 
and performs practical work of preparing subunits for defense. 
At the prescribed time he reports readiness to perform the 
combat mission to the battalion (regimental) commander. 
  On receiving a combat mission for shifting to the defense 
in direct contact with the enemy, the company 
(battalion) commander arranges his work in the following order: 
analyzes the mission received; determines measures which must be 
taken immediately for a most rapid shift to the defense; makes a 
time calculation; and organizes the capture and consolidation of 
the indicated (favorable) line. In the course of consolidating 
the line he estimates the situation, makes the decision, assigns 
missions to organic and attached subunits (by radio or 
personally), organizes coordination, the system of fire, 
C[.sup]2[/], and protection against enemy mass destruction 
and precision weapons, issues instructions on basic questions of 
comprehensive support to battle, and organizes engineer 
preparation of the strongpoint (defense area). 
  Then the commander performs ground reconnaissance, during 
which he updates missions for subunits, the coordination 
procedure, and if necessary also other matters. 
  In all cases company (battalion) subunits must be ready to 
repel an enemy attack and air strikes, to destroy an airborne 
assault force and subunits of airmobile troops, and for 
protection against precision weapons. 
<H5>  4. Company Commander's Work of Organizing the Defense Out of </H5>
Contact With the Enemy 
<H5>  (Variant) </H5>
  Tactical situation (Fig. 4) 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-44A>      Fig. 4. 5th MRC commander's decision for defense </FIG>


  The 2nd MRB, alerted on 15 June and having made a 100 km 
night march, concentrated in Gustoy Forest 3 km east of Ivanovka 
(not on diagram) by 0400 hours 16 June, where it is preparing 
weapons and vehicles for battle. (Not all local features cited 
in the text are shown on the diagram due to its small scale.) 
  As 0515 on 16 June the 5th MRC commander received a combat 
mission, from which he learned the following: 
  1. The enemy is concentrating his main body in assembly 
areas 
for an attack [rayon dlya nastupleniya]. His attack should be 
expected to be launched on the morning of 18 June, and with 
consideration of battle in the security zone his arrival at the 
FEBA is possible as follows: forward subunits by 1330-1400 and 
main body by 1500-1600 18 June. 
  2. 2nd MRB with 1st TC shifts to defense of area Hill 134.2 
(not on diagram), Ploskaya Hill, Okunevo (not on diagram) with 
mission of preventing penetration of enemy tanks and infantry in 
direction of Grusha Hill, Hill 129.0. Battle formation is in two 
echelons: 4th and 5th MRC in the first and 6th MRC in the second. 
  It is planned to have three trenches in the defense area: 
first--west slopes of Hill 137.0, lone house, ruins, rocks; 
second--quarry (not on diagram), Hill 129.0, west slopes of 
Dlinnaya Hill, Karevo; third--Hill 122.3 (not on diagram), Hill 
112.0, Hill 109.2 (not on diagram). 
  Subunits of 1/3 MRR are defending in the security zone. 
  3. 4th MRC of adjacent regiment is shifting to the defense 
on 
right with mission of preventing enemy penetration in direction 
of Grusha Hill, Kuskovo (not on diagram). 
  1st MRC, 1st MRB is shifting to the defense on left with 
mission of preventing enemy penetration in direction of Hill 
110.0, Sapozhnikovo (not on diagram). 
  The regimental artillery battalion is preparing concentrated 
and barrier fires on possible deployment lines and on axes of 
assault against sectors 201, 202, 203; standing barriers Bereza 
[Birch], Sosna [Pine], Klen [Maple]; and rolling barrier Tigr 
[Tiger]. 
  4. 5th MRC with 2nd TP, 1st TC and a grenade launcher squad 
is shifting to defense of the strongpoint Hill 136.8, Ploskaya 
Hill, Kedrovka with mission of preventing penetration of enemy 
tanks and infantry in direction of Hill 80.1, Kedrovka. Zone of 
fire: on right--lone house, north edge of Kruglaya Grove; on 
left--rocks, Hill 74.5. Secondary sector of fire--to right in 
direction of ruins. Company fire concentration sectors: 
SO-1--rocks, bushes; SO-2--lone tree, curve in road. 1st Battery 
is supporting. 
  5. Ammunition expenditure for mission accomplishment: 0.4 
unit of fire for small arms and 0.6 unit of fire for tanks and 
BMP's. 
  Occupy defense by 1030 16 June. Readiness of the system of 
fire 1120 hours 16 June, readiness of engineer obstacles and 
first-order engineer work by 1030 17 June. 
  7. Battalion COP on Hill 119.2 as of 1030 16 June, company 
COP on north slopes of Dlinnaya Hill as of 1035 16 June. 
  Company is 95 percent strength in personnel, weapons and 
vehicles. 
  [Begin side line] On receiving the combat mission the 
company 
commander analyzes it and makes a time calculation. 
  The mission analysis has the purpose of ensuring 
decisionmaking for shifting to the defense in accordance with 
the battalion (regimental) commander's concept. In analyzing the 
mission he has received, the company (battalion) commander must 
understand the goal of the defensive battle, the senior 
commander's concept, and above all the direction for 
concentrating main efforts; the holding of which terrain sectors 
supports stability of the company (battalion) defense; procedure 
for engaging the enemy by fire of organic and attached weapons 
during his forward movement, his assault on the FEBA and his 
destruction in the depth of the defense; and objectives 
(targets) to be engaged by senior commanders' weapons in support 
of the company (battalion). In analyzing the mission the 
commander also has to understand the combat mission, place of 
the company (battalion) in the battalion (regimental) battle 
formation and its role in the upcoming battle, missions of 
adjacent subunits and procedure for coordinating with them, and 
readiness time to perform the mission; and also analyze the time 
for occupying the defense, readiness time of the system of fire, 
and the sequence and time periods of engineer preparation of the 
strongpoint (defense area). 
  In conclusions from the mission analysis, the company 
(battalion) commander usually determines the following: on which 
axis and on holding which sector he must concentrate main 
efforts and for what actions he must be ready; how to align the 
battle formation; how much time is available for organizing the 
defense and what must be done to maintain coordination with 
adjacent subunits. [End side line] 
  Mission analysis 
  2nd MRB is shifting to defense of the area Hill 134.2, 
Ploskaya Hill, Okunevo (1.5 km east of Ivanovo) with the mission 
of preventing penetration of enemy tanks and infantry in 
direction of Grusha Hill, Hill 129.0. 
  Battalion is concentrating main efforts on holding area Hill 
137.0, Ploskaya Hill, Osinovka (not on diagram). 
  Battalion battle formation in two echelons. 5th MRC with 2nd 
TP and grenade launcher squad shifts to defense in first echelon 
on battalion left flank on axis of concentration of main efforts 
with mission of preventing penetration of enemy tanks and 
infantry in direction of Hill 80.1, Kedrovka. 
  4th MRC on right shifts to defense of strongpoint Hill 134.2 
(not on diagram), Hill 137.0, bushes with mission of preventing 
penetration of enemy tanks and infantry in direction of Grusha 
Hill, Kuskovo (not on diagram). 
  1st MRC, 1st MRB on left shifts to defense of strongpoint 
Kamennaya Hill, cemetery, Karevo with mission of preventing 
enemy penetration in direction of Hill 110.0, Sapozhnikovo (not 
on diagram). 
  Occupy defense by 1030 hours 16 June. Readiness of the 
system 
of fire 1120 16 June. Readiness of first-order engineer work by 
1030 17 June. 
  Conclusions: 
  1. Based on 2nd MRB commander's concept, concentrate main 
efforts on axis Hill 80.1, Kedrovka and on firmly holding Hill 
136.8, Ploskaya Hill, Dlinnaya Hill. 
  2. Align battle formation in two echelons, have platoon 
strongpoints on Hill 136.8, Ploskaya Hill, Dlinnaya Hill. 
  [Begin side line] Having drawn conclusions from analyzing 
the 
mission received and having determined the measures which must 
be taken immediately for most rapid preparation of subunits to 
perform the combat mission, the company commander makes a time 
calculation. 
  The time of receiving the mission, time of occupying the 
defense, readiness time of the system of fire, and time of 
briefing the decision (commander's concept) to the battalion 
commander are initial data for the time calculation. 
  In calculating time, determine how many hours set aside for 
preparing for battle are in daylight. It is also necessary to 
determine how much time to set aside for issuing instructions on 
preparing subunits for battle, situation estimate, ground 
reconnaissance, assignment of combat missions, and organization 
of coordination. Having analyzed the mission received and 
performed the time calculation, the company commander begins the 
situation estimate. [End side line] 
  Company commander's time calculation for 
shifting to defense 
  Mission received at 0515 hours 16 June. Occupy defense by 
1030 16 June. Readiness of system of fire 1120 16 June. Total 
time for organizing defense 5 hours. 


