Report occupation of defense    1030 
to battalion commander 


  [Begin side line] In the situation estimate the 
company (battalion) commander clarifies the following: enemy 
makeup, situation, status, degree of protection, possible 
forward movement routes and deployment lines, strong and weak 
points and nature of his operations; makeup, situation, status, 
capabilities, degree of protection and state of supply of his 
own, attached and supporting subunits; makeup, situation, nature 
of terrain, and its effect on company (battalion) operations, 
and the most likely directions of enemy aircraft and helicopter 
operations at low and extremely low altitudes; and the NBC 
situation. 
  In addition, in the situation estimate the state of weather, 
time of year and day and their effect on preparing and 
conducting defensive battle are taken into account. 
  As a result of the situation estimate the company commander 
draws conclusions, based on which he subsequently makes his 
decision. 
  The enemy estimate in organizing the defense is 
made based on his operating tactics with consideration of the 
nature of terrain and other situation conditions. An enemy who 
may attack in the company (battalion) defense frontage, his 
probable axes of forward movement and deployment lines, methods 
and axes of assault, procedure for enemy buildup of efforts in 
the course of battle, and most likely directions of his aircraft 
and helicopter operations are estimated especially carefully. 
  The company (battalion) commander determines the following 
in 
conclusions from the enemy estimate: enemy makeup and 
capabilities, probable axis and time of launching an attack; 
axis where it is advisable to concentrate main efforts and 
terrain sector on whose holding the stability of company 
(battalion) defense will depend; and alignment of the battle 
formation with consideration of taking maximum advantage of the 
capabilities of one's weapons and the terrain. 
  An estimate of own subunits is necessary for 
taking measures which will permit preparing the company 
(battalion) for performing the assigned mission and correctly 
determining the place of subunits in the company (battalion) 
battle formation and their missions considering their state of 
supply and combat capabilities. 
  In studying the situation of his own, attached and 
supporting 
subunits the company (battalion) commander determines within 
what time periods it is possible to establish the battle 
formation and what maneuver must be executed to arrive at the 
designated strongpoint (defense area). 
  In estimating the status of his subunit, he clarifies the 
strength level of the company (battalion), degree of radioactive 
exposure, morale, mental state and combat experience of 
personnel, commanders' job qualities, and technical condition of 
combat vehicles. Then he determines capabilities for combating 
enemy tanks and other armored targets as well as steps which 
must be taken to replenish supplies. 
  In conclusions from the estimate of friendly troops the 
company (battalion) commander outlines the following: what 
subunits are advisable to have on the axis of concentration of 
main efforts and how to distribute means of reinforcement and 
align the battle formation; in what sequence to engage the enemy 
on his approach to the FEBA, during his deployment, when he 
launches an assault, and when he penetrates; what measures to 
take to replenish supplies. 
  In the estimate of the adjacent subunits it is 
necessary to analyze their makeup, situation, nature of 
operations and missions being performed. As a result of the 
estimate of adjacent subunits the company (battalion) commander 
draws conclusions in which the following are determined: 
influence of adjacent subunits on performance of assigned 
missions and on choice of axis of concentration of main efforts; 
with which of the adjacent subunits and in the performance of 
which missions to have closest coordination; measures for 
securing flanks, boundaries and gaps (what forces and assets are 
assigned and the procedure for their operations). 
  The terrain estimate is made by the commander 
initially by studying it on approaches and then in the depth of 
the defense. 
  On approaches to the defense and ahead of the FEBA the 
general nature of terrain (open, offering concealment, semiopen) 
and its influence on the method by which the enemy launches an 
assault are taken into account. Based on this the following are 
determined: probable axes of enemy forward movement, his lines 
of deployment and departure, axis of concentration of main 
efforts and axis of his air operations; firing position areas of 
artillery, mortars and ATGM's and areas of COP's; terrain 
sectors which hamper operations of fighting vehicles and affect 
organization of the system of fire; and places for emplacing 
obstacles ahead of the FEBA. Then the axes are determined for 
which there is a good view to maximum depth. 
  In estimating terrain in the depth of the defense, he also 
studies its general nature (protective and concealing 
properties, condition of roads and so on) and influence on enemy 
operations. The following are determined based on this: axes of 
concentration of main efforts of the enemy and one's own 
subunits and terrain sectors on whose holding stability of the 
defense depends; alignment of the battle formation; trench trace 
and strongpoint locations. In addition, conditions for 
maskirovka, observation and conduct of fire toward the enemy, on 
flanks and in gaps are studied and COP locations of platoons, 
companies and the battalion are selected. 
  The following are determined in conclusions: probable axis 
of 
enemy assault and commence-fire lines for various weapons; axis 
of concentration of main efforts and terrain sector on whose 
holding the stability of the defense depends; alignment of the 
battle formation and locations of platoon (company) strongpoints. 
  In estimating the NBC situation, the company (battalion) 
commander studies the degree and nature of radioactive and 
chemical contamination of terrain in the strongpoint (defense 
area) for the given time and determines the level and doses of 
radiation which personnel received and the effect of these 
factors on conduct of the defense. 
  In his conclusions the company (battalion) commander 
outlines 
the following: basic measures for protection against mass 
destruction weapons and for restoring combat effectiveness; the 
battle formation and locations of strongpoints with 
consideration of the nature of terrain and its contamination; 
forces and assets for performing radiological and chemical 
reconnaissance and their missions. [End side line] 
  Situation estimate 
  The enemy is concentrating his main body in assembly areas 
for the attack [iskhodnyy rayon dlya nastupleniya]. Counting the 
time needed for replenishing supplies and organizing for battle, 
his attack should be expected on the morning of 18 June, arrival 
of forward subunits at the defensive line by 1330-1400 and of 
the main body by 1500-1600 hours 18 June. Operations of his 
aircraft and raiding and reconnaissance parties are possible at 
any time with the beginning of the attack. Konyayevo, Stepanovo, 
Hill 119.2; and Stepanovo, Ivanovo should be considered the most 
likely axes of enemy approach to the defensive line. 
  Enemy deployment into platoon columns is possible on the 
line 
Bezymyannaya Hill, Hill 128.0, and possible line of departure is 
rocks, lone tree. Considering enemy operating tactics, it can be 
presumed that an attack of up to one and one-half company task 
forces, the basis of which will be tanks, should be expected in 
the first echelon ahead of the company defense frontage. In the 
course of battle the enemy may commit the battalion second 
echelon (up to a mechanized infantry or tank task force) with 
the taking of platoon strongpoints located on the FEBA. 
  Conclusions: 
  1. The attacking enemy's most probable axes of operations 
are 
along field roads. 
  2. Company main efforts must be concentrated on holding Hill 
136.8, Ploskaya Hill and Dlinnaya Hill. 
  3. Organize the defense as a system of platoon strongpoints 
prepared for a perimeter defense. It is advisable to align the 
battle formation in two echelons, with two MRP's reinforced by 
tanks in the first echelon and one platoon in the second. 
  The company is at 95 percent strength in personnel, weapons 
and vehicles. There is 0.8 of a fueling. The personnel 
understrength will not substantially affect performance of the 
combat mission. The political attitude and morale of personnel 
is good; 20 percent of them have experience in conducting combat 
operations. The attached TP is at full strength in personnel, 
vehicles and ammunition. 
  Conclusions: 
  1. Based on the strength level of platoons, their training 
level and commanders' experience it is advisable to have 3rd MRP 
on the right flank, 2nd MRP on the left flank and 1st MRP in the 
second echelon. 
  2. Dispose attached tanks in first echelon strongpoints. 
  3. The company's basic efforts must be concentrated on the 
Stepanovo, Dlinnaya Hill axis. 
  4. Refuel equipment by 0730 16 June and complete servicing 
and maintenance of vehicles and preparation of weapons for 
battle by 0830. 
  Subunits of 1st MRB, 3rd MRR are defending in front in the 
security zone with the mission of holding up the enemy, 
inflicting damage on him, forcing him to deploy the main body 
and attack in a direction unfavorable for him, and gaining time 
for preparing the defense. 2nd MRP, 4th MRC is shifting to the 
defense on the right on Hill 137.0 with the mission of 
preventing penetration of enemy tanks and infantry in the 
direction of Grusha Hill, Kuskovo. 
  1st MRC, 1st MRB is shifting to the defense on the left. Its 
mission is to hold the strongpoint and prevent enemy penetration 
in the direction of Hill 99.8, Karevo. 
  Gaps between adjacent subunits are 600-700 m, which requires 
covering them by fire not only of small arms, but also of AT 
weapons. 
  Conclusions: 
  1. To secure flanks it is necessary to assign platoons 
secondary sectors of fire and assign missions to the following 
weapons: tank and machinegunner in 3rd MRP and BMP in 2nd MRP. 
  2. Organize coordination with adjacent subunits to destroy 
the enemy who has penetrated into gaps. 
  Terrain relief ahead of the FEBA is level, with the presence 
of small hills and individual groves, and is accessible for 
operations of all kinds of vehicles. Dirt roads leading from 
west to east toward our FEBA create favorable conditions for 
moving forward from the depth. 
  Berezovyy Forest and Dubovaya and Kruglaya groves as well as 
Bezymyannaya Hill and Hill 128.0 enable the enemy to move 
forward and deploy into approach march and battle formations 
covertly. Enemy deployment into platoon columns is possible with 
his arrival at the line Bezymyannaya Hill, Hill 128.0. 
  Almost all terrain closer to Bezymyannaya Hill and Berezovyy 
Forest is open and easily viewed from our side. 
  The presence of Bezymyannaya Hill, Hill 128.0 and Hill 80.1 
will allow the enemy to conduct observation in our disposition 
up to the line Pridorozhnaya Grove, Malaya Grove. An enemy 
assault most likely will begin from the line rocks, ruins, which 
is 400-600 m from our FEBA. The most convenient axes of advance 
of enemy tanks are along the roads Stepanovo, Hill 119.2; and 
Stepanovo, Ivanovo. 
  The marshy sector on right and left flanks will hamper enemy 
use of tanks in gaps with the adjacent subunit on the right. 
Terrain in the strongpoint of the company and of adjacent 
subunits basically is level and open and permits a favorable 
disposition of platoon strongpoints by taking advantage of Hill 
136.8, Ploskaya Hill, Dlinnaya Hill, with a good field of view 
and fire in the direction of the enemy. 
  Conclusions: 
  1. Based on terrain conditions, the probable axis of 
concentration of main enemy efforts will be in the direction 
Stepanovo, Dlinnaya Hill. 
  2. Dispose platoon strongpoints as follows: 3rd MRP on Hill 
136.8, 2nd MRP on Ploskaya Hill, 1st MRP on Dlinnaya Hill. 
  [Begin side line] After analyzing the mission received and 
analyzing conclusions from the situation estimate, the company 
(battalion) commander makes his decision. 
  The basis of the decision is the commander's 
concept, which specifies the following: axis of concentration of 
main efforts and terrain areas on whose holding stability of the 
defense depends; procedure for fire engagement of the enemy on 
his approach to the FEBA, his deployment, and launching of his 
attack; procedure for destroying an enemy who has penetrated the 
defense; axis of possible counterattacks; battle formation and 
system of strongpoints and firing positions; and methods of 
deceiving the enemy. [End side line] 
  Decision (concept) 
  I decided: concentrate main efforts on axis 
Stepanovo, Kedrovka and firmly hold Hill 136.8, Dlinnaya Hill. 
  Exploiting results of air strikes and taking advantage of 
artillery fire and favorable terrain conditions, inflict damage 
on the enemy and repel his assault by the fire of tanks, BMP's 
and small arms beginning from line Dubovaya Grove, dairy farm; 
and as he approaches the FEBA. 
  In case the enemy penetrates the strongpoint, firmly hold 
Hill 136.8, Ploskaya Hill, Dlinnaya Hill and inflict damage on 
and destroy him by flanking and cross fire of all weapons and by 
actions of fire ambushes and the armored group from occupied and 
alternate positions. 
  Align battle formation in two echelons: 2nd and 3rd MRP's 
reinforced by 1st TP and grenade launcher squad in first echelon 
and 1st MRP in second. 
  Mislead the enemy regarding alignment of the battle 
formation 
by creating a dummy platoon strongpoint in the center of the 
battle formation and dummy tank and BMP firing positions 
simulating their real position. 
  [Begin side line] Having made the decision, the company 
commander communicated it to his deputy and to platoon 
commanders and traveled out to work on the terrain with the 
battalion commander. On completing the work he arrived at Hill 
136.8 by 0720 hours 16 June to conduct ground reconnaissance 
with subordinate commanders. 
  During ground reconnaissance the company (battalion) 
commander usually studies terrain, designates (indicates) 
reference points and updates the following: 

  -  situation, possible enemy forward movement routes 
(assembly areas) and deployment lines, and likely avenues of 
tank approach; 
  -  FEBA trace, strongpoint (defense area), 
boundaries and missions of the company (battalion); 
  -  axis of 
concentration of main efforts and terrain sectors on whose 
holding stability of the defense depends; 
  -  trench and 
communication trench trace, platoon (company) strongpoints, 
combat security outpost position, places for arranging fire 
ambushes and area for armored group if it is established; 
  -  positions of attached tank (motorized rifle) subunit and of 
other means of reinforcement; 
  -  zones of fire of platoons 
(companies) and fire concentration sectors; primary and 
alternate (temporary) positions of organic and attached 
artillery; firing positions and zones of fire (sector of fire), 
fire concentration sectors and defensive fire lines of subunits 
(weapons) intended for securing flanks and boundaries with 
adjacent subunits and gaps between platoons (companies); 
primary, alternate (temporary) launch (firing) positions of air 
defense subunit and its maneuver routes; axes and deployment 
lines for counterattacks of TC and BMP-equipped MRC in the 
second echelon (reserve), and lines of firing positions for the 
armored group; 
  -  sequence and time periods of engineer 
preparation, locations for laying minefields and passages left 
in them, and locations of dummy strongpoints, positions and 
trenches; 
  -  measures for protecting against enemy mass 
destruction and precision weapons, securing boundaries and 
flanks, destroying airborne assault forces, raiding and 
reconnaissance parties, and airmobile parties, and [protecting 
against] subunit operations at night and under other conditions 
of limited visibility; 
  -  locations of COP and of technical 
support and rear subunits as well as of motor vehicles of 
motorized rifle subunits. [End side line] 

  Ground reconnaissance 
  [Begin side line] After briefing his decision to the 
battalion commander at 0700 hours 16 June on Hill 136.8, the 
company commander selected as reference points local features 
easily visible day and night and most resistant to destruction, 
numbered them and determined distances to them. 
  Platoon commanders and the 1st TP commander arrived on Hill 
136.8 at 0720. The company commander oriented the officers on 
the terrain, indicated to subordinates the reference points, 
local features and their codenames ahead of the company defense 
frontage and on its flanks, and began ground reconnaissance. 
[End side line] 
  The enemy is concentrating his main body in areas for the 
attack along the state border 70 km from the defensive line 
(points it out on the map). His launching of an attack is 
possible on the morning of 18 June and arrival of forward 
subunits at the FEBA should be expected by 1330-1400 hours and 
arrival of the main body by 1500-1600 hours 18 June. Operations 
of enemy aviation and raiding and reconnaissance parties are 
possible at any time from the moment he invades. 
  Based on terrain conditions, the most likely axes of enemy 
approach to the strongpoint occupied by the company will be the 
roads Konyayevo, Stepanovo, Hill 119.2; and Stepanovo, Ivanovo. 
  Enemy deployment should be expected on the following lines: 
into platoon columns--Bezymyannaya Hill, Hill 128.0; into battle 
formation--rocks, lone tree. 
  If our withdrawing troop subunits do not succeed in 
disengaging from the enemy, his arrival at the FEBA should be 
expected in approach march or battle formation. 
  Considering terrain relief features and enemy operating 
tactics, up to one and one-half company task forces, the basis 
of which will be tanks, may attack ahead of the company defense 
frontage. In the course of battle, commitment of the battalion 
second echelon (up to a mechanized infantry or tank company task 
force) is possible along field roads (indicates them on the 
terrain) with the taking of first echelon platoon strongpoints. 
The most likely axis of concentration of main enemy efforts is 
Hill 80.1, Kedrovka and the most convenient axes of attack of 
his tanks are along the roads Stepanovo, Hill 119.2; Stepanovo, 
Ivanovo. The possibility of tanks bypassing Hill 136.8 from the 
north is not precluded. 
  The presence of marshy sectors in the gap with 4th MRC and 
ahead of the south slopes of Ploskaya Hill will hamper the enemy 
in using tanks on these axes. 
  Enemy air and helicopter strikes should be expected from the 
Kruglaya Grove, Pridorozhnaya Grove and the Stepanovo, Dlinnaya 
Hill axes. 
  5th MRC with 1st TP and the grenade launcher squad is 
shifting to defense of the strongpoint of north slopes of Hill 
136.8, Ploskaya Hill, Kedrovka, having the FEBA along the line 
lone house, bushes on south slopes of Hill 136.8, west edge of 
Gustaya Grove, Ploskaya, rocks. The company is concentrating 
main efforts on the axis Hill 80.1, Kedrovka and on firmly 
holding Hill 136.8, Dlinnaya Hill with the mission of preventing 
penetration of enemy tanks and infantry. Zone of fire: on 
right--lone house, north edge of Kruglaya Grove; on left--rocks, 
Hill 74.5. Secondary sector of fire--to right in direction of 
ruins. Company fire concentration sectors: SO-1--rocks, bushes; 
SO-2--lone tree, curve in road. 
  3rd MRP with grenade launcher squad in coordination with 
tanks Nos 206 and 207 is to defend strongpoint of lone house, 
bushes on south slopes of Hill 136.8, Ovalnaya Grove (excluded). 
Concentrate main efforts on the Nizkiye Bushes, Ovalnaya Grove 
axis with mission of inflicting damage on enemy by fire of all 
weapons and preventing penetration of his tanks and infantry 
along field road. Prepare one squad position in depth of 
strongpoint 100 m behind trench to strengthen stability of 
defense. Zone of fire: on right-- lone house, north edge of 
Kruglaya Grove; on left--bushes, Hill 80.1. Secondary sector of 
fire- -to right in direction of ruins. Fire concentration 
sector- -clump of trees, Barrow +2. Secure gap with 2nd MRP, 4th 
MRC by fire of BMP and light machinegun. 
  2nd MRP in coordination with Tank No 208 is to defend 
strongpoint of ruins, rocks, black knoll. Concentrate main 
efforts on holding Ploskaya Hill with mission of preventing 
penetration of enemy tanks and infantry in direction of clump of 
trees, Sukhaya Grove. Have squad positions in one trench. Zone 
of fire: on right--ruins, Nizkiye Bushes; on left--rocks, Hill 
74.5. Secondary sector of fire--to right in direction of Barrow 
+2. Fire concentration sector--clump of birches, corner of green 
field. Secure gap with 3rd MRP by fire of tank and light 
machinegun. 
  1st MRP is the second echelon and is to defend strongpoint 
of 
pine on north slopes of Dlinnaya Hill, field road, Kedrovka, 
having the FEBA along west slopes of Dlinnaya Hill. Mission: 
prevent penetration of enemy tanks and infantry in direction of 
Gustaya Grove, Kedrovka. Have one squad position in depth of 
strongpoint 150 m behind trench. Zone of fire: on right--pine, 
clump of birches; on left--knoll, curve in road. Secondary 
sector of fire--to right in direction of Ovalnaya Grove. Fire 
concentration sector-- southeast edge of Gustaya Grove. 
  1st TP is to prevent penetration of enemy tanks in direction 
of Hill 80.1, Dlinnaya Hill. Have tank firing positions as 
follows: No 206 near bushes on north slopes of Hill 136.8. 
Primary sector of fire--east edge of Kruglaya Grove, Nizkiye 
Bushes; secondary--to right in direction of ruins. Alternate 
firing position near knoll. Primary sector of fire--Redkaya 
Grove, rocks; secondary--to right in direction of bushes in 
marsh. No 207- -near wide bush on south slopes of Hill 136.8. 
Primary sector of fire-- felled area, Hill 80.1; secondary--to 
left in direction of clump of birches. Alternate firing position 
near knoll on east slopes of Hill 136.8. Sector of fire--Hill 
129.0, lone tree; secondary--to right in direction of Hill 
119.2. No 208--near knoll on north slopes of Ploskaya Hill. 
Primary sector of fire-- Nizkiye Bushes, north outskirts of 
Stepanovo; secondary--to left in direction of Hill 74.5. 
Alternate firing position--200 m southeast of primary firing 
position. Sector of fire--south outskirts of Stepanovo, Hill 
99.8; secondary- -to left in direction of Kamennaya Hill (not on 
diagram). Platoon fire concentration sector--Nizkiye Bushes, 
ruins. 
  Commence-fire lines: ATGM's--Dubovaya Grove, dairy farm; 
tanks--Grusha Hill, Hill 74.5; BMP guns and machineguns--east 
edge of Kruglaya Grove, Hill 80.1, lone tree; prepare zone of 
continuous fire along line Redkaya Grove, Barrow +2, Pit -3. 
  The company armored group consists of 1st MRP fighting 
vehicles. By 1400 hours 17 June it concentrates in Pridorozhnaya 
Grove in readiness to destroy enemy tanks. I will assign 
missions personally. Group commander is deputy commander of 1st 
MRP. Tank No 207 will operate in a fire ambush; ambush site near 
ruins on north slopes of Hill 80.1. 
  Begin engineer preparation of strongpoints immediately as 
they are occupied by the platoons and as missions are assigned. 
First and second trenches will be dug mechanically from 1040 
until 1400 hours. Complete first- order work by 1030 17 June, 
second-order by 0400 19 June. Combat engineer subunits begin 
laying minefields ahead of strongpoints of 2nd and 3rd MRP's 
from 1220 hours; No 1 extending 200 m in sector of grassy knoll, 
ditch; No 2 extending 450 m in sector of broken birch, 100 m 
west of Sosnovaya Grove, pit; No 3 extending 250 m ahead of 
right flank of 1st MRP. It is planned to make an AT ditch by 
explosive method ahead of right flank of 3rd MRP. A mined abatis 
is being emplaced on road in Sosnovaya Grove. 1st MRP commander 
is to place five persons at the disposal of the combat engineer 
subunit commander from 1820 until 1900 hours. 
  A passage will be left in the minefield along the road ahead 
of the 3rd MRP frontage for passage of our withdrawing troop 
subunits. Commanders of 2nd and 3rd MRP's are to be ready to 
provide fire cover for the combat engineers' work of laying 
minefields. Ammunition supply point and company medical aid 
station are in Malaya Grove. Company COP is on northwest slopes 
of Dlinnaya Hill as of 1025. 
  [Begin side line] After completing ground reconnaissance 
work, the company commander issued a verbal operation order on 
Dlinnaya Hill and organized coordination. 
  In the operation order for defense the company 
(battalion) commander indicates the following: 
  First paragraph--brief conclusions from enemy 
estimate. 
  Second paragraph--objectives and targets to be 
engaged by senior commander's weapons ahead of the company 
(battalion) defense frontage, and missions of adjacent subunits. 
  Third paragraph--company (battalion) combat 
mission and the commander's concept. 
  Fourth paragraph--combat missions are assigned 
following the words "I order": 
  --For first echelon platoons (companies)--means of 
reinforcement; strongpoints and axes for concentrating main 
efforts; missions for repelling an attack and destroying an 
enemy who has penetrated the defense; number of trenches and 
their trace; zones of fire, secondary sectors of fire and fire 
concentration sectors; with what forces and assets to secure 
flanks, boundaries and gaps and who is responsible for them; who 
is supporting; 
  --For second echelon platoon (company)--the very 
same as for first echelon platoons (companies), and for the 
company in addition the axes and deployment lines for 
counterattacks; for the TC and BMP- equipped MRC in addition, 
lines of firing positions; 
  --For reserve--strongpoint (concentration area), 
missions to be ready to execute; for the TC and BMP-equipped MRC 
in addition, lines of firing positions; 
  --For armored group--makeup, area and time of 
assembly in it, lines of firing positions and missions to be 
ready to execute; 
  --For fire ambush--makeup, location, missions for 
destroying an attacking enemy and procedure of operations after 
performing the mission; 
  --For attached artillery subunits and the mortar 
(artillery) battery--procedure for providing fire support 
of combat security outpost, missions for fire damage of enemy on 
his approach to FEBA, his deployment, his launching of the 
attack and his penetration of the defense, and for support of 
second echelon counterattack; and primary and alternate 
(temporary) firing positions; 
  --For grenade launcher subunit--missions for 
supporting first echelon companies and repelling an enemy 
infantry assault; primary and alternate positions, zone of fire, 
secondary sector of fire, fire concentration sectors and 
defensive fire lines; 
  --For AT subunit--place in battle formation and 
direction of possible operations, deployment lines, procedure 
for occupying them and missions to be ready to execute; signals 
for commencing and ceasing fire, procedure of operations after 
performing the mission; 
  --For air defense subunit--missions, launch 
(firing) positions, sectors for reconnaissance of the air enemy 
and conduct of fire, time and degree of readiness, procedure for 
conducting fire; 
  --For subunit assigned to combat security outpost- 
-position, mission, what weapons assigned for support, procedure 
for calling in their fire, and procedure for withdrawal. 
  Fifth paragraph--expenditure of missiles and 
ammunition for conducting defensive battle. 
  Sixth paragraph--readiness time to perform the 
combat mission, time of occupying the defense, readiness time of 
system of fire and engineer obstacles, sequence and time periods 
for performing measures of maskirovka and engineer preparation 
of the strongpoint (defense area). 
  Seventh paragraph--place and time of deployment of 
COP, and the deputies. [End side line] 
  Operation order 
  1. Enemy is concentrating subunits and units in assembly 
areas for the attack 70 km from the defensive line. Launching of 
an attack is possible on the morning of 18 June, and arrival of 
forward subunits at the defensive line by 1330-1400 hours and of 
the main body by 1500-1600 hours 18 June. Operations of his 
aviation and raiding and reconnaissance parties are possible at 
any time. 
  2. Subunits of 1/3 MRR are operating in front in the 
security 
zone with the mission of holding up the enemy, forcing him to 
deploy, inflicting losses on him and gaining time for preparing 
the defense. 
  The enemy is engaged by air strikes and by concentrated and 
defensive fire of the senior commander's artillery during battle 
in the security zone, his approach to the defense, his 
deployment and his assault. 
  4th MRC is defending on Hill 137.0 on right with the mission 
of preventing enemy penetration in direction of Grusha 
Hill, Kuskovo. 
  On the left 1st MRC, 1st MRB is defending the strongpoint of 
Tankovaya Hill, cemetery (not on diagram), 
Karevo with the mission of preventing enemy 
penetration in direction of Hill 99.8, Karevo (not on 
diagram). 
  3. 5th MRC with 2nd TP and grenade launcher squad is 
shifting 
to defense of the strongpoint of north slopes of Hill 136.8, 
Ploskaya Hill, Kedrovka with the mission 
of preventing penetration of enemy tanks and infantry in 
direction of Stepanovo, Kedrovka. Have FEBA (first 
trench) along line of barn, bushes, west edge of 
Gustaya Grove, west slopes of Ploskaya 
Hill, rocks; second trench--west slopes of Hill 129.0, west 
slopes of Dlinnaya Hill, east edge of 
Malaya Grove. Zone of fire: on right--lone tree, 
north edge of Kruglaya Grove; on left--rocks, lone 
tree. Secondary sectors of fire--to right in direction of ruins. 
Company fire concentration sectors: SO- 1--rocks, bushes; 
SO-2--lone tree, curve in road. 
  1st Battery of regimental artillery battalion is supporting. 
  I decided: concentrate main efforts on axis Stepanovo, 
Kedrovka while firmly holding Hill 136.8, 
Dlinnaya Hill. 
  Exploiting results of the senior commander's air strikes and 
artillery fire and taking advantage of favorable terrain 
conditions, inflict damage on the enemy and repel his assault by 
the fire of tanks, BMP's and small arms beginning with the line 
Dubovaya Grove, dairy farm and as he approaches the 
FEBA. 
  In case the enemy penetrates the strongpoint, firmly hold 
Hill 136.8, Ploskaya Hill, Dlinnaya Hill, 
inflict damage on him and destroy him by flanking and cross fire 
of all weapons and by operations of fire ambushes and the 
armored group from occupied and alternate positions. 
  Align battle formation in two echelons: 2nd and 3rd MRP's 
reinforced by a TP and grenade launcher squad in first echelon 
and 1st MRP in second. 
  Mislead the enemy regarding alignment of the battle 
formation 
by creating a dummy platoon strongpoint in the center of the 
battle formation, tank and BMP firing positions simulating their 
real position, and a ramified system of trenches and 
communication trenches. 
  4. I order: 
  3rd MRP with grenade launcher squad in coordination with 
tanks Nos 206 and 207 is to defend strongpoint of lone tree, 
bushes on south slopes of Hill 136.8, Ovalnaya Grove 
(excluded) with mission of preventing enemy penetration along 
road. Concentrate main efforts on axis of Nizkiye 
Bushes, Ovalnaya Grove. Have FEBA along line of lone 
tree, bushes. Battle formation is in two lines. 
  Zone of fire: on right--lone tree, north edge of 
Kruglaya Grove; on left--bushes, Hill 80.1. Secondary 
sector of fire--to right in direction of ruins. Fire 
concentration sector--clump of trees, Barrow +2. Secure gap with 
adjacent subunit on right by fire of BMP and light machinegun. 
  2nd MRP in coordination with Tank No 208 is to defend 
strongpoint of ruins, rocks, black knoll. Concentrate main 
efforts on holding Ploskaya Hill with mission of 
preventing enemy penetration in direction of clump of trees, 
Sukhaya Grove. Have FEBA along west slopes of 
Ploskaya Hill. Have battle formation in a line. Zone 
of fire: on right--ruins, Nizkiye Bushes; on 
left--rocks, Hill 74.5. Secondary sector of fire--to right in 
direction of Barrow +2. Platoon fire concentration sector--clump 
of birches, corner of green field. Secure gap with 3rd MRP by 
fire of tank and light machinegun. 2nd MRP commander is 
responsible. 
  1st MRP is the second echelon and is to defend strongpoint 
of 
pine on north slopes of Dlinnaya Hill, field road, 
Kedrovka with mission of preventing enemy penetration 
in direction of Gustaya Grove, Kedrovka. 
Concentrate main efforts on right flank, have trench on west 
slope of Dlinnaya Hill. Battle formation in two 
lines. Zone of fire: on right--pine, clump of birches; on 
left--knoll, curve in road. Secondary sector of fire--to right 
in direction of Ovalnaya Grove. Fire concentration 
sector-- southeast edge of Gustaya Grove. 
  1st TP is to prevent penetration of enemy tanks in direction 
of Hill 80.1, Dlinnaya Hill by fire from occupied 
positions. Have tank firing positions as follows: 206--near 
bushes on north slopes of Hill 136.8. Primary sector of 
fire--east edge of Kruglaya Grove, Nizkiye 
Bushes; secondary sector of fire--to right in direction of 
ruins. Alternate firing position--near knoll. Primary sector of 
fire-- Redkaya Grove, rocks; secondary--to right in 
direction of bushes in marsh. 207--near wide bush on south 
slopes of Hill 136.8. Primary sector of fire--felled area, Hill 
80.1; secondary--to left in direction of clump of birches. 
Alternate firing position--near knoll on east slopes of Hill 
136.8. Primary sector of fire--Hill 129.0, lone tree; 
secondary--to right in direction of Hill 119.2. 208--near knoll 
on north slopes of Ploskaya Hill. Primary sector of 
fire--Nizkiye Bushes, north edge of 
Stepanovo; secondary--to left in direction of Hill 
74.5. Alternate firing position--200 m southeast of primary 
firing position. Primary sector of fire--south edge of 
Stepanovo, Kamennaya Hill. Platoon fire 
concentration sector--Nizkiye Bushes, ruins. 
  Company armored group consists of 1st MRP BMP's. Assemble in 
Pridorozhnaya Grove by 1400 hours 17 June in 
readiness to destroy enemy tanks from dummy strongpoint, close 
breaches formed as a result of enemy fire strikes, and cover gap 
between 3rd and 2nd MRP's; operate in own strongpoints and from 
following lines of firing positions: No 1--bushes on south 
slopes of Hill 136.8, lone tree; No 2--south slopes of 
Dlinnaya Hill, Malaya Grove. Group 
commander is deputy commander of 1st MRP. 
  Fire ambush is Tank No 207, ambush site is near ruins. On 
north slopes of Hill 80.1 be ready to inflict damage on enemy 
tanks by direct fire, prevent their organized deployment into 
battle formation, and occupy firing position on south slopes of 
Hill 136.8. 
  5. Ammunition expenditure for performing combat mission is 
0.7 unit of fire for tanks and BMP's and 0.4 unit of fire for 
small arms. 
  6. Occupy defense by 1030 hours 16 June. Readiness of system 
of fire 1120 16 June, system of engineer obstacles by 0700 17 
June, and first-order engineer work by 1030 17 June. 
  7. Company COP is on northwest slopes of Dlinnaya 
Hill as of 1025 hours. Deputy is 1st MRP commander. 
  [Begin side line] After assigning combat missions, the 
company (battalion) commander organizes coordination, the 
system of fire, C[.sup]2[/], and protection against mass 
destruction and precision weapons. 
  The commander organizes coordination by missions, probable 
axes of enemy attack, time, and place by running through the 
main tactical episodes in terms of possible actions of his 
subunits. All work is done with the involvement of commanders of 
subordinate and attached subunits by the method of instructions 
or the method of subordinate commanders' reports with a 
successive rehearsal of actions of all subunits. 
  When time is extremely limited, especially when shifting to 
the defense in direct contact with the enemy, the commander 
usually organizes coordination by the method of instructions. 
  In organizing coordination the company (battalion) commander 
coordinates actions of platoons (companies) among themselves and 
with actions of the armored group, fire ambushes, subunits of 
artillery and other weapons, and adjacent subunits for 
destroying the enemy during his forward movement to the FEBA, 
when he deploys, when he launches the assault (in the attack 
position), and when repelling an assault of enemy tanks and 
infantry during penetration of the strongpoint (defense area). 
  The company (battalion) commander indicates (updates) the 
following for engaging the enemy during his forward movement, 
when deploying and when launching an attack (or in the attack 
position): fire missions for artillery subunits, grenade 
launcher subunit, AT subunit and other weapons for destroying 
the enemy; procedure for actions of subunits defending a forward 
position (combat security outpost position) with actions of 
first echelon platoons (companies) and subunits of attached and 
supporting artillery for holding a forward position (combat 
security outpost position), and the procedure for withdrawal of 
subunits defending it; procedure for actions of duty tanks, 
BMP's (BTR's) and other weapons (which ones to assign from whom 
and to where) and subunits for destroying individual enemy 
groups attempting to perform reconnaissance, breach obstacles or 
penetrate into the depth of the defense. 
  In organizing coordination for repelling an enemy tank and 
infantry assault ahead of the FEBA, the company (battalion) 
commander determines (updates) the following: fire missions for 
artillery, grenade launcher subunit and AT subunit for 
destroying (neutralizing) the enemy ahead of the FEBA, on flanks 
and in gaps between strongpoints; procedure for conducting 
observation and for subunits to move out of cover; commence-fire 
line for tanks, BMP's, ATGM launchers, grenade launchers and 
other AT weapons, as well as platoon (company) fire 
concentration sectors on the most important axes and the 
procedure for conducting fire; procedure for actions of first 
and second echelon platoons (companies) with actions of the 
armored group, artillery subunits, grenade launcher subunit, AT 
subunit, attached combat engineer subunit, subunits (weapons) 
operating in fire ambushes, and roving weapons for repelling 
enemy tank and infantry assaults, cutting off infantry from 
tanks, destroying the enemy ahead of the FEBA, on flanks, in 
gaps and on boundaries with adjacent subunits and when he 
penetrates the defense, and combating enemy airborne assault 
forces; procedure for commencing and conducting fire against 
enemy aircraft and helicopters by air defense and motorized 
rifle (tank) subunits; methods and signals for recognition of 
friendly aircraft and helicopters and for marking one's 
position; procedure for actions of forward air controllers and 
recognition and identification posts (points). 
  To destroy the enemy on an axis of possible penetration, the 
company (battalion) commander indicates (specifies) the 
following: missions for artillery and weapons to destroy a 
penetrated enemy and the procedure for performing them; terrain 
sector which must be held firmly to prevent a further spread of 
the enemy into the depth and toward the flanks, and with what 
subunits to hold it; procedure for actions of subunits and 
conduct of fire. 
  In organizing coordination by axes of counterattacks to be 
conducted by the battalion (regimental) commander, the company 
(battalion) commander indicates axes of counterattacks and 
missions for subunits intended for destroying the enemy by fire 
of company (battalion) assets during forward movement and 
deployment of counterattacking subunits, and actions of company 
subunits when they launch an assault. 
  The content of questions to be decided in organizing 
coordination can vary. In each specific case it will be 
determined by situation conditions, time available and the 
commander's experience. [End side line] 
  Coordination instructions 
  In destroying the enemy during his forward 
movement toward the FEBA and his deployment: aircraft and 
artillery neutralize him on forward movement routes and 
deployment lines under the senior commander's plan; with the 
beginning of enemy fire preparation, at the signal Grom 
[Thunder] or a series of red flares, shelter personnel in 
covered slit trenches (dugouts), in readiness to quickly take 
their places at positions to repel the assault; observers, duty 
weapons and squad and platoon commanders remain to observe the 
enemy; BMP and tank crews are in the vehicles; with the enemy's 
arrival at the line Bezymyannaya Hill, Hill 128.0 artillery 
inflicts damage on him by fire concentration against sectors 201 
(edge of Dubovaya Grove), 202 (where road exits Berezovyy 
forest), and 203 (intersection of field roads), neutralizing his 
personnel and weapons; the company destroys his armored 
vehicles, above all tanks, by ATGM and tank fire. The TP is in 
readiness to conduct concentrated fire at the signal Udar 
[Strike]-111 or a green flare; as the enemy approaches the 
forward edge of the company strongpoint, artillery neutralizes 
him by concentrated fire and the company destroys enemy tanks by 
fire of tanks, ATGM's and BMP guns, and destroys dismounted 
infantry by machinegun fire. 
  In performing the mission of repelling an enemy tank and 
infantry assault ahead of the FEBA: aircraft continue 
to deliver strikes against enemy artillery and second echelons; 
with the enemy's arrival at the line of east slopes of Grusha 
Hill, west edge of Stepanovo, at the signal "To battle" or a 
series of green flares, personnel occupy positions and make 
ready to repel the assault, and artillery and mortars inflict 
damage on tanks and other armored vehicles and place the enemy 
battle formation in disarray by standing barrier fire against 
lines Sosna [Pine] and Bereza [Birch] and by rolling barrier 
fire Tigr [Tiger]; when the enemy launches an assault tanks and 
BMP's destroy enemy tanks and APC's by fire of guns and ATGM's. 
At the signal Udar [Strike]-111 or a green flare, 2nd and 3rd 
MRP's conduct concentrated fire from all kinds of small arms and 
the armored group destroys enemy tanks by BMP fire from the 
dummy strongpoint; as the enemy approaches the FEBA, fire of all 
company weapons is brought to highest intensity; tanks are 
destroyed by fire of BMP's, tanks and RPG's; enemy infantry is 
cut off from tanks and destroyed by small arms and machinegun 
fire; the armored group continues to destroy enemy tanks and at 
the signal Shtorm [Gale]-555 occupies the disposition area; 
infantry which has penetrated the forward edge of platoon 
strongpoints is to be destroyed by point-blank fire and grenades 
and in hand-to- hand combat, and tanks are to be destroyed by 
RPG's and by BMP and tank guns. 
  In performing the mission of destroying an enemy who has 
penetrated the company strongpoint: aircraft and 
artillery engage second echelons and neutralize enemy COP's, 
artillery and mortars; in case the enemy penetrates the company 
strongpoint between 3rd and 2nd MRP, artillery neutralizes his 
personnel and weapons by concentrated fire; at the signal Udar 
[Strike]-111 or a green flare 1st MRP commences fire against the 
fire concentration sector, and the BMP destroys tanks and APC's; 
firmly holding platoon strongpoints, 3rd and 2nd MRP's repulse 
the assault ahead of the FEBA. The penetrated enemy is destroyed 
by flanking fire of squads, tanks, BMP's and machineguns and is 
not permitted to spread out laterally and into the depth; the 
armored group occupies Line No 1 or 2. 
  When enemy tanks and infantry wedge into the gap with 
4th MRC: artillery neutralizes his personnel and weapons by 
concentrated fire and prohibits envelopment of the 3rd MRP 
strongpoint; firmly holding the north slopes of Hill 136.8, 3rd 
MRP neutralizes the enemy by fire of all weapons in coordination 
with 4th MRC, destroying his tanks and APC's above all. 
  In case the enemy penetrates the gap with 1st MRC 
on the left flank: artillery neutralizes enemy personnel and 
weapons by concentrated fire and places his battle formation in 
disarray; firmly holding Ploskaya Hill and repelling the enemy 
assault from the front, 2nd MRP destroys the penetrated enemy by 
fire of the left-flank squad, BMP's and tanks from the alternate 
firing position in coordination with 1st MRC; 1st MRP is in 
readiness to destroy enemy tanks and infantry which have 
penetrated by fire from the occupied strongpoint. 
  In conducting a counterattack with the battalion 
second echelon: artillery neutralizes the penetrated enemy 
between strongpoints of 2nd and 3rd MRP's and his tanks are 
destroyed by helicopters; firmly holding the strongpoints, 2nd 
and 3rd MRP's inflict damage on the enemy by fire, not 
permitting him to spread out into the depth and toward the 
flanks; 1st MRP destroys the penetrated enemy by fire of all 
weapons and supports the forward movement, deployment and 
assault of 6th MRC. When 6th MRC launches a counterattack, 1st 
MRP assaults the enemy together with it and restores the defense 
along the FEBA. 
  Signals: 

  -  warning: warning of immediate threat and 
beginning of enemy use of mass destruction weapons--"Uragan 
[Hurricane]"; radioactive contamination--"Radiatsionnaya 
opasnost [Radiation Danger]"; chemical and biological 
(bacteriological) contamination--"Khimicheskaya trevoga 
[Chemical Alert]," chemical attack alarm flare; air 
enemy--"Vozdukh [Air]"; 
  -  control and coordination: 
take cover--"Grom [Thunder]," series of red flares; occupy 
positions--"K boyu [To battle]"; request artillery fire-- 
"Perekat [Leapfrog]-333"; armored group change of positions 
(line)--"Shtorm [Gale]-555"; commence concentrated fire--"Udar 
[Strike]- 111," green flare. 

  [Begin side line] Subsequently the company (battalion) 
commander gives instructions on main questions of comprehensive 
support. [End side line] 
  Reconnaissance instructions 
  Conduct reconnaissance by observation, having lookouts for 
the ground and air enemy in each platoon. 1st MRP commander is 
to assign two persons by 1040 hours for organizing observation 
at the company COP. I will assign the mission personally. 
  Concentrate main reconnaissance efforts in the direction of 
Stepanovo, Berezovyy Forest for performing the following 
missions: promptly establish the enemy's forward movement and 
deployment, the makeup of his subunits ahead of the company 
defense frontage and on flanks, artillery and mortar firing 
positions, and forward movement of reserves in direction of 
Berezovyy Forest, Stepanovo. Organize observation after 
receiving the mission. Report reconnaissance results to me at 
the COP. 
  Instructions on protection against mass 
destruction weapons 
  In determining locations of covered slit trenches and 
preparing dugouts, platoon commanders are to use protective 
properties of the terrain (reverse hillslopes, hollows). 
  Warning signals: warning of immediate threat and 
beginning of enemy use of mass destruction weapons--"Grom 
[Thunder]," radioactive contamination-- "Radiatsionnaya opasnost 
[Radiation Danger]," chemical, biological (bacteriological) 
contamination--"Khimicheskaya trevoga [Chemical Alert]," air 
attack--"Vozdukh [Air]." 
  Give warning signals by radio and voice and duplicate by 
chemical attack alarm flare and rapid honking of vehicle horns. 
  When the enemy employs mass destruction weapons, personnel 
are to make use of individual and collective protective gear. 
Perform partial decontamination without ceasing to fight and 
perform complete decontamination and radiological 
decontamination of emplacements with my permission. 
  Maskirovka instructions 
  Platoon commanders are to use concealing properties of 
terrain for maskirovka of strongpoints and defensive works. 
Camouflage combat equipment using authorized means of maskirovka 
and local materials. Complete performance of maskirovka measures 
in the course of engineer preparation by 0600 hours 17 June. 
  At night do not permit bonfires to be lit or vehicles to 
move 
with headlights on. 
  All radio equipment operates only on receive before the 
beginning of battle. 
  Engineer support instructions 
  Prepare the following at positions and in strongpoints: by 
2400 hours 16 June- -two-man foxholes for riflemen and 
emplacements for machinegunners, grenade launcher operators and 
snipers, and emplace obstacles ahead of FEBA, in gaps and on 
flanks; by 0600 hours 17 September [sic]--squad emplacements and 
emplacements for tanks, BMP's and other weapons; by day's 
end--covered slit trenches for squads and a platoon dugout. 
  Prepare timbers for protective emplacements and covered slit 
trenches in groves in the depth of platoon strongpoints. 
  Mixed minefields will be laid ahead of the company defense 
frontage by forces of the combat engineer platoon from 1200 to 
2300 hours 16 June. Emplace concealed obstacles on company 
flanks by 2nd and 3rd MRP personnel. 
  Chemical support instructions 
  Conduct radiological, chemical and nonspecific biological 
(bacteriological) reconnaissance in platoon strongpoints by 
observers and by the crews of BMP's (BTR's), and at the company 
COP by the chemical observer. 
  Platoon commanders are to take readings from dose rate 
meters 
by day's end. 
  Perform partial decontamination in strongpoints by your own 
forces at my command. Perform decontamination immediately when 
contaminated by chemical agents. 
  From 2100 to 2200 hours platoon commanders are to check 
availability and serviceability of individual protective gear 
and the technical condition of protective masks. 
  Technical and logistic support instructions 
  Platoon commanders are to perform daily routine servicing 
and 
maintenance of weapons and military vehicles and complete it by 
0930 hours 16 June. Check operation of night vision devices. 
Perform routine servicing and maintenance on each vehicle in 
turn. 
  Company first sergeant is to deploy ammunition supply point 
on south slopes of Dlinnaya Hill by 1400 hours. Finish refueling 
combat equipment by 0900 hours 16 June. 
  Ammunition expenditure: small arms 0.4 unit of fire; BMP and 
tank guns 0.7 unit of fire; fuel 0.1 fueling. In the course of 
battle evacuate wounded to company aid station in vicinity of 
Dlinnaya Hill by riflemen- medics. 
  [Begin side line] Based on work done to organize for battle, 
the company (battalion) commander works out a diagram of the 
company strongpoint (battalion defense area). It is recommended 
doing this on a sheet of Whatman paper, which should be marked 
out in advance as a formatted document and have a [legend] 
border, commander's signature, and date to save time in 
preparing the diagram. 
  The company strongpoint diagram shows the 
following (Diagram 5): reference points, their numbers, names 
and distances to them; enemy situation; company zone of fire; 
platoon strongpoints, their zones of fire and secondary sectors 
of fire; primary and alternate firing positions of BMP's 
(BTR's), tanks, and AT, flamethrower and air defense weapons; 
firing positions and sectors of fire of weapons supporting 
company flanks and gaps between platoon strongpoints, and on the 
MRC strongpoint diagram also those of attached tanks; fire 
concentration sectors of the company and of each platoon; 
commence-fire lines for tanks, BMP's, ATGM systems and other 
weapons; concentration area and lines of firing positions of 
armored group; positions and maneuver routes of roving weapons; 
locations of fire ambushes; engineer obstacles and 
fortifications; passages in obstacles for roving weapons and 
weapons operating in fire ambushes; places of deployment of 
technical observation post, ammunition supply point and company 
aid station; COP locations of company and platoons and 
disposition of MRC motor vehicles. In addition, the TC 
strongpoint diagram indicates positions of the attached 
motorized rifle subunit and the system of fire of its weapons. 
  The strongpoint diagram and defense area diagram are plans 
for conducting defensive battle; copies of them are submitted to 
the battalion commander and regimental commander respectively. 
  The battalion defense area diagram usually shows 
the following: reference points; enemy situation; combat 
security outpost position; company and platoon strongpoints, 
their zones of fire and fire concentration sectors, and 
commence-fire lines against the enemy for tanks, BMP's, ATGM 
systems, grenade launchers and other weapons; situation of 
adjacent subunits and boundaries with them; firing positions and 
sectors of fire of weapons supporting battalion flanks and gaps 
between company strongpoints; concentration areas and lines of 
firing positions of armored groups; positions and maneuver 
routes of roving weapons; firing positions and fire missions of 
artillery subunits, air defense subunit, grenade launcher 
subunit and other weapons directly subordinate to the battalion 
commander; locations of fire ambushes; axes of counterattacks 
and deployment lines of second echelon company (reserve), and 
for the TC and BMP-equipped MRC in addition, the lines of firing 
positions. The following should be plotted on the diagram: main 
fortifications and engineer obstacles; passages in obstacles for 
armored groups, subunits (weapons) operating in fire ambushes, 
and roving weapons; locations of technical support and logistic 
subunits, motor vehicles of motorized rifle subunits, and COP's 
of the battalion and companies. Lines of deployment (minelaying) 
of the regimental AT reserve (mobile obstacle detachment) and 
fire missions of organic and attached artillery may be indicated 
within the battalion defense area, ahead of its frontage and on 
the flanks. 
  Firing positions and sectors of fire of tanks, BMP's, and 
AT, 
air defense and other weapons are indicated on the diagram in 
addition with advance preparation of the defense. [End side line] 
  Work of preparing subunits for battle 
  Preparing subunits to perform a combat mission is a very 
important measure taken by the commander in preparing the 
defense. It includes the following: bringing it up to strength 
in personnel and creating prescribed reserves of missiles, 
ammunition, fuel and other supplies; immediate preparation of 
commanders and personnel for performing the combat mission, and 
of weapons and vehicles for combat employment; conduct of 
political work with personnel and tactical exercises (drills) 
with subunits as applied to the nature of the upcoming battle. 
  A defense can be occupied and the battle formation and 
system 
of fire can be created under various situation conditions. The 
defense is occupied covertly in a short time out of direct 
contact with the enemy. Subunits occupy their indicated 
strongpoints, prepare the system of fire and carry out engineer 
preparation of strongpoints (defense areas). 
  When shifting to the defense in direct contact with the 
enemy, special attention is given to creating a battle formation 
and a system of fire and engineer obstacles in a short time 
above all on the probable axis of attack of the enemy main body 
in accordance with the company (battalion) commander's decision, 
and it is also given to maskirovka and fortification of the 
strongpoint (defense area) being occupied. 
  In all cases when shifting to the defense, a company 
(battalion) constantly must be ready to repel an enemy surprise 
attack and strikes by his aircraft, helicopters and 
reconnaissance-strike complexes, and to destroy airborne assault 
forces and airmobile and raiding and reconnaissance parties. 
  Engineer preparation of the strongpoint (defense 
area) is a set of measures taken to adapt the terrain for 
fighting and to create conditions contributing to successful 
performance of missions by defending subunits which hamper the 
enemy attack and reduce the effectiveness of his weapons. 
  Engineer preparation of a strongpoint (defense area) 
includes 
the following: creation of an obstacle plan; construction of 
fortifications (emplacements, trenches, communication trenches, 
slit trenches, dugouts, ditches, escarpments, counterscarps, 
dragons' teeth and so on); preparation of weapon positions; 
preparation of COP's and locations (disposition areas) of rear 
subunits; preparation of maneuver; preparation of water supply 
points (water diversion [vodozabornyy] points) and other 
measures. 
  Two trenches, MRP strongpoints, positions of organic and 
attached weapons of the company, the company COP, ammunition 
supply point and aid station are prepared in the MRC strongpoint. 
  Three or four trenches, company strongpoints, firing 
positions of the mortar battery, grenade launcher subunit and 
air defense subunit, battalion COP, battalion aid station, 
disposition area of the support platoon, and also firing 
positions for tank subunits assigned for reinforcement, lines of 
firing positions of a TC (BMP-equipped MRC) in the second 
echelon (reserve), and lines of firing positions and 
concentration areas of armored groups are prepared in the MRB 
defense area. 
  Trenches and strongpoints of platoons (companies) are 
interconnected by a system of communication trenches to the full 
depth of the defense area (strongpoint). 
  Engineer preparation of the strongpoint (defense area) 
begins 
immediately after positions are specified for subunits and 
weapons and the system of fire is organized. In some cases it 
begins even before occupation of the defense, is done to the 
full extent when subunits occupy strongpoints, and continues 
without let-up in the course of the entire defensive battle. It 
is accomplished simultaneously to the full depth of the defense 
in a sequence ensuring constant readiness of subunits to repel 
an enemy attack and protect them against all weapons, and it is 
done covertly, with full exertion of efforts and maximum use of 
prefabricated fortification structures, constructions and local 
building materials. 
  Engineer preparation of a strongpoint (defense area) is done 
with wide use of heavy equipment out of direct contact with the 
enemy. 
  In first order engineer obstacles are arranged 
ahead of the combat security outpost position and FEBA, and 
fields of view and fire are cleared; emplacements are dug for 
MRS's and for tanks, BMP's (BTR's) and other weapons; structures 
are built for the COP and aid station; covered slit trenches are 
made for each squad, crew or team; sectors of continuous 
trenches are created in platoon and company strongpoints; and 
weapons and vehicles are camouflaged against reconnaissance and 
for protection against enemy precision weapons. In addition, 
obstacles are emplaced in gaps between subunits, on flanks and 
in the depth of the defense; lines of firing positions are 
prepared for the TC (TB) and BMP-equipped MRC (MRB) in the 
second echelon (reserve), and forward movement routes to these 
lines of deployment for counterattacks are prepared; and water 
supply points (water diversion points) are prepared. 
  In second order company and platoon strongpoints 
are additionally equipped, emplacements are dug for tanks, BMP's 
(BTR's) and other weapons at alternate (temporary) firing 
positions, lines of firing positions and in armored group 
concentration areas; a system of trenches and communication 
trenches is created and upgraded from a combat and housekeeping 
standpoint in the battalion defense area; COP's and aid stations 
are additionally equipped; dugouts are made for each squad, crew 
or team, bunkers are made for each company (battery) and at the 
battalion (company) COP, and shelters are made for weapons, 
equipment, missiles, ammunition and other supplies; the main 
dummy objects are prepared in the company strongpoint (battalion 
defense area); obstacles are additionally emplaced ahead of the 
FEBA, in gaps between strongpoints and on flanks, and maneuver 
routes are prepared. 
  Subsequently a system of trenches and 
communication trenches is developed in the strongpoint (defense 
area), the system of engineer obstacles is built up, a network 
of routes for subunit maneuver, supply and evacuation is 
developed additionally, and dummy strongpoints, trenches, firing 
positions and other objects are prepared. 
  Trenches are prepared for creating a system of 
continuous flanking fire and fire ahead of the FEBA and in the 
depth of the defense, protecting personnel against enemy 
enfilade fire, improving protection against the effect of 
nuclear weapons and artillery shellbursts, and for best 
adaptation to terrain relief. Trenches are dug with a 
curvilinear, broken or staggered trace. Straight sectors (faces) 
are made 40-50 m long with mechanized digging of trenches and 
20-30 m long with manual digging. The angle between trench faces 
should be 90-120. Trenches (communication trenches) are dug 
with a varying depth depending on soil condition and time 
available: with a ditch 60 cm deep for firing from a kneeling 
position and moving at a crawl; 110 cm deep for firing from a 
standing position on the bottom of the ditch and for moving bent 
over; and standard depth with a ditch 150 cm deep for firing 
standing from a fire step and for moving upright. 
  The size of trenches (communication trenches) is 90-110 cm 
on 
top depending on soil density and trench depth. The width of the 
bottom of the ditch in standard trenches as a rule does not 
exceed 40-50 cm. 
  Communication trenches are intended for sheltered movement 
of 
personnel between trenches, positions and strongpoints and 
concealed communication with the rear. In contrast to trenches, 
which usually are dug along the front, communication trenches 
for the most part are made at an angle to the front. To protect 
personnel moving along communication trenches against enemy 
enfilade fire, the trenches are carefully adapted to terrain, 
giving them a curvilinear, staggered or broken trace from an 
overhead view. They are dug to the very same depths as trenches. 
  Primary (main) communication trenches, intended for most 
intensive movement of personnel, delivery of ammunition and food 
and evacuation of wounded, are dug 70 cm or more wide at the 
bottom and at least 150 cm deep. Other communication trenches 
are dug 40-50 cm wide at the bottom. 
  Communication trenches in the tactically most important 
sector are adapted for defense, and firing positions, weapon 
(machinegun) platforms and other structures are made in them. 
  In choosing the direction for communication trenches, try to 
conceal them from enemy observation, for which ravines, reverse 
hillslopes, hollows, bushes and so on should be used. 
  If communication trenches are made on forward hillslopes, 
they should be dug in a staggered manner, directing short 
sectors toward the enemy and long ones along the front. 
Communication trenches should not be disposed along the bottom 
of a hollow, since they will be flooded in rainy weather and 
during the snow melt. 
  Trenches and communication trenches are prepared from a 
combat, housekeeping, and sanitary standpoint to improve subunit 
fighting and resting conditions. 
  Combat preparation includes making firing positions, 
machinegun platforms, firing ports, exits, crossings, revetment, 
observation structures, very basic shelters for personnel and 
equipment, ammunition niches, widened areas, cul- de-sacs and so 
on. 
  Housekeeping and sanitary preparation of trenches and 
communication trenches includes making niches for storing food, 
water and property and making latrines, sumps, soakage pits and 
drainage ditches. 
  A company COP usually is prepared in the depth of the 
strongpoint up to 800 m from the FEBA in a place providing 
observation of terrain ahead of the front and on flanks of the 
company defense, a view of one's own strongpoint where possible, 
and convenience in controlling subunits. 
  A battalion COP is prepared where possible in an area 
difficult of access for enemy tanks immediately behind first 
echelon companies or in the vicinity of the battalion second 
echelon (reserve) strongpoint up to 2 km from the FEBA. 
  The COP location should have good protective and concealing 
properties without prominent local reference points near 
structures. 
  An open structure for observation and a bunker are made and 
two BTR (BMP, tank) emplacements are dug at the company COP 
(Fig. 5). 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-58A>      Fig. 5. Company commander's COP </FIG>


  Covered and open structures for observation, a bunker, BTR 
(tank) emplacements, a BTR (BMP) emplacement and two 
emplacements for signal platoon vehicles also are made at the 
battalion COP. 
  All structures and emplacements at COP's are interconnected 
by trench sectors and with trenches by communication trenches. 
Integral assault rifle firing positions are prepared for 
fighting in trenches and communication trenches. 
  In order for the company (battalion) commander to be able to 
direct engineer preparation and monitor work progress, the 
commander (staff) should work out a calculation for engineer 
preparation of the strongpoint (defense area). 
  Subunit commanders check the promptness and correctness of 
subunit occupation of defense areas, strongpoints and positions; 
readiness of the system of fire and readiness of weapons for 
conducting fire, especially at night and under other conditions 
of limited visibility; the personnel's knowledge of their 
missions and the procedure for maintaining coordination in the 
course of battle; status and degree of readiness of engineer 
obstacles and fortification of strongpoints and subunit 
positions; readiness of the second echelon (reserve, armored 
group) for a maneuver to lines of firing positions and to 
indicated axes; fulfillment of measures for comprehensive 
support to battle and C[.sup]2[/]; and occupation of 
positions by the combat security outpost and its readiness to 
perform the combat mission. 
<H5>  5. Conduct of Defensive Battle </H5>
  Before the beginning of an enemy attack the mission of a 
first echelon company (battalion) is to destroy his individual 
groups attempting to perform reconnaissance, breach obstacles or 
penetrate into the depth of the defense, and to destroy 
low-flying enemy aircraft and helicopters. 
  This mission is performed from alternate or temporary firing 
positions by assigned duty tanks, BMP's (BTR's) and other 
weapons. When in direct contact, duty weapons in addition must 
hamper enemy movement into his disposition area and prohibit him 
from performing engineer work. For their part, snipers kill 
officers, snipers, observers, weapon teams and other enemy 
targets. The other subunits upgrade engineer preparation of 
positions, conduct combat and political training classes and 
service and maintain weapons and vehicles while maintaining 
constant readiness to repel enemy assaults. 
  The company commander gives company personnel a rest 
depending on the situation and the battalion commander's 
instructions. For this they use shelters (dugouts) near trenches 
and weapons, ready to take their places when alerted. Observers 
are posted near the shelters who warn all those resting by a 
prearranged signal, summoning them to the positions. 
  Based on personal observation and reconnaissance data, the 
company (battalion) commander must promptly establish enemy 
preparation for an attack and the beginning of his forward 
movement and deployment, report this to the senior commander, 
update missions for subordinate subunits and attached artillery, 
and place them in full readiness to repel the enemy. 
  Small enemy parties and reconnaissance subunits are 
destroyed 
by fire of the combat security outpost. The battalion commander 
directs the battle of the combat security outpost and supports 
it by fire of the battalion mortar (artillery) battery and of 
attached and supporting artillery from temporary firing 
positions. During fighting to hold the combat security outpost 
position the battalion commander moves his COP forward and 
positions it in one of the first echelon company strongpoints. 
  When major enemy forces approach the combat security outpost 
position, they are engaged not only by fire of the assigned 
platoon, but also by assigned weapons from MRC's (TC's) 
operating on the FEBA. In coordination with assigned weapons, 
the combat security outpost destroys chiefly enemy tanks and 
other armored vehicles ahead of its frontage. Assigned tanks, AT 
weapons, mortars and supporting artillery of the battalion as 
well as the senior commander's duty weapons destroy enemy tanks 
and infantry attempting to go around the combat security outpost 
and move to its flank and rear. When the enemy deploys his main 
forces and assets ahead of the defense frontage of battalions, 
by authorization of the regimental commander the battalion 
commander issues an order to the combat security outpost 
commander to disengage and withdraw, after which he moves his 
COP. The platoon's withdrawal is covered by the fire of 
artillery and assigned weapons of first echelon companies and is 
accomplished by leapfrogging, taking advantage of terrain folds, 
obstacles and aerosols (smoke). A combat security outpost 
platoon which has withdrawn takes up a position in the company 
strongpoint or is moved into the battalion reserve. 
  Reconnaissance in force and an assault by enemy forward 
subunits are repelled by fire of assigned assets and by subunits 
defending these axes. Observation of the enemy is beefed up. 
After the combat security outpost withdraws and the assault is 
repelled, weapons which have revealed themselves change 
positions covertly by direction of the company (battalion) 
commander. Passages which the enemy has made in our obstacles 
are immediately closed or, if this is impossible, the fire of 
artillery and other weapons is prepared against them. 
  If the enemy managed to penetrate the strongpoint (defense 
area) as a result of reconnaissance in force, the company 
(battalion) commander takes all steps to destroy him. 
  Fire preparation usually precedes the launching of an attack 
by the enemy main body. This period of battle is the most 
important for the company (battalion), since the most powerful 
fire strike is delivered at this time. 
  With the beginning of fire preparation or delivery of 
nuclear 
strikes by the enemy, personnel of the MRC or TC (MRB or TB) and 
of attached subunits take cover at the commanders' order or 
independently in slit trenches, dugouts, bunkers and fighting 
vehicles (tanks) and on the bottom of emplacements and trenches 
in readiness to take their places quickly at positions to repel 
an assault. In this period the commander conducts continuous 
observation and updates missions for subunits, artillery and 
other weapons for engaging detected enemy precision weapon 
assets, artillery, tanks, other armored vehicles and infantry 
moving forward or readying for an assault. At the same time he 
estimates the situation in areas of nuclear strikes and takes 
steps to close breaches in the battle formation, restore 
C[.sup]2[/] and the system of fire and coordination, and mop 
up in the aftermath of enemy use of mass destruction weapons. 
  Enemy attempts to breach engineer obstacles ahead of our 
FEBA 
in the period of fire preparation are stopped by fire of duty 
weapons. 
  After enemy fire preparation ends, main efforts of all 
forces 
and assets are concentrated on engaging tanks and mechanized 
infantry. At commanders' signals, company (battalion) subunits 
make ready to repel the enemy assault. The transfer of enemy 
artillery and mortar fire from the FEBA into the depth may serve 
as the beginning of the enemy assault. In this situation it is 
always necessary to be attentive, since the enemy may execute a 
dummy transfer of fire to force company (battalion) subunits to 
emerge from shelters and then inflict additional losses on them 
by a repeat strike of artillery, mortars and aircraft. 
Consequently, preservation of company (battalion) combat 
effectiveness and attainment of success in battle largely will 
depend on correctly determining the moment for personnel and 
combat vehicles to emerge from shelters and prepare to repel 
enemy assaults. Therefore foresight, precise operation of the 
observation and reconnaissance system, a good knowledge of enemy 
operating tactics, faultless communications and continuous 
information about enemy actions are necessary. 
  When the enemy launches an assault the company (battalion) 
commander concentrates fire of all weapons against the enemy 
main body. Organic and attached artillery inflicts damage on 
precision weapon assets, tanks and other armored vehicles by 
concentrated fire, fire against single targets, and rolling and 
standing barrier fire and, placing [battle] formations of enemy 
subunits in disarray, creates favorable conditions for their 
destruction by fire of tanks, BMP's, ATGM's and grenade 
launchers from maximum fire or launch ranges. 
  In the period of friendly air operations against an 
attacking 
enemy, artillery engages his air defense weapons, and 
recognition and identification posts and points mark friendly 
troops at the commands (signals) of subunit commanders. 
  Fire of all company (battalion) weapons is brought to 
highest 
intensity as the enemy approaches the FEBA. Defending subunits 
destroy tanks and other armored combat vehicles by the fire of 
tanks and other AT weapons. If enemy infantry assaults in 
dismounted formation, defending subunits use machinegun and 
assault rifle fire to cut infantry off from tanks and destroy it 
by fire. When enemy infantry comes to within 30-40 m of the 
FEBA, personnel of motorized rifle subunits attack it with 
grenades and destroy infantry which has penetrated the forward 
edge of subunit strongpoints by point-blank fire, grenades, and 
in hand-to-hand combat. 
  An enemy assault should be repelled ahead of the FEBA. The 
primary obligation of commanders in this period above all is 
skilled fire control. A battle is fought for each trench 
according to the principle of "not a step backward." 
  To keep the enemy from fanning out through trenches and 
communication trenches, the personnel quickly set up previously 
prepared hedgehogs, knife rests and other portable obstacles in 
them. If necessary, tanks and BMP's (BTR's) which are part of 
the armored group may move forward and take up positions in 
their own strongpoints under cover of aerosols (smoke) or using 
concealed routes. 
  The air defense subunit as well as motorized rifle (tank) 
subunits not engaged in fighting the ground enemy repel raids by 
low-flying enemy aircraft and helicopters. 
  In case the enemy penetrates the strongpoint (defense area), 
the company (battalion) commander uses the fire of all assets to 
stop him from fanning out laterally and into the depth, and 
consolidates his flanks in the penetration sector. 
  Tanks and BMP's (BTR's) which have penetrated into the depth 
of the defense are destroyed by fire of artillery, all AT 
weapons, tanks and BMP's of the company (battalion) from 
occupied positions or lines of firing positions. In addition, 
the battalion commander may move second echelon (reserve) tanks 
(BMP's) up to a line of firing positions at the spot of the 
penetration, and the AT subunit to a deployment line prepared on 
this axis. 
  When an enemy who has penetrated approaches fire ambushes, 
they commence fire suddenly at the company (battalion) 
commander's command or independently, destroying enemy tanks and 
other armored vehicles above all, and force surviving enemy 
tanks and infantry to advance in a direction unfavorable to them 
or onto previously prepared minefields. 
  Under favorable situation conditions an enemy who has 
penetrated is destroyed by a counterattack conducted until he is 
totally annihilated and the defense restored. 
  A counterattack by the second echelon (reserve) is organized 
by the battalion commander personally and usually is carried out 
(as a rule, together with the regimental second echelon) when 
insignificant enemy forces penetrate. 
  In this situation first echelon subunits use fire of all 
weapons to inflict damage on an enemy who has penetrated and, 
firmly holding favorable terrain sectors in the depth of the 
defense, prohibit an enemy advance toward the flank, thereby 
supporting forward movement and deployment of the second echelon 
for a counterattack. Battalion first echelon subunits use fire 
of all weapons to support the second echelon's counterattack or, 
by order of the commander, some of the forces counterattack 
together with it and destroy an enemy who has penetrated the 
defense. As a rule, a counterattack is conducted until the enemy 
is totally annihilated and the defense restored. The regiment 
(battalion) does not conduct a counterattack on an axis of 
attack of superior enemy forces, but defends according to the 
principle of "not a step backward." 
  An enemy who has penetrated at the boundary with an adjacent 
company (battalion) is destroyed in coordination with the 
adjacent unit by fire of all weapons and, under favorable 
situation conditions, also by a decisive counterattack. 
  If the enemy has gone around the strongpoint (defense area), 
a company (battalion) shifts to a perimeter defense and 
continues to hold occupied positions (the most important terrain 
sectors). Some weapons are moved to a threatened axis. 
  The nature of operations of a second echelon company 
(battalion) will be somewhat different. With the beginning of an 
enemy attack the company (battalion) commander must constantly 
know the situation ahead of the defense frontage and on the 
flanks and have communications with commanders of first echelon 
platoons (companies) and supporting artillery. 
  In case the enemy breaks through into the depth of the 
defense, a battalion (regimental) second echelon company 
(battalion) uses fire of all weapons from the occupied position 
to inflict decisive damage on him and stop his further advance. 
A TC (TB) and BMP-equipped MRC (MRB) move forward to a prepared 
line of firing positions if necessary. 
  On receiving an order to take part in a counterattack, the 
company (battalion) commander sends out reconnaissance and 
updates missions for subunits and weapons. Under cover of 
artillery fire and observing measures for protection against 
precision weapons, subunits quickly move forward onto the 
indicated axis, inflict damage on the enemy by fire of tanks, 
BMP's and other weapons, place his battle formations in disarray 
and, in coordination with adjacent subunits, decisively 
counterattack the enemy primarily against his flank or rear. 
  Motorized rifle subunits counterattack the enemy in BMP's or 
dismounted following tanks. 
  Great Patriotic War experience indicates that rifle subunits 
successfully destroy an enemy who has penetrated only through a 
maneuver of fire and counterattacks. 
  A battalion counterattack usually is not carried out when 
there have been heavy losses from enemy nuclear and fire strikes 
and when considerable forces of enemy tanks and mechanized 
infantry penetrate the defense. In that situation the battalion 
commander concentrates main efforts above all on destroying 
subunits attempting to take terrain sectors on whose holding 
stability of the defense depends. To this end he inflicts damage 
on the enemy by concentrated and barrier fire of artillery and 
mortars and by the fire of tanks, BMP's, BTR's, ATGM launchers 
and all assets of motorized rifle (tank) subunits and halts his 
further spread into the depth and toward the flanks. To 
consolidate flanks and reinforce the defense in the enemy 
penetration sector, he uses subunits defending on this axis, the 
battalion second echelon (reserve), AT weapons directly 
subordinate to him, the combat engineer subunit attached to the 
battalion, and forces and assets from sectors not under attack. 
  Motorized rifle (tank) subunits disposed ahead of the front, 
on flanks of the enemy penetration and in the depth destroy 
enemy tanks and mechanized infantry by fire and by stubbornly 
holding occupied positions in coordination with artillery and AT 
weapons of the battalion and with combat helicopters, and 
prohibit them from fanning out into the depth and toward the 
flanks. A battalion second echelon TC (BMP-equipped MRC) may be 
moved up to a prepared line of firing positions by order of the 
commander. 
  After repelling the assault and destroying the enemy who has 
penetrated, the company (battalion) commander takes steps for 
rapid restoration of the system of fire, replenishment of 
reserves of missiles and ammunition, and restoration of 
demolished fortifications and engineer obstacles; and organizes 
restoration of weapons and vehicles which have been disabled and 
preparation for evacuation of wounded and sick. He reports 
battle results to the senior commander. 
  A battalion (regimental) first echelon company (battalion) 
supports the counterattack by fire or, by order of the battalion 
(regimental) commander, participates in the counterattack with a 
portion of its forces, destroys the enemy who has penetrated and 
restores the position. 
  Having established the beginning of the landing of an enemy 
airborne assault force or having received a mission to destroy 
such a force, the commander of a company (battalion) which makes 
up the regiment (division) antilanding reserve sends out 
additional reconnaissance and updates (assigns) missions to 
subunits and attached weapons. The company (battalion) quickly 
moves out to the airborne assault force landing zone, deploys 
into battle formation on the move, inflicts damage on the enemy 
by fire of all weapons and completes destruction of the assault 
force by a decisive assault. 
  If the enemy airborne assault force has succeeded in 
landing, 
assembling and beginning movement toward the attack objective, 
the company (battalion) quickly moves up to the enemy, 
immobilizes him and inflicts damage by actions of fire ambushes 
and march security, and completes destruction of the assault 
force by the main body in a meeting battle. In case it fails to 
destroy the enemy airborne assault force from the move, the 
company (battalion) immobilizes him by active operations, 
inflicts damage by fire of all weapons and, after brief 
preparation, assaults the enemy again and destroys him. 
  After destroying the enemy airborne assault force the 
company 
(battalion) moves out to a designated area in readiness to 
destroy new assault forces or perform other missions. 
<H5>  6. Features of Battalion Operations in a Regimental Mobile </H5>
Defense 
  The MRB (TB) participates in a regimental mobile defense. 
The 
battalion also may conduct it independently when assigned to a 
forward detachment for defense in the security zone. 
In all cases the battalion as a rule fights at several lines, 
withdrawing successively from one to another, making wide use of 
fire ambushes, emplacing obstacles and performing demolition. To 
perform this mission a battalion may be reinforced by a TC 
(MRC), an artillery battalion, air defense subunits (a platoon), 
combat engineer subunits with obstacle assets, and flamethrower 
subunits. In the course of battle a battalion is supported by 
artillery fire and aircraft under the senior commander's plan. 
  The number of lines for conducting battle and their mutual 
distance are determined in each specific case based on the 
senior commander's concept, mission received and nature of 
terrain. Selection of lines for conducting battle must be given 
careful attention. Where possible, they should run behind 
natural barriers, be covered by engineer obstacles and have 
concealed withdrawal routes. 
  At each line the battalion occupies a defense area in which 
individual company and platoon strongpoints are created 
intercepting the most likely axes of enemy attack and supporting 
the holding of favorable terrain sectors. 
  In connection with this, the frontage of the company 
strongpoint (battalion defense area) will be somewhat larger 
than in a defense under ordinary conditions and may reach 1.5-3 
and 5-10 km respectively. The increased defense frontage will be 
achieved through increased gaps between platoon (company) 
strongpoints. 
  Based on this, the battalion battle formation may be aligned 
in one or two echelons with assignment of a reserve or an 
armored group. The bulk of organic weapons and weapons attached 
to the battalion is attached to companies. It is advisable to 
dispose weapons so there is an opportunity for the majority of 
weapons to conduct fire ahead of the front beginning from 
maximum ranges, cover gaps with adjacent strongpoints by fire, 
and cover the withdrawal of first echelon companies by the fire 
of covering-force subunits and of forward subunits moved back 
into the depth in advance. 
  In accordance with the commander's decision, a combat 
security outpost is put out in front of the battalion FEBA, a 
reconnaissance (combat reconnaissance) patrol is sent out, and 
engineer obstacles are emplaced and fire ambushes arranged on 
probable axes of enemy forward movement. 
  A battalion maneuver to a new line is made with permission 
of 
the regimental commander or of the commander who sent out the 
forward detachment. 
  Engineer obstacles will find wide use during defense in a 
security zone, with preference usually given to minefields. The 
latter are emplaced above all on likely avenues of tank 
approach, ahead of platoon and company strongpoints, in areas of 
probable deployment of enemy nuclear weapons and C[.sup]2[/] 
facilities, and on roads not covered by forward detachments but 
along which the movement of enemy troops is not precluded. 
Highway and railroad bridges across water obstacles as well as 
other structures of important economic and military significance 
are prepared for demolition. 
  The necessary number of artillery subunits is assigned for 
support of the battalion by order of the senior commander. They 
may take up temporary positions both in the security zone as 
well as within the main defensive zone depending on the distance 
of defensive lines. 
  In organizing defense at a line (in the security zone), the 
battalion commander determines the following in addition to the 
usual questions: procedure for fire engagement of the enemy from 
maximum ranges and for prohibiting a swift launching of an 
assault by his main body; possible axes of maneuver of subunits 
and fire to prevent envelopment of the battalion defense area 
(company strongpoints); procedure for disengaging (makeup of 
covering- force subunits, assembly area, and sequence for 
subunits to move to it); procedure for executing a maneuver to 
another line; locations of fire ambushes and for arranging 
obstacles and demolitions. 
  Ground reconnaissance conducted to update a decision is an 
important measure in organizing a defense which permits making a 
substantiated decision on defending a security zone. 
  A forward detachment commander usually conducts ground 
reconnaissance from one or two points. 
  In addition to the usual questions in conducting a mobile 
defense (defense in a security zone), in the course of ground 
reconnaissance the company (battalion) commander studies and 
clarifies accessible axes for operations of enemy tank and 
mechanized infantry subunits in front of each line; clarifies 
the axis for concentration of the forward detachment's main 
efforts at each line, terrain areas on whose holding stability 
of the defense at each line depends, and where platoon (company) 
strongpoints should be prepared, and also clarifies tank and BMP 
fire ambush sites; determines alignment of the forward 
detachment's battle formation at each line and locations of 
forward detachment subunits and their missions at each line; 
establishes the procedure and time periods for engineer 
preparation of lines, creation of obstacles ahead of them and in 
gaps between strongpoints, and also the axes and procedure for 
withdrawal of subunits from line to line and into the main 
defensive zone. In addition, he determines COP locations of the 
forward detachment and of commanders of platoons (companies) and 
of attached and supporting subunits in the battle to hold each 
line, as well as locations of technical and logistic support in 
organizing and conducting defensive battle at each line in the 
security zone, and other questions. 
  In assigning missions, in addition to what is set forth in 
organizing a defense under ordinary conditions, the company 
(battalion) commander indicates to subordinates in the operation 
order the procedure for disengaging, the company (battalion) 
assembly area and procedure for withdrawal to the next line. 
  In organizing the system of fire the battalion commander 
determines the following: most likely axes of enemy forward 
movement to each line, possibility of engaging him from maximum 
ranges by fire of his own, attached and supporting weapons as 
the enemy approaches subunit strongpoints (deploys), and also 
ahead of their frontage, in gaps between strongpoints and on 
exposed flanks; procedure for artillery fire cover of the 
removal of subunits out from under an attack by superior enemy 
forces for their occupation of a defense at the next line or 
during withdrawal into the main defensive zone. (A battalion's 
battle in the security zone is shown in Diagram 6.) As the enemy 
approaches, the battalion determines his makeup and direction of 
forward movement by patrol actions and inflicts losses on him in 
personnel and military vehicles (especially tanks) by fire 
ambushes and the combat security outpost. When the enemy moves 
into the impact zone of battalion weapons and begins deploying 
for an assault of the occupied line, the battalion uses fire of 
organic, attached and supporting weapons to inflict maximum 
losses on the attackers. The battalion's primary mission is to 
prevent a breakthrough of the defense from the move and force 
the enemy to deploy the main body and advance in a direction 
unfavorable to him. Skillfully maneuvering fire and subunits and 
taking advantage of obstacles and demolitions, the company 
(battalion) commander prevents the enemy from capturing 
strongpoints of first echelon companies from the move. 
  Individual enemy attempts to envelop strongpoints (defense 
areas) are prohibited by a maneuver of the reserve (armored 
group) to these axes for taking up a line of firing positions or 
executing a sudden, brief counterattack, and also by a maneuver 
of the fire of artillery remaining directly subordinate to the 
battalion commander. 
  The battalion disengages on receiving a withdrawal order. 
Before or in the course of the withdrawal, the battalion may 
counterattack the enemy with the reserve and with subunits, 
above all tank subunits removed from positions not under attack, 
to halt the enemy advance on the most threatened axes. 
  During execution of a maneuver to the next line, a rear 
security element and if necessary also flank security elements 
are assigned from the battalion to oppose close and deep 
envelopments and attacks of an enemy who has penetrated. Taking 
advantage of obstacles previously created on maneuver routes, 
security elements hold up the enemy's advance by fire from in 
place and from the move and by use of fire ambushes until the 
time indicated by the battalion commander. An enemy airborne 
assault force which has landed on a maneuver route is destroyed 
or bypassed after being sealed off. 
  In the course of a maneuver the battalion may cross a line 
defended by other regimental subunits. In this case the 
defending subunits use the fire of their weapons to destroy the 
enemy, supporting the withdrawing subunit's disengagement and 
not permitting an enemy assault on the occupied line from the 
move. Passage of withdrawing subunits is along established axes 
agreed upon in organizing coordination. 
  With its move to the next line the battalion immediately 
occupies a defense and takes measures to restore combat 
effectiveness. The battle at the new line is conducted just as 
at the previous line. 
  A line of combat security outpost positions ahead of the 
FEBA 
can serve as the final mobile defense line of a battalion 
defending in the security zone. Strongpoints are prepared in 
advance if it is planned for the battalion to shift to a defense 
on it. After occupying them the battalion fights in coordination 
with the combat security outpost. 
  The battle to hold each position and strongpoint should be 
distinguished by tenacity, with the goal of holding up the 
attacking enemy for the longest possible time, exhausting his 
forces and inflicting greatest possible losses on him. 
  In the absence of a security zone, a forward position may be 
established in accordance with the senior commander's decision. 
It has the purpose of concealing the trace of the first position 
and alignment of the battle formation from the enemy, inflicting 
damage on the enemy and forcing him to deploy the main body 
prematurely. The distance of the forward position is determined 
in each specific case by the nature of terrain, expected enemy 
operations and other situation conditions and may be 4-6 km. An 
MRB and sometimes also a reinforced MRC (TC), usually from the 
regimental first echelon, is assigned to fight at the forward 
position. 
  Defense at a forward position is built as separate 
platoon and company strongpoints (Diagram 7) prepared for a 
perimeter defense. It is recommended disposing them so they 
intercept axes most likely and accessible for enemy attack. 
  A forward position usually is selected behind natural 
barriers (streams, rivers and so on) or in the tactically most 
important terrain sectors (hills, road junctions and so on). 
  Minefields and nonexplosive obstacles are emplaced and 
strikes of combat helicopters and aircraft and the fire of 
artillery, tanks, BMP's and other weapons are prepared ahead of 
the position, in gaps between strongpoints and on flanks. Fire 
ambushes may be arranged in addition. 
  The system of fire is organized so the enemy is engaged from 
maximum ranges on primary avenues of likely tank approach by 
fire of all weapons, and so gaps between platoon and company 
strongpoints are covered. Special attention is given to 
organizing AT fire. 
  During battle, small enemy groups are destroyed by fire or 
taken prisoner and significant enemy forces are destroyed by 
fire of all weapons in the very same manner as during battle in 
the security zone. 
  The company (battalion) withdraws from a forward position by 
order of the regimental commander in the very same sequence as 
during operations in the security zone. Subunits which have 
withdrawn usually take up a defense at the second position. 
<H5>  7. Defense of a Water Obstacle </H5>
  Water obstacles, which include rivers, canals, reservoirs 
and 
lakes, are characterized by width; depth; current velocity; 
nature of bed, banks and adjoining terrain; and presence of 
fords and hydraulic engineering works. Water obstacles in 
themselves are a serious barrier for an attacking enemy and a 
favorable natural line for a defender. 
  Special attention should be given to selecting the forward 
edge in organizing the defense. Depending on the condition of 
terrain adjoining the river, it may be designated as close to 
the water's edge as possible or be moved back from the bank to a 
more favorable line. In this case it is necessary to put out a 
combat security outpost and emplace obstacles on the bank. 
  In organizing defense of a water obstacle, in addition to 
usual questions of organizing for battle, the company 
(battalion) commander studies the condition of banks and 
determines the water obstacle's width, depth, current velocity, 
nature of bed and the presence of fords and sectors where its 
forcing by the enemy is possible. 
  The system of fire is organized so approaches to the water 
obstacle and the water's surface, especially fords and sectors 
convenient for forcing, are covered by flanking and cross fire. 
Some of the tanks, BMP's, and AT and other weapons may be moved 
up closer to the bank. 
  The greatest AT fire density is created, obstacles are 
emplaced and fire ambushes are arranged in sectors where enemy 
forcing of the water obstacle is possible, especially by tanks 
fording or crossing fully submerged. In addition, fire is 
prepared against the bank itself for repulsing an enemy who has 
crossed. 
  To reconnoiter the enemy the company (battalion) organizes 
continuous observation, especially of sectors convenient for 
forcing and of approaches to them. Out of direct contact with 
the enemy, a reconnaissance (combat reconnaissance) patrol and 
reinforced combat security outpost usually are sent to the 
opposite bank of the water obstacle. All local crossing 
equipment (boats, rafts, ferries) is assembled on the friendly 
bank and placed under guard; if impossible to assemble, it is 
destroyed. 
  Weapons should not reveal themselves before the beginning of 
an attack. Weapons are specially assigned to destroy enemy 
reconnaissance subunits, and they perform missions from 
temporary positions. Enemy groups which have crossed are taken 
prisoner or killed. 
  With the beginning of an enemy forcing of a water obstacle, 
subunits use fire of all weapons to destroy above all his 
crossing equipment, personnel, weapons and vehicles without 
permitting them to come ashore. In case the enemy comes ashore 
he is immediately destroyed by concentrated fire of all weapons, 
and under favorable conditions also by a decisive counterattack. 
The counterattack must be executed earlier than under ordinary 
conditions to keep the enemy from consolidating on the captured 
bank. Executing a counterattack along the bank is not precluded. 
  Independently or in coordination with other subunits, a 
company (battalion) also may defend on the opposite bank to hold 
bridges, crossings and sectors convenient for forcing which have 
been captured on the water obstacle. In this case a forward 
(bridgehead) position is established. In preparing its defense, 
special attention is given to organizing AT fire and air defense 
and securing flanks. To increase stability of the defense, an 
exposed flank or flanks must abut the water obstacle and be 
covered by obstacles. In this case it is advisable to set up 
additional reserves of missiles, ammunition, food and medical 
supplies in subunits. The actions of a company (battalion) in a 
defense on the opposite bank should be distinguished by special 
staunchness and tenacity. 
<H5>  8. Night Defense </H5>
  Night conditions substantially affect defensive battle. On 
the one hand, they give the defender advantages, use of which 
facilitates performance of defense missions, and on the other 
hand these conditions create a number of difficulties in 
preparing and conducting defensive battle. Orientation on 
terrain, engineer preparation of the strongpoint and emplacement 
of obstacles are hampered at night. The enemy receives a greater 
opportunity to approach the defense covertly, attack suddenly, 
and infiltrate through gaps into the depth of the defense. In 
addition, C[.sup]2[/] of subunits, maintenance of continuous 
coordination, and conduct of aimed fire from all kinds of 
weapons are more complicated and expenditure of ammunition and 
illumination assets increases. 
  Based on this, the primary mission of subunits in a night 
defense is to repel a surprise enemy assault. To perform this 
mission the company (battalion) commander must reinforce the 
combat security outpost; beef up observation of the enemy and of 
friendly obstacles ahead of the FEBA; organize listening; post 
local security in all subunits (observers, two-man patrols and 
so on); keep the bulk of subunits and weapons which are 
occupying strongpoints at the first position in constant 
readiness to commence fire and repel enemy assaults; prepare all 
weapons, the reserve and the armored group for night operations 
while it is light; specify the procedure for using night vision 
devices and for weapons situated in the depth of strongpoints to 
occupy temporary firing positions on the forward edge; indicate 
terrain sectors ahead of the FEBA, in gaps between units 
(subunits) and on flanks against which to prepare additional 
fire and provide for other measures to secure gaps between 
strongpoints and to secure boundaries and flanks; establish the 
procedure for illuminating terrain ahead of the forward edge of 
friendly defense and also the enemy in the course of battle; 
determine reference points easily visible at night, the 
identifying markings of friendly troops and methods of 
orientation; assign missions to subunits for destroying and 
blinding enemy night vision equipment; supply defending subunits 
with tracer rounds, cartridges with tracer bullets, and terrain 
illumination assets. If engineer work is being performed in the 
strongpoint (defense area), the company (battalion) commander 
organizes security for the subunits at work and establishes 
assembly points for them in case an enemy surprise attack has to 
be repulsed. 
  In a defense at night special attention is given to 
illuminating terrain with authorized illumination assets. With 
an illumination norm of 0.6 lux, the range of fire of 30-mm or 
40-mm pyrotechnic flares up to 450- 600 m and a radius of 
illumination of 400-500 m, one illumination post is capable of 
providing terrain illumination ahead of the company defense 
frontage in a sector of up to 2 km. Three illumination posts 
will be required with a battalion defense frontage up to 5 km. 
  Using day sights to ranges up to 1,500 m, it is necessary to 
have an illumination of 1.5-2 lux to ensure observation of 
targets and conduct of direct fire against them. To create that 
illumination it is advisable to use 120-mm illuminating mortar 
rounds and 122-mm illuminating artillery rounds with the flare 
ignition setting at a distance no closer than 1,200-2,300 m from 
the friendly troop disposition. With closer flare ignition, 
friendly subunits may be illuminated and revealed. 
  On detecting the launching of an enemy assault, subunits 
defending the combat security outpost position as well as 
artillery, mortars and duty weapons commence fire against him. 
Tanks, BMP's and artillery conduct direct fire against single 
targets and concentrated fire against the assaulting enemy. 
  It is advisable to repel an enemy assault from distances 
ensuring effective conduct of fire, using night vision devices 
or with the enemy battle formation illuminated by all available 
illumination support assets. When he comes to within 300-400 m 
of the FEBA, illumination is accomplished by first echelon 
company illumination posts and blinding is accomplished using 
illuminating and smoke projectiles (mortar rounds and rockets). 
  Enemy artillery and mortars firing illuminating rounds and 
his searchlight installations are destroyed first by fire of 
artillery subunits, tanks and BMP's (BTR's). 
  The air defense subunit as well as motorized rifle subunit 
and tank subunit not engaged in fighting the ground enemy repel 
raids by his aircraft and helicopters and destroy air-dropped 
illumination flares and illuminating artillery and mortar rounds. 
  In case the enemy penetrates the company (battalion) 
defense, 
steps are taken to prohibit his advance toward flanks and into 
the depth. In this period the company (battalion) inflicts 
damage on the enemy who has penetrated, halts his advance by 
concentrated artillery and mortar fire and by flanking fire of 
tanks, BMP's and the AT subunit, and subunits firmly hold 
important terrain sectors. A counterattack by the second echelon 
(reserve) is conducted at night against the enemy flank and rear 
along previously checked axes. Special attention is given to 
ensuring timely arrival of counterattacking subunits at the line 
of deployment for the counterattack. Guides may be assigned to 
each route for this purpose in addition to the marking of 
forward movement routes. 
  When shifting from night to day operations, subunits and 
weapons which were moved to temporary firing positions for the 
night covertly occupy their own primary positions before dawn by 
order of the company (battalion) commander. 
<H5>  9. Defense in a City and Other Built-Up Areas </H5>
  Cities and built-up areas with a large number of sturdy 
buildings can be turned into powerful centers of resistance by 
defenders in a short time. The presence of sturdy stone and 
reinforced concrete buildings, a far-flung system of underground 
utilities and structures and a significant number of obstacles 
and difficult-to-negotiate sectors help create an insurmountable 
defense that is more stable than under ordinary conditions. 
  In a city (built-up area) a battalion usually defends one or 
more blocks, a company defends a block or several buildings, and 
a platoon defends one or two buildings. 
  Using its own forces, a company (battalion) must turn each 
built-up area and lone structure into an insurmountable fortress 
with a perimeter defense ensuring its lengthy holding even in 
total enemy encirclement. 
  In organizing defense in a city (built-up area), the 
battalion (company) commander determines the following in 
addition to the usual questions: what buildings to include in 
strongpoints and prepare for defense; procedure for maneuver of 
forces and assets; in what rooms to prepare bunkers; and the 
procedure and time periods for preparing buildings for defense. 
  Company strongpoints (battalion defense areas) are created 
so 
they overlap main streets, boulevards, squares and bridges over 
rivers and canals. The FEBA usually is prepared along the 
outskirts of a city (built-up area) or is moved ahead if 
commanding heights adjoin the city. Strongpoints are prepared 
for a perimeter defense and must have fire coordination with 
each other. Additional reserves of missiles, ammunition, food, 
potable water and medical and other supplies are established in 
them. Strongpoints are interconnected by communication trenches. 
  Especially sturdy corner buildings with semibasement and 
basement rooms providing an opportunity for firing on streets 
and squares are used above all to create strongpoints. 
  Buildings must be adapted for defense: block up windows and 
doors with bricks (sandbags) and other materials, make firing 
ports and embrasures for assault riflemen and machinegunners, 
and prepare basement rooms to accommodate personnel. 
  It is advisable to cover wooden floors with sand and clear 
all buildings of highly flammable materials. Barricades, 
obstacles, destructive damage and roadblocks are arranged in 
gaps between strongpoints and on streets, and approaches to them 
are mined and covered by flanking and cross fire. Light 
structures hampering observation and conduct of fire are 
demolished. 
  Passages are made for subunits to maneuver within blocks, 
and 
underground structures and sewers also are used. Obstacles are 
arranged in underground structures not used for maneuver and 
fire is prepared against exits from them. 
  The company (battalion) system of fire is built on a 
combination of flanking and cross fire of small arms, guns 
assigned for direct fire, tanks, BMP's, and also the fire of 
ATGM launchers, grenade launchers, flamethrowers and artillery 
at indirect firing positions. 
  Subunits occupying a defense in multistory buildings 
organize 
fire in several tiers so all approaches to strongpoints 
(buildings) are covered by fire. A large portion of weapons, 
including individual guns, are located in lower stories of 
buildings and in semibasements. 
  Tanks attached to an MRB are used for operations from fire 
ambushes or in MRP strongpoints. Firing positions of tanks, 
BMP's (BTR's) and guns assigned for direct fire usually are 
prepared behind stone fences and walls in which embrasures are 
made and carefully camouflaged. 
  Firing positions of ATGM and grenade launchers are chosen in 
those places from which there is an opportunity to conduct fire 
along streets and squares. 
  Flamethrowers are attached to motorized rifle subunits in 
pairs or groups. Positions are prepared for them in buildings 
and behind obstacles and fences, above all at street 
intersections. 
  The bulk of artillery is attached to battalions and 
companies 
and used primarily for direct fire. The remaining artillery 
subunits take up indirect firing positions in parks, squares, 
stadiums and other places from which there is an opportunity to 
conduct fire. 
  Air defense weapons are situated on roofs of buildings, 
where 
platforms are prepared for them. Observation posts (observers) 
also are placed on roofs of buildings which provide all-around 
observation. 
  Combat engineer subunits with listening devices are assigned 
to detect siegecraft mine warfare work being done by the enemy. 
  A defensive battle on approaches to a city is conducted just 
as under ordinary conditions, but in the city (built-up area) it 
usually is nodal in nature and is conducted for holding each 
strongpoint and building. Subunits defending them must be 
capable of fighting independently even in encirclement. 
Therefore they are reinforced by tanks, artillery, and engineer 
and chemical subunits. 
  Subunits repel an enemy assault by fire of all weapons. In 
this period enemy infantry and tanks should be cut off and the 
infantry destroyed above all, since individual tanks or groups 
of them which have penetrated into the depth of the defense 
without infantry can be destroyed quickly. 
  If an enemy has succeeded in penetrating a defended 
building, 
he must be destroyed by point-blank fire, with grenades, and in 
hand-to- hand fighting. Tanks, BMP's, guns, flamethrowers and 
other weapons outside the building keep enemy reserves from 
approaching it. 
  Counterattacks are conducted by small forces to get back 
individual buildings and strongpoints captured by the enemy. 
<H5>  10. Defense Under Special Conditions </H5>
  Defense in the mountains. Mountainous terrain with 
rugged sectors and a large number of natural barriers permits 
subunits to create an insurmountable, stable defense on a 
broader frontage by intercepting the most accessible axes of 
enemy operations. 
  At the same time, the relief of mountainous terrain hampers 
preparation and conduct of defensive battle. 
  The limited number of roads and presence of scattered axes 
constrain subunit maneuver from one axis to another. Based on 
this, the defense is built at separate strongpoints to hold 
important terrain sectors (commanding heights, passes, road 
junctions and so on). On a plateau and in a wide valley the 
defense is built the very same as under ordinary conditions. 
  Based on this, main efforts are concentrated on the defense 
of commanding heights, passes, road junctions and other 
important terrain sectors. Strongpoints are prepared for a 
perimeter defense. Reconnaissance and patrolling is 
accomplished, fire ambushes are organized and obstacles are 
emplaced in gaps between them. 
  The FEBA must be chosen along slopes of mountain ridges and 
hills and along mountain spurs so as to provide a good field of 
view and fire on approaches to them, and also on reverse 
hillslopes. 
  A limited number of forces and assets are assigned to defend 
axes difficult of access. 
  The system of strongpoints, firing positions and trenches in 
the area (strongpoint) can be quite varied. Motorized rifle 
subunits usually defend in the first echelon. 
  If tanks, AT guns and ATGM launchers are attached to an MRC 
(MRB), they are used in strongpoints of platoons (companies) 
defending on the most important axes. Firing positions for them 
are prepared in those places which provide for conduct of fire 
to maximum range. Roads; exits from gorges, mountain valleys, 
tunnels and narrows; convenient crossings over rivers and 
passages across canyons; as well as axes which may be used by 
the enemy for envelopment must be covered most densely by all 
kinds of fire in combination with obstacles. Subunits defending 
passes, commanding heights, passages and road junctions are 
reinforced by flamethrower operators. 
  The air defense subunit as well as motorized rifle subunits 
assigned to combat the air enemy take up positions on hills 
providing an all- around field of view and fire against 
aircraft, helicopters and other airborne targets. 
  The system of fire must be built with consideration of 
terrain relief features and so there is no dead ground and 
concealed approaches ahead of the FEBA, on flanks and in gaps 
between strongpoints. To this end it is advisable to dispose 
weapons in tiers both on hillslopes facing the enemy as well as 
on reverse slopes, supporting the creation of multitiered 
flanking fire, cross fire and surprise, close-range concentrated 
fire with consideration of the possibility of executing a 
maneuver. 
  In organizing a defense in the mountains, in addition to the 
usual questions the company (battalion) commander determines 
what subunits (weapons) must be ready to destroy an enveloping 
enemy, and he takes into account the possibility of sudden 
changes in weather conditions, rockfalls, snowslides, 
avalanches, mud flows, and flooding of dried-up river channels 
during heavy rains and snow melt. 
  In a defense of a narrow mountain valley (gorge), weapons 
should be disposed on adjoining mountain slopes to ensure that 
the valley (gorge) is covered by cross fire. Hills forming the 
entrance to the valley (gorge) are strengthened most heavily. 
Approaches to commanding heights are covered by the fire of 
artillery; mortar and grenade launcher subunits; AT subunits; 
and AT weapons. Artillery is used widely for direct fire. 
  In organizing defense of a pass, main efforts are 
concentrated on holding hills located on approaches to it. A 
portion of company (battalion) forces must be situated directly 
in the pass. Obstacles are emplaced on roads leading to the pass 
from both sides and approaches to the obstacles should be 
covered by cross fire from adjoining hills. 
  Passes, roads, mountain trails and gorges are not assigned 
as 
company strongpoint boundaries. 
  Main reconnaissance efforts are concentrated on axes 
accessible for enemy attack and on axes where envelopment of 
defending subunits is possible. The number of observation posts 
(observers) is increased. 
  Terrain folds, mines and caves are used widely for 
protection 
against mass destruction and precision weapons. 
  In addition to the usual measures, the clearing of slides 
and 
tree blow-downs blocking the exit of people and vehicles from 
structures is organized immediately in restoring combat 
effectiveness of subunits. 
  Great importance is attached to engineer preparation of 
strongpoints (defense areas) because of terrain relief features. 
Thus, in rocky soils structures primarily of a semiburied and 
fill type are built using rocks covered by a layer of soil as 
well as bags of dirt. In these cases engineer preparation is 
conducted with wide use of demolition charges. Emplacements, 
shelters and other structures are prepared so as to preclude the 
possibility of an incendiary mixture or water flowing into them. 
  Rock roadblocks may be created in a strongpoint (battalion 
defense area) as well as abatis on mountainous woodland; sectors 
of roads (trails) and manmade structures are prepared for 
demolition and minefields are laid on roads. 
  Maskirovka of subunits is achieved above all by skillful use 
of the terrain's concealing properties. 
  An enemy assault is repelled by all weapons with wide use of 
grenades. It is most advisable to destroy enemy tanks when they 
are negotiating upgrades, and especially on serpentines. 
  When the enemy penetrates the defense it is necessary to 
inflict damage on him and hold occupied positions, especially 
commanding heights. Under favorable conditions, an enemy who has 
penetrated is destroyed by a determined counterattack. As a 
rule, it is conducted down from above, along a ridge, or along a 
valley. Before a counterattack it is necessary to deploy 
subunits involved in performing this mission on a previously 
prepared line in advance. This is explained by the complexity of 
the maneuver, especially in conducting a counterattack at night. 
  If the enemy attempts to envelop the strongpoint (defense 
area), he is destroyed by fire of artillery and other weapons 
and by decisive actions of second echelon (reserve) subunits or 
the company (battalion) armored group. 
  In a defense on taiga-covered mountainous terrain, special 
attention is given to preparing strongpoints for a perimeter 
defense, clearing zones (sectors) of view and fire, covering 
gaps and flanks with obstacles, and arranging fire ambushes on 
axes where enemy envelopment of defending subunits is possible. 
  In a defense in the mountains or on taiga-covered 
mountainous 
terrain, battalion technical support and rear subunits are 
located at road and trail junctions in immediate proximity to 
the first echelon. Additional reserves of missiles, ammunition, 
food, water and fuel are established in company strongpoints and 
at artillery and air defense weapon firing positions. In 
high-mountain areas the personnel are provided with special 
gear, warm clothing and sunglasses, and measures for warming 
personnel and promptly evacuating the wounded and sick are 
provided for. 
  Defense in the forest. The forest is a significant 
obstacle to an enemy attack and is not passable everywhere even 
in modern combat vehicles. There are not enough roads in the 
forest, which forces the enemy to operate along accessible axes. 
On the other hand, the forest facilitates maskirovka of 
strongpoints (defense areas) and surprise of subunit operations. 
  Considering relief features, defense in the forest must be 
built as separate platoon (company) strongpoints prepared for a 
perimeter defense. They should be so disposed that they 
intercept roads and openings as well as defiles between lakes 
and marshes. In gaps between strongpoints it is constantly 
necessary to conduct reconnaissance, arrange obstacles and fire 
ambushes and perform patrolling. 
  Preparing a defense in the forest includes the very same 
measures as under ordinary conditions. In addition, the company 
(battalion) commander must provide for disposing BMP's (BTR's) 
and tanks at firing positions so as to bring fire above all on 
roads, openings, treelines and glades and for preparing 
concealed armored group maneuver routes, and he must specify 
measures for fighting forest fires. 
  It is advisable to select the FEBA up to 100 m ahead of the 
treeline or move it into the depth by the very same distance. In 
the latter case a combat security outpost is placed at the 
treeline and subunits clear the woods to improve conditions for 
observing and conducting fire in such a way as not to reveal 
their positions in so doing. The company (battalion) aligns the 
battle formation in two echelons. The second echelon (reserve) 
must be disposed in a strongpoint near roads and openings in 
readiness to execute counterattacks or maneuver to a threatened 
axis. 
  In organizing the system of fire it is advisable to dispose 
all weapons so that axes, roads, passages in marshy sectors, 
glades and felled areas accessible for enemy operations and 
along which an enemy approach and attack are possible are under 
flanking and cross fire of defending subunits. In addition, 
concentrated and barrier fire of artillery and mortars should be 
prepared on these axes. Forest salients are used in the defense 
system for arranging ambushes and organizing flanking fire, 
cross fire and surprise, close-range concentrated fire. 
  Visibility is considerably restricted and C[.sup]2[/] 
deteriorates in the forest. Therefore the bulk of weapons is 
attached to platoons and companies. Tanks, guns, grenade 
launchers and ATGM launchers should be disposed in places 
providing an opportunity to conduct fire along roads and 
openings and against glades and sectors of sparse forest. Their 
firing positions must be covered by motorized rifle subunits and 
obstacles. Some riflemen, snipers and machinegunners are 
assigned to conduct fire from trees. 
  In a defense in the forest, air defense and other weapons 
assigned to combat the air enemy as a rule are disposed in 
glades, on treelines and in felled areas of the forest. This 
permits promptly detecting and bringing fire on enemy aircraft 
and helicopters. Air defense gunners also may be disposed on 
platforms prepared in trees. 
  Reconnaissance in the forest is conducted by observation, 
reconnaissance (combat reconnaissance) patrols and 
reconnaissance ambushes. The system of observation must be 
organized so as to provide for viewing approaches to the FEBA, 
for which observation posts (observers) may be disposed in trees 
or moved forward. 
  Emplacements, shelters, trenches and communication trenches 
of the semifill or fill type are made on terrain with a high 
water table. In sectors where there is no need to dig 
communication trenches, movement routes to the rear are denoted 
by signs or marks on trees. 
  Minefields, fougasses, mined abatis, AT barriers and various 
wire obstacles are used as engineer obstacles in the forest. 
  Above all the forest is cleared for subunits and their 
weapons to improve the field of view and fire, and maneuver 
routes are prepared. Firefighting measures also are provided for. 
  Operations of small subunits in fire ambushes and the fire 
of 
all weapons from short range are widely used during battle in 
the forest. 
  Counterattacks usually are executed by small subunits along 
previously studied and prepared axes, as a rule along roads and 
openings. 
  Defense in the desert. On desert terrain a defense 
is occupied on the most likely axis of enemy operations and is 
based on a well organized system of fire and broad maneuver of 
the second echelon (reserve). The presence of terrain sectors 
with sandhills, dunes and moist solonchaks permits a company 
(battalion) to build a defense in a wider frontage in a single 
echelon with assignment of a reserve and to have larger gaps 
between strongpoints than under ordinary conditions. 
  The battalion defense area and company strongpoints are 
prepared for a perimeter defense and carefully camouflaged. 
Artillery fire is prepared and fire ambushes and obstacles 
arranged in gaps between them. 
  In a defense in the desert, fortification of a position with 
consideration of protection against precision weapons, 
disruptive painting of vehicles, installation of light overhead 
cover (screens) over objects, and other camouflage measures 
receive special attention. 
  In addition to the usual questions of organizing for battle, 
the company (battalion) commander provides for conducting 
reconnaissance to a greater depth than under ordinary conditions 
and engages the enemy by direct fire to long ranges. Reliable 
security of flanks and measures for protecting fortifications 
and water supply points from drifting sand and for preparing 
weapons and vehicles for use during sandstorms acquires special 
importance. Considering the possibility of a change in weather 
conditions, he must take steps to establish water and fuel 
reserves and monitor their consumption and the observance of 
water discipline. 
  In engineer preparation of a strongpoint (defense area) 
special importance is attached to reinforcing the sides of 
emplacements and shelters, for which brushwood, sandbags and 
available local materials are used. Sandbags, curvilinear 
reinforced shells, corrugated steel elements, and fabric-over- 
frame and other factory-made constructions are used for making 
covered fortification structures. 
  Subunit commanders at all levels must keep an eye on the 
condition of maneuver routes. For this it is advisable to mark 
them with easily visible, stable markers and to check minefields 
periodically. If they are drifted over with a thick layer of 
sand or their presence is revealed, new minefields are emplaced 
or existing ones relaid. 
  Company (battalion) technical support and rear subunits 
usually are located with the second echelon (reserve) near water 
distribution points. Special attention is given to strict 
fulfillment of sanitary- hygienic measures in personnel 
locations and at water supply points. Water sources are defended 
by assigned subunits. The condition of weapons and vehicles must 
be checked regularly and additional measures are taken to 
protect them from dust. 
  A defensive battle in the desert is fought just as under 
ordinary conditions. 
  Defense in northern areas and in winter. The 
presence of vast areas of tundra, marshy forested tundra and 
forested terrain, a large number of lakes, mountainous terrain 
with boulders and rock streams, a limited number of roads and 
difficulties of engineer preparation of strongpoints (defense 
areas) substantially affect organization of defense and combat 
employment of subunits. 
  In addition, the severe climate with lengthy winter, deep 
snow cover, low temperature, increased persistence of chemical 
agents and the arctic night and day have a negative effect on 
personnel. 
  At the same time, terrain with a large number of marshes, 
lakes, rivers, hills and other sectors difficult to negotiate, 
and in the winter period the deep snow cover, contribute to 
establishment of a defense with fewer forces than under ordinary 
conditions. 
  As a result, the defense in northern areas (Diagram 8) is 
organized across a broad front on axes accessible for enemy 
attack and usually is built as separate platoon (company) 
strongpoints prepared for a perimeter defense. Defending 
subunits concentrate main efforts on holding roads and adjoining 
hills, built-up areas, defiles between lakes, crossings over 
water obstacles and other important objectives. 
  Based on this, gaps between company and platoon strongpoints 
may be greater than under ordinary conditions. Various obstacles 
are emplaced in them and fire ambushes and patrolling are 
organized. 
  In organizing the defense in northern areas and in winter, 
in 
addition to the usual questions of organizing for battle the 
company (battalion) commander determines the following: axes 
most accessible for enemy operations, especially his enveloping 
subunits, amphibious (lake) assault forces, and raiding and 
reconnaissance parties, and methods of their destruction; 
measures for holding road junctions, built-up areas, hills and 
other important objectives, for securing flanks and gaps, for 
preparing weapons, vehicles and protective gear for operation 
under low-temperature conditions, for preparing shelters to warm 
personnel, and for protecting them against hypothermia and 
frostbite; and the procedure for clearing fortification 
structures and restoring obstacles after heavy snowfalls and for 
making sumps in trenches, shelters and at firing positions under 
thaw conditions. 
  To maintain high combat readiness of subunits the company 
(battalion) commander provides for measures for checking the 
personnel's performance of duty in a blizzard and snowfall. 
  In engineer preparation of a strongpoint (defense area), the 
company (battalion) commander must take account of the depth of 
snow cover, freezing of soil, and thickness and condition of ice 
on water obstacles. In permafrost areas, on rocky soil and on 
marshy terrain fortification structures of the fill type usually 
are built. Rocks, bags of dirt, sod, and in winter snow and ice 
in addition are used for this. Making trenches and communication 
trenches out of snow is widely employed with a deep snow cover. 
If time is available it is advisable to ice up slopes facing the 
enemy. 
  Road sectors in defiles, in places difficult to negotiate 
and 
on approaches to the defense, and cover ahead of the FEBA are 
demolished or mined. Minefields, abatis and boulder obstacles 
are emplaced ahead of the FEBA and in the depth of the defense. 
Ice on rivers, lakes and in bays is prepared for detonation in 
some sectors. 
  In organizing technical and logistic support, the company 
(battalion) commander provides for establishing additional 
reserves of missiles, ammunition, food and fuel and keeping 
weapons and vehicles in constant readiness for use under 
low-temperature conditions. Steps are taken in winter to prevent 
frostbite of personnel. In summer personnel are provided with 
means of protection against midges, mosquitoes and other insects. 
  The battalion aid station usually is located in heated 
spaces 
or shelters and supplied with a reserve of fuel as well as warm 
clothing for the wounded and sick. 
<H5>  11. Relief of Subunits </H5>
  Relief of subunits is understood to mean the organized 
receipt and transfer of strongpoints (defense areas) in a combat 
situation. 
  Relief of a company (battalion) in the defense as a rule is 
done at night and under other conditions of limited visibility. 
It must be organized carefully and conducted swiftly, covertly 
and so that subunits being relieved manage to arrive in the 
designated area before dawn and those which have arrived for 
relief manage to occupy strongpoints (defense areas) and 
organize a system of fire. 
  The procedure and time of relief are determined by the 
senior 
commander. Having received a relief order, the company 
(battalion) commander together with the commander of the subunit 
being relieved performs ground reconnaissance, during which he 
studies the enemy; becomes familiar with the disposition of 
subunits turning over the defense, the regime of behavior, 
organization of the system of fire and air defense, engineer 
preparation of the strongpoint (defense area), obstacles, and 
the NBC situation; and determines concealed movement routes to 
the relief area, locations of traffic control posts, places for 
meeting arriving subunits, and the relief procedure. It is of 
great importance to conceal the time of a relief and operations 
of subunits from the enemy in this period. 
  The subunit commander turning over a strongpoint (defense 
area) is obligated to present the relieving subunit commander 
with a diagram of the company strongpoint (battalion defense) 
area, and in addition he must give him all available 
intelligence on the enemy, with an indication of the precise 
location of weapons and minefields. The following must be 
pointed out to subordinate commanders: procedure for turning 
over a strongpoint (defense area), assembly area after the 
relief, measures for covering the relief and for maskirovka, 
where to send guides for rendezvousing with and accompanying the 
relieving subunits, where to place command posts, time for 
beginning and end of relief, and the procedure for actions in 
case of enemy use of mass destruction weapons or if he launches 
an attack during the relief. 
  Subunits taking over the defense are in assembly areas 
[iskhodnyy rayon] before the beginning of relief. Subunits move 
out along designated routes to the relief area at the prescribed 
time at a signal (command) from the company (battalion) 
commander. 
  Observation and a system of fire are organized immediately 
on 
arrival at the strongpoint (defense area), missions are updated 
for subunits to repel possible enemy actions and the company 
(battalion) begins the relief. Personnel of subunits turning 
over the defense are at their places in readiness to hand over 
their positions and repel possible enemy actions. 
  Motorized rifle subunits are replaced first, then tank, 
artillery and air defense subunits. Subunits defending a forward 
position or in a combat security outpost are relieved last. 
  During the relief the company (battalion) commander 
receiving 
the defense as a rule is at the COP of the commander turning 
over the strongpoint (defense area) and directs the relief. 
C[.sup]2[/] of subunits is exercised over operating wire 
communications lines. 
  During the relief the company (battalion) must maintain the 
very same regime of behavior as was the case before the relief. 
  The company (battalion) commander who has turned over the 
defense covertly moves subunits to the designated assembly area 
and then acts in accordance with the mission received. 
  If the enemy launches an attack in the course of the relief, 
the relief stops and all subunits repel the assault. They are 
controlled at this time by the commander of the subunit being 
relieved. Relieving subunits which have arrived also are 
subordinated to him in this period. Relief of the company 
(battalion) continues after the enemy attack is repelled. 
  Relief of a battalion is formalized by a document. The 
report 
of the company (battalion) commander who has accepted the 
strongpoint (defense area) to his immediate commander about 
completion of the relief is considered to be the moment the 
relief ends. 
<H5>  12. Disengagement and Withdrawal </H5>
  As a kind of maneuver of subunits, withdrawal under present 
conditions is their leaving of occupied strongpoints (defense 
areas) and withdrawing to new lines disposed in the depth. It is 
accomplished to move subunits out from under attacks by superior 
enemy forces and have them occupy a more favorable position for 
subsequent operations. A withdrawal must be made only by order 
or authorization of the senior commander in an organized manner, 
covertly and swiftly, so as to have subunits arrive promptly in 
a prescribed area in a combat-effective status or occupy a 
designated strongpoint (defense area). 
  A withdrawal may be made in a forced or deliberate manner 
depending on the situation. 
  A forced withdrawal will be made when it is impossible to 
repel an enemy assault and hold the occupied strongpoint 
(defense area) with available forces and assets and when the 
situation on flanks creates a real threat of encirclement and 
destruction of a defending subunit. 
  A deliberate withdrawal is accomplished when there is an 
unfavorable ratio of forces and assets with the attacker and an 
unfavorable position of friendly subunits relative to the enemy. 
It can be accomplished to move subunits out from under an attack 
by superior enemy forces and occupy a more favorable position 
with respect to the attacker, transfer efforts to another axis 
or draw the enemy into fire sacks prepared in advance. 
  In all instances the withdrawal should be temporary in 
nature 
and be executed in an organized, planned manner so as not to 
turn into flight and not expose the flanks of adjacent subunits 
being moved out from under enemy attacks. 
  The need for a withdrawal may arise in the course of 
defensive or offensive battle, and also with an unsuccessful 
outcome of a meeting battle and when breaking out of 
encirclement. 
  The disengagement and withdrawal may occur under various 
situation conditions in which the commander's work and subunit 
operations are carried out. The position of subunits relative to 
the enemy is of decisive importance for determining the 
conditions. Based on this it follows that the withdrawal of 
subunits may be made in direct contact with the enemy or out of 
contact with him. 
  As shown by Great Patriotic War experience, our troops most 
often had to withdraw from a position of defense while in direct 
contact with the enemy. The withdrawal is the most frequent and 
complicated phenomenon under these conditions. This is connected 
with the fact that in this period subunits are performing 
several missions simultaneously: defending against an actively 
operating enemy while repelling his assaults from the front and 
flanks; withdrawing subunits from battle and exercising 
C[.sup]2[/] of them; accomplishing a withdrawal as part of 
the regimental (battalion) main body; or operating in the 
advance guard (rear or flank security element or as covering- 
force subunits). 
  More favorable conditions for a withdrawal are created when 
this mission is accomplished out of contact with the enemy. In 
this case disengagement is excluded and subunits begin the 
withdrawal immediately. 
  Disengagement when fighting a defensive battle is a common 
phenomenon and is considered the initial stage of withdrawal. It 
is the removal of subunits from direct contact with the enemy to 
a distance precluding the active effect of his fire and 
providing freedom for subsequent maneuver. 
  A disengagement may occur both in the course of a defensive 
battle as well as in the attack. In the defense it is done to 
withdraw, transfer efforts from one axis to another, execute a 
maneuver, reinforce especially dangerous axes, close breaches 
which formed as a result of enemy use of nuclear weapons, and 
cover exposed flanks; in the attack it is done to transfer 
efforts from one axis to another. 
  A battalion (company) as a rule executes a withdrawal as 
part 
of the regiment immediately to the final line (to the designated 
area) in march formation. 
  Covering-force subunits usually are assigned to cover the 
main body's withdrawal. In terms of their [situation], 
covering-force subunits should be in direct contact with the 
enemy and maintain the previous regime of fire, prevent (stop) 
attempts of enemy reconnaissance to penetrate into the depth of 
the defense (to the main body), repel assaults by his forward 
subunits and not allow an organized transition to the pursuit. 
  One reinforced platoon each from a company defending in 
direct contact with the enemy usually is assigned to be part of 
covering-force subunits. In some cases a company may be assigned 
from a first echelon battalion to perform this mission. 
  Covering-force subunits are supplied with an additional 
reserve of missiles and ammunition and with medical transport. 
  A battalion may be assigned to a rear guard with the mission 
of delaying the attacking enemy for the time necessary for 
withdrawal of the main body. 
  For organized disengagement and withdrawal (Diagram 9), 
subunits operating as part of the main body are assigned 
assembly areas, withdrawal axes or routes, phase lines [rubezh 
regulirovaniya] and a final withdrawal line [konechnyy rubezh 
otkhoda]. 
  The procedure and content of the company (battalion) 
commander's work in organizing disengagement and withdrawal 
depend on situation conditions, the mission received and time 
available. On the whole, it takes place in the very same order 
as in organizing the defense, but has its features. 
  Thus, in the concept for disengagement and withdrawal the 
company (battalion) commander additionally specifies the 
following: final withdrawal line (area) and time of occupying 
it, makeup of covering-force subunits supporting the 
disengagement, and makeup of security elements; procedure for 
disengagement of the main body, assembly areas, and withdrawal 
axis or route; and procedure for evacuating wounded, sick, as 
well as damaged (unserviceable) weapons and vehicles. 
  In the operation order the company (battalion) 
commander indicates the following in assigning combat missions: 
  --For main body subunits--objective of the 
withdrawal, missions, procedure for disengaging, withdrawal axis 
or route, assembly area and time of arrival in it, lines (start 
point and phase lines) and time for crossing them, the final 
withdrawal line (designated area) and for what operations to be 
ready; 
  --For covering-force subunits supporting the 
disengagement--makeup, missions, time up to which they must hold 
occupied positions, and procedure for their further operations; 
  --For artillery subunits, air defense subunit, grenade 
launcher subunit and other weapons remaining directly 
subordinate to the commander--missions and withdrawal procedure; 
  --For security subunits--makeup and missions. 
  In organizing coordination the company (battalion) commander 
must indicate the procedure for disengagement and withdrawal of 
subunits, for transporting or carrying out wounded and sick, and 
for evacuating unserviceable weapons and other vehicles; and 
coordinate actions of covering-force subunits and the procedure 
for their withdrawal, for demolition of important installations, 
for emplacement of obstacles, and for support of the covering- 
force subunits by artillery fire. 
  The time and procedure for disengagement depend on the 
nature 
of enemy operations, mission received and other situation 
conditions. In all cases the withdrawal as a rule must be 
carried out at night or under other conditions of limited 
visibility, but it also may be done during the day. Special 
attention here must be given to combating the air enemy and 
enemy tanks. 
  With the beginning of company (battalion) disengagement, 
covering-force subunits remain at occupied positions until the 
time given them or until the order (signal) for withdrawal, and 
they conduct the very same operations as preceded the 
disengagement. C[.sup]2[/] of these subunits is exercised by 
one of the platoon (company) commanders, who is directly 
subordinate to the company (battalion) commander and maintains 
communications with them. Taking advantage of favorable terrain 
conditions and using fire from occupied positions, the subunits 
repel enemy assaults and his attempts to penetrate into the 
depth of the defense. Artillery subunits assigned for their 
support conduct fire in the previous regime. 
  Taking advantage of concealing properties of terrain, 
subunits of the company (battalion) main body move to platoon 
assembly areas and then to the company and the battalion 
assembly area, assume the necessary march formation, and 
continue movement. 
  Covering-force subunits begin withdrawal at the commander's 
order (signal) after the company (battalion) crosses the line 
occupied by the rear guard. They withdraw suddenly, usually all 
of them simultaneously. If the enemy detects their withdrawal 
and begins pursuit, the covering- force subunits withdraw from 
line to line by bounds, delaying his advance, destroying bridges 
(crossings) and roads sections, and they also emplace minefields 
and other obstacles on enemy movement axes. 
  In a disengagement under conditions of active enemy 
operations, the company (battalion) inflicts damage on him by 
fire of all weapons and if necessary may suddenly counterattack 
with some of the forces or at full strength in order to halt the 
enemy and then quickly disengage under cover of assigned 
subunits, artillery and grenade launcher fire, obstacles, smoke 
and aerosols. 
  In the assembly area the company (battalion) commander 
updates missions for the withdrawal for platoons (companies) and 
means of reinforcement and organizes reconnaissance and 
security. On arrival in the assembly area the company 
(battalion) takes its place in the march formation and continues 
the withdrawal. 
  Company (battalion) security during a withdrawal is 
accomplished by the rear security element and if necessary also 
by flank security elements, which delay the enemy's advance by 
fire from the move and from in place and by operations of fire 
ambushes until the time indicated by the battalion commander. By 
order of the battalion commander, security elements also may 
demolish bridges (crossings) and road sections and emplace 
minefields and other obstacles. 
  A battalion assigned for operations in the rear guard takes 
up a defense at the indicated line in advance and holds it until 
the prescribed time or until the order to withdraw. Under all 
situation conditions it must support the regimental main body in 
breaking contact with the enemy and making an organized 
withdrawal. 
  A rear guard withdraws by authorization of the regimental 
commander successively from line to line or by leapfrogging, 
where some subunits withdraw to the next line, occupy positions 
on it across a broad front and support withdrawal of the other 
battalion subunits. In a withdrawal, wide use is made of fire 
ambushes, obstacles and demolitions. After accomplishing the 
mission the rear guard acts by direction of the regimental 
commander. 
  Battalion technical support and rear subunits not used for 
immediate support of the disengagement are withdrawn to the 
designated area in advance. The wounded and sick as well as 
unserviceable weapons and vehicles are evacuated ahead of time. 
Footnotes 
  1. See "Taktika v boyevykh primerakh: Polk" [Tactics in 
Combat Examples: The Regiment], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1974, p 194. 
  2. See "Taktika v boyevykh primerakh: Polk," pp 196-197. 
  3. See "Taktika v boyevykh primerakh: Polk," p 198. 
  4. See "Taktika v boyevykh primerakh: Polk," p 200. 
  5. See "Razvitiye taktiki strelkovykh podrazdeleniy 
Sovetskoy 
Armii v gody Velikoy Otechestvennoy voyny" [Development of 
Soviet Army Rifle Subunit Tactics in the Great Patriotic War], 
Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1988, p 214. 
  6. See "Razvitiye taktiki strelkovykh podrazdeleniy 
Sovetskoy 
Armii v gody Velikoy Otechestvennoy voyny," pp 214-215. 
  7. See "Taktika v boyevykh primerakh: Rota," [Tactics in 
Combat Examples: The Company], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1974, pp 
