<H5>  Chapter V - The Offense </H5>
<H5>  1. Essence and Characteristic Features of Offensive Battle. </H5>
Conditions and Methods for a Company (Battalion) To Launch an 
Attack 
  The history of wars convincingly attests that only the 
offense leads to decisive victory over the enemy. It is the sole 
kind of battle by whose conduct total rout (destruction) of the 
enemy and capture of important lines (areas) and objectives is 
achieved. Herein specifically lies the objective of the offense. 
  Engagement of the enemy with all available weapons, a 
decisive assault, a swift advance of subunits into the depth of 
his battle formation, the killing and capture of personnel, 
capture of weapons and military vehicles, and the taking of 
planned lines (areas) are the essence of modern offensive 
battle. A rout of the enemy is achieved by skillful use of all 
weapons, decisive exploitation of results of artillery fire and 
air strikes, a timely buildup of efforts into the depth, wide 
use of maneuver of forces and assets, and delivery of assaults 
against his flank and rear. 
  The offense must be conducted with full exertion of efforts, 
at a high tempo, nonstop, day and night in coordination with 
subunits of all combat arms and special troops. 
  As one of the basic kinds of battle, the offense has a 
number 
of advantages over the defense. Above all, the initiative in 
operations, in choosing the axis, time and methods of delivering 
an attack against the enemy, in executing a maneuver to the 
flank and rear, and in imposing one's will on him belongs to the 
attacker. A successful offense lifts the morale of attacking 
subunits and at the same time sharply degrades the morale and 
mental state of the defending enemy. 
  The offense may be conducted against an attacking, 
withdrawing or defending enemy. While the attack against an 
attacking enemy is accomplished by a meeting battle and against 
a withdrawing enemy by the pursuit, against a defending enemy it 
usually begins with a penetration of his defense. 
  Penetrating the defense consists of breaking it by strikes 
of 
all kinds of weapons and by a determined assault of tank and 
motorized rifle subunits in a narrow sector, creating a breach 
in the defense and subsequently expanding it into the depth and 
toward the flanks. 
  Sometimes there may be considerable gaps, breaches and 
exposed flanks in the enemy defense. In this case the attack 
begins with fire damage of the enemy and an assault by a portion 
of forces of subunits from the front and by the other forces 
from flanks and rear through the weakest places in the defense. 
The attack usually will be conducted on a broader front than in 
a penetration of the defense. 
  A company and battalion do not penetrate the enemy defense 
independently, but take an active part in its penetration and 
development of the attack. 
  A company (battalion) may attack in the first echelon, make 
up a second echelon or combined arms reserve of the battalion 
(regiment), or operate in an enveloping detachment or a special 
detachment. A company may be assigned to a forward security 
element (when the regiment is attacking with forward movement 
out of the depth and in pursuit of the enemy), and a battalion 
may be assigned to act as an advance guard (above all in pursuit 
of the enemy), forward detachment, raiding detachment or 
amphibious assault force. An MRC (MRB) in addition may be 
employed in a tactical airborne assault force or be the basis of 
an assault team (assault detachment). 
  Means of warfare, especially nuclear and precision weapons, 
have seen further development in recent years, the proportion of 
armored vehicles in units and subunits has grown, the 
effectiveness of artillery and aviation has increased, and 
engineer vehicles and means of combat, technical and logistic 
support have been upgraded. Because of this, decisiveness of 
objectives, high fluidity, intensity and dynamic nature are 
characteristic features of the modern offense. It acquired a 
ground-air nature, the essence of which is accomplishment of 
simultaneous fire damage to the full depth of the enemy troop 
alignment with use of more diverse methods of performing combat 
missions in a difficult electronic environment. 
  The ground-air nature of the offense presumes the delivery 
of 
a combination strike against the enemy and accomplishment of 
more decisive methods of routing him. A simultaneous strike by 
attacking subunits (units) from the front and by tactical 
airborne assault forces from the rear in coordination with 
aviation, especially helicopters, is achieved. Fire superiority 
of the sides beginning from distant approaches is strengthened 
in a modern offense, and the role of maneuver grows. 
  The attack by a company (battalion) may be carried out under 
varying situation conditions. Situation conditions are 
understood to mean factors exerting an influence individually or 
in the aggregate on the procedure and content of commanders' 
work of preparing for battle, especially work of organizing it, 
and also on methods of launching and conducting the attack. 
Those factors basically are the following: employment of 
conventional or nuclear weapons and other weapons; makeup, 
status and nature of the enemy defense; situation, status and 
combat capabilities of friendly subunits by the beginning of the 
attack, and also time available for preparing the attack; nature 
of terrain, condition of weather, time of day and year, and the 
NBC situation. 
  When an attack is conducted using only conventional weapons, 
the enemy is routed by reliable fire damage of his immediately 
opposing forces and assets, with a simultaneous effect on 
reserves and important objectives in the depth of the defense, 
and also by a decisive buildup of efforts to exploit success. 
Under these conditions a successive rout of the defending enemy 
is the basic method of conducting the attack. Subunits usually 
will assault him on a relatively lesser frontage (in a 
penetration sector). In addition, they must be in constant 
readiness to conduct an attack employing nuclear weapons. 
  In attacking an enemy who has shifted to the defense in 
advance, a company (battalion) often will have to cross his 
security zone, in which the enemy will establish nuclear 
minefields. 
  Under conditions of the use of nuclear weapons, the basic 
method of the attack is simultaneous engagement of the enemy and 
important objectives by nuclear strikes to the full depth of the 
defense with subsequent completion of his rout by decisive 
operations of tank and motorized rifle units and subunits. Also 
of great importance are effective steps to disrupt and weaken 
enemy nuclear strikes, subunits' decisive exploitation of 
nuclear and fire damage in order to complete the enemy's rout, 
and beating him to the punch in restoring combat effectiveness 
of friendly subunits and organizing their subsequent operations. 
Under these conditions subunits decisively assault the enemy on 
a broader frontage and usually operate along axes. As a rule, 
with the need to negotiate zones of radioactive contamination 
and sectors of destructive damage, their advance will be uneven 
along the front and into the depth of his defense. 
  Before launching an attack on a defending enemy a company 
(battalion) may take up an attack position [iskhodnaya 
pozitsiya] (assembly area [iskhodnyy rayon]) in direct contact 
with the enemy or be in an assembly area in the rear of friendly 
troops. 
  A company (battalion) may launch an attack against a 
defending enemy from a position of direct contact with him or 
from the move. 
  Based on defensive doctrine, in the initial period of war 
the 
basic method is to launch an attack from a position of 
direct contact with the enemy after regrouping. The essence 
of this method is that the company (battalion) commander's work 
in organizing the attack is done on the terrain and its 
preparation is completed on the whole in direct contact with the 
enemy. A company (battalion) launches an attack in the 
previously established battle formation. It is formed after the 
necessary regrouping from a position of defense and sometimes, 
under favorable conditions, simultaneously with the relief of 
defending subunits while moving forward out of the depth. In 
that method of launching an attack, subunits have an opportunity 
to study the enemy and terrain in advance, but the company 
(battalion) will be in the effect zone not only of enemy 
tactical nuclear attack weapons, but also of his artillery for a 
relatively long time. It is easier for a defending enemy to 
discover the forces and assets of attacking subunits. All this 
hampers preservation of their combat effectiveness and requires 
careful fortification of the attack position (assembly area) and 
conduct of measures for ensuring concealment and achieving a 
surprise assault. 
  In this method of launching an attack, an MRC is assigned an 
attack position equal in size to the company attack frontage and 
consisting of a trench or trenches, the adjoining communication 
trenches, and firing positions of BMP's (BTR's) and attached 
weapons. If it is impossible for BMP's (BTR's) to occupy firing 
positions covertly with their company near the FEBA, they may be 
placed at an attack position or assembly position 
[vyzhidatelnaya pozitsiya] together with tank subunits. The 
attack position of a first echelon MRC is specified in the first 
trench, and that of a second echelon company in the second and 
third trenches. 
  In order to occupy an attack position, the battalion is 
assigned an assembly area (Diagram 10). It should provide for 
concealed disposition of subunits and their least vulnerability 
to all enemy weapons and must be on the axis of attack. 
  An assembly area is specified for a first echelon battalion 
within the first defense position. It is limited from the front 
by the first trench, from the rear by the depth of disposition 
of battalion forces and assets and from the flanks by its 
boundaries. The following are basic elements of the area: attack 
positions of motorized rifle subunits (three trenches with 
communication trenches) and sometimes of tank subunits; firing 
positions of organic and attached artillery and other weapons, 
including those assigned to conduct direct fire, and launch 
(firing) positions of air defense subunits; sites of 
C[.sup]2[/] facilities; routes providing concealed approach, 
disposition and rapid forward movement of the battalion for 
launching an assault; and lines of deployment and departure of 
the tanks. Attack positions of tank subunits are designated 2-4 
km from the enemy FEBA in the case where there is concealment 
against enemy observation and listening. 
  An assembly area as a rule is chosen for the regiment's 
second echelon battalion at the second defense position. An 
assembly position usually is designated for a TB 5-7 km from the 
enemy FEBA. Terrain at the position must provide concealed 
disposition of tanks, their least vulnerability to all kinds of 
enemy weapons and convenience of moving up to the line of 
departure. 
  The essence of a hasty attack is that preparation 
for battle is accomplished in a period when subunits are out of 
contact with the enemy and their forward movement, deployment 
and transition to the assault are conducted nonstop, from the 
move. This method of attack has not only a number of advantages, 
but drawbacks as well: the personnel's physical exertion and 
consumption of fuel and other supplies increase in connection 
with forward movement to the enemy FEBA. The possibility exists 
that during forward movement it will be necessary to cross (or 
bypass) areas of destructive damage, minefields laid by remote 
minelaying equipment, and zones of radioactive and chemical 
contamination, centers of fire and areas of flooding. The enemy 
may deliver nuclear and fire strikes against subunits in the 
period of forward movement, especially with precision combat 
systems. Reliable fire support is accomplished by the senior 
commander's forces and assets to weaken these enemy strikes. 
  An attack usually is launched from an assembly area, which 
is 
assigned to the battalion with an area of up to 10 
km[.sup]2[/]. The battalion usually is disposed in it by 
company with means of reinforcement. A company is disposed in 
the area under cover along the route of forward movement, taking 
advantage of the terrain's protective and concealing properties. 
  The distance of the assembly area from the enemy FEBA should 
preclude engagement of the subunits in the area by artillery 
fire and provide concealment against radar reconnaissance 
assets. The least time possible should be spent moving up to the 
enemy FEBA. Shelters are made for personnel, weapons and 
military vehicles and the area is prepared for defense if 
necessary. Security, air defense, maskirovka, and protection 
against mass destruction and precision weapons are organized in 
it. The ATP and GLP are disposed together with or behind first 
echelon MRC's. The air defense subunit is disposed at firing 
positions in readiness to fire on airborne targets. 
  For organized forward movement, deployment, and assurance of 
simultaneous transition to an assault, the company (battalion) 
usually is assigned a forward movement route, start point 
(line), point (line) of deployment into platoon (company) 
columns, line of departure and safety limit (Diagram 11). In 
addition, a dismount line also is specified for the dismounted 
assault of an MRC (MRB). 
  Places for personnel to board tanks as a mounted force are 
designated for motorized rifle subunits in motor vehicles if 
necessary. 
  A start point (line) is intended for a prompt beginning of 
company (battalion) forward movement from the assembly area. Its 
distance from the assembly area should allow the battalion 
column with means of reinforcement to extend and begin movement 
at a given speed. This distance may be 5-10 km. 
  A route is designated for movement of subunit columns up to 
the first deployment line. Subsequently forward movement will be 
accomplished along cross-country routes. 
  The point (line) of deployment into company columns is 
intended for beginning the battalion deployment into company 
columns. Its distance from the enemy FEBA should ensure that 
tanks and BMP's (BTR's) cannot be engaged by fire of enemy 
ATGM's, tanks and guns assigned for direct fire and may be 
within 4-6 km. 
  The point (line) of deployment into platoon columns is 
designated where possible behind terrain folds 2-3 km from the 
enemy FEBA. Engagement of tanks and BMP's by short-range ATGM 
fire and the fire of IFV guns and other infantry weapons should 
be precluded with their arrival at this line. 
  A line of departure is chosen so that forward movement of 
first echelon companies to it is covert. The distance of the 
line should ensure effective fire from the main kinds of weapons 
of assaulting subunits and permit them to reach the enemy FEBA 
at the designated H hour nonstop at maximum speed. The line of 
departure may be up to 600 m from the enemy FEBA and sometimes 
even more depending on the nature of the enemy defense, degree 
of fire damage, terrain conditions and methods of assault. 
  The motorized rifle subunit dismount line is designated as 
close to the enemy FEBA as possible, usually in places providing 
cover from the fire of his machineguns and short-range AT 
weapons. Based on exercise experience, the dismount line was 
300-400 m from the enemy FEBA. This permits preserving the 
motorized riflemen's energy for the assault dash and at the same 
time ensures their safe distance from friendly artillery 
shellbursts at the moment they dismount. 
  The safety limit is specified so as to preclude damage of 
forward moving subunits from casualty-producing factors of a 
nuclear strike (strikes) delivered by friendly troops against 
enemy strongpoints on the forward edge. 
  Under favorable situation conditions, especially in the 
course of developing an attack, a company (battalion) may 
assault the enemy by deploying into battle formation from march 
columns, i.e., directly from the march. This makes it 
considerably more difficult for the enemy to execute a maneuver 
and at the same time helps achieve surprise. In this situation 
organization for battle usually is accomplished in movement or 
during short halts. Subunits launch the assault as they approach 
the FEBA. 
<H5>  2. Company (Battalion) Attack Frontage, Combat Missions, </H5>
Means of Reinforcement and Battle Formations 
  A company (battalion) attacks in a certain frontage 
determined by its place in the battle formation, its role in 
performing the battalion (regimental) mission, the subunit's 
status and combat capabilities, weapons employed, the defender's 
forces and nature of terrain. 
  Thus, the company (battalion) attack frontage will be 
relatively less when attacking using conventional weapons in the 
regimental penetration sector, i.e., on its main axis of attack. 
At the same time, the company (battalion) attack frontage as a 
rule is wider in operations using nuclear weapons or on another 
axis of regimental attack (not the main one). 
  When attacking in the regimental penetration sector, a 
company (battalion) should attack in that frontage which would 
ensure necessary superiority over the enemy in tanks, BMP's, 
ATGM's and small arms. In the Great Patriotic War a successful 
attack on a deliberate enemy defense required subunits of the 
attacking echelon to create a ratio of 6:1 in tanks and SP 
artillery to enemy tanks and 4:1 in rifle companies in the 
penetration sector. That superiority also is needed under 
present conditions, since subunit combat capabilities are 
growing approximately the very same both for us as well as for 
the probable enemy. 
  Consequently, to determine the company (battalion) attack 
frontage in the regimental penetration sector using only 
conventional weapons, it is necessary to create the indicated 
superiority in forces and assets. Damage done to the enemy in 
tanks and IFV's in appropriate periods of fire engagement, which 
should be at least 60 percent, is taken into account. In this 
case losses of our tanks, BMP's and small arms from enemy fire 
may reach 10- 20 percent. In addition, tank (motorized rifle) 
subunits interworking with (attached to) an MRC or TC (MRB or 
TB) are taken into account in calculations. Thus, the company 
(battalion) attack frontage is determined based on combat 
capabilities of ATGM-equipped BMP's, tanks and small arms. 
  Based on the initial data set forth above, the methodology 
of 
calculating company attack frontage can be as follows, and the 
following are determined in so doing: 

  -  number of ATGM-equipped IFV's and Dragon and TOW ATGM 
systems of the defending enemy mechanized infantry task force 
(made up of three mechanized infantry companies and one TC) with 
consideration of losses from our fire damage; 
  -  density of AT weapons and tanks per kilometer in the first 
echelon of the enemy battle group defending in a frontage of 5 
km (it is considered that up to 70 percent of AT weapons and 
tanks are disposed in the group's first echelon); 
  -  number of 
ATGM-equipped BMP's and tanks necessary for creating a 
superiority of 5-6 times over the enemy per kilometer of attack 
frontage; 
  -  number of BMP's and tanks used in the company attack with 
consideration of permissible losses from enemy fire; 
  -  company attack frontage on condition of establishing 
requisite 
superiority in ATGM-equipped BMP's and tanks over the 
enemy. 


    Let us determine the attack frontage of a BMP-equipped MRC 
interworking with 5-6 tanks (or of an MRB reinforced by a TC). 
  The enemy battalion task force may have 80 ATGM-equipped 
IFV's, Dragon and TOW ATGM systems and tanks, or 32 counting 
losses from our fire damage (up to 60 percent). Around 23 of 
this number of AT weapons and tanks are used in the task force 
first echelon, which will comprise a density of around 5 per 
kilometer with its defense frontage of 5 km. To establish a 
superiority of 5- 6 times over the enemy it is necessary for the 
attacking company to have 25-30 tanks and BMP's per kilometer. 
In the course of the attack, counting permissible losses (up to 
20 percent), an MRC will have 12 BMP's and tanks: (10 BMP's + 5 
tanks) x 0.8. By establishing the necessary superiority, a 
company is capable of attacking in a frontage of 400-600 m, 
i.e., up to 500 m with that number. 
  Let us examine the frontage in which an MRC is capable of 
attacking based on combat capabilities of small arms. The 
following are determined: 

  -  cumulative effective rate of small arms fire of the enemy 
task force first echelon subunits with consideration of losses 
(at least 50 percent) from our fire damage; 
  -  density of enemy fire (number of bullets) per meter per 
minute; 
  -  necessary bullet density per meter of frontage per minute 
with 
consideration of a superiority of 3-4 times over the enemy; 
  -  cumulative effective rate of fire of the company in one 
minute 
with consideration of permissible losses from enemy fire (10-20 
percent); 
  -  company attack frontage. 


    In accordance with the above methodology, let us determine 
an 
MRC's attack frontage based on requirements of achieving the 
necessary small arms ratio. 
  The cumulative effective rate of fire of first echelon 
mechanized infantry subunits of a battalion task force (there 
are two mechanized infantry companies) counting losses (50 
percent) is 24,375 bullets in one minute (rifles--111x175)+(M60 
machineguns--9x250)+(MG3 machineguns- -18x150). With a task 
force defending a frontage of 5,000 m, enemy fire density will 
be 4-5 bullets per meter per minute. To establish a superiority 
of 3-4 times, a company must ensure a density averaging 15-16 
bullets per meter per minute. The cumulative effective rate of 
fire of an MRC is 9,750 bullets (AK [Kalashnikov assault 
rifle]--39x100)+(RPK [Kalashnikov light machinegun]-- 9x150)+(PK 
[Kalashnikov machinegun] and PKT [Kalashnikov tank machinegun]-- 
18x250). Counting permissible losses (20 percent), the rate of 
company small arms fire will be 7,800 bullets in one minute. 
Consequently, to create requisite bullet density per meter of 
frontage, the company must attack in a frontage up to 500 m 
(7,80015=520 m; 7,80016=480 m; (520+480)2=500 m). 
  In what frontage is an MRB (TB) capable of conducting a 
successful attack? The methodology of this calculation is the 
very same as for determining company attack frontage. The 
difference lies only in the fact that it is necessary to take 
into account the density of all forces and assets of the enemy 
battalion task force in its defense frontage, not just of its 
first echelon. 
  Let us calculate the attack frontage of an MRB reinforced by 
a TC based on the need for creating a superiority over the enemy 
in ATGM- equipped BMP's and tanks. 
  There may be ATGM-equipped IFV's, Dragon and TOW ATGM 
systems 
and tanks numbering 80 in a battalion task force defense, or 32 
counting losses from our fire damage (80x0.4). That number of AT 
weapons and tanks permits creating a density of approximately 6 
of them per kilometer (with the force defending in a 5 km 
frontage). To establish a superiority of 5-6 times over the 
enemy, an attacking battalion must have 30-36 ATGM-equipped 
BMP's and tanks per kilometer of frontage. In an MRB reinforced 
by a TC, counting losses there may be 32-34 ATGM-equipped BMP's 
and tanks: (30 BMP's+10 tanks)x0.8=32. Consequently, a battalion 
is capable of conducting a successful attack in a frontage up to 
1,000 m (based on creating the necessary superiority in ATGM- 
equipped BMP's, ATGM systems and tanks). 
  The attack frontage of an MRB based on the presence of its 
small arms should be determined according to the methodology of 
calculating a company frontage, but it is necessary to take into 
account small arms existing in the enemy task force. 
  When nuclear weapons are used, in connection with 
destruction 
of the defending enemy's main forces and assets, a company 
(battalion) attack frontage will be wider than when conventional 
weapons are used. This frontage should ensure interworking among 
subunits and their operations in approach march formation and 
along axes, bypass of destructive damage, and convenience of 
observation and C[.sup]2[/]. Based on this, combat training 
experience has shown that under the conditions in question a 
company is capable of conducting an attack against a defending 
enemy in a frontage up to 1,000 m and a battalion in a frontage 
up to 2,000 m. 
  In conducting an attack on another axis (outside the 
penetration sector), a company and battalion will require 
approximately half the forces and assets to achieve necessary 
superiority per kilometer of frontage. This is explained 
basically by the fact that on such an axis the enemy usually 
will defend on a wider front (for example, a battalion will 
defend up to 8 km) and in addition, the company (battalion) will 
have a more limited mission to perform than in the regimental 
penetration sector. 
  Intervals between attacking tanks and BMP's may reach 100 m, 
and this makes it convenient for observation and C[.sup]2[/]. 
In addition, these intervals permit BMP's to conduct fire 
between attacking tanks, which may execute the assault in a 
zigzag (S-weave) without interfering with each other in the 
course of the assault. Continuous engagement of enemy infantry 
in the attack frontage is provided by single-layer gun fire when 
fire is conducted by tanks attacking with intervals up to 100 m, 
and with double-layer gun fire with intervals of 50 m. 
  It is necessary to specify combat missions for subunits 
correctly in organizing an attack. The procedure of their 
operations also depends on the combat missions. The combat 
mission is the basis for organizing battle, including 
coordination and comprehensive support. 
  It is apparent from the calculations cited above for 
determining attack frontage against a defending enemy that a 
reinforced company is capable (with the necessary superiority) 
of inflicting damage on his personnel and weapons in the platoon 
strongpoint and continuing to advance into the depth. A 
reinforced battalion in turn has an opportunity to crush the 
enemy to the full depth of the battalion defense in the attack 
frontage and preserve forces and assets for continuing it. The 
capability of the company and battalion to inflict such damage 
on the enemy is their common mission. As shown by the experience 
of wars and exercises, based on effective range of fire by 
tanks, BMP's and small arms and also on the need for maximum 
involvement of weapons to engage the enemy in assault 
objectives, a reinforced company is capable of realizing its 
combat capabilities in the initial alignment of the battle 
formation, which also is retained for subsequent operations, 
i.e., when the company attacks, all its forces and assets must 
take part in the assault simultaneously. A reinforced battalion 
is forced to change the initial alignment of forces and assets 
for full utilization of its combat capabilities and for 
performing the common mission (routing the enemy to the depth of 
defense of his battalion) in order to retain necessary 
superiority in forces and assets. 
  In this connection, in an attack on a defending enemy the 
overall combat mission of a first echelon battalion is divided 
into two intermediate missions--immediate and subsequent 
(Diagram 12). The company mission is not divided--it is assigned 
only an immediate mission. The company and battalion commander 
are given a direction for continuing the attack to orient them 
for subsequent operations after performing common missions. 
  As a rule, the combat mission is characterized by 
tactical content and depth. The content of the combat mission is 
destruction of a specific enemy at a specific point (in a 
specific area) and taking of a line on the terrain by a 
designated time. Mission depth is determined by the distance of 
the line to be taken from the enemy FEBA or from the line of the 
previous mission. 
  The enemy unquestionably is the primary objective of the 
attack. Only with destruction (capture) of personnel and damage 
(seizure) of weapons is its goal achieved. Routing the enemy and 
taking a line is a unified process. The line which should be 
taken must be a tactical line favoring the attackers (seizure of 
a hill, water obstacle (bridgehead), pass, opposite edge of the 
forest and so on). 
  Thus, the immediate mission of a first echelon 
company (also including a TC attached to an MRB) is to 
destroy the enemy in the first echelon platoon strongpoint and 
take the strongpoint. Mission depth may be up to 0.5 km. The 
direction for continuing the attack is indicated in such a way 
that it supports performance of the battalion's immediate 
mission. 
  The immediate mission of a second echelon company 
when committed may be to complete destruction of the enemy in 
strongpoints in the depth of the defense together with first 
echelon companies and take the first position. The direction for 
continuing the company attack is assigned so as to ensure 
performance of the battalion's subsequent mission. Mission depth 
may be 3 km or more. 
  The immediate mission of a first echelon battalion 
as a rule is to destroy the enemy in strongpoints of first 
echelon companies in its own attack frontage and take them. The 
subsequent mission is to develop the attack, rout the enemy in 
the depth of the defense area in coordination with adjacent 
battalions and take the first position. The direction for 
continuing the attack is determined so as to ensure performance 
of the regiment's subsequent mission. The depth of missions may 
reach up to 2 km for the immediate and 3 km or more for the 
subsequent mission. 
  The immediate mission of a second echelon battalion 
when committed may consist of completing the destruction 
of enemy brigade (regimental) reserves together with first 
echelon battalions and taking their line. The depth of the 
immediate mission may be 5-7 km and sometimes even more. 
  New missions are assigned to a first echelon company and 
battalion after performance of combat missions. As with second 
echelon subunits, they usually are assigned one mission and a 
new direction for continuing the attack. The mission content may 
differ and is determined by the existing situation. Under some 
conditions the mission may be to develop the attack into the 
depth and take an important line and, under others, to repel an 
enemy counterattack. 
  To perform combat missions during an attack, a company 
(battalion) is reinforced by subunits of other combat arms and 
special troops. Depending on the assigned mission, a mortar 
(artillery) battery and an AT, grenade launcher, flamethrower 
and combat engineer squad may be attached to the MRC and an 
artillery battery, MRP and combat engineer squad may be attached 
to the TC. In addition, the MRC (TC) may be supported by fire of 
an artillery (mortar) battery and interwork with a tank 
(motorized rifle) company (platoon). 
  An MRB (TB) usually is reinforced by one or two TC's 
(MRC's), 
an artillery battalion or battery, combat engineer platoon, 
subunits of AT and air defense weapons, subunits of chemical 
troops, mineclearing equipment, bridgelayer, obstacle-clearing 
engineer vehicle (or BAT route clearance dozer) and other 
equipment. In addition, the battalion is supported by fire of an 
artillery battalion, sometimes by combat helicopters, and is 
covered by air defense weapons in the regimental system. 
  An MRC attached to a TB as a rule is resubordinated to TC's 
by platoon. A TC attached to an MRB usually operates at full 
strength and is directly subordinate to the battalion commander. 
A TC may be attached to MRC's by platoon when attacking in a 
city, in the mountains, in the forest and against a fortified 
area. 
  The mortar (artillery) battery and GLP operate at full 
strength in direct subordination to the battalion commander. 
Sometimes the battery is attached by platoon and the GLP by 
squads to first echelon MRC's. The AT squad (platoon) as a rule 
remains at the disposal of the company (battalion) commander and 
operates at full strength. 
  To perform the assigned mission in an attack against a 
defending enemy, company (battalion) forces and assets are 
aligned in a battle formation which should conform to the 
mission, concept of upcoming battle and situation conditions at 
hand. 
  The following requirements are placed on the battle 
formation 
in the attack. It is aligned so as to ensure the following: 
successful conduct of the attack with employment both of 
conventional as well as nuclear weapons; timely concentration of 
efforts on the selected axis; maximum involvement of weapons in 
the battle and full use of subunits' combat capabilities; 
decisive damage to the greatest possible depth; swift 
exploitation of results of nuclear and fire damage of the enemy 
and of favorable terrain conditions. The need for building up 
efforts in the course of battle and executing a maneuver, least 
vulnerability of subunits to strikes of all kinds of weapons, 
maintenance of continuous coordination, and convenience of 
C[.sup]2[/] also are very important requirements placed on 
the battle formation alignment. 
  A typical feature of the modern company (battalion) battle 
formation is their greater tactical and fire independence than 
in the Great Patriotic War. This is explained by the fact that 
at the present time the company and battalion possess higher 
striking power, firepower and mobility. In addition, subunits of 
other combat arms and special troops are attached to or support 
them. In connection with this the number of elements of the 
battle formation has increased and its alignment is becoming 
more varied than before. 
  As a rule, the battle formation of a company in the attack 
is 
aligned in a single echelon and consists of platoons and 
reinforcing weapons and subunits which remain directly 
subordinate to the company commander. The battalion battle 
formation may be formed in one or two echelons. It consists of 
first echelon companies with means of reinforcement, a second 
echelon or reserve, and also reinforcing weapons and subunits 
remaining directly subordinate to the battalion commander. 
  The first echelon is intended for performing the immediate 
mission and in addition must develop the attack into the depth. 
Therefore it must be stronger. Thus, as a rule all MRP's are 
used in the first echelon of the MRC and interworking tank 
subunits attack with them in addition. Usually two and sometimes 
even three reinforced MRC's (less a platoon) and tank subunits 
attached to the MRB are used in the MRB first echelon. 
  The battalion second echelon, usually up to a company, 
performs the mission of exploiting success of the first echelon 
in the depth of the enemy defense, widening the penetration of 
the defense toward the flank. In addition, it may be used to 
repel a counterattack, replace subunits which have lost combat 
effectiveness, and destroy the enemy remaining on the flanks and 
in the rear of the first echelon. A specific combat mission is 
assigned to the second echelon simultaneously with the first 
echelon. 
  A reserve is assigned when there is a single-echelon 
alignment of the battalion battle formation. It is intended for 
performing missions arising in the course of the attack. From a 
platoon to a company is assigned to the reserve. A combat 
mission is assigned to it during commitment. 
  The attached artillery battalion (battery) is used to 
destroy 
and neutralize enemy means of nuclear and chemical attack, 
tanks, AT weapons, C[.sup]2[/] facilities and electronic 
equipment, demolish fortifications and provide illumination 
support. 
  Supporting artillery subunits perform fire missions in 
support of the company (battalion) under the battalion 
(regimental) commander's plan. 
  Air defense subunits are used for combating low-flying 
aircraft, helicopters and drones and destroying enemy airborne 
assault forces at low and medium altitudes. Being in the battle 
formation, air defense subunits conduct fire against airborne 
targets in movement or from short halts. 
  The AT squad of the MRC (MRB) and AT grenade launcher 
subunits are intended for destroying enemy tanks, IFV's and 
other armored targets. They also may be employed for destroying 
weapons, including those in fortification structures, and for 
combating helicopters. 
  The MRB's GLP is intended for engaging enemy personnel and 
weapons outside of shelters, in open emplacements (trenches) and 
behind terrain folds. 
  The attached subunit of engineer troops basically is used in 
the course of an attack for performing engineer reconnaissance 
of terrain, destroying enemy nuclear mines, breaching obstacles 
and destructive damage, making crossings over barriers and 
preparing and maintaining crossings. 
<H5>  3. Fire Engagement and Methods of Assault </H5>
  The goals of fire engagement are as follows: destroying 
(neutralizing) means of nuclear and chemical attack and the main 
enemy grouping; winning and maintaining fire superiority over 
the enemy; disorganizing C[.sup]2[/] and fire control; 
disrupting his air defense system and operation of the rear; and 
creating favorable conditions for units and subunits to perform 
combat missions successfully. These goals are achieved by 
comprehensive fire effect on the enemy by forces and assets of 
subunits of the Armed Forces, combat arms and special troops 
using missiles and ammunition filled with conventional means. 
  Fire engagement is organized, planned and carried out by the 
senior commander and his staff and is conducted to a 
considerable depth of the enemy defense. 
  Missile subunits, artillery, aviation (including army 
aviation), weapons of defending units (subunits), as well as 
tanks, ATGM launchers and guns for direct fire, ordinarily 
assigned from second echelons of units, usually are used for 
fire engagement in support of attacking troops. 
  Fire engagement of the enemy in an attack usually 
is planned for three periods: fire preparation of the assault, 
fire support of the assault, and fire accompaniment of attacking 
subunits in the depth. Sometimes it may be conducted for the 
last two periods in a meeting battle and when the battalion 
(regimental) second echelon is committed. 
  Fire engagement of the enemy includes artillery and air 
engagement. In taking part in it, artillery uses the following 
types of fire: against a single target, concentrated, massed, 
standing barrier, rolling barrier, successive fire concentration 
(it may be single, double or triple), rolling barrage (single, 
double) and so on. 
  Battalion artillery and artillery attached to the company 
(battalion) may employ fire independently against a single 
target, concentrated fire and standing barrier fire and also be 
used to conduct massed fire, rolling barrier fire and a rolling 
barrage as part of or together with the regimental artillery 
group. 
  Fire preparation of the assault is accomplished 
before subunits launch the assault and is conducted to a 
considerable depth of the enemy defense. Thus, back in the Great 
Patriotic War a trend appeared toward increasing the depth of 
simultaneous fire engagement of the enemy, which at the end of 
the third period often reached 15 km and more. 
  The goal of fire preparation of the assault is to inflict 
damage on means of nuclear and chemical attack, artillery, AT 
weapons, tanks, personnel and weapons in defense strongpoints, 
the C[.sup]2[/] system, precision weapons, air defense 
weapons, electronic equipment and so on. 
  When launching an assault against a defending enemy from a 
position of direct contact with him, fire preparation of the 
assault begins when subunits are ready for the assault and ends 
with the arrival of tank subunits at the line of departure from 
assembly areas (attack positions). 
  In an attack launched from the move, fire preparation of the 
assault begins when first echelon subunits approach the line 
reached by enemy artillery fire, but not later than when they 
reach the line of deployment into battalion columns, and ends 
with the subunits' arrival at the line of departure. 
  Duration of fire preparation of the assault basically 
depends 
on preparedness of the defense and its necessary degree of 
damage, extent of fire missions to be performed, artillery's 
technical capabilities and ammunition available and may be 
around one hour. 
  Fire preparation of the assault is conducted by several 
artillery fire assaults and usually by one air raid of front 
aviation. In the first fire assault artillery usually engages AT 
weapons, tanks and personnel in platoon strongpoints of 
companies of the first line, as well as artillery, mortars, and 
C[.sup]2[/] facilities of first echelon battalions. In the 
middle of artillery preparation, fire assaults are conducted 
against targets both in the depth of the enemy defense (in 
second echelon battalions) as well as on the forward edge (in 
the first position), especially against AT weapons and tanks. 
Fire preparation of the assault ends with a powerful artillery 
fire assault against strongpoints of the first line and against 
C[.sup]2[/] facilities. 
  Tanks, ATGM's, guns and other weapons assigned for direct 
fire destroy and neutralize above all enemy AT and armored 
weapons on the FEBA and in its immediate depth in the period of 
fire preparation of the assault. 
  Air preparation of the assault is accomplished by front and 
army aviation, which most often performs its missions in the 
middle and at the end of fire preparation, when artillery is 
neutralizing the enemy at the first position. 
  Fire support of the assault is conducted to keep 
the enemy from restoring the disrupted system of fire and 
C[.sup]2[/] and to create conditions for assaulting subunits 
to complete the enemy's rout. This is achieved by engaging means 
of nuclear attack, elements of the automated artillery fire 
control system, AT weapons, tanks and other targets which have 
been newly detected or have come alive. 
  Fire support of the assault begins with arrival of first 
echelon subunits at the line of departure and is conducted 
continuously to the depth of defense of the enemy first echelon 
brigade (regiment) (8-10 km and sometimes even more), with main 
efforts concentrated on damaging him at the first position. 
  Artillery support of the assault may be conducted by a 
rolling barrage, successive fire concentration, concentrated 
fire against single targets or a combination of these methods. 
Basic methods of artillery support of the assault to the depth 
of the enemy first echelon battalion may be a successive fire 
concentration or rolling barrage, since these methods conduct 
fire against several lines simultaneously and thus provide for 
engaging AT weapons at a considerable depth. 
  Front aviation destroys newly detected targets in the depth 
of the enemy defense, and combat helicopters in pairs and 
flights deliver strikes against tanks, other armored targets, AT 
weapons and counterattacking enemy subunits. 
  Fire accompaniment of attacking subunits in the 
depth begins following the end of fire support of the 
assault and, depending on the nature of the defending enemy, is 
accomplished to the depth of new missions assigned to subunits 
in developing the attack in the enemy defense. 
  The basic method of artillery accompaniment of subunits' 
attack in the depth is concentrated, massed and barrier fire and 
fire against single targets. Air accompaniment of the attack is 
accomplished by delivering strikes against newly detected means 
of nuclear attack, approaching reserves, airfields, 
C[.sup]2[/] facilities and other targets. Army aviation 
delivers simultaneous or successive strikes against a 
withdrawing enemy, above all against tanks and AT weapons. 
  Nuclear strikes may be delivered against the enemy before 
troops launch an attack and in its course. 
  The company (battalion) commander's skillful use of 
principles of fire engagement of the enemy is of great 
importance in achieving success in the attack. The most 
important principles are the following: massing of weapons on 
the axis of concentration of main efforts; swift maneuver of 
fire; close, continuous coordination of attacking subunits and 
weapons; assurance of survivability of weapons from enemy fire 
strikes; surprise delivery of fire strikes against the enemy; 
continuous fire pressure on the enemy; and flexible control of 
subunits and weapons. 
  Fire engagement is organized in the company (battalion) in 
accordance with the situation and mission received. It is an 
important component in organizing the attack as a whole and 
usually includes the following: making the decision for fire 
engagement; assigning missions to weapons, including those 
assigned for direct fire; organizing coordination among weapons 
and assaulting subunits; organizing fire control; establishing 
safety measures for subunits in conducting fire; and monitoring 
readiness of weapons to perform missions. 
  Under conditions where the company (battalion) attacks as 
part of a battalion (regiment), the bulk of fire engagement 
matters are decided by the senior commander, including with the 
involvement of battalion weapons. In this case the commander 
usually determines the following based on a mission analysis and 
situation estimate: secondary missions for organic, attached and 
supporting artillery (if fire capabilities exceed the scope of 
missions assigned it by the senior commander) by periods of fire 
engagement; missions for weapons assigned for direct fire; 
missions for weapons in the capture of strongpoints, repulse of 
counterattacks, commitment of follow-on forces, consolidation of 
the captured line and so on; and procedure for interworking of 
weapons. In the course of estimating the situation the company 
(battalion) commander may listen to commanders of organic, 
attached and supporting artillery subunits about missions they 
have received and fire capabilities. 
  Fire engagement of the enemy is organized by the company 
(battalion) commander to the full extent when a company 
(battalion) is performing a mission independently in isolation 
from the main body (such as during operations in a special or 
enveloping detachment, and for the battalion in addition in a 
forward or raiding detachment). 
  In the decision for fire engagement he usually specifies the 
following: missions for organic and attached artillery by 
periods of fire engagement; procedure for engaging the enemy by 
fire of tanks, BMP's (BTR's), grenade launchers and other 
weapons when destroying the enemy in the course of performing 
the mission; weapon readiness times to perform the mission. Fire 
engagement missions are assigned to subunits in the operation 
order. 
  In organizing coordination the procedure and time of forward 
movement of artillery and weapons assigned for direct fire and 
of their occupation and preparation of firing positions are 
updated; the procedure for fire engagement by periods is 
coordinated; distribution of enemy objectives (targets) for 
engagement by fire of artillery and other weapons is clarified; 
the procedure for shifting from fire preparation to fire support 
of the assault as well as the beginning and end of fire by 
weapons assigned for direct fire and the procedure for their 
further actions is indicated; the procedure for requesting, 
transferring and ceasing fire in the course of battle is 
established; artillery fire and air strikes are coordinated with 
subunit actions in penetrating the defense and developing the 
attack, in repelling counterattacks, during commitment of 
follow-on forces and in performing other missions; and methods 
of marking the front line and the procedure for target 
designation for aviation are clarified. 
  Depending on the degree of fire damage of the enemy, the 
nature of his defense and terrain and the outfitting of 
motorized rifle subunits with combat vehicles, the assault is 
accomplished by two methods: dismounted following tanks, or in 
BMP's (BTR's) without dismounting the personnel. Tank subunits 
assault the enemy in an extended line under any situation 
conditions. 
  An assault is a swift, nonstop movement of tank 
and motorized rifle subunits in battle formation in combination 
with intensive fire from tanks and BMP's (BTR's) and, as they 
close with the enemy, also from other kinds of weapons for 
purposes of destroying him. It is the most decisive moment of 
the attack and is conducted at a fast tempo with full exertion 
of attackers' efforts. 
  Success of the assault largely is ensured by its 
forcefulness, the daring of attackers' actions, surprise of the 
strike, swiftness of the maneuver and a continuous combination 
of fire and movement. 
  In terms of time of operations it is a day or night assault 
and in terms of directions of conduct it is frontal, flanking 
and from the rear. The assault begins from attack positions or 
from a line of departure depending on methods of launching the 
attack. 
  A dismounted assault by motorized rifle subunits is 
conducted 
in penetrating a deliberate enemy defense and fortified areas, 
and also on very rugged or difficult terrain for tanks and BMP's 
(BTR's). Dismounted personnel attack in an extended line 200-250 
m behind the extended line of tanks, which ensures their mutual 
support. 
  After personnel dismount, gunner-operators (machinegunners), 
drivers and deputy platoon commanders remain in the BMP's 
(BTR's). BMP's (BTR's) displace by bounds from cover to cover 
(from line to line) behind assaulting subunits at a distance 
which would ensure their reliable fire support. BMP's with 
stabilized weapons usually attack directly in the extended line 
of their own subunits. 
  Motorized rifle subunits in motor vehicles as a 
rule assault the enemy in dismounted formation. In some cases 
they may operate as a mounted force on tanks (especially in the 
season of bad roads, in the presence of a deep snow cover and so 
on). After the personnel dismount, motor vehicles proceed to 
designated assembly sites and are disposed by company or by 
battalion 2-4 km from the enemy FEBA. The battalion commander, 
or the company commander with his permission, summons motor 
vehicles to the subunits. 
  A dismounted assault permits motorized rifle 
subunits to accomplish it to the full depth of the combat 
mission only at a relatively slow tempo, on the order of 1-1.5 
km/hr, which is confirmed by Great Patriotic War experience. It 
is natural that the tempo of the direct assault on the enemy 
FEBA should be higher by approximately 2-3 times or more. During 
development of the battle in the depth, when subunits execute a 
maneuver in approach march formations and in columns, the tempo 
of the attack naturally will be higher than when destroying the 
enemy at positions. 
  The assault by motorized rifle subunits is 
accomplished in BMP's (BTR's) under situation conditions where 
the enemy defense has been reliably neutralized by fire and a 
large portion of his AT weapons have been destroyed, in an 
attack on a hastily occupied defense that has had insufficient 
engineer development, and on favorable terrain. 
  In this case the tanks assault right after friendly 
shellbursts, and motorized rifle subunits in BMP's (BTR's), in 
an extended line 100-200 m behind the tanks, destroy AT weapons 
and other targets by their fire. 
  Tanks and BMP's (BTR's) should move up to the line of 
departure and directly into the assault at a speed of 15-20 
km/hr or more. Remember that the higher the speed of tanks and 
BMP's (BTR's) when closing with the enemy, the faster his zone 
of continuous, multilayered fire is crossed and consequently 
also the greater the degree to which their survivability 
increases. 
  With this method of assault, motorized rifle subunits are 
provided with high tempos of advance as a whole to the full 
depth of combat missions. The high assault tempos permit 
subunits to exploit results of fire and nuclear damage of the 
enemy in shorter time periods and hamper him in closing breaches 
in the defense and executing counterattacks. War and exercise 
experience shows that with an increase in assault tempos by one 
and one-half times, losses of assaulting subunits to enemy fire 
are reduced by 2-3 times. 
  Close interworking of tank, artillery and motorized rifle 
subunits and subunits of other combat arms and special troops 
must be achieved with any methods of assault. 
<H5>  4. Preparation of an Attack Against a Defending Enemy </H5>
  Preparation of the attack begins in the company (battalion) 
on receiving a combat mission. It envisages conduct of a set of 
measures, the most important being the following: organization 
for battle; preparation of the company (battalion) to perform 
the combat mission; preparation of the attack position (assembly 
area); organization and conduct of political work; practical 
work of the company commander (battalion commander, his deputies 
and staff) in the subunits; and other measures. 
  It should be noted that under present conditions in 
connection with qualitative change in means of warfare, the 
scope of work to prepare the attack has grown sharply on the one 
hand and the time for performing it has been shortened on the 
other. Thus, while 2-3 days usually were spent at the 
battalion-company level to prepare the attack in the past war, 
now the time has decreased considerably. 
  Organization for battle includes the following: 
decisionmaking by the company (battalion) commander for the 
attack; ground reconnaissance; assignment of combat missions to 
subunits; and organization of coordination; fire damage of the 
enemy, comprehensive support and C[.sup]2[/]. 
  The procedure and content of the company (battalion) 
commander's work of organizing for battle are determined by 
situation conditions and above all by methods of launching the 
attack, the combat mission and time available. Thus, in 
launching an attack from a position of direct contact with the 
enemy, the company (battalion) commander has an opportunity to 
perform all work of organizing for battle directly on the 
terrain. 
  It should be noted that when launching an attack from a 
position of direct contact with the enemy, simultaneously with 
questions of organizing for battle, the company (battalion) 
commander also decides questions of regrouping or relieving 
defending subunits. When launching an attack after regrouping 
from a position of defense, organization for battle on the 
terrain (in the direction of attack) is accomplished in the 
period when the company (battalion) is in the strongpoint 
(defense area) under enemy fire pressure. But when launching an 
attack with simultaneous relief of defending subunits or from 
the move, battle is organized on the terrain in the 
concentration area and in the assembly area respectively out of 
contact with the enemy. 
  Sometimes when attacking from the move there will be no 
opportunity to travel out on the terrain with subordinate 
commanders. In this case organizing for battle is done in the 
assembly area from a map or on a terrain model, but during 
subunits' forward movement to the line of departure and with the 
beginning of the assault the commander updates the mission and 
coordination procedure for them. 
  In a situation where it is necessary to participate in 
penetrating a defense (as a rule, hastily occupied) in the 
course of developing the attack, the company (battalion) 
commander is forced to make a decision from the map and assign 
missions to subordinates during their forward movement toward 
the enemy defense. Missions and the coordination procedure are 
updated for the subunits in the period of deployment into 
approach march and battle formations and with the beginning of 
the assault. 
<H5>  5. Company Commander's Work of Organizing the Attack From a </H5>
Position of Direct Contact With the Enemy 
<H5>  (Variant) </H5>
  Tactical situation (Fig. 6) 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-010L-83A>      Fig. 6. 2nd MRC commander's decision for the attack </FIG>

  As a result of losses, the enemy has been forced to cease 
the 
attack and by the end of 5 July shifted to a defense at the line 
reached. 
  Our subunits withdrew to a prepared defensive line along the 
east bank of Chernyy Brook, halted the enemy advance, and 
simultaneously are preparing for an attack. 
  At 1200 hours 6 July 1st MRB commander assigned missions to 
subunit commanders in the vicinity of the farmstead and 
organized coordination, from which the 2nd MRC commander learned 
the following: 
  1. 1st MRB with 2nd TC is launching an attack after 
regrouping from a position of defense. The battalion destroys 
the enemy in the company strongpoint barn, Bibirevo, Hill 108.0 
and takes the line Kvadratnaya Grove, Sinkovo. The battalion 
concentrates main efforts in the direction of sand pit, 
windmill. 1st Artillery Battalion is supporting. 
  2. 2nd MRC with grenade launcher squad in coordination with 
2nd TC (less TP) destroys the enemy in the platoon strongpoint 
barn, rocks (excluded), Hill 105.0 by an assault from the attack 
position barn (excluded), farmstead and takes the line Hill 
110.0 (excluded), sheepfold. Direction for continuing the 
attack--lone house, Hill 108.0. 1st Battery, 1st Artillery 
Battalion is supporting. Report decision at 1320 hours. 
  Begin regrouping at 2230 and complete it by 2400 6 July; 3rd 
MRP relieves 1st MRC and 2nd MRP relieves subunits of 3rd MRC. 
  3. 4th MRC on right destroys enemy in vicinity of spruce, 
barn, Hill 102.0 and takes the line lone house, Hill 110.0; 
direction for continuing attack-- north slopes of Hill 110.0, 
barrow. 
  Boundary with it is lone tree (excluded), bushes, 
Kvadratnaya 
Grove. 
  1st MRC on left destroys enemy in vicinity of rocks, 
Bibirevo, Ovalnaya Grove and takes the line sheepfold 
(excluded), Belaya Grove; direction for continuing 
attack--Ovalnaya Grove, north outskirts of Sinkovo. 
  4. In period of fire preparation of assault artillery 
neutralizes enemy artillery and mortars and destroys tanks, 
IFV's and ATGM's on FEBA and in depth of enemy battalion defense 
area; artillery support of assault is by double successive fire 
concentration to depth of defense of enemy battalion. 
  5. Readiness for attack 0400 7 July. 
  2nd MRC defends strongpoint barn, Hill 104.3, Veselovo 
(excluded). 
  Company is 85 percent strength in personnel, weapons and 
military vehicles. Two BMP's require routine maintenance. 
Strength level of opposing enemy is 60-65 percent. 
  Mission analysis 
  The company attacks to destroy the enemy in platoon 
strongpoint barn, rocks (excluded), west slopes of Hill 105.0 
and takes the line Hill 110.0 (excluded), sheepfold. Direction 
for continuing attack is lone house, Hill 108.0. Support 
battalion performance of immediate mission in this manner. 
  In his commander's concept, 1st MRB commander envisages the 
following: by concentrating main efforts in direction of sand 
pit, windmill, destroy enemy in company strongpoint barn, 
Bibirevo, windmill with an assault by two MRC's from attack 
positions in coordination with the TC and take the line 
Kvadratnaya Grove, Sinkovo. Subsequently develop the attach by 
committing the second echelon, complete the rout of enemy 
battalion's personnel and weapons in coordination with 2nd MRB 
and take the first position. In the period of fire preparation 
of the assault the mortar platoon, four ATGM's, a tank and an 
IFV are destroyed (neutralized) in support of the company. 
Artillery support of the assault is by a double successive fire 
concentration to the depth of defense of the enemy battalion. 
  2nd MRC with grenade launcher squad has the mission of 
destroying the enemy in platoon strongpoint barn, rocks 
(excluded), west slopes of Hill 105.0 in coordination with 2nd 
TC (less TP) by an assault from the attack position barn 
(excluded), farmstead and taking the line Hill 110.0 (excluded), 
sheepfold; direction for continuing attack is lone house, Hill 
108.0. 
  The company attacks in a frontage of 450 m in the first 
echelon on the battalion right flank, with its left flank 
adjoining the axis of concentration of battalion main efforts. 
Company main efforts also should be concentrated on this flank. 
  4th MRC, 2nd MRB attacks on right, destroys enemy personnel 
and weapons in vicinity of spruce, barn (excluded), Hill 102.0 
and takes the line lone house, Hill 110.0; direction for 
continuing the attack--north slopes of Hill 110.0, barrow. 
  Boundary with it is lone tree (excluded), bushes, 
Kvadratnaya 
Grove. 
  On left our battalion's 1st MRC destroys enemy in vicinity 
of 
rocks, Bibirevo, Ovalnaya Grove and takes the line sheepfold 
(excluded), Belaya Grove; direction for continuing the attack is 
Ovalnaya Grove, north outskirts of Sinkovo. 
  In organizing coordination it is advisable to update with 
4th 
MRC commander the procedure for destroying the enemy on south 
slopes of Hill 110.0, and with 1st MRC commander the procedure 
for engaging the enemy in the vicinity of Ovalnaya Grove. It is 
desirable above all to update with TP commanders the procedure 
for the joint assault, negotiation of obstacles and barriers, 
fire coordination and target designation. 
  Readiness for attack 0400 7 July; a total of 16 hours are 
available for preparing for battle and 12 hours for preparing 
and executing a regrouping. 
  [Begin side line] After analyzing the mission the company 
commander determines measures which must be carried out for 
fastest preparation of subunits to perform the combat mission, 
performs a time calculation, issues instructions to platoon 
commanders and the grenade launcher squad commander on preparing 
to perform the combat mission and on the time and procedure of 
work on the terrain, and estimates the situation. [End side line] 
  Time calculation 
  Mission received 1200 hours 6 July. 
  Readiness for attack 0400 7 July. 
  There are 16 hours for preparing the attack, of which around 
9 hours are daylight, and there are 12 hours for preparing and 
executing a regrouping. 
  Distribute time as follows: 

  -  analyzing mission and determining measures which must be 
taken immediately--1200-1210 6 July; 
  -  calculating the time--1210-1220; 
  -  issuing instructions to commanders on preparing to perform 
the 
combat mission and on the time and procedure of work on the 
terrain--1220- 1230; 
  -  preparing subunits to perform the combat mission--1230 6 
July-0330 7 July; 
  -  estimating the situation--1230-1300; 
  -  making the decision--1300-1320; 
  -  briefing decision to battalion commander--1320-1340; 
  -  conducting ground reconnaissance with commanders of platoons 
and of attached and supporting subunits--1340-1600; 
  -  assigning missions to commanders of platoons and attached 
subunits and organizing regrouping, coordination and fire 
engagement-- 1600-1700; 
  -  issuing instructions on organizing comprehensive support of 
attack, C[.sup]2[/], and political work--1700-1715; 
  -  work of platoon commanders with squad commanders for 
organizing 
battle on the terrain--1715-1915; 
  -  return of commanders and practical work in their own 
subunits--1915-2130; 
  -  practical work in subunits for preparing 
them for battle-- from 1930; 
  -  conducting regrouping with 
simultaneous turnover of strongpoints of 2nd and 3rd MRP's to 
subunits of 1st and 3rd MRC's--2230-2400; 
  -  report of subunit commanders on readiness for attack--0330 7 
July; 
  -  report to battalion commander on company readiness for 
attack--0400 7 July. 


    Situation estimate (conclusions) 
  The enemy shifted to a defense along west bank of Chernyy 
Brook. 
  A mechanized infantry platoon with tank is defending ahead 
of 
the company attack frontage. A company second echelon platoon is 
defending in the depth of the company strongpoint in vicinity of 
Kvadratnaya Grove (excluded), windmill (excluded), Hill 108.0. 
Enemy is concentrating main efforts on axis Hill 104.7, north 
slopes of Hill 108.0. Weakest defense is in direction of sand 
pit, windmill. Emplacements for mechanized infantry squads, 
emplacements for tanks and IFV's, covered slit trenches, 
sections of continuous trenches in the platoon strongpoint, 
obstacles ahead of the FEBA and in the depth of the defense, 
lines of firing positions and other engineer structures may be 
prepared in his defense by the beginning of the company attack. 
  Destruction of enemy personnel and weapons in the 
strongpoint 
barn, rocks (excluded), Hill 105.0 will sharply reduce stability 
of his defense and support performance of immediate mission. 
Company is at 85 percent strength and, with consideration of 
fire damage by senior commander's weapons, is capable of 
performing the assigned mission by fire of organic and attached 
weapons in coordination with 2nd TC (less platoon). 
  4th MRC, 2nd MRB and 1st MRC, 1st MRB are attacking on right 
and left respectively, and conditions for coordination with them 
facilitate joint destruction of the enemy on contiguous flanks. 
  The nature of terrain is favorable and permits achieving 
relatively high assault tempos; Chernyy Brook is not a barrier. 
  It is advisable to concentrate main efforts in direction of 
sand pit, tower. 
  Execute dismounted assault, with 2nd MRP on right flank, 1st 
MRP in center and 3rd MRP on left flank, and with grenade 
launcher squad behind 1st MRP. 
  It is advisable to assign combat missions to subunits as 
follows: 

  -  2nd MRP in coordination with Tank No 101 is to assault and 
destroy emplaced tank, ATGM, AT rocket launcher and enemy 
personnel from attack position of barn (excluded), rocks; 
direction for continuing the attack-- barrow, north edge of 
Ogurets Grove; 
  -  1st MRP in coordination with tanks Nos 102 and 103 is to 
assault and destroy enemy ATGM, machinegun and personnel from 
attack position of rocks (excluded), rock pillar; direction for 
continuing attack--Hill 100.2, lone tree; 
  -  3rd MRP in coordination with 2nd TP is to assault and destroy 
enemy ATGM, IFV, AT rocket launcher and personnel from attack 
position of rock pillar (excluded), farmstead; direction for 
continuing attack--Romb Grove, tower; 
  -  1st Grenade Launcher Squad is to neutralize personnel at 
company COP in trench on north edge of Romb Grove. Firing 
position--300 m northeast of rock pillar. In the course of 
assault the grenade launcher squad is to neutralize enemy 
personnel and weapons ahead of frontage of 1st and 3rd MRP's and 
is to displace behind left flank of 1st MRP; 
  -  company COP is behind 1st MRP, displace it in direction of 
rock 
pillar, north slopes of Hill 105.0, Hill 108.0. 

  [Begin side line] After the situation estimate and 
performance of necessary tactical calculations the company 
(battalion) commander makes the decision. 
  The basis of the decision is the commander's concept, in 
which the company (battalion) commander specifies: direction for 
concentrating main efforts; methods of routing enemy (which 
enemy, where, in what sequence and how to rout, with an 
indication of the procedure for his engagement by fire of tanks, 
BMP's and other organic and attached weapons, measures for his 
deception, and procedure of subunit operations); company 
(battalion) battle formation. After reporting the decision to 
the senior commander, the company (battalion) commander performs 
ground reconnaissance. 
  Ground reconnaissance is performed to study terrain and the 
enemy and update the decision made from the map. It is done by 
commanders under cover of subunits defending ahead or of 
specially assigned subunits. The company (battalion) commander 
involves commanders of subordinate, attached and supporting 
subunits in the ground reconnaissance. If it is impossible for 
company commanders to travel out on the terrain with their 
subordinates, the battalion commander also involves commanders 
of platoons of first echelon companies in ground reconnaissance. 
  With the ground reconnaissance party's arrival in the 
vicinity of the subunit defending in the direction of the 
company (battalion) attack, communications are established with 
its commander, who usually subsequently gives help in studying 
the enemy himself. 
  Then the company (battalion) commander performs orientation, 
designates reference points and updates the trace of the enemy 
FEBA, disposition of enemy strongpoints and weapons, especially 
AT weapons, and targets to be engaged by senior commanders' 
weapons. Enemy weapons, observation posts and other targets for 
engagement by fire of guns and tanks assigned for direct fire, 
by ATGM's and by the fire of grenade launchers are determined. 
Possible axes of operations of enemy combat helicopters and 
their lines of attack are updated. Approaches to the enemy FEBA 
and the presence and nature of obstacles and barriers are 
studied, and passages in them, time of preparation and procedure 
for marking these passages are outlined. The commander updates 
and determines the attack frontage, direction for concentrating 
main efforts, combat missions for subunits, enemy objectives 
(targets) subject to fire engagement, firing positions of 
weapons and time periods of their engineer preparation. Points 
for equipping tanks with roller-type mineclearing devices, 
forward movement routes, and points (lines) of deployment, 
departure and the safety limit are designated and updated. Sites 
and directions of displacement of C[.sup]2[/] facilities and 
places for deployment of technical support and rear subunits are 
determined. 
  In an attack from a position of direct contact with the 
enemy, the company (battalion) commander additionally updates 
the attack positions (assembly area) of the company and platoons 
and places for passing tanks through positions of the motorized 
rifle subunits. If the attack is launched from the move, then in 
moving along the route the ground reconnaissance party 
additionally studies its features, the start point (line), and 
deployment points (lines); updates bypass routes and crossing 
(fording) sites; and updates lines of departure for platoons 
(companies). In a dismounted assault the MRC (MRB) commander 
specifies the platoon (company) dismount line. [End side line] 
  Operation order 
  1. The enemy shifted to a defense along west bank of 
Chernyy Brook. Platoon strongpoints have been 
prepared ahead of the company attack frontage in areas: barn, 
rocks (excluded), west slopes of Hill 100.2; 
Kvadratnaya Grove (excluded), windmill (excluded), 
Hill 108.0. 
  Weapons detected as follows: mortar platoon--50 m west of 
Ogurets Grove; tank--50 m southeast of barrow; 
IFV--south edge of Romb Grove; three ATGM's: 
first--120 m left of barn, 2nd--right of lone tree, third--50 m 
northeast of edge of Romb; two AT rocket launchers: 
first--barn, left 15; second--rocks, right 20. 
  Antitank and antipersonnel minefields emplaced ahead of 
FEBA. 
  2. On 2nd MRC axis of attack personnel and weapons in 
platoon 
strongpoints on FEBA and on Hill 108.0 are neutralized by senior 
commanders' assets in period of fire preparation of assault. 
Emplaced tank and IFV and three ATGM's are destroyed by weapons 
assigned for direct fire. Artillery support of assault is by 
double successive fire concentration. 
  4th MRC, 2nd MRB attacks on right, destroys enemy in area of 
lone tree, barn (excluded), Hill 102.0 and takes line of lone 
house, Hill 110.0; direction for continuing attack--north slopes 
of Hill 110.0, barrow. 
  1st MRC attacks on left, destroys enemy in area of rocks, 
Bibirevo, Ovalnaya Grove and takes line of sheepfold 
(excluded), Belaya Grove; direction for continuing 
attack--Ovalnaya Grove, north edge of 
Sinkovo. 
  3. 2nd MRC with grenade launcher squad in coordination with 
2nd TC (less TP) destroys enemy in platoon strongpoint of barn, 
rocks (excluded), west slopes of Hill 105.0 by an assault from 
attack positions of barn (excluded), farmstead and takes line of 
Hill 110.0 (excluded), sheepfold; direction for continuing 
attack--lone house, Hill 108.0. 
  I DECIDED: Concentrate main efforts in direction 
of forest, tower. Exploiting results of artillery fire and air 
strikes, destroy personnel and weapons in platoon strongpoint in 
area of barn, rocks (excluded), north slopes of Hill 105.0 by an 
assault from attack position of barn (excluded), farmstead by 
BMP and small arms fire and by H plus 20 minutes take line of 
Hill 110.0 (excluded), sheepfold. Direction for continuing 
attack-- lone house, Hill 108.0. Destroy enemy in strongpoint in 
depth by assault of 1st and 2nd MRP's from front and of 3rd MRP 
against flank in direction of windmill, Hill 108.0. 
  Repel counterattack of battalion reserve from the move by 
fire of all weapons in coordination with 2nd TC and adjacent 
subunit on left. 
  Battle formation in one echelon; execute dismounted assault. 
  Ensure surprise of attack by observing previous regime of 
fire and by covertness in conducting regrouping and occupying 
attack position. 
  4. I order: 

  -  2nd MRP in coordination with Tank No 101 is to destroy 
emplaced enemy tank, ATGM, AT rocket launcher and personnel from 
attack position of barn (excluded), rocks; direction for 
continuing attack--barrow, north edge of Ogurets Grove; 
  -  1st MRP in coordination with tanks Nos 102 and 103 is to 
destroy enemy ATGM, machinegun and personnel from attack 
position of rocks (excluded), rock pillar; direction for 
continuing attack--Hill 100.2, lone tree; 
  -  3rd MRP in coordination with 2nd TP is to destroy enemy ATGM, 
IFV, grenade launcher and personnel from attack position of rock 
pillar (excluded), farmstead; direction for continuing 
attack--Romb Grove, tower; 
  -  1st Grenade Launcher Squad is to neutralize personnel at 
platoon COP on north edge of Romb Grove in period of 
fire preparation. Occupy firing position 100 m east of bushes. 
Direction of fire--north edge of Romb Grove, Hill 
105.0. Readiness for commencing fire--H minus 1 hour 20 minutes. 
During attack support 1st and 3rd MRP's, displace behind left 
flank of 1st MRP. 


    5. Ammunition consumption for performing mission: 0.3 unit 
of 
fire for small arms, 0.2 unit of fire for BMP weapons. Fuel 
consumption 0.08 fueling. 
  6. Readiness for attack 0400 hours 7 July. 
  7. Company COP is 150 m east of rock pillars as of 0400 
hours 
7 July, displaces behind 1st MRP during battle. Deputy is 1st 
MRP commander. 
  The company (battalion) commander further organizes 
coordination on the terrain and updates it with supporting and 
adjacent subunits. Coordination is organized to the full depth 
of the company (battalion) combat mission by missions, lines, 
time and methods of performing missions. In organizing 
coordination the commander must precisely specify the goal of 
the company (battalion) attack and be sure that subunit 
commanders have correctly understood the assigned missions and 
methods of their execution. 
  Coordination instructions 
  1st MRP occupies attack position of rocks (excluded), rock 
pillars by 2250 hours 6 July. After handing over its strongpoint 
to 3rd MRC, 2nd MRP moves out along communication trench toward 
1st MRP strongpoint and occupies attack position of barn, rocks 
by 2320. 3rd MRP hands over strongpoint to 1st MRC and, moving 
along the trench, occupies attack position of rock pillars 
(excluded), farmstead by 2330 hours. 
  BMP's of MRP's are to take up firing positions 100-150 m 
behind their subunits by H minus 20 minutes in readiness for 
assault in the period of fire preparation of the attack. 
  Grenade launcher squad is to occupy firing position 100 m 
east of bushes behind 1st MRP by 2330. 
  In the period of regrouping be ready to repel possible 
actions of enemy reconnaissance and enemy assaults. 
  Friendly minefields ahead of company frontage are removed by 
engineer subunits on the night of 6/7 July. 
  Cross minefield ahead of enemy FEBA through passages as 
follows: 2nd MRP No 4, 1st MRP No 5, 3rd MRP No 6 under cover of 
fire of BMP's and grenade launcher squad. 
  At H minus 5 minutes tanks move out to the line of departure 
of northwest slopes of Hill 104.7, north slopes of Hill 104.3 
(excluded) and continue moving in extended line, firing from the 
move. By this moment motorized riflemen use sapper shovels to 
mark passages for them through their attack positions. After 
passing tanks through themselves along passages, motorized 
riflemen launch the assault following the tanks and burst onto 
the enemy FEBA at H hour. BMP's support the assault of their 
subunits by fire from occupied firing positions. They are to 
displace after MRP's negotiate enemy minefields. The grenade 
launcher squad destroys personnel in the company COP; it is to 
begin changing its firing position when assaulting subunits take 
the enemy FEBA. 
  2nd MRP completes destruction of ATGM's, AT rocket launcher 
and personnel north of Hill 100.2. 1st MRP destroys ATGM, 
machinegun and personnel west of Hill 100.2. 3rd MRP completes 
destruction of IFV, ATGM, AT rocket launcher and personnel at 
squad position. Complete destruction of enemy in assault 
objectives by H plus 15 minutes, after which continue the attack 
nonstop in indicated directions. Forces of 1st and 2nd MRP's are 
to complete destruction of mortar platoon on west edge of 
Ogurets Grove. Company performs immediate mission and takes line 
of Hill 110.0 (excluded), sheepfold by H plus 20 minutes. 
  2nd and 1st MRP's are to assault the enemy defending on Hill 
108.0 from the front in coordination with 2nd TC. 2nd MRP 
destroys the machinegun, and 1st MRP the ATGM and personnel. 1st 
Grenade Launcher Squad displaces to new firing positions and 
neutralizes the ATGM--lone house, up 100. 
  3rd MRP moves forward swiftly in direction of tower, 
windmill 
and completes destruction of enemy by an assault against the 
flank. 
  With the company's arrival at the line of Kvadratnaya Grove, 
southwest slopes of Hill 108.0, be ready together with 2nd TC 
and adjacent subunit on left to repel counterattack of battalion 
reserve by fire of all weapons from the move. 
  In repelling the counterattack of superior forces, tanks and 
BMP's take up firing positions behind the nearest cover and 
destroy enemy by fire from in place. 
  Signals: 

  -  warning: immediate threat of enemy use of mass 
destruction weapons--"Grom [Thunder]," radioactive 
contamination-- "Radiatsionnaya opasnost [Radiation Danger]," 
chemical and biological (bacteriological) contamination-- 
"Khimicheskaya trevoga [Chemical Alert]," air enemy-- "Vozdukh 
[Air]"; 
  -  control and coordination: assault--"Groza 
[Thunderstorm]-222," transfer artillery fire--"Perekat 
[Leapfrog]-444," request artillery fire-- "Uragan 
[Hurricane]-777"; target designations--tracer bullets and rounds 
in direction of target, for aviation "Friendly troops here"-- 
series of red-smoke signal flares. 


    [Begin side line] After organizing coordination the company 
(battalion) commander issues instructions for comprehensive 
support to battle, for C[.sup]2[/] and for political work. 
[End side line] 
  Reconnaissance instructions 
  With occupation of attack positions organize observation of 
(listening for) the ground and air enemy, having observers in 
each platoon and also at the company COP. 
  During preparation and conduct of the attack: uncover the 
location of tanks, ATGM's, machineguns, mortars and artillery, 
the system of fire and obstacles, and C[.sup]2[/] facilities; 
determine the makeup and direction of forward movement of the 
reserve for a counterattack. 
  Concentrate main reconnaissance efforts in direction of rock 
pillars, lone house. 
  With company arrival at line Kvadratnaya Grove, Hill 108.0, 
1st MRP is to be ready to act as a combat reconnaissance patrol 
in direction of west slopes of Hill 108.0, Zelenaya Grove. 
  Report information on enemy to me by radio in the course of 
battle. 
  Security instructions 
  After occupying attack position, concentrate special 
attention in direction: 2nd MRP--rocks, barrow; 1st MRP--rocks, 
Hill 100.2; 3rd MRP- -rock pillar, Romb Grove. 
  Organize observation in platoons and have duty weapons for 
preventing penetration of enemy reconnaissance to occupied 
positions. Be ready to repel enemy assaults. 
  Password "Karabin," reply "Kursk." 
  Instructions on protection against mass 
destruction weapons 
  With occupation of attack position, to protect against mass 
destruction weapons make use of available fortifications: open 
and covered slit trenches, emplacements, trench, communication 
trench, personnel dugout, and emplacements and shelters for 
BMP's. 
  Signals: 

  -  warning of immediate threat of enemy use of mass 
destruction weapons-- "Grom [Thunder]"; 
  -  warning: radioactive 
contamination--"Radiatsionnaya opasnost [Radiation Danger]"; 
chemical and biological (bacteriological) contamination-- 
"Khimicheskaya trevoga [Chemical Alert]." 

  On receiving a signal of immediate threat of enemy use of 
mass destruction weapons, continue performing missions and take 
measures for protection and for shifting to operations under 
conditions of the use of mass destruction weapons. 
  By 2330 check that personnel have preventive means and their 
readiness for use of antiradiation drugs, antidotes and 
antibiotics. 
  Check readiness of system for protection of BMP crews and 
the 
presence and serviceability of decontamination equipment. 
  Perform radiological and chemical reconnaissance by a 
trained 
chemical observer, who is to be located at the COP. 
  Maskirovka instructions 
  Carry out movement of personnel covertly along trench and 
communication trench during regrouping. Personnel movements are 
prohibited on occupying attack positions. 
  Strictly observe sound and light discipline and operate 
radios only in "listening watch" mode. 
  Platoon commanders are to constantly monitor compliance with 
camouflage discipline. 
  Engineer support instructions 
  At attack position each platoon is to make maximum use of 
previously prepared emplacements and other fortification and 
structures for personnel, machineguns, grenade launchers and 
other weapons. If necessary prepare new emplacements for them, 
strictly observing maskirovka and making maximum use of 
protective properties of the terrain. 
  Obstacles ahead of our positions are removed from 0200 to 
0400. Passages are made in enemy obstacles from H minus 22 to H 
minus 10 minutes by forces of engineer subunits of the senior 
chief by the explosive method ahead of the following frontage: 
2nd MRP--150 m southwest of bushes; 1st MRP--100 m east of lone 
tree; 3rd MRP--100 m southwest of sand pit. Passages are marked 
by signs Nos 4, 5 and 6 respectively. 
  1st MRP commander is to prepare 3rd MRS for breaching and 
crossing minefields laid by the enemy by remote assets in the 
course of our attack. 
  Chemical support instructions 
  BMP crews are to be ready to perform radiological and 
chemical reconnaissance. Have radiological and chemical 
reconnaissance devices constantly turned on in the course of the 
attack. 
  Check whether or not personnel have dose rate meters by 
2330. 
Platoon commanders are to take their readings by day's end and, 
in crossing zones of contamination, after exiting from them. 
  Perform partial decontamination with your own forces at my 
command. Perform decontamination immediately on contamination by 
chemical agents. 
  By 2330 6 July check serviceability and fit of individual 
protective gear. 
  Instructions on organizing C[.sup]3[/] 
  Carry out C[.sup]3[/] via couriers on arrival at attack 
positions. Have radios in platoon commanders' BMP's on receive. 
Location of company COP--200 m west of rock pillar; it deploys 
by 2250. 
  C[.sup]2[/] in the course of battle is accomplished over a 
radio net, through couriers and by signals. COP displaces behind 
1st MRP in the course of battle. 
  Work of preparing subunits for battle 
  Preparation of subunits for performing combat 
missions usually begins after the company (battalion) 
commander's order is issued to subordinates based on the mission 
analysis and time calculation. In accordance with the order, 
personnel first of all prepare weapons and military vehicles for 
combat employment and replenish ammunition, missiles, fuel and 
other supplies to established norms. 
  The appropriate kind of routine servicing and maintenance is 
performed depending on the expenditure of service life of 
weapons and vehicles. As a rule, daily routine servicing and 
maintenance with elements of TO [periodic servicing and 
maintenance inspection] No 1 will be carried out. The important 
thing here is to ensure their reliable operation in the course 
of the attack. Repair of vehicles and their return to formation 
also is completed by the beginning of the battle. 
  Reserves of supplies in subunits and in the battalion rear 
usually are replenished to unit-level supply norms, but as a 
rule additional reserves of ammunition are established for the 
mortar battery, attached artillery and guns used for direct 
fire. The amount of these reserves must ensure performance of 
fire missions of engaging the enemy without a change of 
positions in the period of fire preparation and support of the 
assault. Additional reserves are established at the expense of 
the senior commander and usually are laid out at firing 
positions (on the ground) before the beginning of battle. 
  The battalion aid station is cleared of sick and wounded and 
augmented with necessary medical equipment and supplies. All 
personnel must be supplied with everything necessary along the 
line of medical support. 
  Preparation of personnel to perform combat missions is 
carried out under the subunit commander's plan. There are 
provisions for the personnel to study (become clearer on) enemy 
weapons and engineer obstacles and his defense as a whole as 
well as the terrain. A check is made of the personnel's 
knowledge of missions, readiness of weapons, availability of 
ammunition and other means. War experience shows that holding 
classes with subunits together with attached forces and assets 
in a near-real situation considerably improves their preparation 
and confidence in performing combat missions. 
  Preparation of subunits for the attack ends with a check 
made 
by the commander. 
  Preparation of the position (assembly area) for attack from 
a 
situation of direct contact with the enemy usually begins after 
regrouping from a position of defense or after relief of 
defending subunits. During preparation of the attack position 
(assembly area), existing fortification structures for weapons, 
vehicles, COP's and accommodation of technical and logistic 
support subunits are used and additionally prepared, and new 
ones also are created if necessary. Forward movement routes of 
tanks are prepared from assembly positions to the line of 
departure. All work of preparing the attack position (assembly 
area) is done under the guise of improving the defense and 
conducting other deceptive actions. Elements of the position's 
fortification are carefully camouflaged. 
  In a hasty attack preparation of the assembly area 
consists of engineer preparation of platoon locations and areas 
of companies and the battalion as a whole, and accomplishment of 
maskirovka. Slit trenches, shelters and bunkers for personnel 
and emplacements and shelters (dug-in) for weapons and military 
vehicles and also firing positions for air defense weapons are 
dug and prepared in the area. All work of preparing the attack 
position (assembly area) usually is done at night and under 
other conditions of poor visibility. 
  Practical work of the company commander (battalion 
commander, his deputies, chief of staff) is performed in 
the subunits to give assistance and check their readiness to 
perform the combat mission. 
  The work of assisting subordinates essentially is performed 
with the beginning of preparation for the attack. By listening 
to decisions and suggestions in the course of the work, the 
company commander (battalion commander, his deputies) convince 
themselves of subordinates' knowledge of their missions, methods 
of performing them, and procedure for coordination within 
subunits and between elements of the battle formation, and of 
their knowledge of warning, control and coordination signals, 
and so on. 
  After occupation of an attack position (assembly area), at a 
certain time the company commander (battalion commander, chief 
of staff) checks the correctness of its occupation by subunits 
and of the work of additional preparation of the position (area) 
with fortification structures. Personal gear and equipment of 
motorized riflemen (teams, crews) and the presence and 
serviceability of weapons and necessary gear, ammunition, food 
and protective gear are carefully checked in subunits. 
  In addition, the chief of staff checks preparedness for 
operation of communications equipment and the communications 
layout diagram with the chief of communications. 
  The company senior technician (deputy battalion commander 
for 
weapons) checks readiness of weapons and military vehicles for 
combat employment. Main attention is given to serviceability of 
running gear, weapons and communications equipment. Forces and 
assets assigned to the battalion technical maintenance echelon 
as it moves from the assembly area in launching a hasty attack 
are checked. There is monitoring and a check of technical 
support forces and assets for operation as the battalion repair 
and recovery team, and of preparedness of the technical 
observation post for operation,. 
  The deputy battalion commander for rear checks the presence 
of necessary supplies in subunits and in the support platoon, 
disposition of battalion rear C[.sup]2[/] facilities in the 
assembly area and their shelter and maskirovka, and promptness 
of food preparation and its issue to personnel. 
  Deficiencies discovered are remedied by personnel on the 
spot. At the designated time the company (battalion) commander 
announces the time of fire preparation of the assault and of H 
hour to subordinate subunit commanders. 
<H5>  6. Regrouping and Relief of Defending Subunits </H5>
  Organization of regrouping is a component part of organizing 
the attack. All necessary questions of regrouping are decided by 
the commander during ground reconnaissance, and the procedure 
for accomplishing it is indicated to subordinates when 
coordination is being organized. 
  Regrouping is accomplished in accordance with the 
commander's decision for the attack, and only the most 
necessary, simple subunit movements concealed from the enemy 
should be envisaged in organizing it. 
  Under situation conditions in question, a regrouping is 
conducted by direction of the senior commander usually at night 
before an attack, with fulfillment of measures for deceiving the 
enemy regarding intentions. 
  The company commander's COP is located up to 200 m behind 
the 
company attack position, and that of the battalion commander up 
to 300 m behind first echelon companies. 
  Occupation of the attack position (assembly area) in 
trenches, communication trenches and shelters ensures subunits' 
concealment against enemy observation and protection against his 
possible fire strikes. 
  It is advisable to leave subunits in place which have taken 
up a defense in the battalion (regimental) second echelon within 
a designated zone of advance, since they can move forward for 
the assault directly from occupied areas. 
  Tanks, BMP's and other weapons which are in forward platoon 
strongpoints in the zone of upcoming attack also should be left 
in place and used for conducting direct fire. Tanks, guns and 
BMP's disposed in the defense somewhat aside from the zone of 
advance or in strongpoints of first echelon companies being 
relieved also may be used for conducting such fire. Where 
possible, during regrouping of subunits the BMP's should be left 
at previous firing positions and advanced to new ones for 
destroying assigned targets with the beginning of fire 
preparation of the assault. Sometimes it is advisable to use 
these weapons to conduct direct fire also without changing 
firing positions. 
  To achieve concealment of a regrouping of first echelon 
motorized rifle subunits in insignificant frontage, it is 
desirable to leave their BMP's in the previous strongpoint and 
have them move out to their subunits during fire preparation of 
the assault. 
  If one of the battalion's companies is being relieved by a 
newly arriving subunit, the company should be moved to the 
assembly area [rayon sbora] covertly using trenches and 
communication trenches. It is advisable to designate the 
assembly area within the first position of the defense. 
Subsequently the company displaces to its battalion's assembly 
area [iskhodnyy rayon] and occupies the second and third 
trenches. As a rule, the company is moved out of the strongpoint 
simultaneously with its relief. 
  Tanks in the zone of advance may launch the assault from the 
strongpoints they occupy. 
  If the mortar battery is to one side of the battalion 
assembly area, it displaces to new firing positions and occupies 
them up to 500 m behind first echelon companies. Air defense 
subunits are disposed at launch (firing) positions in the 
companies' battle formations. 
  The grenade launcher subunit and AT subunit occupy firing 
positions up to 300 and 100 m respectively behind first echelon 
companies. The AT squad usually is disposed in [the company] 
trench. 
  A TC (TB less company) attached to an MRB usually occupies 
assembly positions 5-7 km from the enemy FEBA. Under favorable 
situation conditions these positions may be designated to one 
side of the axis of advance, which will ensure surprise to a 
certain extent. 
  Subunits must be ready to repel enemy reconnaissance and 
assaults during regrouping. 
  A relief of defending subunits is the organized 
receipt and transfer by subunits of positions and strongpoints 
(defense areas) in a combat situation. The procedure and 
sequence of the relief are determined by the senior commander. 
  On receiving a relief order, a company (battalion) commander 
performs ground reconnaissance together with the commander of 
the subunit being relieved. During ground reconnaissance the 
nature of terrain, the enemy FEBA, and his weapons and engineer 
obstacles in the attack frontage and on flanks are studied. Then 
the company (battalion) commander familiarizes himself with the 
disposition of the subunit turning over the position, with its 
regime of behavior, system of fire, organization of air defense, 
fortification of the strongpoint (strongpoints) and obstacles 
emplaced ahead of the FEBA and in the depth of the defense. 
Familiarization with the NBC situation also is important. 
  In addition, he updates (determines) concealed forward 
movement routes to the relief area, locations of traffic control 
posts, places for arriving subunits to be met by guides, and the 
relief procedure. The procedure for joint repulse of a possible 
enemy attack launched during the relief also is established. 
  The company (battalion) commander receives a diagram and all 
available data on the enemy from the commander turning over the 
strongpoint (defense area). 
  Defending subunits are relieved in accordance with the 
senior 
commander's relief plan. Usually on the night before an attack 
the MRC (MRB) moves up from the depth in BMP's (BTR's) and motor 
vehicles and dismounts on arriving at the line which can be 
viewed by enemy ground reconnaissance equipment. Subsequently it 
proceeds along a designated concealed route or routes in 
dismounted formation to the point (place) of rendezvous with 
guides of the subunit being relieved. The company (battalion) 
moves further along communication trenches and [fighting] 
trenches to its attack positions (to the assembly area) with the 
help of the guides and occupies them in readiness to repel 
possible enemy assaults. BMP's (BTR's) remain under cover at 
dismount locations on the axes of their subunits' operations. As 
a rule, they move up to the subunits in the period of fire 
preparation of the assault. Motor vehicles remain at the 
designated assembly point and are disposed by company or by 
battalion in readiness for movement. 
  A TC (TB) attached to an MRB occupies its assigned assembly 
positions 5-7 km from the enemy FEBA. The BMP's (BTR's) of MRC's 
also may be together with it. 
  If the enemy launches an attack during the relief, the 
relief 
stops and all subunits repel his assault. Their battle is 
controlled by the commander of the subunit being relieved, since 
he knows the situation well. 
  The relief of subunits continues after repulse of the enemy 
attack. It is considered completed after the company (battalion) 
commander reports to his senior commander. 
  It should be noted that a regrouping of subunits from a 
position of defense and a relief of defending subunits for 
occupying an attack position are accomplished covertly with 
observation of sound, light and radar discipline. 
  An MRC (MRB) which has relieved defending subunits must 
strictly follow their regime of conduct before the relief. 
<H5>  7. Conduct of Attack by MRC (TC) </H5>
  As a result of regrouping and relief of defending subunits, 
a 
first echelon MRC occupies the attack position in the first 
trench and adjoining communication trench, and a TC occupies an 
assembly position and sometimes also an attack position, where 
they complete preparation for the assault. 
  In case the enemy conducts a counterpreparation, company 
personnel except for observers and duty weapons take cover in 
bunkers, dugouts, slit trenches as well as combat vehicles. 
  Fire preparation of the assault begins at the prescribed 
time 
at a signal (command) from the senior commander. During this 
time tanks, ATGM launchers, guns and other weapons assigned to 
conduct direct fire destroy and neutralize enemy weapons in 
strongpoints at his first position. 
  From the COP the company commander observes results of fire 
preparation of the assault, detects enemy targets that were not 
engaged or which have newly appeared, and updates combat 
missions to platoons for their destruction. In addition, he 
monitors the timely making and marking of passages by combat 
engineer subunits ahead of the enemy FEBA and conducts 
observation of the forward movement of his own BMP's (BTR's) and 
of tank subunits interworking with the company. He reports 
readiness for the assault to the battalion commander. 
  A TC begins forward movement from the assembly (attack) 
position to the line of departure during fire preparation of the 
assault at the command (signal) of the senior commander. The 
command (signal) is given so as to ensure the arrival of tanks 
at the enemy FEBA at the prescribed H hour simultaneously with 
assaulting motorized rifle subunits. This requires taking into 
account the distance of tanks from the FEBA and their possible 
rate of movement. BMP's (BTR's) of the MRC which were located 
with the tank subunits also move forward behind them. 
  As it moves forward, the TC deploys into platoon columns 
and, 
on arriving at the line of departure, also into an extended 
line. Moving at maximum permissible speed, it destroys the enemy 
by gun fire and subsequently also by machinegun fire from the 
move. BMP's (BTR's) move up to their subunits following the 
tanks. 
  In a dismounted assault by an MRC, when tanks working 
together with it arrive at its attack position, the company 
commander gives the command "Get ready for assault," and after 
the tanks pass the position--"Charge--forward!" At this command 
the personnel leap from emplacements (the trench) and rush into 
the assault following the tanks. 
  BMP's (BTR's) displace behind their subunits by bounds from 
cover to cover (from line to line) and provide reliable support 
of assaulting tanks and motorized riflemen by fire of their 
weapons. BMP's equipped with stabilized weapons proceed in the 
extended line of motorized rifle subunits during the assault. 
  When the attack position is a considerable distance from the 
enemy FEBA, MRC subunits may board BMP's (BTR's), launch the 
assault following the tanks, and then dismount at the dismount 
line. 
  In a situation where the MRC is to assault the enemy in 
BMP's 
(BTR's), its personnel board during fire preparation of the 
assault. For this, at a command (signal) of the company 
commander, the BMP's (BTR's) approach their subunit covertly and 
stop. Subsequently the company launches the assault following 
the interworking tanks. 
  Artillery shifts to artillery support of the assault with 
the 
beginning of the tank assault. Firing into gaps between 
assaulting subunits and from behind their flanks, tanks, guns, 
ATGM launchers and other weapons assigned for direct fire 
destroy enemy targets which have survived and have newly 
appeared. Subsequently these weapons operate in accordance with 
assigned missions. 
  In a dismounted assault, company personnel usually cross 
minefields by squads following tanks in their tracks and through 
breached passages. BMP's equipped with mineclearing devices 
cross independently. Passages are made (by the explosive method) 
for BMP's (BTR's) and other combat vehicles not having 
mineclearing devices figuring one passage per assaulting 
platoon. After crossing a minefield BMP's (BTR's) catch up with 
the subunits and support their assault by fire of their weapons. 
  If an MRC is assaulting in BMP's equipped with mineclearing 
devices, it crosses the enemy minefield independently following 
tanks without closing up the battle formation, and the other 
vehicles without mineclearing devices do so through passages. In 
this case passages are made for passing the vehicles through 
figuring one or two per assaulting company. 
  The company's MRP's should move as close as possible to the 
tanks during an assault. This achieves reliable coordination 
among them and precludes the danger of motorized riflemen being 
cut off from tanks by enemy fire. 
  When assaulting subunits approach the safety limit of 
friendly shell and mortar (grenade) bursts, artillery (grenade 
launchers) shifts fire into the depth at the senior commander's 
command (signal). 
  The safe distance from friendly shellbursts is considered to 
be 400 m (200 m from grenade bursts) for motorized riflemen in a 
dismounted assault. The safe distance for tanks and BMP's 
(BTR's) is 200 and 300 m respectively. 
  Motorized rifle and tank subunits burst onto the enemy FEBA 
at precisely the prescribed H hour. After destroying his 
personnel, weapons and vehicles, the company continues the 
assault nonstop into the depth right after friendly artillery 
shellbursts. 
  The grenade launcher subunit attached to an MRC may operate 
up to 300 m behind its battle formation and also in gaps between 
platoons or on one of the company flanks. If necessary, it may 
move up directly into battle formations of motorized rifle 
subunits. A subunit with grenade launchers mounted on BMP's 
(BTR's) usually operates in battle formations of motorized rifle 
subunits. 
  The company's AT squad usually attacks in the battle 
formation of MRP's, in gaps between them or on one of the 
company flanks. Occupying firing positions in succession, it 
destroys tanks, IFV's and other armored targets hampering the 
company's advance. 
  The flamethrower subunit attached to the MRC attacks in the 
company battle formation, conducting fire at the company 
commander's command or independently. 
  The air defense subunit covering the company usually 
advances 
behind it, conducts continuous reconnaissance of the air enemy, 
especially helicopters, and destroys him by fire from the move 
or from short halts. 
  A company may not deploy into battle formation and may 
operate in approach march formation in an attack on an axis 
where the enemy has been reliably neutralized and is not 
offering organized resistance. 
  In the period of fire support of the assault, artillery 
subunits continuously and successively neutralize personnel and 
weapons, above all AT weapons, and neutralize and destroy 
precision weapon system elements, C[.sup]2[/] facilities and 
newly detected targets. Artillery displaces to new firing 
positions after the company takes the platoon strongpoint. 
  During fire support of the subunits' assault, combat 
helicopters destroy enemy tanks, ATGM's, IFV's and other targets 
2-3 km or more ahead of the assaulting tanks. Fighter-bombers 
engage enemy objectives at a greater depth. 
  If it is impossible to bypass minefields suddenly laid by 
the 
enemy by remote minelaying equipment ahead of an attacking 
company, it negotiates them through passages made by the 
battalion obstacle clearing party and the company non-T/O 
mineclearing team. In the course of the attack the mineclearing 
team (a squad of motorized riflemen equipped with mine 
detectors, sappers' grappling hooks and a set of markers) moves 
behind the company battle formation close to the company 
commander's COP. 
  During the assault the company commander at the COP moves 
200 
m behind the extended line of armored vehicles or riflemen. As a 
rule he dismounts in a dismounted assault by the company. The 
company commander must carefully observe development of the 
battle, control the fire of all weapons, promptly support 
platoons which have achieved greatest success, and take skillful 
advantage of fire to support their maneuver and surprise assault 
against the flank and rear of the enemy strongpoint. Having 
completed destruction of the enemy in platoon strongpoints of 
the first position, the company develops the attack into the 
depth. The battle in the depth of the enemy defense is 
characterized by uneven advance of the company's platoons and 
develops in a complex, swiftly changing situation. The enemy 
will attempt to move ATGM's and tanks up to previously prepared 
firing positions for delivering a fire strike against the 
assaulting company's flank. In this situation it is advisable to 
use some of the forces, artillery fire and blinding smoke 
screens to isolate the enemy from the threatened sector and use 
the company main body to execute a maneuver and complete the 
enemy's destruction by an assault against the flank and rear of 
the strongpoint. 
  After destroying the enemy in the depth of the first 
position, the company may send out a combat reconnaissance 
patrol with the primary mission of reconnoitering enemy tanks, 
precision weapon systems, artillery, AT weapons and obstacles. 
  During battle in the depth of the first position the company 
must be ready to repel enemy counterattacks. Methods of 
combating him basically depend on the force ratio between the 
sides and directions of his counterattacks (Diagram 13). 
  In the case where a company has superiority over the enemy 
or 
equal forces with him, as a rule it destroys him by fire and a 
decisive assault on the move, i.e., in a meeting battle. If the 
enemy has superiority in forces and assets, it is more 
advantageous for the company to inflict damage on him by fire 
from in place and subsequently complete his rout by a determined 
assault in coordination with an adjacent subunit. Tanks and 
BMP's (BTR's) take up firing positions behind the nearest cover 
and MRP personnel dismount and take up positions providing 
favorable conditions for destroying the enemy and for 
coordination with the tanks. The AT squad is disposed at firing 
positions on a likely avenue of tank approach, usually in gaps 
or on the company (platoon) flank. The attached grenade launcher 
subunit as a rule takes up firing positions in the company 
battle formation on the axis with the greatest amount of enemy 
infantry. Initially the company repels a counterattack by 
concentrated fire of subunits from all weapons at maximum range. 
When the enemy approaches, the force and intensity of fire are 
brought to highest intensity. 
  One of the deciding conditions of successful combat against 
a 
counterattacking enemy is to inflict maximum damage on him by 
fire of artillery, mortars, tanks, AT weapons and BMP's and by 
strikes of combat helicopters, and make skilled use of smoke 
assets. A concealed move of company subunits to the flank and 
rear of a counterattacking enemy and surprise of the assault are 
achieved by laying down blinding and concealing smoke screens. 
  If the enemy offers no organized resistance, platoon 
personnel board vehicles at their commanders' commands and 
continue a swift attack into the depth, taking advantage of 
artillery fire, strikes by aircraft and their own weapons. 
  In terrain sectors difficult of access for tanks, dismounted 
MRP's may overtake the tanks and attack under cover of their 
fire and the fire of BMP's (BTR's). As these sectors are 
crossed, the tanks again move in front and continue the attack. 
  The company goes around obstacles and barriers encountered 
in 
the course of battle or crosses them through passages made by 
combat engineer subunits and tanks equipped with bulldozer 
attachments. Contaminated terrain sectors usually are bypassed, 
but if this is impossible they are crossed along axes ensuring 
the least degree of exposure (contamination) and wearing 
protective gear. 
  The position of platoons in the battle formation may be in a 
line, wedge (inverted wedge), or echelon right or left during 
the attack, especially in the depth of the enemy defense and 
based on the nature of his actions. 
  In case of an enemy withdrawal the company commander 
immediately organizes a pursuit, reports this to the battalion 
commander and informs adjacent subunits. In organizing the 
pursuit, the company commander first and foremost sends out a 
combat reconnaissance patrol and assigns missions to subunits. 
  The high mobility of tanks, BMP's (BTR's) and artillery 
permits a company to employ the more advisable method of 
pursuing the enemy along parallel routes. For this the company 
reforms into a column, swiftly overtakes the enemy along 
parallel routes, moves to his withdrawal routes and destroys him 
in detail by a determined assault against the flank and rear in 
coordination with subunits operating from other directions. 
  If pursuit of the enemy along parallel routes is impossible 
because of situation conditions, it is done from the front. In 
this case the company resolutely destroys enemy covering-force 
subunits, penetrates to his main body and swiftly assaults the 
enemy from the move in coordination with subunits conducting the 
pursuit along parallel routes. 
  In the pursuit a company may operate in battle, approach 
march or march formation. Personnel in motor vehicles may pursue 
the enemy as a mounted force on tanks or in the motor vehicles 
under cover of tanks. 
  With successful development of the attack a company may 
receive a mission for operations in a special detachment. Its 
mission may be to destroy means of nuclear and chemical attack, 
precision weapon systems, C[.sup]2[/] facilities and so on. 
  On receiving the mission, the company commander sends out a 
combat reconnaissance patrol, makes the decision and assigns 
missions to subunits. Taking advantage of gaps in the enemy 
battle formation and his exposed flanks, the company moves 
quickly and covertly to the designated area. Then it decisively 
assaults from the move from different directions, usually 
without dismounting the motorized riflemen, destroys the 
covering force, makes the capture and performs the assigned 
mission. Subsequently the company either receives a new mission 
or moves out to the operating area of its battalion (or of 
friendly troops). 
  In an attack on a fortified area an MRC may make up an 
assault team, which usually is part of an assault detachment. In 
this case tanks, guns (primarily self-propelled), mortars, ATGM 
launchers, flamethrowers, grenade launchers and a combat 
engineer subunit may be attached to the company. As a rule, an 
assault team consists of fire, obstacle clearing (demolition) 
and capture elements. 
  The assault team is given an immediate mission and direction 
for continuing the attack. The mission content is to capture or 
destroy a permanent emplacement or other important structure on 
the axis of attack. The direction for continuing the attack is 
assigned so as to ensure capture and destruction of the next 
enemy weapon emplacement or other emplacement. 
  An assault team begins the assault on its objective 
simultaneously with the assault of first echelon tank and 
motorized rifle subunits. The team blocks and destroys a 
surviving emplacement after fire preparation of the assault. 
Subsequently the team destroys another permanent emplacement. 
  Tanks and motorized rifle subunits of the assaulting echelon 
boldly penetrate into gaps between permanent emplacements and 
advance into the depth, and some of the forces destroy an enemy 
relief subunit together with the assault team. 
  A company also may attack with a crossing of nuclear 
minefields. In organizing an attack under these conditions, 
along with other questions the company commander decides 
questions of the capture and destruction of a nuclear mine 
located on the company axis of operations. In particular, he 
organizes reconnaissance of the nuclear mine cover and security 
outpost positions, specifies the procedure for routing the enemy 
at these positions, and also the procedure for capture and 
destruction of the mine. In addition, the commander determines 
his subunit's makeup, reinforcement, outfitting and place in the 
battle formation for immediate capture and destruction of a 
nuclear mine and the procedure of its operations. 
  An MRP, tanks with mineclearing devices and bulldozer 
equipment, combat engineers with special technical assets and 
chemical warfare scouts may be assigned to the makeup of a 
nuclear mine capture and destruction subunit. To perform the 
mission, the capture and destruction subunit is divided into a 
capture team (main body of the subunit and tanks with 
mineclearing devices and bulldozer equipment) and a destruction 
team (combat engineer subunit). 
  In an assault on nuclear mine cover and security outpost 
positions, a subunit assigned for its capture and destruction 
advances behind the company battle formation in the course of an 
attack or assaults together with it. After destruction of the 
nuclear mine cover and security outpost subunit, the capture 
team breaches obstacles, takes the nuclear mine disposition 
area, moves to a safe distance from where it is emplaced and 
cordons off this area. The destruction team reconnoiters the 
nuclear mine's location and destroys it. 
  As noted above, the company may launch a hasty 
attack. Before launching the attack it usually is in the 
battalion assembly area, disposed along a route ensuring its 
movement onto the battalion forward movement route to the start 
point. Personnel and military vehicles are in carefully 
camouflaged shelters. Observation and local security are 
organized in the company. 
  The company moves up from the occupied area at the battalion 
commander's command (signal). After the column forms up the 
company takes its prescribed place in the battalion march 
formation, which is determined by the company's place in the 
battalion battle formation alignment when it launches the 
assault. The company moves up with means of reinforcement, which 
helps it to deploy into approach march and battle formations 
from the move without a halt. As a rule the company crosses the 
start point at a given rate of movement. 
  Fire preparation of the assault begins with the company's 
arrival at a line which can be reached by enemy artillery fire 
(or from a line designated by the senior commander). On reaching 
the point of deployment into company columns, the company moves 
onto its axis of attack along a cross-country route. 
  An MRC in motor vehicles moving forward behind tank subunits 
stops on arriving at the point for boarding tanks as a mounted 
force (2-4 km from the enemy FEBA) and boards, after which it 
continues moving toward the dismount line. 
  Motor vehicles freed of motorized riflemen move to the 
assembly area and remain there in readiness to move up to their 
company at the commander's signal. 
  Company tanks assigned to be outfitted with roller-type 
mineclearing devices are moved to the designated place at the 
designated time by direction of the battalion commander. 
  In the course of fire preparation the company continues 
moving forward at maximum speed, deploying into platoon columns 
from the indicated line, and arrives at the line of departure in 
battle formation. 
  During forward movement to the line of departure the company 
must observe measures of protection against precision weapons 
and must observe radar, sound and light discipline. 
  If it is impossible to bypass minefields laid by enemy 
remote 
minelaying equipment in the course of forward movement to the 
line of departure, the company crosses through passages made by 
the senior commander's movement support detachment, the 
battalion obstacle clearing party or the company nonT/O 
mineclearing team. 
  An MRC may execute an assault in BMP's (BTR's) or in 
dismounted formation. In a dismounted assault, motorized rifle 
subunit personnel dismount from BMP's (BTR's) on arriving at the 
dismount line, deploy into an extended line on the move and 
assault the enemy following the tanks. BMP's (BTR's) displace 
behind their own subunits and support them by fire. 
  On approaching the dismount line BMP's (BTR's) must speed up 
and catch up with the assaulting tanks to ensure close 
interworking of motorized riflemen with tanks when they reach 
the enemy FEBA. 
  As in a dismounted assault, in an assault in BMP's (BTR's) 
motorized rifle subunits of the company also must move as close 
to the tanks as possible (not over 200 m). This will ensure 
continuous fire coordination between motorized rifle and tank 
subunits in the interests of successful mission performance. 
  The company's negotiation of obstacles in the course of an 
assault and its operations to destroy the enemy are similar to 
company operations when launching an attack from a position of 
direct contact with the enemy. 
<H5>  8. Conduct of Attack by MRB (TB) </H5>
  The attack of an MRB from a position of direct contact with 
the enemy is made from an assembly area occupied after 
regrouping from a position of defense or simultaneously with 
relief of defending subunits. 
  In the battalion assembly area for the attack, first echelon 
companies occupy attack positions in the first trench and 
adjoining communication trenches, and the second echelon company 
does so in the second and third trenches. 
  Depending on the situation, BMP's may be in the previous 
places or together with attached tank subunits at attack or 
assembly positions. 
  Air defense subunits are in battle formations of companies, 
and the mortar (artillery) battery is up to 500 m from first 
echelon companies. 
  The AT subunit and grenade launcher subunit are disposed up 
to 100 and 300 m respectively behind first echelon companies. 
  Tank subunits attached to the battalion and which were in 
the 
defense may occupy an assembly or attack position after 
necessary regrouping. When an attack is launched as motorized 
rifle subunits are relieving defending subunits, the TB (tank 
subunit attached to an MRB) as a rule occupies an assembly 
position. In it the battalion usually is disposed by company 
with consideration of conducting a defense in case the enemy 
launches an attack after a counterpreparation. Measures of 
protection against precision weapons and of radar, sound and 
light discipline are followed. 
  When the enemy conducts counterpreparation fire, personnel 
and military vehicles are in shelters, except for observers and 
duty weapons. 
  Fire preparation of the assault begins at the prescribed 
time 
at a signal (command) from the senior commander. In its course 
the AT subunit, grenade launcher subunit and artillery attached 
to the battalion and assigned to conduct direct fire destroy and 
neutralize enemy weapons and personnel in his forward 
strongpoints. 
  The battalion commander observes results of fire preparation 
of the assault from his COP, assigns supplementary missions to 
weapons for destroying surviving and newly detected targets if 
necessary, and monitors forward movement of the attached tank 
subunit from its occupied position. He reports readiness for the 
assault to the regimental commander. 
  A TB intended for attacking in the first echelon (or a tank 
subunit attached to an MRB) moves forward from the assembly 
position to the line of departure during fire preparation of the 
assault. 
  As they approach the enemy FEBA, TC's deploy into platoon 
columns and arrive at the line of departure in battle formation. 
Without stopping at this line, the TB (tank subunit attached to 
an MRB) launches the assault at the maximum permissible rate of 
movement. Tanks destroy enemy personnel and weapons by fire from 
the move. BMP's (BTR's) move up to their subunits. 
  When tanks approach the attack positions of first echelon 
MRC's, in a dismounted assault the motorized riflemen assault 
following the tanks. BMP's (BTR's) operate behind their subunits 
by bounds from line to line at a distance ensuring their 
effective fire support. When assaulting in BMP's (BTR's), 
motorized rifle subunits board personnel during fire preparation 
of the assault. 
  When tanks begin launching the assault, artillery begins 
artillery support of the assault at the senior commander's 
command (signal). Battalion weapons assigned for direct fire 
continue to destroy enemy targets, firing into gaps between 
friendly subunits and from behind their flanks. 
  In a dismounted assault by MRC's, motorized riflemen cross 
minefields following in the tracks of tanks and along passages 
which have been breached. BMP's equipped with mineclearing 
devices cross minefields independently, and those without 
mineclearing devices (including also BTR's) do so along passages 
breached by combat engineer subunits, usually by the explosive 
method. If motorized rifle subunits assault in BMP's equipped 
with mineclearing devices, they cross minefields without closing 
up the battle formation, and military vehicles without 
mineclearing devices do so along passages which have been made. 
  Artillery (grenade launcher) fire is transferred into the 
depth when assaulting MRC's and tank subunits approach the 
safety limit from bursts of friendly artillery and mortar rounds 
(grenades). At precisely the established H hour, 
motorized rifle and tank subunits of the battalion first echelon 
burst onto the enemy FEBA, destroy his personnel and weapons and 
develop the assault into the depth. 
  The battalion assault is accomplished with support of 
artillery fire and air strikes, including also combat helicopter 
strikes. Fire support of the assault is conducted continuously 
to the full depth of defense of the enemy first echelon brigade 
(regiment). Combat helicopters destroy tanks, AT weapons and 
other armored targets located 2-3 km or more ahead of the 
attacking subunits, and fighter-bombers engage enemy objectives 
at a greater depth. 
  Battalion organic and attached artillery continuously and 
successively neutralizes personnel and weapons, especially AT 
weapons, ahead of the front and on flanks of the battalion 
attack in coordination with the senior commander's weapons. This 
artillery displaces to new firing positions by order of the 
battalion commander, usually after the attackers take forward 
enemy platoon strongpoints. A transfer of or request for fire in 
conducting artillery support of the assault by a successive fire 
concentration, concentrated fire, and fire against single 
targets also may be accomplished at a command (signal) from the 
battalion commander. 
  The battalion GLP attacks behind first echelon companies, in 
their gaps or on one of the battalion flanks. If necessary the 
platoon may move up into battle formations of MRC's. 
  The ATP displaces behind one of the first echelon companies 
on a likely avenue of tank approach in readiness to repel enemy 
tank counterattacks. 
  Moving behind first echelon companies, the air defense 
subunit reconnoiters the air enemy and covers subunits from the 
air. 
  Exploiting results of fire damage, assaulting tank and 
motorized rifle subunits of the battalion destroy personnel and 
weapons in strongpoints from the move and create conditions for 
routing the enemy in the depth of the defense. The battalion may 
conduct the attack in approach march formation on an axis where 
the enemy has been reliably neutralized and offers no organized 
resistance. 
  The enemy may counterattack the battalion with brigade 
reserves. In this case, when the battalion's assaulting subunits 
have superiority over the counterattacker or equal forces and 
assets with him, as a rule he is destroyed by fire and a 
determined assault from the move. If the counterattacking enemy 
has superiority in forces and assets, it is more advantageous 
for the battalion to inflict damage on him by fire from in place 
and subsequently complete the rout by a determined assault in 
coordination with adjacent subunits, artillery and combat 
helicopters. 
  When first echelon companies have performed the immediate 
mission the battalion commander assigns them a new mission and 
takes steps to build up efforts by committing the second 
echelon (reserve). 
  Depending on the situation, it may be committed as or after 
the battalion completes performance of the immediate mission. 
The second echelon (reserve) displaces covertly from line to 
line 1- 2 km behind first echelon subunits, as a rule in 
approach march formation, taking advantage of concealing and 
protective properties of the terrain. It is committed in gaps 
between companies, from behind the flank of one of the 
companies, and sometimes also by leapfrogging over their battle 
formations (Diagram 14). 
  With commitment of the second echelon (reserve), the 
battalion commander usually updates by radio (points out to the 
reserve) the following: latest data on the enemy; situation of 
first echelon subunits; commitment line and time of moving to 
it; immediate mission and direction for continuing the attack; 
means of reinforcement and places and time of their arrival; 
missions for organic and attached artillery; procedure for fire 
support and coordination with first echelon subunits and 
adjacent subunits. 
  On receiving a mission for commitment, the commander of a 
second echelon (reserve) company of the battalion updates 
(assigns) combat missions to platoons (squads, tanks) on the 
move by radio. On arriving at the commitment line, he indicates 
on the terrain the position of the enemy and his weapons, 
commitment line, assault objectives and direction for continuing 
the attack, and he organizes coordination. 
  In coordination instructions the commander of a second 
echelon (reserve) company communicates the procedure for joint 
actions of motorized rifle and tank subunits, for their 
deployment into battle formation, and for conducting fire and 
movement and negotiating minefields and barriers; coordinates 
actions of motorized riflemen with tanks, with attached weapons, 
with each other and with adjacent subunits for destroying the 
enemy; indicates the procedure for dismounting motorized 
riflemen (if necessary) and using BMP's; and announces warning, 
control and coordination signals. 
  The battalion second echelon (reserve) moves up to the 
commitment line at maximum speed and deploys quickly into battle 
formation on approaching the line. Before its commitment, 
artillery, grenade launchers and other weapons conduct a fire 
assault. The second echelon's forward movement and deployment is 
covered by air defense subunits and supported by first echelon 
companies. Firing from the move, a second echelon company 
swiftly assaults the enemy and performs the assigned mission 
together with the battalion's first echelon companies and 
supported by artillery. With commitment of the second echelon, 
the battalion commander establishes a reserve from subunits 
operating off the axis of concentration of the battalion's main 
efforts. The battalion commander moves up a reconnaissance 
(combat reconnaissance) patrol for conducting reconnaissance on 
the axis of attack. 
  In a dismounted assault by motorized rifle subunits, after 
the enemy is destroyed in his first position personnel usually 
mount BMP's (BTR's, or as a mounted force on tanks). The 
battalion continues a determined attack into the depth, 
exploiting artillery fire, fire of its own weapons and air 
strikes. 
  Minefields laid ahead of assaulting companies by enemy 
remote 
minelaying assets are crossed through passages if it is 
impossible to go around them. Passages are breached by the 
battalion obstacle clearing party, by mineclearing teams of 
companies and by other mineclearing methods. Subunits move along 
passages in approach march formations under cover of fire of 
artillery, tanks, BMP's (BTR's), and the battalion AT subunit 
and grenade launcher subunit. To ensure timely forward movement 
of the obstacle clearing party for breaching obstacles, it is 
advisable to have it displace behind first echelon companies 
near the battalion commander's COP. 
  During the attack the battalion COP displaces behind first 
echelon companies at a distance giving the commander an 
opportunity for continuous observation of the battlefield and 
stable communications with the senior commander and with 
attached and supporting subunits. The battalion commander must 
constantly reconnoiter the enemy and terrain and observe the 
battlefield; promptly give artillery fire support to subunits 
which have achieved greatest success; and skillfully exploit the 
success for developing the attack. 
  When attacking on an axis where the enemy is reliably 
neutralized and not offering organized resistance, a battalion 
may not deploy into battle formation, but assault in approach 
march formation. Assigned subunits may deploy into battle 
formation to destroy the remaining enemy. 
  If the battalion launches an attack outside of the 
regimental 
penetration sector, then it must use aggressive actions, above 
all the fire of all weapons, to keep the enemy from removing a 
portion of his forces from the occupied position and 
transferring them to the penetration sector. When there has been 
reliable fire damage of the enemy or upon discovery of removal 
of a portion of forces or their withdrawal from the occupied 
position, the battalion should assault the enemy decisively with 
artillery fire support. It is advisable to conduct the assault 
with the main body along an axis adjoining the penetration 
sector. Making wide use of a maneuver of fire and subunits, one 
should destroy the enemy in strongpoints and develop the attack 
into the depth. A situation may take shape where the enemy 
offers stubborn resistance on the FEBA. In this case it is 
advisable to commit the battalion second echelon in the 
penetration sector with the mission of routing the enemy by 
striking the flank and rear of his strongpoints, expand the 
penetration sector and develop the attack into the depth. 
  When the regiment attacks in the entire zone without a 
penetration sector being designated, the battalion, taking 
advantage of gaps in the enemy battle formation and exploiting 
results of fire damage, penetrates the defense with the main 
body from the move and advances nonstop into the depth, covering 
its flanks with a portion of the forces. An enemy who continues 
to offer resistance is sealed off with minimal forces and 
destroyed by the second echelon (reserve) or by assigned 
subunits. 
  The battalion goes around strongpoints in the depth of the 
enemy defense which are delaying the advance, using smoke in so 
doing, and decisively destroys him by strikes against the flank 
and rear with support from the front. War experience indicates 
that only a skilled maneuver of subunits and fire and the 
delivery of strikes against the flank and rear in coordination 
with subunits of all combat arms can achieve decisive 
destruction of the enemy in strongpoints. 
  Based on the nature of enemy operations and the position 
occupied, companies in the battalion battle formation may be in 
a line, wedge (inverted wedge), or echelon right or left. 
  Lines and objectives captured in the depth of the enemy 
defense and which are of great importance are consolidated by 
subunits assigned for this. On arriving at the line the subunit 
digs in and prepares fire to repel a possible enemy 
counterattack. 
  Success attained in fighting in the depth of the enemy 
defense must be exploited immediately to achieve his total rout. 
  With an enemy withdrawal the battalion commander updates the 
mission for the reconnaissance (combat reconnaissance) patrol, 
sends out new patrols if necessary and assigns missions to 
subunits for the pursuit. The commander reports to the senior 
chief and informs adjacent subunits about shifting to the 
pursuit. 
  Depending on situation conditions a battalion usually 
conducts the pursuit by two methods: along parallel routes or 
from the front. Pursuit along parallel routes is the most 
advisable method. 
  In the course of pursuit a battalion operates in battle, 
approach march or march formation depending on the situation. 
Personnel in motor vehicles may pursue a retreating enemy as a 
mounted force on tanks or in motor vehicles covered by tanks. 
  With successful development of the attack, an MRB (TB) may 
operate in a forward or raiding detachment. 
  The mission of a forward detachment is to capture 
an important line (objective) in the depth of the enemy defense 
and hold it until the main body arrives. A raiding 
detachment may be assigned a mission to destroy or capture 
one or two important objectives: tactical missile batteries, 
individual elements of a reconnaissance-strike complex, an 
artillery battalion, fire support helicopter basing site, a 
base, a depot, bridge crossing and other objectives. After 
performing a mission the raiding detachment as a rule joins 
(moves up to) the main body, avoiding a fight with the enemy. 
  Conditions under which detachments have to operate are 
determined and characterized by the following basic factors: 
considerable separation from the main body and presence of 
exposed flanks; possibility of an enemy ground and air attack on 
the detachments from different directions; frequent changes in 
directions of detachment operations. In the course of performing 
missions, detachments often will interwork with an airborne 
(amphibious) assault force, aviation, and reconnaissance, 
forward and raiding detachments operating from adjacent units 
and formations. 
  To increase independence of operations an MRB (TB) may be 
reinforced by a TC (MRC), SP artillery battalion, air defense 
battery, and also a combat engineer platoon. 
  The alignment of a detachment's forces and assets must 
conform to the commander's decision and ensure the following: 
swift commitment and advance into the depth of the enemy 
defense; deployment of forces and assets from the move into 
approach march and battle formations from a column; independence 
of operations by companies; buildup of efforts in conducting 
battle and when it is necessary to disengage; and convenience of 
C[.sup]2[/]. 
  It is desirable to have the following alignment of a 
detachment march formation when moving up to the objective: 
march security (forward, flank and rear security elements), 
movement support detachment, main body, and necessary number of 
technical support and rear vehicles. MRC's (TC's) usually are 
reinforced by tank (motorized rifle) subunits. The combat 
reconnaissance patrol will perform reconnaissance missions in 
support of the battalion. 
  To rout the enemy a forward detachment and raiding 
detachment 
as a rule deploy into a battle formation which consists of first 
echelon subunits (two reinforced MRC's or TC's), a reserve (up 
to a company), artillery, and air defense subunits. In addition, 
there may be destruction (demolition) and capture teams in the 
raiding detachment battle formation if necessary. 
  On receiving a mission the battalion commander sends out 
reconnaissance and makes his decision based on a mission 
analysis and situation estimate. The following usually are 
specified in the commander's concept: direction of operations 
(if not indicated by the senior commander); sequence and methods 
for destruction, capture or disabling of enemy objectives during 
commitment and operations in the depth; detachment alignment 
during commitment and operations in the enemy rear; procedure 
for forward movement, methods of commitment, and nature of 
maneuver in the enemy rear; and methods of achieving surprise of 
operations. The commander's concept is determined for the full 
depth of detachment operations, while combat missions are 
assigned to subunits only for capture of a line (for the forward 
detachment) or for smashing (destroying) a priority objective 
(for the raiding detachment). 
  In accordance with the decision, the battalion commander 
assigns missions to subordinates, organizes coordination and 
issues necessary instructions for comprehensive support of 
operations. Combat missions for subunits and the procedure for 
coordination as a rule are updated on initial engagement of the 
enemy. 
  Taking advantage of gaps in the enemy battle formation, the 
detachment decisively penetrates into the depth of his defense. 
Without becoming engaged with him, the detachment moves swiftly 
up to the indicated line or objective and captures it. If 
necessary, the detachment's commitment may be supported by 
artillery fire, helicopter strikes and operations of first 
echelon subunits. After taking the designated line, the forward 
detachment shifts to a defense and holds it until the main body 
arrives. It must be a perimeter defense and ensure repulse of 
enemy assaults from different directions. If the situation 
permits, the forward detachment advances by authorization of the 
commander who sent it out in order to preempt the enemy in 
seizing a new line. 
  The past war's experience shows that the forward 
detachment's 
successful performance of the mission is achieved by its 
decisive, highly mobile operations. 
  On arrival at the planned objective and with initial 
engagement of security, the raiding detachment commander as a 
rule updates the decision and missions for subordinates. The 
detachment destroys the enemy by a surprise assault of the main 
body from the move, usually from two or three directions, puts 
his objective out of commission and moves to the assembly area. 
If necessary, the destruction team blows up structures and 
destroys vehicles and the capture team seizes documents, weapons 
and prisoners. 
  In the course of disabling or destroying the first 
objective, 
the detachment commander sends out reconnaissance to the next 
enemy objective. The detachment maneuvers onto the new axis 
covertly and quickly in columns. Measures for deceiving the 
enemy, especially regarding the true axis of operations, should 
be provided for here. 
  Nighttime and other conditions of limited visibility should 
be used fully to execute a maneuver in the depth of the enemy 
defense and deliver surprise attacks. 
  After executing a mission the raiding detachment moves up to 
the main body covertly and joins it. If necessary, it may hold 
the objective until the main body arrives. 
  An MRB (TB) also may operate in a special detachment during 
development of the attack. The detachment mission is to destroy 
means of nuclear and chemical attack and precision weapon 
systems. Operations of a special detachment essentially are 
similar to those of a raiding detachment. 
  On receiving the combat mission, the battalion commander 
immediately sends out a reconnaissance (combat reconnaissance) 
patrol. Taking advantage of intervals, breaches and gaps in the 
enemy battle formation and his exposed flanks, the detachment 
moves covertly and quickly to the designated area. Then it 
decisively assaults the enemy, usually from different 
directions, destroys covering-force subunits, and captures and 
destroys his launchers (guns) and missiles (ammunition). After 
performing the assigned mission the special detachment may 
receive a new combat mission or it moves to the operating area 
of its own units. 
  When attacking a fortified area, an MRB may operate as an 
assault detachment. Assault teams are formed in the assault 
detachment to destroy the enemy or seal him off in permanent 
weapon emplacements and other important structures. Each team 
includes up to a reinforced MRC. 
  The assault detachment is reinforced by tanks, artillery, 
flamethrowers, ATGM and air defense subunits and a combat 
engineer subunit. The detachment is given an immediate mission 
and direction for continuing the attack. 
  An assault detachment's immediate mission is to seize and 
destroy permanent weapon emplacements and other important 
structures in strongpoints of enemy first echelon companies. The 
direction for continuing the attack is determined so as to 
ensure capture and destruction of enemy weapon emplacements and 
other structures in the depth of his first position. To perform 
the combat mission the assault detachment takes up an attack 
position in immediate proximity to the assault objectives. 
  An assault on the enemy by the assault detachment begins 
simultaneously with first echelon tank and motorized rifle 
subunits. In coordination with a portion of forces of tank and 
motorized rifle subunits advancing into the depth of the enemy 
defense, the detachment seals off and destroys sturdy structures 
which survived fire preparation of the assault. 
  An MRB (TB) may launch a hasty attack on a defending enemy 
with forward movement from an assembly area. In this case the 
battalion column alignment should support its swift deployment 
into approach march and battle formations and transition into 
the assault. Therefore MRC's (TC's) move forward with means of 
reinforcement, and the tank subunit attached to the MRB moves at 
the head of the MRB column. Air defense subunits are dispersed 
through the column. Heading up the COP, the battalion commander 
moves forward at the head of the column. An ATP and GLP not 
involved in fire preparation of the assault proceed in front of 
the second echelon (reserve). 
  The mortar battery and attached artillery battery which are 
used for fire preparation of the assault, and also regimental 
weapons, including those assigned for direct fire, move forward 
and take up firing positions in advance under the senior 
commander's plan. Tanks to be equipped with roller-type 
mineclearing devices also are moved up by his direction (usually 
to the vicinity of the line of deployment into company columns). 
  Minefields which the enemy may lay by remote minelaying 
assets in the period of forward movement are negotiated through 
passages breached by the senior commander's movement support 
detachment, by the battalion obstacle clearing party and by 
mineclearing teams of companies. 
  The battalion moves forward, observing measures of 
protection 
against enemy precision weapons and radar and optical 
reconnaissance. 
  If the enemy delivers nuclear and chemical strikes or massed 
precision weapon strikes, subunits which have retained combat 
effectiveness continue moving up to the line of departure. A 
first echelon company which has lost combat effectiveness is 
replaced by the second echelon (reserve). In case the enemy 
employs incendiary munitions, subunits are moved out of the area 
of the fire, extinguish centers of fire on vehicles and continue 
performing the assigned mission. 
  Fire preparation of the assault begins with the battalion's 
arrival at the line reached by fire of the bulk of enemy 
artillery (or from a line designated by the senior commander). 
In the course of fire preparation, guns, tanks and other weapons 
assigned for direct fire destroy enemy armored targets in and 
between strongpoints on the FEBA and in the depth. 
  In the period of fire preparation of the assault the 
battalion deploys successively into company and platoon columns 
at appropriate lines or points. On approaching the line of 
departure, they deploy into battle formation and launch an 
assault without stopping, conducting fire from tanks and BMP's 
(BTR's). 
  Artillery and aviation shift to fire support of the assault 
when the battalion's first echelon companies begin arriving at 
the line of departure. 
  The assault on the enemy defense is made with close 
interworking of TC's and MRC's. TC's assault in an extended line 
and MRC's in dismounted formation following the tanks or in 
BMP's (BTR's) without the personnel dismounting, depending on 
the situation. In the course of the assault and development of 
the attack in the depth of the enemy defense, battalion 
operations subsequently are similar to those of a battalion 
which launches an attack from a position of direct contact with 
the enemy. 
<H5>  9. Night Attack </H5>
  One of the principles of conducting an attack is its 
continuity. Nonstop conduct of the battle both day as well as 
night is of the greatest importance in achieving this principle. 
This permits maintaining the initiative, imposing one's will on 
the enemy, disrupting his plans and, as a result, achieving 
decisive victory sometimes with lesser forces. Based on this, a 
night attack may begin with penetration of the enemy defense or 
may be a continuation of daytime combat operations. The night 
contributes to achieving covert maneuver and surprise. 
  Orientation, recognition of targets (objectives), 
C[.sup]2[/] of subunits, their support by artillery fire and 
air strikes, as well as coordination among them is complicated 
at night. Driving combat and transport vehicles, executing a 
maneuver, and detecting barriers and obstacles is hampered and 
personnel fatigue increases. At night the danger arises of 
subunits losing the axis of attack, and effectiveness of all 
kinds of fire drops perceptibly. Subunits may end up in a vague 
situation and be subjected to various surprises more often than 
during the day. Performing fire missions may require 1.3-1.5 
times more time and a greater expenditure of rounds by all 
weapons even when using illumination assets and night vision 
devices. At night the casualty effect of thermal radiation from 
a nuclear burst increases sharply. 
  Therefore successful conduct of a night attack requires 
subunit personnel to have high morale, proficiency, conditioning 
and comprehensive training and requires preparation of weapons 
and vehicles, which is confirmed by war and exercise experience. 
  Poor visibility or its total absence is the chief factor 
negatively influencing conduct of a night attack. Artificial 
illumination assets and night vision devices are used to create 
favorable conditions for such a battle. 
  Illumination assets (air-dropped illumination flares, 
illuminating artillery and mortar rounds, pyrotechnic flares and 
searchlights) and light signaling assets (signal flares and trip 
flares with colored lights; tracer bullets and rounds; colored 
air-dropped parachute signal flares (colored marker-signal 
shells), sets of signal lights, route signal lights and lighted 
markers (indicators)) are used for artificial illumination. 
  Illuminating artillery and mortar rounds are used to 
illuminate the terrain and objectives, blind observation posts 
and weapon crews, adjust artillery fire and place lines of 
marker lights (light markers). Parachute flares serve to 
illuminate large terrain sectors and large enemy objectives. 
Searchlights are used to illuminate terrain and objectives, 
blind the enemy, orient friendly troops, and combat enemy 
searchlights and night vision devices. 
  Illuminating flare cartridges (pyrotechnic flares) are 
intended for illuminating terrain and enemy targets directly 
ahead of friendly subunit battle formations. Light signaling 
assets are used for orientation on the terrain; accomplishing 
target designation; calling in, transferring and ceasing fire; 
giving (or duplicating) signals (commands); identifying and 
marking friendly subunits and so on. C[.sup]2[/] of subunits 
and maintenance of continuous coordination among them are 
considerably facilitated with their help. 
  Orientation may be accomplished by placing light markers 
(lines of marker lights), illuminating boundaries between 
battalions, and marking movement routes (cross-country routes), 
lines, passages, crossings, landing sites and so on. Night 
vision devices are used to conduct observation, reconnoiter the 
enemy, and control the heading and rate of movement of tanks and 
BMP's (BTR's), and they also are used for conducting small arms 
fire and the fire of artillery systems. 
  An attack on a defending enemy at night may be launched both 
from a position of direct contact with him as well as from the 
move. The attack may begin at the beginning or in the middle of 
the night or just before dawn. Launching an attack at the 
beginning of the night permits taking advantage of more hours of 
darkness for routing the enemy, while the second half of the 
night or the time before dawn is advantageous in that enemy 
vigilance as a rule is reduced in this period. 
  When a night attack is a continuation of daytime operations, 
enemy positions and lines usually are assaulted from the move. 
This keeps him from upgrading the defense, drawing up reserves 
or disengaging and breaking off from attacking subunits to 
occupy a defense at a new line. 
  Open terrain without significant natural barriers, but with 
reference points visible in the darkness used for directing the 
operations of subunits (highways, field roads, treelines, 
streams, openings and so on), is most favorable for a night 
attack. 
  The width of attack frontage and content of company 
(battalion) combat missions are the very same as for a daytime 
attack, but in assigning missions it is advisable that the 
battalion immediate or subsequent mission be accomplished by 
dawn. If this is impossible to do, a battalion may be given a 
supplementary line which it must take by dawn. Designation of 
such a line is caused basically by the need to create favorable 
conditions for committing the second echelon and for repelling 
possible enemy counterattacks at dawn. The determination of this 
line depends basically on length of the night, time the attack 
is launched, preparedness of subunits for night battle and the 
availability of illumination support assets to them. When the 
attack occurs in the depth of the enemy defense, a battalion 
most often will receive a combat mission for the entire night in 
the course of the attack's development. 
  The battalion battle formation usually is aligned in two 
echelons. Commitment of the second echelon under nighttime 
conditions presents some difficulty. Therefore it is advisable 
to assign that number of forces and assets to the first echelon 
which would ensure its performance of the mission assigned for 
the night without committing the second echelon. 
  Illumination support is organized by the senior commander 
and 
accomplished under a unified plan. A battalion receives a 
certain amount of illumination and light signaling assets to 
perform missions envisaged by the plan and those which arise 
suddenly. A mortar (artillery) platoon may be assigned in the 
battalion for employing those assets, and two or three 
illumination posts (one per platoon) controlled by the company 
commander may be established in companies. Air defense subunits 
also should be assigned missions of destroying enemy 
illumination support assets (illuminating mortar and artillery 
rounds and parachute flares) in the air. 
  Preparation for a night attack occurs most often in hours of 
daylight and has a number of features. Thus, in addition to 
general questions, in organizing for battle the company 
(battalion) commander indicates to subordinate commanders the 
reference points visible at night and azimuth of the direction 
of attack; he may designate a guide platoon (company) and 
missions for destroying enemy night vision devices and 
illumination support assets; and he determines the procedure for 
marking friendly subunits and using night vision devices and 
short-range reconnaissance radars. In addition, the procedure is 
clarified for illumination of terrain and assault objectives and 
placement of light markers (lines of marker lights) by artillery 
fire and other means to mark the direction of the attack, and 
the procedure is established for marking lines reached 
(occupied) by subunits, their flanks, and movement routes. 
  Measures for protection against thermal radiation of nuclear 
bursts also are envisaged without fail, and support of subunits 
with illumination assets, tracer rounds, cartridges with tracer 
bullets, and signaling devices is organized. 
  The use of illumination devices should not reveal friendly 
subunits, hamper use of night vision devices or create favorable 
conditions for the enemy to conduct fire against attacking 
subunits. 
  Special attention in preparing the subunits should be given 
to checking the technical condition of night vision devices and 
external and internal illumination of vehicles, applying 
identifying markings to them and replenishing reserves of light 
signaling assets. Illumination posts are prepared. 
  The company (battalion) launches an attack as a rule after 
fire preparation of the assault. Sometimes the attack also may 
be launched without conducting such a preparation in order to 
achieve surprise. 
  Motorized rifle subunits usually assault the enemy in 
dismounted formation in close coordination with tanks and 
artillery. As a rule the tanks and BMP's (BTR's) operate in the 
motorized riflemen's extended line. 
  During an attack subunits precisely maintain their indicated 
directions, skillfully use illumination assets and mark their 
position. Special attention is given to covering flanks and 
conducting reconnaissance. Under nighttime conditions surprise 
counterattacks even by small forces may have a significant 
psychological effect on personnel. 
  The battalion second echelon (reserve) may be committed even 
before daybreak, but without executing a complicated maneuver. 
During commitment, in addition to the usual questions the second 
echelon (reserve) also is given an azimuth for the direction of 
the attack during the mission update (assignment). For 
successful operations of the second echelon (reserve), artillery 
neutralizes and illuminates the enemy and places a light marker 
in the direction of the attack. 
  When shifting from night to daytime operations, 
reconnaissance is organized, missions are updated for (assigned 
to) subunits, artillery and weapons move closer to them, air 
defense is reinforced, flanks are secured, and subunits' 
ammunition and other supplies are replenished. 
<H5>  10. Forcing Water Obstacles </H5>
  The attack of an MRC or TC (MRB or TB) often will be 
accomplished with the forcing of a water obstacle. The 
surmounting of a water obstacle by attacking subunits when its 
opposite bank is defended by the enemy is called forcing. Water 
obstacles above all are rivers, which are narrow (up to 100 m), 
medium (from 100 to 250 m), wide (250-600 m) and major (over 600 
m). 
  A forcing is made by a company (battalion) as a rule from 
the 
march with preparation back before approaching the water 
obstacle. If a forcing from the march did not succeed, it is 
done with deployment of the main body at the water obstacle 
after additional preparation in a short time or after thorough 
preparation. In this case the forcing may be done from a 
position of direct contact with the enemy or from the march with 
forward movement from a staging area [iskhodnyy rayon]. 
  Airborne assault forces may be landed prior to forcing of a 
water obstacle from the march to seize crossings and prohibit 
the approach of reserves. 
  A company (battalion) usually forces a water obstacle as 
part 
of the battalion (regimental) main body, and independently when 
operating in a forward security element (or a battalion in a 
forward or raiding detachment or the advance guard). In all 
cases the forcing of water obstacles requires careful 
preparation of personnel, weapons and military vehicles, conduct 
of measures to keep them from accumulating at crossings, and 
strict compliance with safety measures. 
  Primary and secondary crossings are assigned to a company 
when forcing a water obstacle as part of the main body, and a 
crossing sector [uchastok] is assigned to a battalion. When the 
regimental main body deploys at a water obstacle, a battalion 
additionally is assigned a staging area for the forcing directly 
at the water obstacle. A company usually occupies a staging 
position [iskhodnoye polozheniye] in the battalion area. When 
the regiment occupies a staging area at certain distance from a 
water obstacle, a company (battalion) is assigned a staging area 
for the forcing. 
  Amphibious vehicle crossings, ferry crossings, a fording 
site 
or a fully submerged crossing site may be organized in the 
battalion forcing sector. Amphibious vehicle crossings are 
organized on tracked amphibian carriers and ferry crossings on 
amphibious river-crossing equipment or tracked selfpropelled 
ferries. Motorized rifle subunits usually cross water obstacles 
in BMP's (BTR's); tanks cross on ferries (amphibious river- 
crossing equipment, tracked self-propelled ferries), by fording, 
or fully submerged; and nonamphibious artillery and wheeled 
vehicles cross on tracked amphibian carriers. The number and 
kinds of crossings are determined by availability of crossing 
equipment, nature of the water obstacle and established 
procedure for the crossing of subunits. 
  For an organized forcing from the march, a line of 
departure for the forcing [iskhodnyy rubezh dlya forsirovaniya] 
is designated 1-2 km from the water's edge, and an area for 
boarding (loading) on assault crossing equipment and an armor 
inspection and deepfording preparation area 5-6 km from the 
water's edge. When a staging area for the forcing is occupied 
right at the water obstacle, the line of departure for the 
forcing is designated 100300 m from the water's edge and the 
boarding (loading) area and armor inspection and deepfording 
preparation area are designated in sheltered places near the 
water obstacle. 
  Commandants are appointed from among commanders of engineer 
troop subunits to ensure firm order in the forcing sector and at 
crossings, and the TB commander (chief of staff) or tanker 
officer is assigned for this at a fully submerged tank crossing 
(or fording). 
  The width of attack frontage and content of combat missions 
of the company (battalion) with forcing of a water obstacle as 
part of the main body basically are the very same as in an 
attack on a defending enemy without a forcing. 
  The mission of a company operating in a forward security 
element usually is to destroy the enemy on approaches to the 
water obstacle, force it from the march, destroy the enemy in 
the platoon strongpoint on the opposite bank and take a line 
supporting the forcing of the water obstacle from the march by 
the main body of a forward (raiding) detachment or advance guard. 
  As a rule, a battalion assigned to a forward detachment is 
assigned the mission to seize from the march crossings (bridges) 
and sectors favorable for forcing and hold them until the main 
body approaches. The depth of the captured bridgehead must not 
permit enemy AT weapons and tanks to conduct direct fire against 
the crossing. 
  The mission of a battalion operating in the advance guard 
may 
be to destroy the enemy on approaches to the water obstacle, 
support the main body in moving to it, force it from the march 
and rout the enemy on the opposite bank. 
  To support the forcing of a water obstacle from the march, 
in 
addition to usual means of reinforcement, an MRB operating in a 
forward (raiding) detachment or the advance guard may receive 
the attachment of an amphibious river-crossing equipment platoon 
or tracked self-propelled ferry platoon and a tracked amphibian 
carrier platoon, and a TB may receive the attachment of one or 
two amphibious river-crossing equipment or tracked self- 
propelled ferry platoons and a tracked amphibian carrier 
platoon. Crossings are prepared under the senior commander's 
plan during company (battalion) operations as part of the main 
body. 
  The commander must organize reconnaissance of the water 
obstacle, make the decision for the forcing, assign missions to 
subordinates and organize coordination in advance. 
  A combat reconnaissance patrol and patrol squads (tanks) are 
assigned for reconnoitering the enemy, the water obstacle and 
planned crossing sites. On arriving at the water obstacle, 
reconnaissance must determine enemy forces and assets on the 
opposite bank; the presence and condition of crossings and fords 
and the most convenient places for preparing amphibious vehicle 
crossings, ferry crossings and tank crossings by fording or 
fully submerged. Reconnaissance entities cross independently in 
the absence of an enemy on the opposite bank. 
  Based on reconnaissance data the commander updates the 
decision made from the map, the crossing sites and the procedure 
for using attached crossing equipment. In addition to the usual 
questions the commander determines the following in the decision 
for the forcing: procedure for destroying the enemy on 
approaches to the water obstacle and on the opposite bank; sites 
and kinds of primary and alternate crossings and the 
distribution of crossing equipment; routes and procedure for 
moving up to the water obstacle; sequence of the crossing of 
subunits. In organizing the forcing, the commander also 
determines the procedure for preparing weapons and military 
vehicles. 
  In forcing a water obstacle from the march, combat missions 
are communicated to (updated for) subordinates by operational 
instructions, usually by radio. First of all missions are 
assigned to those subunits which must perform them (act against 
the enemy) earlier than others and which need more time to 
prepare. Coordination instructions also are issued 
simultaneously in the operational instructions. If the forcing 
is being done with deployment of the regimental main body at the 
water obstacle, missions as a rule are assigned to subordinates 
by a verbal operation order. 
  In assigning the mission to subunits for the forcing of a 
water obstacle, the company (battalion) commander additionally 
indicates the following in the operation order: 

  -  for platoons (companies)--missions on the 
approach to the water obstacle, during the forcing and on the 
opposite bank, primary and alternate crossing sites, armor 
inspection and deepfording preparation area, locations for 
boarding personnel and loading weapons and vehicles on self 
propelled assault crossing equipment, line of departure for the 
forcing and the time of crossing the line; 
  -  for artillery subunits, grenade launcher subunit and AT 
subunit-missions for supporting subunits in forcing the 
water obstacle and in the battle on the opposite bank, and also 
firing positions, readiness time for commencing fire and the 
crossing procedure; 
  -  for the air defense subunit--missions for covering 
subunits against enemy air strikes during forward movement to 
the water obstacle, during the forcing, and in the battle on the 
opposite bank, and also launch (firing) positions, readiness 
time for commencing fire and the crossing procedure; 
  -  for attached subunits of engineer troops--missions 
for engineer reconnaissance of crossing sites, preparing and 
maintaining crossings, and preparing forward movement routes to 
them, and also locations of assault crossing equipment during 
forward movement to the water obstacle. 


    Amphibious combat vehicles are prepared before they arrive 
at 
the water obstacle. Special attention must be given to tight 
closure of hatches, firing ports and doors and to serviceability 
of bilge pumps and the presence and tight closure of drain 
plugs. Personnel in vehicles put on life vests. Tanks are 
prepared for a fully submerged crossing on the approach, and 
this is completed in the armor inspection and deepfording 
preparation area. 
  Subunits move up to the water obstacle at maximum rate of 
speed in readiness for forcing it from the march. 
  Fire preparation of forcing and the assault usually is 
conducted before forcing, and fire support of forcing and the 
assault is carried out on completion of fire preparation (during 
forcing). The moment first echelon subunits shove off from the 
near bank is considered to be the beginning of forcing (H), and 
the arrival of all company (battalion) forces and assets at the 
opposite bank is the end of forcing. 
  A company operating in a forward security element decisively 
destroys the enemy on approaches to the water obstacle, seizes 
crossings (bridges, fords) and moves to the opposite bank. In 
the absence of crossings or if they have been blown up by the 
enemy, the company forces the water obstacle from the march. 
Exploiting results of artillery and tank fire, MRP's cross the 
water obstacle in BMP's (BTR's) and destroy the enemy on the 
opposite bank by fire of all weapons from afloat. The enemy 
firing against company flanks is destroyed by the fire of tanks 
and guns and blinded by aerosols (smoke). On arriving at the 
opposite bank the company captures the indicated line, 
supporting the main body's crossing and commitment. SP 
amphibious artillery crosses independently and tanks cross on 
ferries or by fording depending on the situation. The company 
commander crosses to the opposite bank right after the platoons. 
  If a water obstacle has failed to be forced from the march, 
the company consolidates on the captured bank. It neutralizes 
and destroys the enemy on the opposite bank by fire of all 
weapons and thereby creates favorable conditions for main body 
commitment. 
  A battalion assigned to a forward detachment moves up to a 
water obstacle swiftly without engaging the enemy on approaches 
to it. Exploiting success of the forward security element and 
results of air strikes and artillery fire, it crosses the water 
obstacle at crossings and in amphibious BMP's (BTR's) and 
assault crossing equipment. It destroys the enemy on the 
opposite bank by decisive actions, captures a bridgehead with 
favorable sectors for forcing, and holds it until the main body 
arrives. The battalion often performs its mission in 
coordination with a tactical airborne assault force. 
  If the battalion is operating in a raiding detachment, it 
usually crosses the water obstacle in the course of forward 
movement to its indicated objective over a bridge or ford 
captured by the forward security element, in amphibious fighting 
vehicles and assault crossing equipment. 
  A battalion operating in an advance guard decisively 
destroys 
the enemy covering approaches to the water obstacle and moves up 
to it. Exploiting success of the forward security element, it 
crosses the water obstacle from the march over captured 
crossings or in assault crossing equipment. Subsequently the 
battalion continues the attack into the depth of the enemy 
defense, supporting the main body's forcing and crossing. 
  Actions of a reinforced TB, the advance guard of 61st Guards 
Tank Brigade, on 20 January 1945 were an example of such 
actions. Decisively destroying the enemy on approaches to the 
Warta River as a forward security element, it took a bridge from 
the march (combat engineers disarmed explosives emplaced in it). 
The entire battalion rushed in on the heels of the forward 
security element, took the terrain sector ahead of the bridge 
and supported the crossing of the brigade main body and 
development of success into the depth.[.sup]1[/] 
  Organic and attached artillery and the grenade launchers 
take 
up firing positions from the march and use their fire to support 
battle of the forward security element and the main body's 
crossing and battle on the opposite bank. Tanks and guns moved 
up to conduct direct fire and ATGM systems destroy enemy AT 
weapons, tanks and personnel and cover flanks. Aircraft deliver 
strikes against the enemy in the depth, especially against the 
nearest reserves. 
  Exploiting results of fire and under cover of aerosols 
(smoke), motorized rifle subunits in amphibious BMP's (BTR's) 
and assault crossing equipment force the water obstacle, destroy 
the enemy by their fire from afloat and develop the attack into 
the depth after taking the opposite bank. 
  The forcing begins and is conducted on selected axes 
simultaneously by all first echelon forces. 
  Subunits assigned to cross on self-propelled crossing 
equipment on the first trip load weapons and vehicles and board 
personnel in sheltered places. They move swiftly out from these 
places toward the water obstacle and cross to the opposite bank 
from the move. On succeeding trips weapons and vehicles are 
loaded and personnel board the crossing equipment directly at 
the water obstacle. 
  As a rule, the crossing of tanks fully submerged is 
accomplished after motorized riflemen take the opposite bank. On 
emerging onto the bank, tank subunits swiftly move out to their 
own axes and perform assigned missions. 
  Attached and organic artillery, the air defense subunit, AT 
subunit and grenade launcher subunit usually cross in amphibious 
vehicles and assault crossing equipment to ensure continuity of 
support and cover of subunits on the opposite bank. AT weapons 
and self-propelled artillery should cross first of all to assist 
motorized rifle subunits in repelling possible enemy 
counterattacks. 
  Engineer subunits conduct engineer reconnaissance of the 
water obstacle; prepare, camouflage and maintain crossings and 
approach routes to them; breach obstacles; and organize and 
perform commandant's service at the crossing. 
  Battalion technical support and rear subunits cross in 
assault crossing equipment following the artillery and air 
defense subunits. The aid station and ammunition vehicles should 
be sent across first of all. Wounded and sick usually are sent 
across to the near shore by assault crossing equipment returning 
after landing subunits, and if necessary also by specially 
assigned crossing equipment. 
  If the advance guard failed to force the water obstacle from 
the march, it consolidates on the line reached, inflicts damage 
on the enemy by fire of all weapons and supports the main body's 
forcing of the water obstacle. 
  Exploiting success of the forward detachment (advance guard) 
and a tactical airborne assault force, a company (battalion) 
operating as part of the main body forces the obstacle over 
crossings captured by them, or motorized rifle subunits do so in 
BMP's (BTR's), tank subunits do so under water, and others do so 
in assault crossing equipment nonstop as they approach the water 
obstacle. Subsequently the company (battalion) assaults the 
enemy from the move, widens the bridgehead in coordination with 
the forward detachment (advance guard) and other subunits, and 
develops the attack into the depth. 
  If the company (battalion) is performing a mission where a 
forward detachment (advance guard) is not operating, the forcing 
of a water obstacle from the move usually begins after fire 
preparation of the forcing and the assault, supported by the 
fire of artillery, aircraft, tanks and guns assigned for direct 
fire. 
  In forcing with deployment of the main body at the 
water obstacle, an MRC (MRB) operating as part of the 
battalion (regimental) first echelon boards BMP's (BTR's) and 
self- propelled assault crossing equipment in sheltered places. 
It moves up to the water obstacle in the course of fire 
preparation of the forcing and the assault. For the crossing of 
a TC (TB), assault crossing equipment and tanks move up to 
crossing sites, where tanks are loaded. 
  The battalion commander gives the signal to move forward 
based on the beginning time of the forcing and the time needed 
to cover the distance from the boarding site to the water's edge. 
  Subunits of the first trip move forward swiftly to the water 
obstacle and shove off from the near bank exactly at H hour. On 
arriving on the opposite bank, the subunits assault the enemy 
and develop the attack into the depth. Fire support of their 
assault, especially at first, also is provided by fire of guns 
and tanks assigned for direct fire, by ATGM systems and by 
grenade launchers. 
  Second echelon subunits cross the water obstacle right after 
the battalion first echelon in readiness for commitment. 
  With the arrival of the company (battalion) on the opposite 
bank the enemy will attempt to throw it back from the captured 
bridgehead. A counterattack of his superior forces usually is 
repelled by fire of all weapons from in place supported by fire 
of artillery and combat helicopters. Having inflicted damage, 
the company (battalion) completes the enemy's rout in 
coordination with adjacent subunits and continues the attack 
into the depth. 
  C[.sup]2[/] of the company (battalion) is exercised from 
the COP, which displaces in the direction of concentration of 
main efforts. The company COP usually is located at the water's 
edge and moves to the opposite bank behind the first trip of 
subunits. The battalion COP is disposed 100-200 m from the river 
bank, and COP's of the attached TC (MRC) and artillery battalion 
(battery) are located near it. The battalion commander crosses 
to the opposite bank behind first echelon subunits. 
  In winter a company (battalion) may force water obstacles 
over ice crossings. Thickness of 30 cm or more of the 
transparent part of the ice stands up to movement of BMP's 
(BTR's), and 60 cm or more stands up to movement of tanks. If 
ice thickness does not permit combat vehicles to move over it, 
the water obstacle initially is crossed by motorized rifle 
subunits in dismounted formation. Vehicles cross after the ice 
is reinforced or over ferry assault crossings prepared in gaps 
in the ice, and also over bridges. Under favorable conditions 
tanks may cross a water obstacle at fords or fully submerged. 
With intensive ice movement, water obstacles as a rule are 
crossed over captured bridges and motorized rifle subunits are 
airlifted across. 
  Actions by a forward detachment of a brigade of 6th Guards 
Tank Corps in 1945 were an example of such actions. On 13 
January the detachment approached the Nida River. Assault 
riflemen forced the river over the thin ice, and tanks and SP 
artillery forded. The ice was broken up by fire from tank guns 
so it did not hamper tank movement. Combat engineers reinforced 
the ice with wooden decking for the crossing of artillery and 
motor vehicles.[.sup]2[/] 
<H5>  11. MRC (MRB) in Tactical Airborne Assault Force </H5>
  An MRC (MRB) may be assigned to a tactical airborne assault 
force in the course of conducting the attack and the defense. It 
is landed in the enemy rear to capture and hold important lines 
(objectives) until the approach of friendly troops, to deliver 
strikes against the flank and rear of approaching enemy reserves 
and his withdrawing units and subunits, and to destroy (disable) 
means of nuclear and chemical attack, ground elements of 
reconnaissance-strike complexes and launchers. The assault 
force[.sup]3[/] also is employed to capture airfields, road 
junctions, hydraulic engineering works, bridges, crossing 
equipment, sectors convenient for forcing or crossing of units, 
passes, mountain gaps, gorges and road junctions and for 
performing other missions. 
  For example, on 19 August 1945 a group of 200 persons was 
formed from 30th Guards Mechanized Brigade for the landing of an 
assault force in Manchuria's capital of Changchun. Initially an 
advance party [peredovaya gruppa] with scouts took off in the 
aircraft, captured an airfield and supported the main body's 
landing. Subsequently the assault force took the city railroad 
station, post office and telegraph office.[.sup]4[/] 
  The conditions under which an assault force has to perform 
missions in isolation from the main body are characterized 
basically by constant, abrupt changes of the situation and also 
by the high likelihood of the enemy delivering strikes against 
it from different directions on the ground and from the air. 
  Combat operations of an assault force are distinguished by 
high mobility, swiftness, and maximum intensity of personnel's 
physical and moral efforts. To support such operations the 
assault force should not have heavy weapons and vehicles, it is 
reinforced by subunits of other combat arms and special troops, 
and it is also supported by forces and assets of the commander 
by whose decision it is being employed. 
  The landing of a company (battalion) is accomplished by one 
sortie of a subunit (unit) of transport, transport-attack and 
combat helicopters. Thus, a company less BMP's (BTR's) and 
reinforced by a mortar platoon may require 4 Mi-8 and 3 Mi-26 
helicopters, and a reinforced battalion may require up to 20 Mi- 
8 and 17-18 Mi-6 or Mi-26 helicopters. The helicopters form into 
a combat formation during airlift of the assault force. It 
usually includes an assault element (columns of helicopters of 
the main body and the advance party) and a support element, 
which may consist of reconnaissance helicopters, escort 
gunships, helicopters for neutralizing air defense weapons, and 
jamming helicopters. 
  For preparing and airlifting the assault force by 
helicopters 
to the area for performing the combat mission, it is assigned an 
assault airlift staging area [iskhodnyy rayon dlya 
desantirovaniya], an en route corridor, and primary and 
alternate landing areas [rayon desantirovaniya] (Diagram 15). 
  The assault airlift staging area is intended for 
completing preparation of the assault force and helicopters for 
the landing and operations. It may be 20-30 km from the front 
line. The assault airlift staging area usually includes a 
marshaling area [rayon sosredotocheniya] for the company 
(battalion) assigned to the assault force and primary and 
alternate helicopter landing sites [posadochnaya ploshchadka]. 
The size of this area for a company may be up to 3 
km[.sup]2[/] and for a battalion up to 10 km[.sup]2[/]. It 
should provide convenience in preparing the company (battalion) 
for the landing and performance of the mission, protection 
against mass destruction and precision weapons and a rapid move 
of the assault force for boarding (loading) the helicopters. The 
battalion is disposed in it by company with means of 
reinforcement. 
  Landing sites are intended for completing 
preparation of the helicopter subunit (unit) for the air 
assault, loading weapons, military vehicles and supplies in 
them, boarding the personnel and taking off for the air assault. 
It is advisable to select and prepare them in or near the 
assault force marshaling area. One landing site is prepared for 
no more than one helicopter squadron. In case the primary 
landing site is put out of commission, an alternate one is 
prepared, usually figuring one [alternate] site for two primary 
ones. 
  The en route corridor is intended for the combat 
flight of the helicopter subunit (unit) from the assault airlift 
staging area to the landing area. It is selected along a flight 
route where the enemy has the least amount of air defense 
weapons or where they have been reliably neutralized and the 
nature of terrain permits flying at low (to 300 m) and extremely 
low (1015 m) altitudes. The en route corridor may be 2-4 km wide. 
  The primary and alternate landing area (the 
alternate area is designated away from the primary one) is 
selected on terrain suitable for landing helicopters and giving 
the assault force favorable conditions for engagement. The 
landing area may be up to 10 km from the front line for the 
company and up to 20 km for the battalion. The landing area size 
is determined basically based on the combat mission and the 
commander's concept and may reach 2 km for the company and 5 km 
for the battalion laterally and in depth. One landing site 
[ploshchadka prizemleniya] in each landing area is designated 
for a company and 2-3 for a battalion for the landing. If it is 
impossible to use designated landing sites, the assault landing 
is made from a helicopter hover mode or "like an assault," i.e., 
on the move at minimum helicopter flight speed. 
  For an organized, timely flight of the helicopter subunit 
(unit) and beginning of operations with arrival in the landing 
area, it also is assigned a line of departure and a combat 
separation line. 
  A company (battalion) assigned to an assault force is given 
a 
combat mission for the entire period of its 
operations in the enemy rear. This mission usually is divided 
into immediate and subsequent missions. If necessary, a company 
(battalion) also may be given an assembly point (area). 
  The company (battalion) immediate mission usually 
consists of completing the enemy's destruction in the landing 
area and destroying (disabling) the indicated objective or 
capturing a certain line (area). The mission depth is the depth 
of the objective (objectives), including positions of its 
defending subunits, or the depth of the line (area) which the 
assault force is taking. 
  The subsequent mission may be to hold the captured 
line (area) until the approach of friendly units or to capture 
and destroy (disable) an objective in a new area and perform 
other missions. 
  An assembly point (area) is designated for a company 
(battalion) after performance of the combat mission for checking 
its status and preparing for further operations. Sometimes it 
also may be designated directly after landing (unloading) for 
assembling the subunits and updating missions for them. The 
presence of subunits at the assembly point (area) must be covert 
and brief. 
  Depending on the nature of the assigned mission, an assault 
force may perform it by an attack, by a defense and by raiding 
operations, during which conduct of a meeting battle also is not 
precluded. Destruction of the enemy and capture of a line (area) 
or objective usually is accomplished by an attack, and holding 
them until the approach of the main body usually is accomplished 
by the defense. A raid (raiding operations) usually will be 
conducted by the battalion as a raiding detachment. 
  The following usually are indicated in assigning missions to 
an assault force: brief information on the enemy in the en route 
corridor and in the landing zone [rayon vysadki] and the 
possible nature of his operations; makeup, means of 
reinforcement, primary and alternate landing areas and combat 
mission; assault airlift staging area; en route corridor and 
readiness time for the landing. In addition, means of fire 
support during airlift of the assault force, during the landing 
and during the battle under the senior commander's plan are 
announced. 
  To increase independence in performing the combat mission, a 
company (battalion) is reinforced by artillery, ATGM's, air 
defense and reconnaissance subunits and also subunits of 
engineer and chemical troops. An artillery officer and forward 
air controller with communications equipment are included in the 
assault force for requesting and adjusting fire of the main 
body's artillery and vectoring aircraft to targets respectively. 
  All subunits are provided with ammunition (often exceeding 
unit- level supply norms), food, individual protective gear and 
means to assist the wounded and sick. An assault force also 
should be reinforced by medical personnel. 
  The company (battalion) is aligned in a battle 
formation for fighting in the enemy rear. It usually 
consists of an advance party, first echelon subunits, a reserve 
(second echelon), subunits of artillery and other weapons, and 
air defense subunits. 
  The advance party is intended for completing 
destruction of the enemy at the landing site (sites), its 
capture, and support of the landing of the assault force main 
body. If an assault force consisting of an MRC is assigned, then 
up to a platoon is assigned to its advance party (up to two 
MRP's if the assault force is at battalion strength). The 
platoons are reinforced by air defense gunners, combat engineers 
and chemical scouts. A patrol squad (reconnaissance patrol, 
combat reconnaissance patrol) as well as artillery scouts of 
supporting (attached) artillery are landed together with the 
advance party. 
  Preparation for the landing and for assault force operations 
in the enemy rear includes the following: organization of the 
landing and the battle, and preparation of personnel, weapons, 
vehicles and supplies of subunits for the landing and 
performance of the combat mission; move of subunits to the 
assault airlift staging area and to the landing sites, loading 
of weapons and military vehicles and boarding personnel in the 
helicopters; and monitoring readiness of subunits for performing 
the combat mission. 
  On receiving the mission, the company (battalion) commander 
analyzes it, estimates the situation, makes the decision, 
performs a calculation for boarding (loading) the helicopters, 
issues the operation order and organizes coordination and 
preparation of subunits. 
  In analyzing the mission, in addition to general 
questions, the company (battalion) commander must understand the 
following: goal of employing the assault force and senior 
commander's concept, and the assault force mission and role in 
the upcoming battle; procedure for delivering strikes against 
the enemy in the landing area by the senior commander's assets; 
the landing procedure; conditions and procedure for coordinating 
with helicopters, artillery and units attacking from the front 
in the direction of assault force operations; duration of its 
operations in the enemy rear; from which landing sites and by 
what makeup of helicopters the landing is accomplished; and 
readiness time for the landing. 
  As a result of mission analysis, measures are outlined which 
are advisable to conduct immediately for preparing subunits to 
perform the mission. Then the commander performs a time 
calculation, issues instructions to subordinates for preparing 
subunits, weapons and military vehicles for operations as an 
assault force, and estimates the situation. 
  The following are determined in studying and estimating the 
enemy: presence of his air defense weapons in the en 
route corridor, presence of reserves and of tactical aviation 
near the landing area; possible nature of enemy actions in the 
en route corridor and in the combat operations area; strong and 
weak points of the enemy in and near the objective; nature of 
defense and security of the line (objective) to be captured 
(destroyed); direction for concentrating main company 
(battalion) efforts in taking and holding the line (destroying 
the objective); procedure for fire engagement of the enemy; 
advisable method of his destruction and alignment of the assault 
force battle formation. 
  The following are determined in estimating the 
situation and makeup of the company (battalion) and of 
attached and supporting subunits: their capabilities for 
fire engagement of the enemy during and after the landing; 
capabilities of the helicopter subunit (unit) assigned for the 
landing; makeup of elements of the battle formation and missions 
for subunits; which subunits are to board helicopters in what 
order and at what sites and land from them in the landing area; 
combat formation in flight and so on. 
  As a result of an estimate of the situation, makeup and 
nature of operations of units (subunits) attacking in the 
direction of the company (battalion) landing, the following are 
outlined: procedure for maintaining communications, time of 
their movement to the assault force and capability for 
supporting battle; linkup points, cessation of fire and 
procedure for joint operations; coordination and recognition 
signals. 
  As a result of an estimate of the nature of 
terrain in the landing area and in the area of assault 
force operations, the following are determined: presence and 
status of helicopter landing sites; direction for concentrating 
company (battalion) main efforts in capturing the objective; 
terrain sectors on whose holding stability depends in case of 
their defense; lines desirable for subunits to take in an 
assault on the objective and the trace of strongpoints in its 
defense, and also maskirovka conditions. 
  In estimating the NBC situation, the commander 
outlines measures ensuring successful subunit operations with 
use of mass destruction weapons. 
  The effect of weather, time of year and time of day on 
assault force operations also are taken into account in the 
course of estimating the situation. 
  The decision is made as a result of the mission analysis and 
situation estimate, and after the calculation is made for 
boarding (loading) helicopters, missions are assigned to 
subunits and then coordination is organized. Then the company 
commander (battalion staff) draws up the plan for loading 
weapons and vehicles and boarding personnel, and a list of 
weapons and supplies for each helicopter. In planning the 
landing, the time calculation is made from the established time 
(H)--beginning of the landing of the assault force advance party. 
  In his decision the company (battalion) commander 
usually specifies the following: commander's concept (on what to 
concentrate main efforts of the assault force; what enemy to 
capture or destroy where, in what sequence and how, with an 
indication of the procedure for fire engagement and measures for 
his deception); battle formation and landing procedure; what 
subunits board (load) helicopters at what sites, and at what 
landing sites they disembark (unload) in the landing area; 
combat missions for subunits; basic coordination questions; and 
organization of C[.sup]2[/]. 
  In assigning the mission for the landing to subunits the 
company (battalion) commander indicates the following in 
the operation order: 

  -  for first echelon subunits--means of 
reinforcement, combat mission, who is supporting, and numbers 
(quantity) of helicopters and landing sites; 
  -  for second echelon subunit--makeup, combat mission, 
who is attached and who is supporting, numbers of helicopters 
and landing sites; 
  -  for the reserve--makeup, concentration area, nature 
of possible missions after landing, numbers of helicopters and 
landing sites; 
  -  for the advance party--makeup, combat mission, who 
is supporting, numbers of helicopters, time of landing; 
  -  for artillery subunit and other weapons--missions 
for supporting battle of the assault force, numbers of 
helicopters and of landing sites; 
  -  for air defense 
subunit--procedure for conducting fire in repelling enemy 
air raids, numbers of helicopters and of landing sites. 


    If the landing area is a considerable distance from the line 
(objective) for capture (destruction), the commander may give 
subunits a route (direction) of forward movement and lines of 
deployment and departure at which they must arrive by the 
established time. 
  In organizing coordination, initially the 
procedure for forward movement of subunits to the marshaling 
area and their boarding of helicopters is worked out, then the 
landing procedure. Here special attention should be given to 
questions of joint operations of assault force subunits and 
aviation for fire engagement of the enemy during the airlift. 
Coordination is organized in greater detail for the assault 
force's performance of the immediate mission. 
  The assault landing is the airlift of the assault force into 
the enemy rear for performing the combat mission. It includes 
takeoff of the helicopter subunit (unit), the combat flight and 
landing of helicopters with subsequent disembarking of personnel 
and unloading of equipment at landing sites. 
  Before the assault landing, the company (battalion) moves 
into the marshaling area at the established time. It is disposed 
in it using natural cover and carefully camouflages itself. 
Commanders check subunit readiness for boarding (loading) of 
helicopters in accordance with the calculation. 
  With the helicopters' arrival at the landing sites the 
commander of the assault force and commander of the helicopter 
subunit (unit) update the calculation for the assault landing; 
procedure for loading weapons, military vehicles and supplies 
and boarding of helicopters by personnel; landing sites in 
primary and alternate landing areas; combat formation in flight; 
and procedure for coordination of motorized rifle and helicopter 
subunits in flight and when disembarking. All these questions 
also can be resolved with the helicopter subunit (unit) 
commander before the helicopters arrive in order to reduce the 
time they are at the landing site. 
  Preparation, loading and securing of weapons, vehicles and 
supplies are done by subunit personnel under the direction of 
helicopter crews. Personnel board helicopters immediately before 
takeoff and finish boarding before helicopter engines are 
started. 
  Fire and nuclear damage and EW suppression of enemy air 
defense and of his troops in the en route corridor and in and 
near the landing area are carried out before the beginning of 
the landing and in its course. 
  The assault landing begins at a signal of the commander 
employing the assault force, and responsibility for its 
disembarking at the prescribed time and in the designated area 
is borne by the helicopter subunit (unit) commander. 
  The combat flight to the landing area usually is made as one 
formation in trail. Helicopters with the advance party fly ahead 
of the main body at a 1020 minute interval. As a rule, 
helicopters with motorized rifle subunits fly at the head of the 
assault force main body, and helicopters with artillery subunits 
behind them. The company (battalion) commander is with the 
helicopter subunit (unit) commander in flight. 
  Escort gunships, and sometimes also escort transport-gunship 
helicopters are used to neutralize the enemy and his air defense 
weapons in the en route corridor. Proceeding in front of and on 
flanks of the formation in trail with the assault force, they 
conduct fire against the enemy from on-board weapons, and 
assault force subunits do so with small arms. On approaching a 
zone of contamination, small windows, hatches and doors in 
helicopters are closed, cabin heating and ventilation systems 
are turned off and the personnel put on breathing masks 
(protective masks). 
  When the advance party approaches the landing site, the 
enemy 
there is neutralized and destroyed by fire of helicopter weapons 
and the party's small arms, and motorized riflemen are landed. 
After this the helicopters support the party's battle by fire 
from the air and together with it support the landing of the 
assault force main body. 
  Air defense subunits of the advance party take up launch 
(firing) positions in readiness to combat the air enemy, and at 
this time combat engineers reconnoiter landing sites and remove 
or mark obstacles and local objects hindering the landing of 
helicopters. 
  The patrol squad (reconnaissance, combat reconnaissance 
patrol) conducts reconnaissance in the direction of company 
(battalion) operations and updates the enemy makeup and 
position. Chemical warfare personnel conduct radiological and 
chemical reconnaissance. 
  Based on data received from the advance party, from 
reconnaissance and from other sources, the company (battalion) 
commander may update the procedure for unloading (disembarking) 
if necessary with the main body's landing approach to the 
landing area. The main body disembarks under cover of air and 
combat helicopter strikes and the fire of artillery and the 
advance party. Artillery subunits take up firing positions and 
conduct fire against observed targets, then perform missions of 
support to the subunits. After disembarking the company 
(battalion) commander updates missions for subunits on the 
terrain or assigns new ones, issues coordination instructions 
and controls their battle. 
  The assault force must be disembarked in a short time; this 
is done directly on or near the objective or on approaches to it 
depending on the situation. 
  When disembarking on approaches, the assault force's forward 
movement to the objective to be captured (destroyed) must be 
covert and quick, usually in approach march formation under 
cover of security elements. With its arrival at the designated 
objective, the assault force deploys into battle formation from 
the move, decisively assaults the enemy flank and rear, destroys 
(disables) his installation and moves to a new objective or to 
an assembly point (area). 
  With the capture of an important line (area), the 
assault force shifts to a defense and holds it until the 
approach of friendly troops. It must be a perimeter defense and 
ensure repulse of an enemy attack delivered from several 
directions simultaneously. The dimensions of the company 
strongpoint (battalion defense area) are the very same as and 
sometimes even larger than for defense under ordinary conditions. 
  If a mission of delivering strikes against a forward 
moving reserve of the enemy is being executed, the assault 
force should move to its likely routes of forward movement, 
occupy a favorable line and from there deliver a surprise fire 
strike against the flank, making wide use of fire ambushes. This 
mission should be performed in coordination with combat 
helicopters and friendly subunits (units) attacking from the 
front or conducting a defense. 
  In performing the mission of destroying (disabling) 
ground elements of a reconnaissance-strike complex and means of 
nuclear and chemical attack, the assault force covertly 
moves forward to their disposition, destroys covering-force 
subunits by a determined assault from the move and puts the 
installations out of commission. 
  If it is to capture nuclear mines emplaced in 
wells, the assault force destroys the enemy near them, occupies 
a favorable line and supports actions of combat engineer 
subunits to disarm the nuclear mines. 
  With the capture of hydraulic engineering works, 
bridges, crossings, crossing equipment or sectors 
convenient for forcing, the assault force moves up to the 
designated objective after disembarking, captures it by an 
assault on the enemy on one or both banks and holds it until the 
approach of friendly units. 
  To capture a pass the assault force lands near it 
and takes the adjoining commanding heights. Then it moves to the 
enemy's flank and rear and seizes the pass after destroying him. 
To take a gap the assault force lands at its entrance, takes 
commanding heights, and seals off and destroys the enemy. 
  In performing combat missions, the assault force's actions 
must be daring, determined and distinguished by high mobility, 
activeness and boldness. The enemy must be destroyed before he 
manages to organize resistance, with weapons used skillfully in 
the process. 
<H5>  12. Battalion in Amphibious Assault Force </H5>
  An assault force[.sup]5[/], in which an MRB (TB) may 
operate as a forward detachment or as part of the assault force 
main body, is landed to capture an island or the opposite shore 
of a strait. The purpose of detachment operations is to support 
the landing of the assault force main body on the coast, and 
that of a battalion in the main body is to destroy the enemy and 
seize a beachhead. 
  The battalion may operate independently as an assault force 
when our troops attack along the coast. The capture and holding 
of important coastal objectives (sectors), assistance to units 
and formations in penetrating a defense, disruption of enemy 
lines of communication, and prohibition of the approach of his 
reserves and withdrawal of units along the coast are the goals 
in employing such an assault force. The Azov and Danube naval 
flotillas made 38 assault landings to fulfill these objectives 
in just the second and third period of the Great Patriotic War. 
  The assault force usually is sealifted at night or under 
other conditions of limited visibility. 
  During the Great Patriotic War all assault forces were 
sealifted and landed at night or at dawn. The landing of an 
assault force during the day as a rule was forced. 
  A battalion is assigned a waiting area [rayon ozhidaniya] 
and 
a primary and alternate embarkation (loading) point for boarding 
and a primary and alternate landing beach (offloading point) up 
to 2 km wide for landing. 
  A waiting area is designated for preparing subunits for 
operations. A battalion is disposed in this area by company with 
means of reinforcement, with measures taken for protection 
against mass destruction and precision weapons and with 
consideration for moving out to embark (load). Depending on the 
situation, an assault force may arrive at the embarkation 
(loading) point several minutes before assault transport 
vehicles depart without entering a waiting area. 
  A battalion is given a combat mission, which usually is 
divided into the immediate and subsequent mission. Thus, the 
immediate mission of a battalion operating in a forward 
detachment is to capture a landing beach and the subsequent 
mission is to hold it and support the main body's landing. When 
operating as part of the main body, the content of missions 
basically is the very same as when attacking a defending enemy. 
When a battalion operates independently in an assault force, the 
content of the immediate mission may be to destroy the enemy at 
the landing beach and take a coastal objective (line), and the 
subsequent mission may be to hold it until the approach of units 
attacking along the seacoast. 
  To ensure greater independence in performing the mission, a 
battalion is reinforced by subunits of other combat arms and 
special troops as when attacking a defending enemy. Increased 
reserves of supplies, especially ammunition, are established in 
subunits and it is desirable to reinforce the battalion aid 
station with medical personnel and means for giving medical aid 
to wounded and sick. 
  The amphibious task force, which includes assault transport 
vehicles, fire support ships and covering forces, is designated 
for landing the assault force. 
  After receiving the mission, the battalion commander 
analyzes 
it. In so doing he analyzes missions of the assault force and of 
his battalion and the senior commander's concept, especially 
targets (objectives) to be destroyed (engaged) by the senior 
commander's assets during the landing and battle in the 
beachhead, forces and assets assigned for the landing, the 
mission of an airborne assault force if it is landed, the 
procedure for coordinating with it, with aviation and with the 
amphibious task force, and readiness time for the landing. 
  In the course of the situation estimate the battalion 
commander determines and clarifies the following: nature of the 
antilanding defense, presence of obstacles in the water and on 
shore and methods of negotiating them; objectives to be 
destroyed (neutralized) in the period of fire preparation and 
support of the landing; combat capabilities of the assault force 
and of allocated assault transport vehicles and the possible 
distribution of subunits to them. The following are outlined and 
updated in addition: place and procedure for boarding (loading) 
the assault force; advisable method of operations in conducting 
battle at the landing beach; nature of terrain, battle formation 
and missions of subunits ashore; meteorological conditions 
during the sealift and at the landing beach (offloading point). 
  If the assault force is being landed in support of troops 
attacking along the coast, then missions of units moving to link 
up with the assault force and conditions of coordination with 
them also are analyzed. 
  A decision is made as a result of the combat mission 
analysis, the situation estimate and the calculations performed. 
In addition to the usual questions covered in organizing an 
attack, it spells out subunit missions for destroying the enemy 
at the landing beach (offloading point) and in the onshore area, 
distribution of organic subunits and means of reinforcement to 
the assault transport vehicles and the sequence of their 
boarding (loading) and disembarking (unloading). 
  In assigning missions to subunits the battalion commander 
usually indicates the following in the operation 
order: 

  -  for companies--means of reinforcement, missions 
for destroying the enemy at the landing beach and during 
subsequent operations, landing places, assault transport 
vehicles for the sealift, and boarding (loading) and 
disembarking (unloading) sequence; 
  -  for artillery subunits and other weapons--missions 
for supporting the battle ashore, places in assault transport 
vehicles, and boarding (loading) and disembarking (unloading) 
sequence; 
  -  for the air defense subunit--missions for covering 
the battalion against enemy air strikes during the sealift and 
after the landing, places in assault transport vehicles and 
boarding (loading) and disembarking (unloading) sequence. 


    Coordination is organized by the battalion 
commander from a map and on a terrain model. The procedure for 
moving out and boarding (loading) assault transport vehicles may 
be worked out directly on the terrain. 
  In organizing coordination the commander gives primary 
attention to coordinating subunit actions in negotiating 
antilanding obstacles, seizing the landing beach (offloading 
point), and in the battle ashore, and to coordinating their 
actions with ship gun fire, air strikes and operations of an 
airborne assault force if one is landed. 
  Preparing the battalion for the landing usually includes 
drilling its subunits for embarking (loading) and disembarking 
(unloading) and drilling obstacle clearing parties of the 
amphibious task force and assault force in breaching antilanding 
obstacles. Based on war experience, it is also necessary to 
drill subunits in fighting to capture a beach with consideration 
of the antilanding defense and nature of terrain at the landing 
beach and preparation of weapons, vehicles and supplies for 
loading and unloading as well as preparation of tanks, 
amphibious vehicles and assault transport vehicles for crossing 
a water obstacle under their own power. 
  The battalion usually moves out to the embarkation (loading) 
point from the waiting area in company columns with means of 
reinforcement. Rear subunits proceed in front, then reserve 
(second echelon) subunits, the staff, and first echelon 
subunits. The sequence of loading weapons and military vehicles 
on assault transport vehicles must be in reverse of the order of 
their unloading with consideration of fighting ashore. Personnel 
board after equipment and supplies have been loaded. 
  The battalion commander is resubordinated to the commander 
of 
the ship on which the battalion is being sealifted from the 
moment the order is received for boarding (loading) until the 
end of disembarking (unloading). 
  The battalion commander's COP during boarding (loading) is 
near the amphibious task force C[.sup]2[/] facility if it is 
located ashore. During the sealift, C[.sup]2[/] of the 
battalion is exercised through the commander of the amphibious 
task force. The battalion commander and chief of staff usually 
are on different ships with the commander and chief of staff of 
the amphibious task force. The battalion commander controls his 
own forces and assets on arriving ashore. An embarkation point 
commander is appointed for directing the boarding (loading) and 
for maintaining order. 
  During the sealift the battalion is covered from the air and 
from enemy strikes from the sea by covering (escort) and support 
ships. 
  During battalion operations in a forward detachment or as an 
independent assault force (when our troops are attacking along 
the coast), as the assault transport vehicles approach the 
landing beach (offloading point) the battalion commander updates 
for subunits the places and procedure for landing and missions 
ashore. Missions for neutralizing the antilanding defense also 
are updated for weapons. After making ready to land, assault 
force personnel release vehicles from fastenings and place 
weapons in readiness. 
  As a rule, a battalion lands as one echelon, and amphibious 
tanks and BMP's (BTR's) with motorized rifle subunits proceed in 
the first waves. Reforming of assault transport vehicles from 
cruising to battle formation ends when the first wave approaches 
the starting line. This line is designated at a distance from 
shore precluding conduct of fire against assault transport 
vehicles by enemy weapons moved up for direct fire. 
  Battalion subunits move up to the landing beach under cover 
of air strikes and the fire of ship guns and battalion weapons 
and taking advantage of passages breached in obstacles. 
Amphibious tanks and BMP's (BTR's) usually are launched before 
the landing ships approach the landing beach, and proceed to 
shore under their own power. Landing ships (fast assault landing 
craft) move behind the amphibious tanks and BMP's (BTR's) and 
land subunits on shore (or in the water when it is no more than 
one meter deep). Nonamphibious vehicles may be unloaded at 
places where the depth and bottom permit them to proceed under 
their own power. 
  An assault landing party consisting of up to a reinforced 
MRC 
may be assigned from the battalion. Taking advantage of air 
strikes and ship gun fire, it comes ashore, assaults the enemy 
at the landing beach and takes a line in supporting the 
battalion's landing, deployment and battle. 
  Under cover of air strikes and the fire of ship guns and its 
own weapons as well as of the assault landing party, the 
battalion main body proceeds in BMP's (BTR's) and assault 
landing craft and comes ashore. It deploys into battle formation 
from the move, launches an assault and seizes the landing beach 
to a depth supporting the landing of the assault force main 
body. Subsequently the battalion continues to fight to widen the 
beachhead in coordination with first echelon subunits of the 
assault force. 
  A battalion operating in support of troops attacking along 
the seacoast seizes a designated line (objective) and holds it 
until they approach, or it performs other missions. 
  If a battalion lands as part of the assault force main body, 
it comes ashore, exploiting success of the forward detachment. 
Under conditions where the sealift is accomplished in 
transportation assets, the battalion usually is transferred to 
landing craft with the approach to shore. After unloading, 
battalion subunits deploy into battle formation from the move 
and develop the attack into the depth in coordination with first 
echelon subunits of the assault force. A battalion attacking in 
the direction of operations of an airborne assault force 
continues performing the mission in coordination with it after 
linkup. 
  When a terrain sector ashore has been taken, some landing 
support forces may be used for fire support of the assault and 
fire accompaniment of the battalion attack in the depth, for 
covering it against enemy strikes from the sea, for evacuating 
wounded and for delivering supplies. 
<H5>  13. Attack in a City </H5>
  Conditions of an attack in the city basically are 
characterized by the density of construction of various sizes 
and types of buildings, presence of parks and squares, layout 
and width of streets, and the underground utility network. 
Cities usually are built up with large brick, stone and concrete 
buildings. Destructive damage and centers of fire will arise in 
a city as a result of use of aircraft, artillery and other 
weapons. Under these conditions the attack of a company 
(battalion) as a rule breaks down into isolated battles of 
platoons and squads for individual houses and other structures. 
C[.sup]2[/] of subunits is complicated and the field of view 
and fire and the maneuver of forces and assets is restricted. 
The battle of subunits is characterized by ferocity which often 
develops into hand-to-hand fighting. 
  A successful attack is achieved only with close coordination 
of motorized rifle (tank) platoons (companies) maintained with 
subunits of other combat arms and special troops. For this, tank 
subunits and the bulk of artillery subunits are attached to 
motorized rifle squads, platoons and companies. 
  Helicopters and flame weapons will find wide use in street 
fighting. Direct fire, including of large caliber guns, is the 
most effective fire. Mortars can destroy the enemy successfully 
in courtyards, behind various cover, and within blocks, and 
artillery can engage his artillery and reserves from indirect 
positions. A company (battalion) attack in the city is 
characterized by a successive fight to take individual 
strongpoints, buildings and blocks. 
  The company (battalion) attack frontage will be less than 
under ordinary conditions, since a battle in the city is 
conducted along streets and in buildings, and in the latter case 
on all floors and in basements successively or simultaneously. 
It is advisable for a company to advance along one street with 
the adjoining houses or within a block, and for a battalion to 
advance along one or two parallel streets with adjoining blocks; 
frontage may reach 1,000 m in this case. A combat mission is 
assigned to the company (battalion) based on objectives and 
blocks, and to a lesser depth than on open terrain. 
  As shown by war experience, cities usually were captured 
from 
the move in the course of developing an attack, but when a city 
failed to be taken from the move, an assault on it was organized. 
  In attacking a city from the move the content of the 
company's immediate mission and of the battalion's immediate and 
subsequent missions may be the very same as under ordinary 
conditions. But as a result of the execution of missions the 
battalion must take important objectives on approaches to the 
city and within the city itself. In an assault on a city the 
company's immediate mission is to take a building (or part of a 
large building or several small buildings) in the enemy 
strongpoint. The battalion immediate mission may consist of 
capturing a strongpoint or one and sometimes two or three 
blocks. The content of its subsequent mission is to take 
important objectives (blocks) in the depth of the enemy defense. 
  Assault teams and detachments are formed to capture large 
city structures prepared for defense. An MRC usually is the 
basis of a team and a battalion the basis of an assault 
detachment. There may be 2-3 assault teams and a reserve in a 
detachment. 
  Teams and detachments include artillery, tanks, mortars, 
ATGM's, flamethrowers and grenade launchers and they also are 
supplied with demolition charges, with incendiary, smoke and 
signaling devices, and with devices for assaulting buildings and 
negotiating obstacles. 
  For example, in the assault on the city of Gdynia (March 
1945), assault detachments were formed with a strength of up to 
an MRB reinforced by a tank company, SP artillery battery, 76-mm 
gun battalion, 155-mm howitzer battery, M-13 rocket artillery 
platoon and from a platoon to a company of combat 
engineers.[.sup]6[/] 
  In organizing the attack, the company (battalion) commander 
estimates the nature of the defense and enemy system of fire on 
approaches to and within the city and studies the direction and 
width of streets and disposition of structures whose capture 
will disrupt stability of the defense. As a result of this the 
commander specifies methods for fire engagement of the enemy and 
capture of objectives and the number, makeup, combat missions 
and battle formation of assault teams. 
  In organizing coordination the company (battalion) commander 
works out the procedure of the assault on the enemy and the 
assault on buildings and determines the place of tanks, guns, 
ATGM's and other weapons in the battle formation of subunits and 
the procedure for coordination among them and for communications 
and recognition. All commanders usually are supplied with large- 
scale maps or aerial photos (street maps). 
  In capturing a city from the move, artillery and aircraft 
inflict fire damage on the enemy in strongpoints on city 
approaches and outskirts. When subunits arrive at the outskirts, 
artillery transfers fire against buildings and shelters in enemy 
strongpoints and neutralizes artillery and reserves. Subunits 
burst into the city from the move, exploiting results of fire 
damage and weakly defended places and gaps in the defense. The 
attack is conducted along streets and through courtyards, and 
subunits take buildings and blocks. Buildings or parts of 
buildings which have not been captured are sealed off, blinding 
smoke screens are laid down and flanks and rear are covered. 
  Some platoons may advance through courtyards and gardens and 
along both sides of the street in an envelopment of buildings, 
while one platoon with tanks, ATGM's, artillery and BMP's 
(BTR's) advances along the street. Advancing along sidewalks, 
tanks and BMP's (BTR's) fire on the enemy in buildings on the 
opposite side of the street. Motorized riflemen advancing to the 
right and left of the tanks and BMP's (BTR's) fire against lower 
floors, and motorized riflemen advancing directly behind the 
fighting vehicles fire against upper floors of buildings. 
  Actions of an assault team (detachment) may be as follows: 
in 
the period of fire preparation of the assault its tanks, guns 
and flamethrowers destroy the enemy in the building being 
assaulted and in adjacent buildings. Taking advantage of 
breaches in walls, underground utilities, communication tunnels, 
pedestrian subways and other concealed approaches, motorized 
riflemen move up to the objective and burst into the building 
under cover of fire from all weapons. Stairwells, entrances, 
exits, and passages within the building should be taken first of 
all, which will permit splitting the enemy and destroying him in 
detail. 
  Operations in a building must be bold, daring and 
determined; 
the enemy must be destroyed with grenades and point-blank fire 
and floors cleared simultaneously or successively. Combat 
engineer subunits clear mines, breach obstacles and if necessary 
demolish structures. 
  The actions of Stalingrad's fighters teach us: "Burst into a 
building together--you and a grenade; both be dressed light--you 
without a combat field pack and the grenade without a jacket; 
burst in with the grenade in front and you behind; go through 
the entire building, again with a grenade--grenade in front and 
you right after."[.sup]7[/] 
  A company (battalion) commander should keep a watchful eye 
on 
the situation and development of battle and be ready to support 
platoons (companies) by fire. Radio and signaling devices are 
the basic means of communication. 
<H5>  14. Attack Under Special Conditions </H5>
  Attack in the mountains. The following exert 
considerable influence on conduct of an attack by a company 
(battalion) in the mountains: ruggedness of relief and abundance 
of dead ground and concealed approaches, which hamper 
orientation, observation and use of weapons; predominance of 
rocky soils and possible landslides and roadblocks; difficulty 
of using engineer vehicles, including mineclearing devices; poor 
road network and difficulty of off-road movement; shielding 
effect of mountains on operation of radios, radars and sound 
ranging equipment; and abrupt weather changes in the course of a 
24 hour period. When tanks and BMP's (BTR's) are on upgrades, 
downgrades and slopes, their capabilities of conducting fire are 
reduced considerably, especially against targets located higher. 
  Fuel consumption and wear and tear on vehicles increase in 
the mountains and vehicle power drops at high altitudes. Rivers 
exert a substantial influence with their narrow valleys, steep, 
precipitous banks and rocky beds, which hampers crossing them. 
  Based on that nature of terrain, an attack in the mountains 
usually is conducted along hillslopes, roads, valleys, ridges 
and other possible axes, with wide use of close and deep 
envelopments for concealed movement to enemy flanks and rear in 
order to capture commanding heights, passes and other important 
objectives. Taking these objectives creates favorable conditions 
for developing the attack. The features of mountainous terrain 
also facilitate infiltration of small subunits into the enemy 
rear in places where he least expects them. Deep envelopment, 
infiltration and movement to the enemy rear even by small forces 
produce a significant result. 
  A company (battalion) may attack as part of the main body, 
it 
may attack independently in isolation from it on a separate 
axis, or it may operate in an enveloping detachment. 
  When attacking as part of the main body, a company is given 
an immediate mission and the battalion is given an immediate and 
subsequent mission. In addition, they are assigned a direction 
for continuing the attack. The content of missions is affected 
above all by the nature of the enemy defense and of the terrain 
objective he occupies. On armor terrain, the content of company 
(battalion) missions basically is the very same as when 
attacking a defending enemy under ordinary conditions. When 
attacking on rugged terrain against a defense with engineer 
development, the content of the battalion's immediate mission 
may be to destroy the enemy in platoon strongpoints and the 
subsequent mission to destroy him in coordination with adjacent 
subunits in a company strongpoint and take the strongpoint. In 
addition to destroying the enemy, the content of missions 
usually also includes taking a particular objective (hill, pass, 
gorge and so on). 
  When a company (battalion) attacks on an independent axis, 
it 
usually is given an immediate mission and direction for 
continuing the attack. The content of the mission is to defeat 
the enemy in a platoon (company) strongpoint covering this axis. 
The direction for continuing the attack must ensure the 
company's (battalion's) move to enemy flanks and rear to deliver 
a strike against him in coordination with the main body 
attacking from the front. 
  If a company (battalion) has been assigned to an enveloping 
detachment, it is assigned the mission of capturing a tactically 
important line (objective), the taking of which creates 
favorable conditions for the main body's successful attack. 
Sometimes the detachment will perform its mission in 
coordination with a tactical airborne assault force (air assault 
subunits). 
  The attack frontage of subunits may change considerably 
depending on the nature of terrain. In connection with this, the 
battle formation is formed deeper in operations along narrow 
valleys: as a rule, the company in two echelons and the 
battalion sometimes even in three echelons. 
  A company (battalion) attacking on an individual axis or in 
an enveloping detachment usually is reinforced by artillery, AT 
weapons, and combat engineer and other subunits and supported by 
the main body's artillery and by helicopter strikes. Subunits 
are supplied with mountain gear for operations in high mountain 
areas. 
  In organizing an attack in the mountains, the company 
(battalion) commander additionally studies the system of fire in 
all tiers and terrain accessibility and determines favorable 
directions for operations of combat arms subunits and for making 
deep and close envelopments. He also outlines measures for 
covering flanks and rear and for orientation, and also possible 
enemy ambush sites. 
  The following are specified in the decision in addition to 
the usual questions: procedure for capturing passes, tunnels, 
gorges and other important objectives; missions of subunits 
making a deep (close) envelopment and the procedure for their 
coordination with subunits attacking from the front or with a 
tactical airborne assault force; and measures for covering 
flanks and destroying enemy ambushes. Measures for orientation, 
maintaining direction, marking the position of attacking 
subunits and protecting against landslides, avalanches and 
mudflows, and the procedure for providing subunits with 
necessary mountain gear also are outlined. 
  In organizing coordination the company (battalion) commander 
pays special attention to coordinating the operations of 
subunits making a deep (close) envelopment with those attacking 
from the front. Operations of artillery and assaulting subunits 
are coordinated for taking important objectives in the course of 
the attack. 
  As a rule, an attack is made from a position of direct 
contact with the enemy. Artillery destroys and neutralizes the 
enemy in all tiers in the periods of fire preparation and fire 
support of the assault. The enemy is engaged in the lower tier 
basically by direct fire of artillery, tanks and ATGM's; in the 
second tier by artillery and mortar fire; and in subsequent 
tiers by helicopter strikes. Strongpoints adjoining axes of 
attack by subunits are neutralized with greatest fire density. 
Mortars, howitzer artillery and helicopters are used to engage 
the enemy on reverse slopes. 
  Motorized rifle subunits assault in dismounted formation on 
rugged terrain. Tanks may operate in or behind the extended line 
of motorized riflemen, with BMP's (BTR's) behind the tanks, and 
by their fire destroy the enemy hampering the advance of 
attacking subunits. Air defense subunits displace behind the 
attackers in readiness to repel enemy helicopter strikes, 
especially from low altitudes. On encountering obstacles, 
motorized riflemen negotiate them together with combat engineer 
subunits under cover of artillery and tank fire, supporting the 
tanks' advance. 
  In attacking along a narrow mountain valley, it is necessary 
above all to take adjoining hills, which will ensure that the 
valley is covered by fire. Successful destruction of the enemy 
is achieved by coordinated operations of combat arms subunits 
attacking along the hills and along the valley. In assaulting 
the enemy defending a hill with a tiered system of fire, when 
subunits approach the hill artillery transfers fire against 
enemy weapons in upper tiers and on the flanks. It is advisable 
to assault the enemy from different directions, i.e., from the 
front, the flanks and the rear. 
  A company (battalion) attacking from the front may take a 
mountain pass or gorge either independently or in coordination 
with an enveloping detachment, tactical airborne assault force 
and combat helicopters. Initially the hills and slopes facing 
the pass and gorge are captured. Subsequently the enemy in the 
pass or gorge is pinned down by some of the forces from the 
captured line and destroyed by a strike of the main body against 
the flank and rear. Pass approaches, gorge entrances and exits 
and other important objectives are carefully guarded. 
  Canyons usually are negotiated by subunits from the move 
along captured passages. If the passage fails to be taken from 
the move, dismounted motorized riflemen seize it by an assault 
against the flank and rear supported by artillery and tank fire 
after a deep envelopment of the enemy. When an enemy defending a 
passage has failed to be enveloped, capture of the passage is 
organized by an assault from the front in close interworking of 
subunits of all combat arms and special troops. 
  A company (battalion) assigned to an enveloping detachment 
as 
a rule attacks in dismounted formation. Taking advantage of 
concealed approaches and gaps in the defense, the detachment 
decisively penetrates into its depth and seizes hills adjoining 
the objective (pass, mountain gap, and so on). Subsequently it 
takes the objective by assaulting the enemy in the flank and 
rear independently, in coordination with subunits attacking from 
the front, or in coordination with a tactical airborne assault 
force. 
  In an attack in the mountains the company (battalion) 
commander pays special attention to reconnoitering the enemy and 
securing the flanks. Reconnaissance is conducted by a larger 
number of observation posts, observers, patrol squads and 
reconnaissance (combat reconnaissance) patrols than under 
ordinary conditions. Exposed flanks of the company (battalion) 
are secured by forming an echelon battle formation of platoons 
(companies), by conducting reconnaissance and observation, and 
by readiness of the second echelon (reserve) for a maneuver 
toward the flanks. 
  The company (battalion) COP and technical support and rear 
subunits come up closer to first echelon subunits. 
  An attack in the forest is one of the most 
difficult. The following affect conduct of the attack: terrain 
affording concealment with the presence of marshy sectors; 
limited number of roads; possibility of the enemy creating 
abatis in combination with mines, of the outbreak of fires and 
of the lengthy persistence of chemical agents. All this hampers 
observation, target designation, maneuver of combat vehicles, 
fire adjustment, coordination among subunits and their 
C[.sup]2[/]. 
  The limited nature of sectors of fire and difficulty of 
subunit operations on a continuous front increase the importance 
of independent squad, platoon and company operations. In a 
forest battle the role of commanders' initiative at all levels, 
surprise, and decisive actions of subunits and even of 
individual motorized riflemen grows, since the battle is fought 
basically at close ranges. 
  To achieve close coordination among combat arms subunits it 
is advisable to attach a TC and mortar (artillery) battery by 
platoon and a grenade launcher and AT subunits by squad to MRC's 
(MRP's). This also ensures their conduct of independent combat 
operations. Smoke assets are successfully employed in the forest. 
  An attack in the forest is conducted along axes, primarily 
along roads and openings, in combination with close and deep 
envelopments. A move even of small subunits to the flank and 
rear may disorganize the enemy defense. 
  A company (battalion) may attack as part of the main body or 
independently in an enveloping detachment. It is assigned a 
combat mission to a lesser depth and the mission content usually 
includes taking objectives (openings, forest crossroads, 
drainage canals, defiles and so on). The position of subunits in 
the battle formation changes more often in the course of an 
attack than under ordinary conditions. This is [caused] by the 
need to secure exposed flanks and the rear. 
  In organizing an attack, in addition to the usual questions 
the company (battalion) commander determines the following: 
azimuth of attack for subunits and measures for orientation and 
mutual recognition; procedure for negotiating abatis, other 
obstacles and sectors difficult to negotiate; procedure for 
putting out fires and directions for bypassing them; procedure 
for destroying the enemy left in the rear and for conducting 
fire from trees. The second echelon (reserve) may be used to 
destroy the enemy left in the rear, and snipers and assault 
riflemen should be assigned in platoons to destroy the enemy 
firing from trees. 
  As a rule the commander makes the decision and assigns 
missions from a map. In organizing coordination the company 
(battalion) commander coordinates in detail the actions of 
subunits attacking from the front and making a close (deep) 
envelopment to capture road junctions, openings, defiles between 
lakes and other important objectives. Attention also is given to 
rehearsing questions of ensuring reliable orientation, 
maintaining the direction of attack, target designation, and 
marking of the lines reached. 
  When the enemy FEBA runs along the treeline, the company 
(battalion) begins the assault by capturing forest salients. 
Subsequently a strike is delivered against the flank and rear to 
destroy the enemy in strongpoints and advance swiftly into the 
depth. 
  In the depth of the forest the enemy is assaulted on a 
narrower front and from closer range after his fire damage. 
Felled areas and glades are bypassed, since the enemy usually 
arranges fire ambushes in them. Necessary forces and assets are 
assigned for making a deep (close) envelopment and an assault 
against the flank and rear of enemy strongpoints. Motorized 
rifle subunits usually assault the enemy in dismounted 
formation, and tanks proceed in or immediately behind the 
riflemen's extended line. BMP's (BTR's) operate behind the tanks 
and support the advance of attacking subunits by their fire. 
Under cover of weapons, combat engineer subunits breach abatis 
and other obstacles and support their negotiation by motorized 
riflemen and tanks. Sometimes tanks and BMP's (BTR's) are used 
to reduce an abatis. Motor vehicles of motorized rifle subunits 
displace behind the battalion second echelon in a battalion 
column. 
  Enemy strongpoints covering crossroads, glades and other 
objectives are captured by an assault against the flank and rear 
in coordination with subunits attacking from the front. 
  During a battle in the depth of the forest one should not 
allow vehicles and subunits to concentrate on roads, in glades 
and in open terrain sectors, since these objectives usually are 
registered by artillery and may be engaged by enemy aircraft. In 
conducting an attack in the forest subunits constantly must be 
ready to conduct fire, they must advance swiftly, conduct 
observation continuously, employ grenades skillfully, beef up 
security from flanks and rear, send out foot patrols and conduct 
reconnaissance. 
  It is advisable for the second echelon (reserve) to displace 
in approach march formation and be closer to the assaulting 
subunits. COP's are brought closer to first echelon subunits; 
technical support and rear subunits are brought closer to battle 
formations of the companies and as a rule are disposed near 
roads and openings. 
  On emerging from the forest, subunits draw up to its edge 
and 
assume battle formation as under ordinary conditions. Guns and 
platoons operating separately join their batteries, 
C[.sup]2[/] of artillery and tanks may be centralized, and 
thorough reconnaissance is conducted. 
  In an attack in the desert (Diagram 17) it is 
necessary to take the effect of its diverse natural conditions 
into account. Open relief, an almost total absence of built-up 
areas and of clear-cut reference points, and poor road networks 
hamper orientation, target designation and maskirovka. The 
presence of rocky terrain sectors difficult of access and with 
inland sand dunes, moist solonchaks, the shortage or total 
absence of water, and the extremely sparse vegetation noticeably 
reduce the cross-country capability of vehicles and maneuver of 
subunits on a number of axes and complicate the supply of water 
and fuel. Sharp temperature fluctuations during a 24 hour period 
have a negative effect on personnel, and sand, sandstorms and 
sandy dust hamper observation and conduct of fire to long ranges 
and degrade C[.sup]2[/] of subunits. Sandy dust also has a 
negative effect on operation of weapons, engines and vehicle 
running gear. Mirages appear after sunrise on sultry days, 
distorting the appearance and nature of reference points, 
hampering a determination of distance and leading to a sharp 
deterioration in orientation. Certain desert areas may be 
unfavorable from a sanitation-epidemic standpoint. This will 
require taking preventive measures against possible sickness of 
personnel. 
  In the desert an attack usually is launched from the move 
and 
conducted across a broad front, off the roads, and along 
scattered axes basically to capture and hold vital areas, oases 
and water sources. The absence of a continuous front in the 
enemy defense and the possibility of accomplishing a wide 
maneuver create favorable conditions for delivering strikes 
against his flank and rear. It is advisable to concentrate basic 
company (battalion) efforts on an axis leading to important 
areas and objectives. The effect of high temperature is reduced, 
maskirovka is ensured and surprise of operations is achieved 
when night falls. The night also can be used for executing a 
maneuver with subsequent delivery of a strike against the enemy 
at dawn. 
  A company (battalion) performs missions as part of the main 
body, independently, or operating in an enveloping detachment; 
and the battalion in addition does so on a separate axis or in a 
raiding detachment. The company (battalion) attack frontage and 
combat missions during operations as part of the main body are 
the very same as under ordinary conditions. If a battalion is to 
operate on an independent axis, then its attack frontage as a 
rule will be wider and the combat mission is assigned to a 
greater depth than when it is employed as part of the main body. 
  Enveloping (raiding) detachment missions are to destroy 
means 
of nuclear and chemical attack, ground elements of 
reconnaissance- strike complexes, and C[.sup]2[/] facilities; 
to disorganize the enemy rear, capture oases, road junctions, 
water sources and other important objectives; and to assist 
subunits attacking from the front in encircling and destroying 
the enemy. 
  As under ordinary conditions, the company (battalion) is 
reinforced by subunits of other combat arms and special troops 
to increase independence in performing missions. The battle 
formation also is formed with consideration for covering exposed 
flanks. This is achieved by conducting intensified 
reconnaissance, by forming the battle formation in an echelon 
right or left or assigning weapons to cover the flanks, and by 
displacing the second echelon (reserve) behind the exposed flank. 
  In organizing an attack, in addition to usual questions the 
company (battalion) commander specifies the following: azimuth 
of the direction of attack; routes for subunits to move to the 
line of departure and procedure for marking them; measures for 
maskirovka, security of flanks and rear, preparation of weapons 
and military vehicles for use during sandstorms, protection of 
personnel with abrupt changes in meteorological conditions, and 
prevention of heat strokes; procedure for supplying subunits 
with water and fuel; and measures for increasing off-road 
capability of wheeled vehicles as well as for maintaining a 
sanitary and hygienic condition at personnel locations and at 
water supply points. In organizing coordination, special 
attention should be given to coordinating actions of subunits 
for capturing key positions, oases and other important 
objectives, also including on the flanks, and to the procedure 
for securing flanks. 
  A company (battalion) launches an assault after fire 
preparation of the assault, during which strongpoints, 
individual centers of defense and C[.sup]2[/] facilities 
basically are neutralized. Guns and tanks assigned for direct 
fire as well as ATGM launchers and AT grenade launchers are 
widely used for destroying and neutralizing enemy weapons during 
fire preparation of the assault. 
  The basic methods of subunit operations in fighting in the 
depth of the enemy defense are to make a deep and close 
envelopment, deliver strikes against him from the flank and rear 
and with a portion of the forces from the front, break up the 
enemy and destroy him in detail, and make a determined advance 
into the depth to capture important objectives. 
  The aid station is brought closer to first echelon subunits, 
and other logistic support points are brought closer to the 
battalion battle formation, especially when it operates on a 
separate axis. 
  Attack in northern areas and in winter. In 
organizing and conducting an attack in northern areas, one must 
take into account the effect of abundant boulders and talus and 
of vast areas of tundra terrain, marshy forest-tundra, wooded 
terrain, and on some axes also mountainous terrain with a large 
number of lakes. Northern areas also are characterized by an 
extremely limited network of roads and axes accessible for 
subunit operations, a severe climate with lengthy winter and 
presence of a deep snow cover, the arctic night and day, adverse 
meteorological conditions, ionospheric and geomagnetic 
perturbations disrupting normal operation of radio equipment and 
compasses (errors may be up to 15, difficulty of using 
engineer vehicles and mineclearing devices, and difficulty of 
orientation and maskirovka. 
  Good conditions are created for use of tanks and BMP's 
(BTR's) with the onset of winter as a result of the bitter cold, 
which firmly binds lakes, marshes, rivers and bays. It should be 
borne in mind, however, that some lakes and marshes do not 
freeze but are merely covered with unconsolidated ice and a 
layer of snow. 
  Blizzards, fog and night help execute a covert maneuver and 
close with the enemy, but with greater expenditure of time than 
in the summer. In some places the snow cover may reach more than 
50 cm, which limits and sometimes even precludes the movement of 
subunits in the absence of a hard snow crust. Frequent blizzards 
drift up the roads and various obstacles and structures, which 
forces organization of snow-clearing in some sectors and removal 
of drifts and hummocks. At the same time, formation of a hard 
crust (upper layer) of snow in spring permits making wide 
off-road use of military vehicles. The snow cover changes the 
external appearance of terrain, hampers orientation, and hides 
lakes, ravines and marshes. 
  Low air temperature forces the issue of special thermal 
clothing to personnel, which to a certain extent constrains 
their actions, especially those of tank crews. In addition, time 
periods for preparing vehicles for operations are increased and 
their maintenance becomes more complicated. Steps must be taken 
against frostbite of personnel. They are equipped with white 
camouflage robes and helmets, and combat vehicles and other 
weapons are painted white. 
  As a rule an attack is launched from a position of direct 
contact with the enemy, and also from the march on terrain 
accessible for forward movement and deployment of subunits. The 
attack is conducted basically along a road, a river or other 
accessible axes. 
  A company (battalion) performs missions while operating as 
part of the main body or independently, and also as an 
enveloping detachment. 
  The company (battalion) attack frontage may change in the 
course of battle, and the battalion sometimes is forced to 
operate as companies with considerable gaps between them. In 
aligning the battle formation one should take into account the 
difficulty of changing it in the course of battle and the need 
for securing exposed flanks. This requires conducting 
reconnaissance on flanks and it requires security, especially in 
the fog and the arctic night. 
  As a rule, the content of subunit combat missions is the 
very 
same, but rates of advance on some axes will be lower than under 
ordinary conditions. 
  In an attack along roads or individual axes on terrain 
difficult of access, an MRC may be reinforced by a TP, mortar 
(artillery) platoon, grenade launcher subunit and combat 
engineer subunit and may be supported by fire of an artillery 
battery. The battalion is reinforced and supported by subunits 
of other combat arms and services, as under ordinary conditions. 
  A company (battalion) assigned to an enveloping detachment 
is 
given an objective in the depth of the enemy defense which it 
must take independently or in coordination with a tactical 
airborne assault force. Such objectives may be road junctions, 
bridges and so on. The detachment also is assigned a mission of 
destroying means of nuclear and chemical attack and 
C[.sup]2[/] facilities, disrupting work of the rear, and 
assisting subunits attacking from the front. 
  In preparing for an attack, in addition to the usual matters 
the company (battalion) commander specifies the presence of 
flanks and unoccupied gaps in the enemy defense, axes favorable 
for subunit operations, the azimuth of the direction of attack 
and the procedure for orientation and for crossing sectors 
difficult of access. He organizes warming posts and takes steps 
to prevent hypothermia and frostbite of personnel and also for 
preparing weapons, vehicles and individual protective gear for 
use under low temperature conditions. Measures are taken for 
painting vehicles to resemble the terrain background, to supply 
subunits with camouflage robes, to improve off-road capability 
of vehicles, especially wheeled vehicles, and to establish 
additional reserves of fuel, food and means of illumination. 
Measures also are envisaged for receiving supplies from 
helicopters and aircraft. In addition, the company (battalion) 
commander carries out advance preparation of the attack position 
(assembly area) under conditions of an attack launched from a 
position of direct contact with the enemy. Special attention is 
given to making emplacements out of snow and shelters for 
warming the personnel. 
  An assault of motorized rifle subunits when there is a deep 
snow cover and under other difficult conditions usually is made 
in dismounted formation, including on skis. Tanks attack in or 
behind the extended line of motorized riflemen. BMP's (BTR's) 
operate behind tanks and by their fire destroy the enemy 
hindering the advance of tanks and motorized rifle subunits. 
When attacking over a snow crust or expanse of ice, the assault 
of motorized rifle subunits may be conducted in BMP's (BTR's). 
  Taking advantage of gaps and exposed flanks in enemy battle 
formations, the enveloping detachment covertly penetrates his 
defense with the beginning of or before the attack of the main 
body, and by attacking from the rear and flanks helps subunits 
attacking from the front to destroy the enemy, or it performs 
other missions. 
  During battle in the depth, main efforts of attacking 
subunits are concentrated on destroying the enemy defending 
defiles, built-up areas, commanding heights and other objectives 
covering roads and axes accessible for attack. To capture these 
objectives, wide use should be made of deep and close 
envelopments with a move into the enemy rear, and an assault 
should be made from different directions supported by fire of 
artillery and other weapons from the front. 
  More attention is given to consolidating captured lines and 
organizing the warming of personnel with the beginning of a 
snowstorm and in snow flurries. Personnel are notified 
immediately about possible snow flurries and a snowstorm. 
  The wounded and sick must be swiftly located and carried 
(transported) from the battlefield in the course of an attack, 
especially in winter. Vehicles with good off-road capability and 
helicopters as well as deer teams, dog teams, ski mountings and 
sledges are used for their evacuation. 
Footnotes 
  1. See A. I. Radziyevskiy, "Tankovyy udar" [Tank Attack], 
Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1977, p 158. 
  2. See Radziyevskiy, p 161. 
  3. Here and further in the section, assault force is 
understood to mean a tactical airborne assault force. 
  4. See G. T. Zavizion and P. A. Kornyugin, "I na Tikhom 
okeane..." [And in the Pacific...], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1967, p 
230. 
  5. Here and further in the section, assault force is 
understood to mean amphibious assault force. 
  6. See M. Ye. Katukov, "Na ostriye glavnogo udara" [At the 
Point of the Main Attack], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1976, p 336. 
  7. See V. I. Chuykov, "Nachalo puti" [Beginning of the 
Path], 
Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1959, p 332. 
<H5>  Chapter VI - The Meeting Battle </H5>
<H5>  1. Principles of the Meeting Battle </H5>
  The meeting battle is a variety of offensive battle. It is 
an 
attack on an enemy who also is attempting to accomplish his 
missions by an attack. 
  The goal of a meeting battle is to rout the attacking enemy 
in a short time, seize the initiative and create favorable 
conditions for further operations. It may arise during a march 
in an encounter with an enemy who is moving up; in an attack on 
a defending enemy while repelling counterattacks or in a clash 
with his subunits moving up to close breaches; in the defense 
when conducting counterattacks, and in a number of other cases. 
  A meeting battle usually begins with engagement by march 
security and with delivery of preemptive fire strikes against an 
enemy who is moving up (attacking), and it ends as soon as one 
side gives up the attack and begins shifting to a defense or 
withdrawing. 
  A meeting battle is characterized by the sides' rapid 
closing 
and their engagement from the move; by an intensive struggle to 
gain time, seize and hold the initiative and create fire 
superiority over the enemy; by an abrupt, frequent change in the 
situation; by conduct of operations on a broad front and to a 
great depth and by their fast-moving nature; and by the presence 
of significant gaps between subunits and of exposed flanks 
allowing freedom of maneuver for moving to the enemy flank and 
rear. 
  The sides' rapid closing, the complicated and constantly 
changing situation, and the highly dynamic nature of operations 
demand that the company (battalion) commander organize for 
battle in a short time and promptly update the decision and 
combat missions for subunits. 
  The struggle to win time and seize and hold the initiative 
will begin back on the approach to the line of the sides' 
probable encounter with the delivery of fire strikes and with 
operations of other forces and assets to hold up the enemy's 
forward movement and inflict considerable losses on him. With 
initiation of a meeting battle by security elements, first 
echelon subunits will unfold an intensive struggle for 
preemption in seizing a favorable line, in moving to a line of 
departure and in delivering swift assaults against the flank and 
rear of the enemy main body in order to split and swiftly 
destroy him in detail. 
  A maneuver of forces and assets executed for delivering 
strikes against the flank leads to abrupt situation changes and 
an expansion in the frontage of battle. The frontage of subunit 
operations also increases because the subunit immobilizing the 
enemy is deployed on a wider line and there are gaps between it 
and the subunit operating as part of the company (battalion) 
main body. 
  The following are conditions for achieving success in a 
meeting battle: continuous reconnaissance on a broad front and 
to a great depth for prompt collection of reliable data on the 
advancing enemy; prompt decisionmaking and rapid communication 
of missions to subordinates; advance establishment of the 
necessary grouping of forces and assets based on the concept of 
upcoming battle; preempting the enemy in commencing artillery 
fire; rapid execution of a maneuver to seize a favorable line 
and for forces and assets to move onto the axis of concentration 
of main efforts; preempting the enemy in deploying the main body 
and delivering a strong surprise attack against the flank and 
rear, breaking up his grouping and destroying it in detail; wide 
use of engineer obstacles on the enemy main body axis of 
operations; constant securing of flanks and rear; seizing the 
initiative and holding it throughout the battle, and determined, 
bold actions by subunits; reliable air defense and 
accomplishment of measures for comprehensive support of battle; 
firm, continuous C[.sup]2[/] and maintenance of close 
coordination among subunits in battle. 
  An important feature of the meeting battle is that it 
usually 
is conducted with relative equality of the sides' forces and 
assets. In fact, if forces of one side considerably surpass 
forces of the other, the commander of the latter, having 
intelligence on this, most likely will prefer to repel the enemy 
attack by defensive operations and not by a surprise 
counterstrike. 
  At the same time, preemption in commencing fire, deploying 
and launching an assault permits achieving victory over a 
stronger enemy. 
  A company (battalion) may conduct a meeting battle 
independently, operating in isolation from the battalion 
(regimental) main body (as a rule, in a forward security 
element, forward detachment, or advance guard), or as part of 
the main body. 
  Based on missions assigned to it in the course of the march 
and in the attack, a forward detachment conducts a meeting 
battle before seizure of a designated line only if it is 
impossible or inadvisable to go around the enemy. 
  The combat mission of the subunit in a meeting 
battle and its content and indicators (depth, frontage) depend 
on the place of the company (battalion) in the battalion 
(regimental) battle formation. 
  In a meeting battle a company (battalion) is assigned an 
immediate mission and is given a direction for continuing the 
attack (Diagram 18). 
  Assignment only of an immediate mission is a result of 
abrupt, frequent situation changes. In addition, by the time the 
battalion is given a combat mission for a meeting battle, there 
usually not only is no clear-cut enemy battle formation in the 
area where engagement may occur, but not even that grouping with 
which it is to do battle, since the latter still will be moving 
into this area. In connection with this, it is impossible to 
assign a battalion in advance a number of missions to be 
performed successively. 
  The immediate mission of a company operating in a 
forward security element is to destroy enemy 
reconnaissance and security subunits, seize a favorable line and 
support deployment of the battalion main body. The depth of the 
company's immediate mission depends on the makeup of enemy 
reconnaissance and security subunits, their distance from the 
main body and the time needed to consolidate at the indicated 
line; it usually is 1-2 km. 
  The immediate mission of a battalion operating in a 
forward detachment is to seize and hold the indicated 
line (designated earlier or with initiation of the meeting 
battle), inflict damage on the enemy's lead subunits by fire of 
all weapons and support forward movement and deployment of the 
regimental main body. 
  The size of the line which must be taken by a company as a 
forward security element (or by a battalion as a forward 
detachment) is directly connected with its combat capabilities. 
Counting means of reinforcement, a company is capable of 
repelling an assault by one and one-half enemy companies 
(company task forces) by fire from an unprepared line, and a 
battalion is capable of repelling an assault by up to one and 
one-half enemy battalions (battalion task forces). A line must 
be assigned for a company (battalion) to capture and hold 
against which the forces indicated above will attack. According 
to enemy views, a company attacks in a frontage of up to 1.2-1.5 
km and a battalion in a frontage of 3-5 km or more. Consequently 
a company/forward security element can seize and hold a line on 
a frontage up to 2 km and a battalion on a frontage of 4-6 km or 
more. 
  When the main body launches an assault the company 
(battalion) operates in the previously indicated direction for 
continuing the attack. 
  The immediate mission of a battalion operating in an 
advance guard is to destroy enemy security subunits, 
immobilize his main body by active operations and support 
deployment and commitment of the regimental main body. 
  The immediate mission of a company (battalion) operating 
as part of the main body of a battalion (regiment) is 
to rout the main body of the first echelon company (battalion) 
of the opposing enemy subunit (unit) on its axis, destroy or 
capture his artillery and take a line providing favorable 
conditions for destroying approaching reserves and developing 
the attack. 
  The depth of the battle formation of a reinforced enemy 
company (battalion) in a meeting battle usually is 1-2 (4-6) km 
and sometimes even more. With consideration of this, the 
immediate mission of a company (battalion) operating on the axis 
of concentration of main efforts is designated with a depth of 
1-2 (4-6) km and sometimes even more. 
  The direction in which a company (battalion) which is part 
of 
the main body is to continue an attack must ensure swift 
destruction of enemy reserves and performance of the battalion 
(regimental) immediate mission. 
  The battle formation in a meeting battle must 
ensure delivering a strong initial attack and performing 
missions that arise suddenly in the course of battle. A 
single-echelon alignment with assignment of a reserve in the 
battalion meets these requirements to the greatest extent. 
  Usually 2-3 MRC's and the organic (attached) TC are assigned 
to an MRB first echelon. First echelon companies may be 
reinforced by tanks, AT subunits and grenade launcher subunits. 
As a rule, a TC is attached to MRC's by platoon, but also may be 
employed at full strength. 
  In the TB the first echelon usually consists of 2-3 TC's and 
an attached MRC, which is attached to the TC's, but sometimes 
also is used at full strength. 
  The battalion reserve is established with the strength of 
from a platoon to a company. 
  Subunits usually enter a meeting battle with those means of 
reinforcement which they had in the course of preceding 
operations. In some cases a redistribution of forces and assets 
is accomplished if required by situation conditions and there 
are opportunities, depending on the place of subunits in the 
battle formation and the missions they are performing. 
  In a meeting battle an attack is conducted on a broader 
front 
in the presence of considerable gaps between subunits. Thus, a 
battalion operating as part of the main body usually attacks in 
a frontage of 2-3 km and sometimes even more. Companies may have 
an attack frontage of from 500 to 1,000 m. A battalion operating 
in a forward detachment (advance guard), having two MRC's and a 
TC in the main body and an MRC in the forward security element, 
will deploy and conduct a meeting battle in a frontage of 3-5 km. 
<H5>  2. Organization of the Meeting Battle </H5>
  Organization of the meeting battle usually includes 
decisionmaking; assignment of combat missions to subunits; 
ground reconnaissance; and organization of fire engagement of 
the enemy, coordination, comprehensive support to battle and 
C[.sup]2[/]. Depending on situation conditions, it may begin 
with receipt of the combat mission or intelligence about enemy 
forward movement, or it may begin with engagement by march 
security when there is a surprise encounter with him. 
  The commander of a company (battalion) operating as part of 
the main body as a rule organizes the meeting battle based on 
the combat mission received. 
  On receiving the combat mission, the commander analyzes it, 
estimates the situation, makes the decision, communicates combat 
missions to subunits, and issues instructions on organizing 
coordination and on the most important questions of 
comprehensive support to battle. This work usually is done in 
movement from a map. 
  If possible, the situation and decision must be reported to 
the senior commander before assigning combat missions. 
  Subsequently the decision made from the map is updated on 
the 
terrain as one moves up to the line of departure, and the 
updated combat missions and coordination procedure are 
communicated to subunits. 
  The commander of a company operating in a forward security 
element (or the commander of a battalion operating in a forward 
detachment or advance guard) begins organizing for a meeting 
battle on receipt of the combat mission or when march security 
encounters the enemy. 
  The content of the company (battalion) commander's work of 
organizing for a meeting battle when it begins both with 
initiation by security elements as well as on receipt of a 
combat mission essentially is identical, but in the first case 
organizing for battle begins with a situation estimate and in 
the second case with analysis of the combat mission received. 
  In analyzing the mission, the commander must 
understand the objective of upcoming operations; the senior 
commander's concept (especially the sequence of routing the 
enemy); the company (battalion) mission, place in the battle 
formation and role in the battle; missions of adjacent subunits 
and procedure for coordinating with them and with subunits of 
other combat arms; and readiness times for performing the 
mission. 
  The commander draws conclusions from analyzing the mission 
in 
which he outlines the direction for concentrating main efforts, 
the kind of maneuver, the procedure of company (battalion) 
operations for swift, effective exploitation of results of fire 
strikes, and the battle formation. 
  After analyzing the mission, he estimates the situation. In 
estimating the enemy he must study the makeup, 
status, position, degree of protection, possible forward 
movement routes, possible nature of his operations, the most 
important objectives for engagement by artillery fire, and that 
part of the grouping whose destruction will lead to disruption 
of the attack or a breakup of the enemy battle formation and 
creation of conditions for his defeat in detail. 
  Because of incompleteness of information, the enemy estimate 
is made chiefly based on his table of organization structure and 
operating tactics. 
  In the estimate of friendly troops account is 
taken of their makeup, situation and nature of operations 
preceding the meeting battle. Estimated above all are 
capabilities for inflicting fire damage on the enemy by organic 
and attached artillery and for preempting him in deploying the 
main body into battle formation. 
  As a rule, in organizing for a meeting battle the enemy and 
friendly troop estimate is made together. For example, it is 
possible to assign combat missions to subunits only based on an 
estimate of the situation, nature of operations and capabilities 
of enemy and friendly subunits. The integrated situation 
estimate lies in the fact that the company commander does not 
study its elements to the full extent, but makes an estimate of 
the enemy, friendly troops and terrain, for example, only in 
order to determine the direction for concentrating main efforts, 
then to resolve other questions, the concept, and the decision 
as a whole. That method of determining the decision permits 
significantly reducing time of organizing for battle, but 
requires commanders to have high training. 
  Based on the estimate of the enemy and friendly troops, the 
company (battalion) commander determines the ratio of forces and 
assets and the time for execution of a maneuver by subunits, and 
he performs other necessary calculations. 
  In estimating the terrain the following are 
established: most advantageous maneuver routes providing egress 
to enemy flanks and rear, lines of deployment and departure and 
the direction of attack of friendly subunits. 
  The company (battalion) commander draws conclusions from the 
situation estimate in which he notes the following: measures for 
prohibiting organized enemy deployment and for preempting him in 
seizing an advantageous line; procedure for fire engagement of 
the main enemy grouping during its deployment into battle 
formation and in the course of battle; missions of the point 
(forward security element); alignment of the battle formation; 
firing position area of organic and attached artillery and 
readiness time for commencing fire; form of maneuver of subunits 
and place of the company (battalion) COP. 
  As a result of comparing conclusions from an analysis of the 
assigned mission and from the situation estimate, the company 
(battalion) commander determines the commander's 
concept, in which he reflects the following: direction for 
concentrating main efforts and form of maneuver; methods for 
routing an enemy who is moving forward (attacking) (what enemy 
to rout where, in what sequence and how, with an indication of 
the fire engagement procedure and measures for his deception); 
and the battle formation. 
  The constant threat of use of nuclear and precision weapons, 
the growth in combat capabilities of forces and assets, changes 
in the organization of units and subunits, and the rapidly 
changing situation demand that in determining elements of the 
concept the company (battalion) commander have creativeness and 
initiative and constantly improve methods of employing forces 
and assets in battle. 
  The direction for concentrating main efforts, the form 
of maneuver, and methods and sequence of defeating the 
enemy must be determined in such a way that the company 
(battalion) main body has superiority over the enemy on its axis 
of operations. The axis for concentrating main efforts should be 
selected on terrain providing most effective employment of 
motorized rifle and tank subunits. It should lead to the flank 
of the opposing enemy's main body, support a move to the combat 
mission line [rubezh boyevoy zadachi] over the shortest distance 
and provide for defeating the enemy in detail. It is advisable 
to select the axis so as to preclude superfluous changes of 
formation and movement of subunits, to achieve superiority over 
the enemy in forces and assets by at least one and one-half 
times, and to ensure the most favorable conditions for his 
defeat. 
  In an actual situation it is hardly possible to select an 
axis of possible concentration of main efforts satisfying all 
the requirements advanced here. Therefore correct determination 
as to which of them should be deemed most important depends only 
on the commander. It may happen that main efforts will be 
concentrated on what is not the most convenient terrain sector 
if this achieves surprise and provides superiority over the 
enemy and delivery of an attack against his flank. 
  In an encounter with an equal or stronger enemy grouping, 
superiority can be achieved by preempting him in commencing 
artillery fire; by immobilizing the main body with fire of 
subunits from advantageous lines and delivering an attack with 
one's main body against the weakest place in the enemy battle 
formation; by using the bulk of forces and assets and the most 
combat effective subunits on the selected axis; and by 
displaying initiative and creativeness and employing 
nonstereotyped operations. 
  Maneuver in a meeting battle must be simple in concept and 
ensure preemption of the enemy in deploying and in inflicting 
maximum damage by fire, a breakup of his march (battle) 
formation, and his destruction in detail. Such forms of maneuver 
as close and deep envelopment are used most often in a meeting 
battle. Wide opportunities appear for their use in connection 
with the presence of exposed flanks and gaps. 
  The main method for defeating the enemy in a 
meeting battle is to engage his advancing subunits by preemptive 
fire of all weapons during deployment into battle formation and 
complete their defeat by a determined assault against the flank 
and rear with his simultaneous immobilization by part of the 
forces from the front. 
  An assault from the front is possible in those cases where 
the enemy is reliably engaged by fire (including by the senior 
commander's weapons) and where it is difficult or impossible for 
subunits to maneuver to the enemy flank and rear due to the 
shortage of time. It permits splitting the enemy apart over the 
shortest axis and simultaneously developing the attack toward 
flanks. Success of a frontal assault can be achieved if it is a 
surprise and the enemy is reliably neutralized by fire of 
artillery and other weapons, otherwise a frontal assault may 
lead to a protracted battle and loss of the initiative. 
  In determining the concept, the procedure for fire 
engagement 
is envisaged to be such that the following occurs: artillery 
fire support of subunits immobilizing the enemy and supporting 
the forward movement and deployment of the main body; 
neutralization of his artillery and mortar subunits and AT 
weapons; engagement of approaching columns and disruption of 
their organized deployment and engagement; support of the 
forward movement and deployment of friendly first echelon 
subunits for the assault; and their support throughout the 
battle. 
  Fire engagement of the enemy can be divided into three main 
stages (periods): delivery of preemptive fire strikes against 
the enemy; artillery preparation of the assault, which usually 
is conducted as one fire assault; and artillery support of the 
assault to the depth of the battalion's immediate mission. 
  In determining the battle formation, the company 
(battalion) commander should proceed from the assumption that it 
is necessary to ensure superiority over the enemy on the axis of 
concentration of main efforts, delivery of a strong initial 
blow, his breakup and his destruction in detail. 
  It must be borne in mind that in organizing for a meeting 
battle the company (battalion) commander may assign missions to 
subunits, for example artillery, to deliver preemptive fire 
strikes against the advancing enemy long before completion of 
such organization, after the situation estimate, after 
determining the concept and so on. This is dictated by the 
limited time for organizing for battle and by the desire to 
provide as much time to subordinate commanders for work as 
possible and preempt the enemy in operations. 
  Company (forward security element) commander's 
concept for a meeting battle 
  (Variant) 
  I decided: Concentrate main efforts on the axis 
Hill 150.0, Sidorovo (Fig. 7). 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-10L-122A>      Fig. 7. 1st MRC commander's decision for a meeting battle </FIG>

  Point in coordination with ATP is to pin down enemy march 
security on the line lone tree, dam. Neutralize enemy personnel 
and weapons by fire of artillery battery as he moves forward and 
deploys in vicinity of edge of Temnyy Forest, trig point, curve 
in road. Execute a maneuver of two MRP's and a TP along the 
route of pipe on the road, grove and rout the enemy company main 
body in the vicinity of the lone house, barrow, Hill 164.5 by an 
assault in fighting vehicles from the line of the dam, barrow, 
take the line of the well, brook by 1030 and support deployment 
of the battalion main body. When main body launches assault, 
attack in direction of curve in road, Sidorovo. 
  Assign a tank to an ambush on the south edge of Temnyy 
Forest 
to prevent the enemy from enveloping the company right flank. 
  The company battle formation is in one echelon. Use the 
artillery battery and ATP centrally. 
  The company (battalion) commander assigns combat missions to 
subunits based on their place in the battle formation and their 
role in defeating the enemy, in accordance with the commander's 
concept and with consideration of the nature of terrain, enemy 
operations and other situation factors. 
  The company (battalion) commander determines the principal 
questions of coordination for the full depth of the meeting 
battle usually for the following missions: inflicting damage by 
preemptive artillery fire on an enemy moving up (attacking); 
capture of a favorable line by a portion of the forces; the 
battle of these subunits in the interests of supporting a 
maneuver of the company (battalion) main body; fire damage of 
the enemy when subunits move forward and deploy for an assault; 
the assault and execution of the immediate mission by the 
company (battalion); and development of the attack. 
  In each mission the company (battalion) commander singles 
out 
the most important stages of operations in which efforts of the 
subunits involved must be coordinated; determines the makeup of 
forces and assets to be working together and subunits performing 
the primary mission and in whose support all others are 
functioning; and plans the time, lines and signals with which 
coordinated operations of troops begin or end. On the whole, the 
methodology of determining the main questions of coordination in 
making a decision for a meeting battle is the very same as in 
decisionmaking for an attack on a defending enemy. 
  In organizing C[.sup]2[/] in a meeting battle the company 
(forward security element) commander determines the places and 
time of deploying COP's and attached subunits and the procedure 
for their displacement in the course of battle. 
  The company (battalion) commander additionally may specify 
tasks for political work and for kinds of support, above all 
reconnaissance, protection against mass destruction weapons, 
chemical warfare support and maskirovka. 
  After making the decision the company (battalion) commander 
assigns missions to subordinates by radio and simultaneously 
communicates the coordination procedure to them. As a rule, 
missions are communicated in brief operational instructions and 
all points, lines and objectives are indicated using codenames 
of local features and signal tables. 
  In some cases the company (battalion) commander may issue an 
operation order if the situation permits. 
  In assigning missions the battalion commander indicates the 
following in the operation order (operational 
instructions): 

  -  for forward security element--makeup, movement 
route, what line to capture and hold and by what time for 
supporting main body deployment, and the procedure of operations 
with beginning of the main body assault; 
  -  for attached 
artillery subunits, mortar (artillery) battery and grenade 
launcher subunit--missions for supporting battle of the 
forward security element and main body, firing position areas, 
readiness time to commence fire, signals for commencing, 
transferring and ceasing fire, and the procedure for 
displacement in the course of battle; 
  -  for MRC's (TC's)--immediate mission and direction 
for continuing the attack, line of departure, time of assault, 
route of forward movement to line of departure, and who is 
supporting; 
  -  for reserve--makeup, place in battle formation, and 
direction and procedure for displacement in the course of 
battle; 
  -  for AT subunit--missions for covering flanks or 
likely avenues of tank approach, firing positions (deployment 
lines), time to occupy them, procedure for commencing and 
ceasing fire, and procedure for displacement in the course of 
battle; 
  -  for air defense subunit--in what directions to 
conduct reconnaissance of the air enemy; what subunits to cover 
against air strikes during forward movement, deployment and in 
the course of battle; place in battle formation and procedure 
for displacement; 
  -  for other reinforcing subunits--procedure for 
supporting forward movement, deployment and assault of battalion 
subunits, place in battle formation and procedure for 
displacement in the course of battle. 


    In the operation order the company (forward 
security element) commander indicates the following: 

  -  for point--makeup, combat mission, procedure 
for operations on encountering the enemy and for reporting the 
situation; 
  -  for motorized rifle (tank) platoons--combat mission, 
procedure for operations on encountering the enemy; 
  -  for reinforcing subunits--missions which they are to 
be ready to execute and place in company march and battle 
formations. 


    In assigning missions to motorized rifle (tank) platoons the 
commander of a company operating as part of the battalion main 
body indicates the combat mission, line and time of departure, 
and coordination procedure. 
  With initiation of a meeting battle, the commander of a 
company operating in the forward security element indicates the 
very same data in assigning combat missions to subunits as does 
the commander of a company in the main body. 
  Fire engagement of the enemy, coordination, comprehensive 
support and C[.sup]2[/] in a meeting battle are organized 
during decisionmaking by the company (battalion) commander and 
during assignment of combat missions to subunits and are not 
singled out as a separate stage of work. In this connection the 
organization of a meeting battle essentially ends with 
assignment of combat missions to subunits. 
<H5>  3. Conduct of a Meeting Battle </H5>
  When a forward moving enemy is discovered, efforts of all 
reconnaissance forces and assets are directed toward uncovering 
his makeup, direction of column movement, and the time, areas 
and lines of deployment of tanks, mechanized infantry and 
artillery. 
  On encountering enemy reconnaissance and march security, the 
battalion's reconnaissance (combat reconnaissance) patrol 
immediately reports this to the battalion commander; without 
engaging, it covertly penetrates to his main body columns, 
determines their makeup and probable nature of operations, and 
keeps an eye out for the approach and direction of forward 
movement of reserves (second echelons). 
  Fire damage of the enemy to disrupt his forward movement and 
organized commitment and to create conditions for defeating him 
in detail begins by the senior commander's assets back before 
enemy columns enter the impact zone of company and battalion 
weapons. As the sides close, pressure on the enemy is built up 
by forces and assets of subunits. 
  A meeting battle of the forward security element, forward 
detachment and advance guard as a rule begins with battle of the 
march security. 
  On encountering small enemy groups, the point destroys them 
by fire and by a determined assault from the move and continues 
performing the assigned mission. On encountering an enemy 
superior in force, the point inflicts damage on him by fire from 
a favorable line and pins down his main body. The company 
commander immediately moves forward, and makes his decision and 
assigns combat missions to platoons and means of reinforcement 
during forward movement. 
  With the point 3-5 km from the company main body, the 
company 
commander spends approximately 8-12 minutes in moving up to it 
at a speed of 25 km/hr. Consequently, in that time he must 
estimate the situation, make a decision and assign missions to 
subordinates. 
  On arriving at the point, the company commander updates his 
decision based on results of its battle and his personal 
observations and communicates updated combat missions and if 
necessary also the coordination procedure to subunits. In 
addition, missions are updated right there on the terrain for 
the point commander and commanders of attached artillery, since 
they are with the company commander, and missions are updated 
for the others by radio. 
  Assignment of missions in meeting battle to 
subunits by the commander of a company operating 
in a forward security element 
  (Variant) 
  1st MRP, the point, is to complete destruction of the enemy 
and by 0940 hours take the line of the forest edge, road and 
hold it until the main body launches the assault. Subsequently 
continue moving in direction of lone house, well. 
  Artillery battery is to neutralize the enemy mechanized 
infantry company--head of column at Hill 160.0, prohibit his 
forward movement and deployment on the line well, trig point. 
Firing positions near road in vicinity of embankment. Readiness 
to commence fire 0925. 
  "Sosna [Pine]-12 (2nd MRP), this is Dub [Oak]-14 (company 
commander), together with Sosna-14 (TP) destroy enemy personnel 
and weapons on south slopes of Hill 164.5 by assault from line 
of trig point, barrow in direction of Hill 150.0, Sidorovo. 
Direction for continuing attack--bushes, curve in road. Route of 
forward movement--embankment, Hill 150.0, barrow. Assault at 
signal `Strela [Arrow]-444' and red flare, this is Dub-14, over." 
  "Sosna-13 (3rd MRP), this is Dub-14 (mission is assigned in 
a 
similar manner)." 
  "Zorkiy [Vigilant]-17 (ATP), this is Dub-14, destroy enemy 
tanks and IFV's by fire from in place, prevent his penetration 
in direction of Hill 164.5, spring. Take up deployment line of 
lone house, dam (excluded) by 0925. Commence-fire signal is 
`Udar [Strike]-21.' During battle displace behind Sosna-13, this 
is Dub-14, over." 
  After assigning combat missions the company commander 
monitors their execution and controls subunits. 
  The forward security element main body moves up swiftly to 
the line of departure indicated for it and, having deployed into 
battle formation from the move, assaults the enemy decisively. 
  Methods of the forward security element's operations in a 
meeting battle (Diagram 19) can be quite varied. Thus, on 
encountering lesser or equal enemy forces, it is capable of 
inflicting damage on them by fire of all weapons from in place, 
destroying tanks and IFV's (APC's), then completing the enemy's 
rout by a swift assault. 
  To ensure the enemy's defeat in detail, the forward security 
element may leave the route or, after executing a maneuver, let 
the enemy lead column pass by, take up a favorable line and 
prevent the approach of succeeding columns. In this situation 
the commander of a battalion operating in an advance guard 
(forward detachment) accomplishes defeat of the enemy who has 
broken away by swift, decisive actions from the front and by a 
flank attack. 
  On encountering an enemy superior in force, the forward 
security element takes up a favorable (designated) line, 
inflicts damage on enemy personnel, tanks and artillery by 
active operations of subunits and by fire of all weapons, and 
supports forward movement and deployment of the battalion main 
body. 
  When the forward security element engages, the commander of 
a 
battalion operating in a forward detachment (advance guard) 
moves up to it. His work of organizing for the meeting battle is 
accomplished in the very same sequence as the work of the 
forward security element commander after the point engages, 
which already has been examined. 
  Field training exercise experience shows that updating of 
the 
battalion commander's decision on the terrain and its 
communication to companies should be completed before they begin 
deploying into platoon columns. This will enable the company and 
platoon commanders to complete organization for battle in their 
subunits promptly. 
  Under cover of the forward security element and the fire of 
artillery and taking advantage of concealed approaches and if 
possible also maskirovka by aerosols (smoke), the forward 
detachment (advance guard) main body quickly executes a 
maneuver, deploys into battle formation from the move and 
completes destruction of enemy march security by a swift assault 
against the flank and rear. 
  Artillery subunits take up firing positions, open fire 
against approaching enemy columns, neutralize his artillery and 
AT weapons, support battle of the forward security element, and 
support the battalion main body's forward movement, deployment 
and commitment. Fire is commenced by battery as they are ready, 
and subsequently is conducted by the full complement of 
artillery. 
  Artillery commences and conducts fire so as to preempt the 
enemy in commencing fire and to disorganize and put his battle 
formations in disarray back before he engages. 
  Deployment of an SP artillery battery from the march and 
preparation for commencing fire takes 11-14 minutes, and a 
battalion requires 15-20 minutes. Combat missions must be 
updated for artillery above all so that all artillery is ready 
to conduct a fire assault against the enemy 10-15 minutes before 
the company (battalion) main body launches the assault. 
  A fire assault lasts 5-10 minutes and sometimes even more. 
Enemy artillery, tanks, IFV's (APC's), AT weapons and personnel 
are engaged during the fire assault. 
  During a meeting battle air defense weapons are in the 
battle 
formation of motorized rifle (tank) subunits in constant 
readiness to engage airborne targets both from short halts as 
well as in movement. 
  The battalion air defense platoon, usually operating by 
squad, covers the main body, artillery, and forward security 
element against enemy air strikes. If the battalion is 
reinforced by air defense weapons, as a rule they are used 
centrally to cover subunits of the main body and artillery. In 
this case the air defense platoon may be attached to a forward 
security element at full strength. 
  The battalion reserve displaces covertly up to 1.5-2 km 
behind first echelon subunits, as a rule on the most threatened 
flank, in readiness to exploit success or accomplish missions 
which arise suddenly. 
  The reserve as a rule is committed by authorization of the 
regimental commander. 
  On receiving his authorization the battalion commander 
assigns a mission to the reserve commander, where he indicates 
means of reinforcement and the procedure for their 
resubordination during commitment. 
  Commitment of the reserve takes around 10-15 minutes (the 
reserve covers 1.5-2 km at an average rate of forward movement 
and deployment of 15 km/hr in 6-8 minutes; in addition, 4-6 
minutes are needed for assigning the combat mission). 
  In making the decision to commit the reserve, the battalion 
commander must provide for its reestablishment at the very first 
opportunity. This may be a platoon from a company which was 
operating in the forward security element, or the company itself 
after it performs its mission. 
  Subunits of AT weapons deploy on likely avenues of tank 
approach and by their fire cover the battalion main body flanks 
against possible enemy assaults. They often operate together 
with subunits supporting commitment of the main body (with the 
forward security element). 
  With initiation of the meeting battle, the battalion 
reconnaissance platoon continues performing its missions, 
concentrating primary efforts on determining (updating) the 
makeup, possible nature of operations, forward movement routes 
and deployment lines of enemy follow-on forces. 
  Logistic and technical support subunits are used in a 
meeting 
battle as in an attack on a defending enemy. They usually deploy 
behind the battalion battle formation, where possible in an area 
difficult of access for tanks. The battalion (company) aid 
station (post) and technical observation posts displace behind 
assaulting subunits. 
  In the course of the meeting battle, combat engineer 
subunits 
attached to the battalion usually operate as part of the main 
body, supporting the forward movement and execution of a 
maneuver by MRC's and TC's. In those cases where battalion 
subunits will be unable to bypass or negotiate obstacles and 
barriers from the move, the combat engineer subunit breaches the 
obstacles and barriers with its own assets. Reinforcing the 
battalion with combat engineer subunits with wide enemy use of 
remote mining of terrain acquires special importance. The time 
for the battalion to move out of an area that has been mined and 
its losses will be considerably less in this case. 
  After destroying enemy march security, the forward 
detachment 
seizes and holds its designated line until the approach of the 
regimental main body, and the advance guard boldly penetrates to 
the enemy main body and immobilizes it. Subsequently the forward 
detachment and advance guard usually operate as part of the 
regimental first echelon. Their launching of an assault together 
with main body subunits is possible only in the presence of 
favorable conditions: gaps in the enemy battle formation and 
attempts to withdraw or execute a maneuver to another axis. 
  If superior enemy forces have preempted the forward 
detachment in moving to its designated line, have preempted the 
advance guard in deployment and are conducting an attack, the 
battalion inflicts damage on them by the fire of organic and 
attached artillery and all other weapons, immobilizes the enemy 
by active operations at the line reached and on a broad front, 
and provides the most favorable conditions for deployment of the 
regimental main body. 
  During the battle to hold a captured line, personnel of 
motorized rifle subunits dismount and the BMP's (BTR's) and 
tanks take up firing positions behind cover so as to conduct 
fire to maximum ranges. 
  A company (battalion) operating as part of the main body 
moves forward covertly to its axis at maximum possible speed, 
deploys into battle formation and assaults the enemy swiftly. 
The battalion reserve is committed after execution of the 
immediate mission and sometimes even earlier. Any kind of halt 
or delay at the battalion's immediate-mission line is 
impermissible. As a rule, at this time the regimental commander 
communicates a new mission to the battalion, but if one is not 
assigned, the battalion commander takes steps to develop the 
attack in the previously indicated direction. 
  With an enemy attempt to consolidate at a favorable line and 
support commitment of the main body, the company (battalion) 
breaks him apart by fire and a determined assault from the front 
and flanks, destroys personnel and weapons and continues 
performing assigned combat mission. 
  On detecting an enemy withdrawal the battalion immediately 
shifts to the pursuit, destroys covering-force subunits, swiftly 
penetrates to his main body and destroys it in coordination with 
subunits conducting a pursuit along parallel routes. A company 
(battalion) operating on an enveloping flank must move swiftly 
along the shortest routes onto the enemy withdrawal axis and 
assault him decisively. 
  The commander exercises C[.sup]2[/] of company (battalion) 
subunits in a meeting battle by brief commands, instructions and 
signals from the COP, which usually displaces up to 200 (300) m 
behind battle formations of first echelon companies on the axis 
of concentration of main efforts. 
  The company (battalion) commander must keep a watchful eye 
on 
a change in the situation and promptly update the decision and 
combat missions for subunits. On discovering enemy preparation 
to deliver fire strikes and an attempt to execute a maneuver or 
commit the reserve, it is necessary to inflict fire damage on 
the enemy by artillery, move friendly subunits out from under 
the strike and, making wide use of the maneuver of forces and 
assets and ambushes, complete his defeat by an assault of 
motorized rifle and tank subunits. 
  On encountering the enemy, a company operating in a flank 
security element immobilizes him by fire and active operations 
on favorable lines and gives the regimental main body an 
opportunity to maneuver for performing the assigned mission. If 
the regiment (battalion) deploys toward the flank on which the 
flank security element is located, the latter operates in the 
very same manner as the forward security element. 
  If a tactical airborne assault force is landed on the axis 
of 
company (battalion) operations, the commander must take all 
steps to link up with it and perform the assigned mission by 
joint operations. 
<H5>  Chapter VII - Battle in Encirclement and Breakout of </H5>
Encirclement 
<H5>  1. Battle in Encirclement </H5>
  An encirclement does not arise suddenly. It is the result of 
an unsuccessful outcome of battle and a move of enemy subunits 
to the flanks and rear of a company (battalion). 
  A company (battalion) may find itself in encirclement 
(Diagram 19) in an attack when it is operating in isolation from 
the main body as a tactical airborne assault force or a 
reconnaissance, special (forward) or raiding detachment. In 
addition, having halted attacking troops, the enemy may cut off 
a company (battalion) from the main body by counterattacks and 
then encircle it. 
  Encirclement also is possible with an unsuccessful outcome 
of 
a meeting battle and in a withdrawal when the pursuing enemy's 
rate of advance is higher than the rate of withdrawing subunits. 
But encirclement will occur most often in a defensive battle as 
a result of enemy penetration of the defense of adjacent 
subunits and his move to the flanks and rear of a company 
(battalion) with subsequent establishment of a perimeter of 
envelopment. 
  A company (battalion) which has ended up in encirclement or 
in the enemy rear (but not encircled) must pin down as many of 
his forces as possible by active, determined actions, thereby 
contributing to the main body's successful performance of the 
combat mission. 
  As a rule, an encirclement is preceded by battles with an 
enemy of superior force, and so a company (battalion) may have 
considerable losses and in addition may end up in encirclement 
not at full strength. 
  If subunits which are not a part of the company (battalion) 
end up in encirclement together with it, the company (battalion) 
commander is obligated to subordinate them to himself and 
subsequently employ them in accordance with the situation at 
hand. 
  The makeup of forces and assets which end up encircled 
together with the company (battalion) is impossible to determine 
in advance but, as the experience of wars and exercises shows, 
these may be air defense, artillery and technical and logistic 
support subunits which previously were located in or near a 
company strongpoint (battalion defense area) or withdrew from 
previously occupied positions (areas). 
  The company (battalion) mission in battle in 
encirclement is to firmly hold the occupied strongpoint (defense 
area), prevent the enemy from breaking subunits apart and 
inflict significant losses on him. 
  The size of a strongpoint (defense area) depends on the 
makeup of forces and assets of subunits which ended up in 
encirclement. It must ensure repulse of enemy attack and 
preclude dissipation of forces and assets and a reduction in 
fire density. At the same time, the area of the strongpoint 
(defense area) should not be restricted, otherwise it will lead 
to overcompaction of forces and assets, increased losses from 
enemy fire and impedance of maneuver. 
  These basic requirements on size of a company strongpoint 
(battalion defense area) are realized in the case where the 
company holds a strongpoint 1.5-2 km around the perimeter and 
the battalion holds a defense area up to 6-8 km in circumference 
around a circular front. In this case the average depth of a 
company strongpoint will be around 500-700 m and that of the 
battalion defense area 2-3 km, which ensures a dispersed 
disposition of the battle formation. 
  An MRC holding an area with a perimeter up to 1.5-2 km 
during 
battle in encirclement can create small arms fire densities 
(with losses up to 25 percent) of 4-6 bullets per meter of 
frontage per minute and densities of AT weapons, BMP's and tanks 
(counting RPG's and the attached TP) of 8-10, which as a whole 
is considered sufficient for creating a stable defense under 
these conditions. Usually the size of the company strongpoint 
(battalion defense area) is the very same as in the defense or 
somewhat less. 
  The battle formation of the company (battalion) 
for battle in encirclement is created as the threat arises and 
as the situation permits regrouping forces and assets for 
shifting to a perimeter defense. 
  The considerable extent of the circular defense frontage and 
usually the presence of several threatened axes and a shortage 
of forces and assets require an alignment of the company 
(battalion) battle formation which would ensure concentration of 
efforts on each threatened axis. This requirement is met to the 
greatest extent by a single-echelon alignment of the battle 
formation with assignment of a reserve: in the company up to a 
squad in strength and in the battalion up to a platoon and 
sometimes even more. Thus, the company (battalion) battle 
formation includes the following: first echelon subunits; a 
reserve; weapons and reinforcing subunits remaining directly 
subordinate to the company (battalion) commander; and armored 
groups and fire ambushes. 
  A platoon (company) of a first echelon company (battalion) 
prepares strongpoints in such a way that they intercept the most 
likely avenues of enemy assaults in order to split his company 
(battalion) battle formation and destroy him in detail. 
  The company (battalion) reserve will be disposed in the 
center of the strongpoint (defense area) in a place from where 
it is possible to execute a maneuver quickly to threatened axes. 
  As a rule, tank (motorized rifle), artillery, air defense, 
grenade launcher and AT subunits that are organic or attached to 
the battalion and which ended up in encirclement with it are 
attached to companies and disposed in their strongpoints. Part 
of the artillery is moved up to conduct direct fire. Artillery 
remaining directly subordinate to the battalion commander takes 
up firing positions in the center of the battalion defense area 
in readiness for a maneuver to repel enemy assaults from any 
threatened axis. 
  Both in the company as well as in the battalion, it is 
advisable to make wide use of armored groups and fire ambushes 
during battle in encirclement. Their makeup and the procedure 
for their combat employment will be the very same as in an 
"ordinary" defense. 
  Subunits of engineer and chemical troops attached to the 
battalion are disposed near the battalion COP. 
  The company (battalion) COP is prepared in the depth of the 
strongpoint (defense area) in a place difficult for tank access 
and providing visual observation of operations of the enemy and 
friendly subunits on the most dangerous axis. 
  On the whole, during battle in encirclement the company 
(battalion) battle formation has the very same elements as in an 
ordinary defense, but their disposition must permit reacting as 
quickly as possible to enemy attempts to penetrate the defense 
frontage on any axis. 
  The system of company (battalion) strongpoints and firing 
positions is distinguished from an ordinary defense by the 
absence of a combat security outpost position in the battalion, 
by the circular disposition of platoon (company) strongpoints, 
and by establishment of the largest possible number of alternate 
firing positions, which must ensure conduct of fire not only 
toward the front, but also to the rear and toward flanks. One 
does not always succeed in preparing trenches and communication 
trenches in strongpoints or accomplishing engineer preparation 
of the occupied position to the full extent because of the 
shortage of time and also enemy pressure. Therefore it is 
necessary to take skilled advantage of the nature of terrain and 
its protective and concealing properties and prepare fire sacks 
and ambush sites. The company (battalion) commander should take 
all steps and realize all opportunities for engineer preparation 
of the defense. 
  A feature of battle in encirclement is that battalion rear 
and technical support subunits usually are disposed together 
(having the very same entities as in a defense). There is 
engineer preparation of their location and it is included in the 
system of strongpoints and firing positions. 
  The company (battalion) system of fire in battle in 
encirclement should conform to the situation at hand and ensure 
engagement of the enemy ahead of the entire frontage and in the 
depth of the perimeter defense. The system of fire is created 
with consideration of the fire damage being accomplished by the 
senior commander. 
  Companies and platoons are assigned zones of fire and 
weapons 
conducting direct fire are assigned sectors of fire. Zones of 
fire of adjacent subunits (weapons) should overlap. 
  A first echelon company (platoon) usually prepares a firing 
position in a zone of 2-3 km (500-700 m). 
  To mislead the enemy regarding the structure of the company 
(battalion) system of fire, roving guns (BMP's, tanks) are 
assigned and fire ambushes are prepared on possible enemy 
penetration axes. 
  The system of fire is tied in in a most thorough manner with 
the disposition of minefields so that when tanks, IFV's, APC's 
and other fighting vehicles attempt to go around the minefield 
they present their most vulnerable places to fire. 
  The possibility of an enemy penetration on any threatened 
axis requires preparation of a maneuver both of weapons as well 
as of fire. 
  Lines of firing positions are prepared for reserves, armored 
groups and other weapons, and alternate firing positions are 
prepared for the SP artillery battery to destroy individual 
enemy groups that have penetrated. 
  A system of engineer obstacles is established with 
consideration of terrain and the company (battalion) battle 
formation and is tied in closely with systems of strongpoints 
and firing positions and especially with the system of fire. 
  In connection with the fact that company (battalion) 
capabilities for laying minefields are limited in a period of 
organizing and conducting battle in encirclement, it is 
necessary to make wide use of minefields laid in advance, 
coordinating the disposition of strongpoints and positions with 
their location, and sometimes relocate them if time is 
available. It is necessary to make wider use of abatis and 
demolition of various objects, which will hamper enemy maneuver. 
  Thus, alignment of the company (battalion) defense and 
missions of subunits in a battle in encirclement to a 
considerable extent remain the very same as under ordinary 
conditions. At the same time, they are distinguished by a number 
of features already noted which the commander must take into 
account in preparing for battle. 
  Preparing for battle in encirclement includes those same 
measures as preparing a defense under ordinary conditions. A 
number of them are carried out in advance, such as preparing 
subunits to perform the combat mission and organizing and 
conducting political work. Subsequently this work is only 
concretized with consideration of the situation at hand and with 
a change in missions. 
  Organization for battle in encirclement usually is preceded 
by conduct of measures to prevent encirclement. 
  If a threat of encirclement arises the company (battalion) 
commander is obligated to do the following: beef up observation 
and additionally organize reconnaissance and fire ambushes on 
flanks, boundaries and in gaps, reliably supporting them by AT 
fire and obstacles; strive not only to prevent encirclement, but 
also to defeat enveloping enemy subunits; organize the 
concentration of fire of all weapons, and especially AT fire, on 
threatened flanks; regroup forces and assets, above all tanks 
and BMP's, move the second echelon (reserve) up to a threatened 
axis, prevent the company (battalion) battle formation from 
being broken up and prevent the enemy from moving to the flanks 
and rear; and boldly, swiftly and decisively counterattack 
against the flank and rear of enveloping enemy subunits in 
coordination with the senior commander's forces and make wide 
use of artillery fire and the assistance of adjacent subunits. 
  In case measures to prevent encirclement taken by the 
company 
(battalion) commander and senior commander will not lead to 
success and a withdrawal order (instruction) is not received, a 
decision is made for battle in encirclement. It will be made 
under difficult situation conditions, where subunits are 
fighting an intensive battle with an enemy attempting to 
complete encirclement of the company (battalion). In some cases 
the decision for battle in encirclement is made based on the 
senior commander's operational instructions. 
  To make the advisable decision, the company (battalion) 
commander organizes reconnaissance by observation and by other 
methods if possible in order to clarify the situation and makeup 
of the enemy surrounding the company (battalion). 
  In estimating the enemy special attention must be given to 
where he is preparing to launch an attack and with what forces. 
  In estimating friendly troops, in addition to those 
questions 
studied under ordinary conditions the company (battalion) 
commander must study the status, capabilities, degree of 
protection and degree of supply of subunits which are not part 
of the company (battalion) but which have ended up in 
encirclement, and subordinate them to himself. 
  The commander must perform the situation estimate throughout 
the entire period of operations preceding encirclement, and so 
very little time is spent on this stage of the work of 
decisionmaking. 
  Based on the situation estimate the company commander takes 
steps to shift to a perimeter defense, reinforce likely avenues 
of tank approach with tanks, BMP's and AT weapons, close gaps in 
the battle formation by fire and obstacles, prepare a maneuver 
of forces and assets to threatened axes and establish a reserve. 
While subunits are performing these measures he determines the 
decision, which includes the very same questions as a decision 
for a defense. 
  The company commander makes the decision for battle in 
encirclement basically on the terrain and the battalion 
commander does so on the terrain and from a map, then he updates 
it once again on the terrain on those axes not viewed from the 
COP. 
  An operation order is not issued in connection with the fact 
that battle in encirclement is organized in the course of a 
defense or other operations. The company (battalion) commander 
assigns combat missions to subunits as brief operational 
instructions. The coordination procedure, and if necessary also 
some of the most important questions of comprehensive support, 
must be communicated to subordinate commanders. 
  Coordination is organized for those same missions as in 
defensive battle. The efforts of platoons (companies), weapons 
and the reserve are coordinated additionally in case the enemy 
delivers strikes from several directions and splits the battle 
formation into parts. 
  Organization of logistic support is difficult during company 
(battalion) battle in encirclement. Encircled subunits will be 
forced to fight with those reserves of ammunition and supplies 
which they have. In connection with this the company (battalion) 
commander immediately must make a strict accounting of all 
available ammunition, fuel, food and other supplies, establish a 
rigid regime of consumption and if necessary redistribute them 
among subunits in accordance with missions being performed. 
  Reserves of supplies may be replenished by air delivery, and 
use of captured weapons and ammunition is possible. 
  Conduct of battle in encirclement begins from the moment 
superior enemy forces move to the flanks and rear of a company 
(battalion) and intercept all withdrawal routes for linkup with 
friendly troops. 
  Simultaneously with encirclement, the enemy immediately will 
attempt to break up the company (battalion) battle formation and 
destroy it in detail. To keep this from happening, it is 
necessary to conduct reconnaissance constantly, estimate the 
situation at hand thoroughly and comprehensively, and update the 
decision and communicate combat missions to subunits promptly. 
  Subunits must hold occupied strongpoints firmly, maneuver 
forces, assets and fire to a threatened axis quickly and 
covertly, and be ready to destroy an enemy who has penetrated by 
fire and a determined counterattack. 
  An enemy assault is repelled by fire of all company 
(battalion) weapons. When the enemy penetrates, the company 
(battalion) commander takes all steps to stop his advance and 
then destroy him by a swift counterattack. 
  If he has not achieved success on one axis, after regrouping 
forces and assets the enemy will attempt to deliver an attack in 
another sector. In this situation a commander must promptly 
discover the transfer of enemy efforts and quickly organize and 
accomplish a maneuver of the reserve or of subunits from sectors 
not under attack to the threatened axis. 
  In those cases where the enemy has penetrated in several 
sectors, steps must be taken to destroy him on the most 
dangerous axis. A shortage of forces and assets will not allow 
routing a penetrated enemy on other axes as well, and so there 
it is advisable to prevent a further advance of his subunits 
into the depth of the company (battalion) defense. 
  During battle in encirclement the company (battalion) must 
maintain constant coordination with subunits operating outside 
of encirclement, promptly mark the position of subordinate 
subunits for friendly aviation, and participate in 
counterattacks conducted by the senior commander. 
  To receive cargoes a company (battalion) prepares sites for 
helicopters to land in its disposition and organizes the receipt 
and gathering of cargoes dropped from aircraft. 
  It is necessary to conduct political work skillfully and 
purposefully to keep the personnel's morale at a high level and 
to preserve efficiency and constant combat readiness of subunits. 
  In organizing and conducting battle in encirclement the 
company (battalion) commander must strive to inflict maximum 
damage on the enemy and create conditions for breaking out of 
encirclement. 
<H5>  2. Breakout of Encirclement </H5>
  Breaking out of encirclement consists of breaking through 
the 
noose of encirclement in a selected sector (on a selected axis) 
for linkup with friendly troops (Diagram 20). 
  To achieve surprise and concealment of operations it is 
advisable to begin the breakthrough of encirclement at night and 
under conditions of limited visibility, sometimes even without 
conducting fire preparation. 
  A breakout of encirclement is accomplished by permission of 
the senior commander in coordination with subunits conducting 
oncoming combat operations from the outer perimeter, or 
independently. 
  The senior commander indicates the direction of breakthrough 
and of further operations in a breakout of encirclement in 
coordination with subunits conducting oncoming combat operations 
from the outer perimeter. If a company (battalion) is breaking 
out independently, the company (battalion) commander determines 
the direction for breakout and procedure for further operations. 
  Breaking out of encirclement in small groups and without 
armament usually leads to heavy losses and disruption of the 
organizational integrity of subunits, and therefore is 
impermissible. 
  In aligning the battle formation it should be taken into 
account that a company (battalion) not only has to break through 
the perimeter of envelopment, but also hold the strongpoint 
(area) for a certain time, secure flanks of subunits 
accomplishing the breakthrough and perform missions that arise 
suddenly. Therefore the company (battalion) battle formation 
should include the following: breakthrough subunits; subunits 
assigned to cover the breakthrough, including those assigned to 
secure flanks (screens); a reserve; and reinforcing weapons and 
subunits remaining directly subordinate to the company 
(battalion) commander. 
  At least half of all subunits and a large part of the 
artillery are assigned to break through the noose of 
encirclement. Motorized rifle (tank) subunits are reinforced by 
tanks (motorized rifle subunits), AT weapons, and mineclearing 
(obstacle breaching) equipment. The makeup of breakthrough 
subunits includes the most combat-effective forces and assets. 
  A minimum number of subunits remains on the rest of the 
perimeter of envelopment for covering the breakthrough with the 
mission of holding occupied positions, misleading the enemy by 
active operations, diverting a portion of his forces (reserves) 
from the breakthrough axis, prevent a narrowing of the perimeter 
of envelopment and of the breakthrough sector, and supporting 
the exit of all company (battalion) subunits from the noose of 
encirclement. Usually a platoon (company) and sometimes even 
more is assigned from the company (battalion) to the covering 
force. The least amount of forces and assets is assigned in 
those cases where the enemy shows no activeness and the breakout 
of encirclement is done at night or under conditions of poor 
visibility. As a rule, an MRP (TP), tanks, and BMP-equipped 
MRS's are assigned to screens. The number of screens depends on 
the depth of the perimeter of envelopment on the breakthrough 
axis. Screens are disposed at that distance from each other 
ensuring cover of flanks of subunits making the breakthrough on 
the most threatened axes. Screens operate as flank security 
elements after the company (battalion) breaks out of the noose 
of encirclement and until linkup with friendly troops. As a 
rule, screens are assigned from the makeup of subunits assigned 
as a covering force. 
  Subunits assigned as a covering force are reinforced by 
artillery, tanks (motorized rifle subunits), and subunits of 
engineer troops with obstacle assets. 
  A company reserve usually is established consisting of an 
MRS 
(tank), and a battalion reserve consisting of a platoon, 
intended for performing missions arising in the course of 
battle. It is disposed in that place from where there is an 
opportunity to support subunits assigned for the breakthrough in 
a short time, exploit their success and if necessary repel 
assaults of an enemy who has penetrated the defense of covering- 
force subunits. 
  Attached and organic artillery as well as artillery which 
has 
ended up in encirclement together with the company (battalion), 
with the exception of that assigned to reinforce covering 
forces, is used centrally on the axis of breakthrough of the 
perimeter of envelopment. 
  Artillery, other weapons and subunits remaining directly 
subordinate to the company (battalion) commander take up firing 
positions (areas) behind battle formations of subunits breaking 
through the perimeter of envelopment, in readiness to support 
their actions and the breakout of remaining forces and assets 
from encirclement through the breach formed. When the perimeter 
of envelopment is small, they may remain at occupied firing 
positions (or in occupied areas). 
  When a company (battalion) breaks out of encirclement as 
part 
of a battalion (regiment) in coordination with subunits 
conducting oncoming combat operations from the outer perimeter, 
the combat mission is assigned to the company (battalion) by the 
senior commander. With an independent breakout of encirclement 
by a company (battalion), its combat mission as a 
rule is specified by the commander of this company (battalion). 
A company is given an immediate mission and a direction for 
continuing the attack and a battalion is given an immediate and 
subsequent mission. 
  The battalion's immediate mission usually is to destroy the 
enemy on the breakthrough axis and breach the perimeter of 
envelopment. 
  The subsequent mission is for subunits to break out of 
encirclement and link up with troops operating toward them in 
assisting the breakout, or to take an area providing favorable 
conditions for further operations. 
  The company's immediate mission usually is to destroy the 
enemy on the breakthrough axis and breach the perimeter of 
envelopment. 
  The immediate mission of a company operating as part of a 
battalion will coincide with the battalion's immediate mission 
in depth, and so the direction for continuing the attack is 
determined so as to ensure performance of the battalion's 
subsequent mission. 
  In other cases this direction should ensure a linkup with 
subunits operating toward the company from the outer perimeter 
of envelopment or the company's breakout into an area favoring 
further operations. 
  The depth of the company (battalion) immediate mission will 
depend on the makeup and alignment of the enemy grouping on the 
axis of breakthrough of the perimeter of envelopment. 
  As shown by an analysis of enemy views on conduct of combat 
operations to destroy encircled groupings, the basis of troops 
forming the inner perimeter of envelopment usually consists of 
battalions (battalion task forces) whose battle formation is 
formed in one or two echelons depending on the makeup of the 
encircled grouping. In this case the depth of the perimeter of 
envelopment averages 3-5 km. The depth of the company 
(battalion) immediate mission accordingly will be the very same. 
  Enemy subunits making up the perimeter of envelopment as a 
rule are in an offensive grouping, and so a company (battalion) 
needs to create a superiority of no more than 1-1.5 times for 
success of the breakthrough. But in connection with the fact 
that in this case densities of enemy forces and assets are 
significantly higher than in the defense and subunits fighting 
the battle in encirclement have considerable losses, the 
breakthrough frontage of the company (battalion) usually is up 
to 500 (1,000) m. 
  Organizing the breakout of encirclement begins with receipt 
of the combat mission or with the senior commander's 
authorization to break out of encirclement. 
  The company (battalion) commander makes the decision from 
the 
map and updates it during ground reconnaissance of the 
breakthrough sector. 
  The very same questions are determined in the 
decision for breaking out of encirclement as in the 
decision for the attack: commander's concept, combat missions 
for subunits, the main questions of coordination, and 
organization of C[.sup]2[/]. 
  In the commander's concept the company (battalion) 
commander outlines the following: sector and axis for 
breakthrough of the perimeter of envelopment; methods of 
defeating the enemy (what enemy to defeat where, in what 
sequence and how, with an indication of the procedure for his 
engagement by fire of tanks, BMP's and other organic and 
attached weapons; measures for deception, including the sector 
and axis of diversionary actions; actions of subunits in 
breaking out of encirclement; and the order of withdrawal of 
subunits covering the breakthrough and assigned to screens); 
company (battalion) battle formation; forces and assets used for 
the breakthrough and for covering and securing flanks; attack 
position of subunits intended for the breakthrough and the 
procedure and time for occupying it. 
  The breakthrough axis should be selected where it is 
possible 
to concentrate forces and assets in the breakthrough sector 
covertly in a short time, where the enemy's perimeter of 
envelopment has least depth, and so as to provide for linkup 
over the shortest distance with subunits conducting oncoming 
combat operations from the outer perimeter. 
  Choosing the time for breaking through the perimeter of 
envelopment requires the company (battalion) commander to 
perform a thorough analysis of the situation at hand. It is most 
advantageous to begin the breakthrough at that moment when the 
enemy has ceased active operations to destroy the encircled 
subunits or has shifted to sealing them off, but has not managed 
to consolidate and change his battle formation and to create a 
defensive grouping. 
  Diversionary actions are conducted to mislead the enemy 
regarding the axis of the company (battalion) breakout of 
encirclement and to divert his reserves from the breakthrough 
sector. An axis and sector are designated for conducting 
diversionary actions; up to a platoon is assigned for this in 
the company and up to a company in the battalion with means of 
reinforcement, and they are supported by artillery fire. 
Diversionary actions may begin simultaneously with the 
breakthrough of the perimeter of envelopment or somewhat 
earlier, depending on the situation. If they precede the 
breakthrough, there is the possibility of diverting enemy 
reserves from the breakthrough sector, but at the same time the 
diversionary actions may give the enemy grounds to presume that 
a breakout of the company (battalion) from encirclement is 
imminent. 
  In his decision the company (battalion) commander assigns 
missions to subunits in the following sequence: 
breakthrough subunits; subunits for covering and securing 
flanks; the reserve; and reinforcing weapons and subunits 
remaining directly subordinate to him. 
  The main questions of coordination additionally 
reflect the procedure for coordinated operations of company 
(battalion) subunits with troops which are outside the perimeter 
of envelopment. 
  Subsequently the company (battalion) commander determines 
the 
following: missions by kinds of support to battle and 
organization of reconnaissance before and during the 
breakthrough of the perimeter of envelopment and in the course 
of further operations; and the procedure for expenditure of 
ammunition and fuel, evacuation of wounded and destruction of 
unserviceable vehicles and weapons. 
  In the course of ground reconnaissance he clarifies the 
following: enemy makeup, situation and nature of operations; 
whether the enemy is shifting to sealing off the encircled 
troops or is preparing repeat assaults; targets, attack position 
of subunits, procedure for occupying it, and method of assault; 
missions for breakthrough subunits, procedure for breaking out 
of encirclement, and questions of coordination among weapons and 
assaulting subunits. 
  With a breakout of encirclement at night the company 
(battalion) commander specifies the line which subunits must 
reach by dawn. 
  Combat missions are communicated to subunits in the form of 
an operation order and sometimes also by brief 
operational instructions. The following are indicated in 
assigning missions: 

  -  for subunits designated for the breakthrough-- 
means of reinforcement, missions, attack position for the 
breakthrough and time of occupying it; 
  -  for covering-force subunits--means of reinforcement, 
mission, sector of diversionary actions, what forces and assets 
to allocate for covering flanks (to screens), who is supporting, 
and the time and procedure for withdrawal; 
  -  for the reserve--makeup, assembly area and procedure 
for displacement; 
  -  for attached artillery subunit, mortar (SP artillery) 
battery, grenade launcher subunit, air defense subunit and AT 
subunit--missions for fire engagement of the enemy and for 
covering friendly subunits against air strikes, and the time and 
procedure for breaking out of encirclement. 


    After assigning combat missions the company commander issues 
coordination instructions, in which he first of all 
coordinates actions of subunits breaking through the perimeter 
of envelopment with each other, with weapons and with covering- 
force subunits. 
  Coordination of efforts with covering-force subunits 
consists 
of determining the method and procedure for them to hold 
positions and withdraw from line to line. The number of 
withdrawal lines depends on the nature of enemy pressure and 
terrain conditions. 
  Special attention is given to coordinating oncoming combat 
operations of friendly subunits and troops operating outside of 
encirclement in terms of time, axes of operations and the lines 
they capture, above all in the approach to the linkup point in 
order to preclude mutual engagement by fire. 
  After assigning combat missions and organizing coordination 
the company (battalion) commander issues instructions on 
organizing comprehensive support in which he establishes the 
following: missions for observers (for reconnaissance); measures 
for ensuring concealment and surprise of the breakthrough; 
nature and procedure of engineer preparation of terrain in the 
breakthrough sector and at the covering-force position 
(positions); places, time and methods of breaching enemy 
obstacles; what should be mined, demolished or destroyed and at 
what time; organization of C[.sup]2[/] during the 
breakthrough; procedure for marking one's position for aviation 
and for recognition of friendly troops operating from the outer 
perimeter of envelopment; procedure for evacuating wounded and 
sick as well as weapons and vehicles; and commanders responsible 
for fulfilling comprehensive support measures. 
  If the breakout of encirclement is done at night, the 
company 
(battalion) commander additionally indicates the procedure for 
illumination support of the attack and withdrawal, reference 
points, and azimuth (direction) of attack. Conventional signs 
which are placed on equipment and the personnel's clothing also 
are established. 
  Ammunition and fuel are redistributed, with the bulk 
allocated to subunits making the breakthrough of the perimeter 
of envelopment. 
  Organizing comprehensive support is an important moment in 
preparing for battle, since a successful breakout of subunits 
from encirclement depends on it to a considerable extent. 
  Conduct of battle when breaking out of encirclement is 
characterized by a short duration and extreme ferocity. In a 
short time the company (battalion) commander has to break 
through the perimeter of envelopment, create a breach in the 
noose of encirclement and support the breakout of all subunits 
at full strength with weapons. 
  Success in breaking out of encirclement depends largely on 
timely establishment of the battle formation, disengagement, and 
occupation of an attack position by breakthrough subunits. 
  Disengagement and occupation of an attack position by 
breakthrough subunits can be done simultaneously or successively 
with observance of maskirovka. Depending on terrain and 
visibility conditions, it is advisable to conceal these 
operations by use of smoke (aerosols) while preserving the 
regime of previous troop activity on the entire company 
(battalion) defense frontage. 
  Covering-force subunits conducting diversionary actions 
decisively assault the enemy at the prescribed time, supported 
by fire of attached artillery, and divert his reserves to 
themselves; if the assault is disrupted they conduct a 
firefight, denying the enemy an opportunity to execute a 
maneuver of forces and assets. 
  As a rule, the breakthrough begins with fire preparation. If 
fire preparation is not conducted, for example at night, then 
fire commences when breakthrough subunits launch the assault and 
artillery immediately accomplishes fire support of the assault. 
  Tanks may be used in fire preparation. 
  It is advisable to conduct the assault in BMP's (BTR's) for 
rapid exploitation of results of fire damage of the enemy. 
Subunits assault in dismounted formation if an assault in 
fighting vehicles is impossible or inadvisable because of 
situation conditions (terrain difficult of access, insufficient 
degree of damage of enemy AT weapons). 
  Subunits which are breaking through the perimeter of 
envelopment advance swiftly without allowing an enemy who has 
been neutralized by fire to restore combat effectiveness. 
Artillery and weapons assigned for direct fire neutralize and 
destroy enemy targets which have come alive or have been newly 
detected. 
  Subunits assigned for covering flanks (screens) consolidate 
at favorable lines as the breakthrough develops, in readiness to 
repel enemy assaults against the flank of the breakthrough 
subunits, and form a corridor into which company (battalion) 
subunits immediately begin moving in the previously established 
order. If necessary, screens are reinforced by the reserve. 
Technical support and rear subunits break out of encirclement 
immediately behind subunits making the breakthrough, and 
transportation assets are provided first of all for evacuating 
the wounded and sick. Weapons, vehicles, missiles, ammunition, 
fuel and other supplies which cannot be evacuated are destroyed 
only by order of the company (battalion) commander. 
  During the breakthrough, covering-force subunits hold 
occupied positions, not allowing a narrowing of the perimeter of 
envelopment, and withdraw only by order of the company 
(battalion) commander. The withdrawal is made from line to line 
under cover of fire of all kinds of weapons, aerosols (smoke), 
obstacles and screens, which withdraw only after withdrawal of 
covering-force subunits. If the distance of subunits attacking 
from the outer perimeter is significant, the withdrawal of 
covering-force subunits can begin only after breakthrough of the 
perimeter of envelopment. 
  With a short distance to troops operating from the outer 
perimeter of envelopment, covering-force subunits withdraw after 
the company (battalion) links up with friendly troops. 
  After the breakthrough the company (battalion) continues 
nonstop movement for linkup with friendly troops, using a 
portion of the forces to hold the breach which has formed until 
all subunits break out of the noose of encirclement. 
  Artillery concentrates efforts on destroying enemy weapons 
on 
flanks of the corridor, supporting the unhindered advance of 
columns of subunits breaking out of encirclement. Artillery from 
the makeup of breakthrough forces displaces as in offensive 
battle in such a way as to ensure continuous fire support of the 
assaulting subunits. Artillery and other weapons assigned to 
reinforce the covering forces change firing positions in advance 
before motorized rifle and tank subunits begin to withdraw. 
  AT and air defense subunits displace in battle formations of 
the assaulting subunits or immediately behind them at shortened 
distances. 
  During the breakout of encirclement the company (battalion) 
commander organizes march security using screens which have 
performed their mission, and conducts continuous reconnaissance. 
  Special subunits are assigned to preempt the enemy in 
capturing favorable lines, defiles, and crossings over water 
obstacles. These same subunits are first to move to the 
established linkup point with troops attacking from the outer 
perimeter. 
  When there is a threat of the enemy closing the breach and 
breaking up the company (battalion) battle formation, some of 
the subunits which have broken out of the noose of encirclement 
return and assault the enemy, restoring the corridor. The 
company (battalion) reserve is used for this same purpose. 
  The company (battalion) commander exercises C[.sup]2[/] of 
subunits during the breakout of encirclement from his COP, 
located in a BMP (BTR, tank), and proceeds with subunits making 
the breakthrough. 
  As a rule, communications are maintained over wire means 
before the beginning of the breakthrough, and subsequently by 
radio. Radio operating data for communicating with troops 
operating from the outer perimeter are communicated to 
commanders of platoons (companies, separate platoons) in case of 
independent operations when communications are lost with the 
company (battalion) commander. 
  The company (battalion) is assigned a new combat mission 
after it breaks out of encirclement (links up with friendly 
troops, takes an area providing favorable conditions for further 
operations). 
<H5>  Chapter VIII - Movement </H5>
<H5>  1. Principles of Movement and the March </H5>
  A company (battalion) always must be ready for movement 
under 
conditions of the threat of enemy use of mass destruction and 
precision weapons and remote minelaying systems and the effect 
of his aviation, airborne assault forces, airmobile and raiding 
and reconnaissance parties, NBC contamination, and destructive 
damage of roads and crossings. 
  A company (battalion) may move under its own power (by 
march), be transported by rail or sea (river) transportation, or 
move by a combination method. In addition, an MRC (MRB) may be 
carried by air transport and a TC (TB) on trucktrailer rigs. 
  A march is the organized movement of subunits in 
columns along roads and cross-country routes for moving to a 
designated area or an indicated line. It is the basic method of 
company (battalion) movement. 
  Depending on the company (battalion) mission and its 
distance 
from the enemy, a march may be made in anticipation of 
engagement with the enemy or without the threat of a 
clash with him, and in terms of direction of movement it 
may be made toward or along the front or from front to rear. 
  In all cases a march must be made covertly, as a rule at 
night or under other conditions of limited visibility, and also 
during the day in a combat situation and in the deep rear of 
friendly troops. Under all situation conditions subunits must 
arrive in the designated area or at the indicated line promptly, 
at full strength and ready to perform the combat mission. 
  The company (battalion) marches as one column. The distance 
between vehicles and subunits in a column may be 25-50 m. 
Distances are increased when moving under conditions of limited 
visibility, along dusty roads, with ground surface icing, on 
steep upgrades, downgrades and turns, and at increased speed. 
Distances between combat vehicles may be 100-150 m when moving 
on open terrain when there is a threat of enemy use of precision 
weapons. 
  March capabilities of subunits and units are 
understood to mean the capability of covering the maximum 
possible distance under one's own power in one or more days with 
retention of combat effectiveness and full readiness to perform 
the assigned mission. Basic indicators of company (battalion) 
march capabilities are average rate of movement and amount of a 
day's march. Average rate of movement on a march not counting 
time for halts is the determining indicator. 
  The average rate of movement of an MRC or TC (MRB 
or TB) not counting time for halts may be 20-25 km/hr. It may be 
reduced to 15-20 km/hr when making a march in the mountains, 
deserts, northern areas, on marshy woodland, in the season of 
bad roads, in fog and under other unfavorable conditions. In all 
cases the march must be made at the maximum speed possible for 
given conditions. 
  In calculating the march the company (battalion) commander 
also determines rate of movement when forming up and 
concentrating the column. Experience shows that it is taken to 
be from 0.5 to 0.75 of the average rate of movement of a column 
on the march, i.e., approximately 10-12 km/hr. 
  The amount of a day's march is affected not only 
by average rate of movement, but also by the overall time of 
column movement in a 24 hour period. The experience of the Great 
Patriotic War and postwar exercises has established that drivers 
retain high working capacity during 10-12 hours of movement in a 
24 hour period. The amount of a day's march is determined with 
consideration of the established average rate of movement of 20- 
25 km/hr as well as the time of movement proper. 
  March capabilities of a company (battalion) in terms of fuel 
are determined from a calculation of the consumption only of its 
authorized unit reserves. They are figured by the ratio of the 
fuel reserve in vehicle tanks (less the minimum level of 
supply-- 0.2 of a fueling) to fuel consumption per kilometer of 
route and depend on fuel tank capacity (the fueling), fuel 
consumption per kilometer of route when moving in a column, and 
presence of unit- level supplies in the subunit. 
  On the march a company may operate in a forward, flank, or 
rear security element or march as part of a battalion column. A 
battalion may march as part of the regimental main body and also 
may operate in a forward detachment or advance guard. 
  The mission of a company (battalion) marching as part of the 
battalion (regimental) main body is to arrive on time in the 
designated area or at an indicated line in readiness to conduct 
battle. 
  A company operating in march security must support the 
unhindered movement of the main body, prevent penetration of 
enemy ground reconnaissance to it, preclude an enemy surprise 
attack and provide the protected column with favorable 
conditions for deploying and engaging. 
  The march formation of a company (battalion) on the march is 
a column. When a company operates in march security and a 
battalion operates in a forward detachment or advance guard, 
their march formation consists of a main body column and 
security elements. The march formation for a march in 
anticipation of engagement is formed based on the concept of 
upcoming battle and situation conditions; without the threat of 
an encounter with the enemy it is formed with consideration of 
convenience of movement and protection against enemy mass 
destruction and precision weapons and his technical 
reconnaissance assets. The more advisable place of organic and 
attached subunits of combat arms and special troops in the 
company (battalion) main body column is shown in Figs. 8 and 9. 

<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-10L-135A>      Fig. 8. Alignment variations of company march formation for operating in forward security </FIG>



<FIG ID=JPRS-UMA-10L-136A>      Fig. 9. Alignment variations of march formation of battalion in forward detachment: </FIG>


  a. Reinforced TB 
  b. Reinforced MRB&lt;/graphic&gt; 

  In anticipation of engagement a reconnaissance patrol is 
sent 
out from a battalion operating in a forward detachment, advance 
guard, or at the head of the regimental main body column. If the 
reconnaissance platoon is not sent out on patrol, it marches at 
the head of the battalion main body column, as a rule behind the 
COP. 
  A battalion intended for operations in a forward detachment 
or advance guard sends out a forward security element for column 
security made up of a reinforced platoon or a company to a 
distance of 5-10 km in the direction of movement, and if 
necessary sends a flank security element (rear security element) 
or patrol squads (tanks) toward the flanks and to the rear. A 
company operating in a forward security element sends out a 
point consisting of a platoon to a distance of 3-5 km in the 
direction of movement, and a forward security element up to a 
platoon in strength sends out a patrol squad (tank) to a 
distance ensuring observation of it and its support by fire. The 
distance away of march security depends on its makeup and the 
mission received and should enable conducting battle with the 
enemy independently until the approach of the main body. 
  The depth of the company (battalion) march formation is 
figured from the head of the march security to and including the 
trail vehicle (technical maintenance echelon). To calculate it, 
multiply the number of vehicles in the column (less one) by the 
prescribed distance between them, adding the distance of march 
security and the cumulative length of all vehicles in the column. 
  For the timely, organized beginning and end of the march, a 
battalion assigned to an advance guard and a company assigned to 
a forward security element is given a start point [iskhodnyy 
punkt] and control points [punkt regulirovaniya] and times of 
crossing them, and places and time of short halts and the day's 
(night's) rest halt (Diagram 21). The distance of the start 
point should ensure forming up the company (battalion) column 
from the disposition area and may be 5-10 km. 
  Short halts and the day (night) rest halt are designated for 
checking the condition of weapons and vehicles, for servicing 
and maintaining them, and for the personnel's meals and rest. 
The following are designated: short halts lasting up to one hour 
every 3-4 hours of movement, one lasting up to two hours in the 
second half of a day's march, and a day (night) rest halt at the 
end of each day's march. 
  Combat, technical and logistic support are of decisive 
importance in the company's (battalion's) successful performance 
of the mission on the march. 
  Reconnaissance is conducted on the march for timely 
collection of necessary intelligence on the enemy and terrain. 
The battalion commander sends out a reconnaissance patrol in 
anticipation of an encounter with the enemy. The company 
(battalion) commander receives data on the enemy and terrain 
from march security entities and also from the senior commander 
(chief) and reconnaissance entities. 
  Protection against mass destruction weapons is achieved by 
strict observance of prescribed distances; by preventing an 
accumulation of subunits ahead of the start point, at short 
halts and forced stops, when negotiating chokepoints, water 
obstacles and passes, and in rest areas; by skillful use of 
protective properties of combat vehicles, transport, the terrain 
and individual protective gear; and by engineer preparation of 
rest and concentration areas. 
  Concealment of the movement and concentration of company 
(battalion) subunits are goals of maskirovka on the march. This 
is achieved above all by choice of the movement route, short 
halts, and day (night) rest halt areas, with maximum advantage 
taken of the terrain's concealing properties and also by 
subunits' observance of camouflage discipline. 
  Engineer support must create conditions ensuring unhindered 
movement of the company (battalion) along the route at the 
prescribed speed and its timely arrival in the designated area 
or at the indicated line. It includes engineer reconnaissance; 
performance of engineer work on the route, in halt (rest) areas 
and in the concentration area; and accomplishment of maskirovka 
measures. 
  A forward security element at company strength usually is 
reinforced by a combat engineer squad, and an advance guard 
(forward detachment) by up to a combat engineer platoon with 
engineer assets (route clearance vehicles, bridgelayers and so 
on). In this case, the company commander usually assigns up to a 
combat engineer squad to the point to perform engineer 
reconnaissance and the battalion commander in addition assigns 
2- 3 combat engineers to the reconnaissance patrol. 
  Chemical warfare support on the march provides for 
conducting 
NBC reconnaissance of the movement route and adjoining terrain, 
at short halt sites, and in day (night) rest halt areas; 
accomplishing radiological monitoring of personnel exposure and 
contamination of equipment by radioactive substances, and 
chemical warfare monitoring of their contamination by chemical 
agents after enemy use of mass destruction weapons; performing 
decontamination of subunits and providing them with means of 
protection when preparing for the march. Chemical warfare 
support is accomplished by a specially trained squad (crew, 
team) in each company (battery), equipped with radiological and 
chemical reconnaissance devices. In some cases the radiological 
and chemical reconnaissance squad attached to the battalion may 
be included in the reconnaissance patrol or forward security 
element. 
  Technical and logistic support basically is achieved by the 
presence of the company (battalion) technical maintenance 
echelon, by making a visual inspection of weapons and vehicles 
at halts, by performing daily routine servicing and maintenance 
in the concentration area, and by organizing meals for personnel 
and medical aid for them if necessary. 
  Before the march the company (battalion) commander is 
obligated to take steps for timely replenishment of ammunition, 
fuel, food, medical equipment and supplies, and other supplies 
to prescribed norms. 
<H5>  2. Organization and Execution of the March </H5>
  Organization of the march. Successful performance 
of the mission on the march depends largely on skilled 
organization, which begins with the company (battalion) 
commander receiving the operation order or operational 
instructions. The procedure and content of his work are 
determined by the mission received, time available and the 
specific situation. In all cases the company (battalion) 
commander must analyze the mission, determine measures which 
must be taken immediately for most rapid preparation for the 
march, perform a time calculation, issue instructions to 
commanders of subordinate and attached subunits on preparing for 
the march, estimate the situation, make the decision, issue the 
operation order, organize coordination, and give instructions on 
organizing comprehensive support of the march, on C[.sup]2[/] 
and on political work. Then he directs immediate preparation of 
subunits for the march. 
  In analyzing the mission the following are studied 
from a map in addition to the usual questions: movement route, 
its length and passability, conditions for executing the march, 
lines and time of likely encounter with the enemy or for what 
actions to be ready, places and time of short halts, and also 
places, time and procedure for vehicle refueling, personnel 
messing, and replenishment of reserves of supplies consumed 
during the march. 
  Based on the mission analysis the company (battalion) 
commander determines the measures for preparing subunits for the 
march and performs a time calculation. The following 
may be such measures: familiarization of deputies and platoon 
(company) commanders with the combat mission received; issuing 
necessary instructions on preparing for the march and organizing 
reconnaissance; preparing subunits assigned to march security; 
replenishing reserves of ammunition, fuel and other supplies to 
prescribed norms; servicing and maintaining weapons and 
vehicles; evacuating the wounded and sick; and turning over 
unserviceable equipment which cannot be repaired by the 
beginning of the march. 
  The time the mission is received and the time of crossing 
the 
start point are the initial data for calculating the time for 
organizing the march. The overall time for organizing the march 
is determined based on these data and is allotted to the 
principal measures. Account is taken of the time for extending 
the company (battalion) column up to the start point. 
  Having calculated the time, with respect to questions of 
preparing for the march the commander indicates information on 
the enemy, actions for which the company (battalion) must be 
ready, procedure for preparing personnel, weapons and vehicles 
for the march and the time and place of arrival of means of 
reinforcement (if assigned). 
  In the situation estimate the company (battalion) 
commander studies march capabilities of organic and attached 
subunits; determines permissible rates of movement by route 
sectors and the distance between vehicles for purposes of 
protection against precision weapons and figures movement time 
along each sector; estimates the nature of terrain and 
conditions for protection and maskirovka in short halt and day 
(night) rest halt areas and the concentration area; determines 
the extent of their engineer preparation; performs other 
necessary calculations; and determines the procedure for 
observation and maintaining communications during the march. 
  In the course of estimating the situation the company 
(battalion) commander performs a march calculation. It consists 
of determining the length of the route, overall time for 
executing the march, average rate of movement and rate of 
movement in individual route sectors, time for crossing the 
start point and control points and time of arrival of march 
security entities in the designated area or at the indicated 
line, and places, time and duration of short halts for march 
security entities as well as for the main body column, if they 
were not indicated for the latter by the battalion (regimental) 
commander. 
  Based on analysis of the mission received, conclusions from 
the situation estimate and the march calculation, the company 
(battalion) commander makes his decision and formalizes it on 
the map. In the concept for the march the company 
(battalion) commander specifies the following: alignment of the 
march formation; makeup, missions and distance away of the march 
security; rate of movement along route sectors and distances 
between vehicles; procedure for repelling enemy air strikes; in 
addition, in anticipation of engagement with the enemy, the 
procedure for actions of the point (forward security element), 
patrol squads (tanks) and main body, alignment of the battle 
formation and form of maneuver. 
  In formalizing the decision the following are reflected 
on the map: situation of the enemy and troops operating in 
front; disposition area of the company (battalion) and its 
subunits; movement route broken down into sectors of 5-10 km 
each; start point, control points and time of crossing them by 
the column head of the point (forward security element) and main 
body; movement routes of flank security elements; locations of 
traffic control posts and commandant's posts; places, time and 
duration of short halts for the main body column and march 
security; area or line which subunits must reach after executing 
the march; probable company (battalion) deployment lines for 
battle in an encounter with the enemy and possible procedure for 
operations there by the point (forward security element) and 
main body column; movement routes of adjacent subunits and their 
missions. The following are plotted on the map in addition: 
march formation diagram indicating the distribution of forces 
and assets along the column, depth of the main body column and 
distance away of march security; route sectors in terms of 
movement conditions, and their size and rates of movement in 
each of them; overall time for the march, time for extending the 
column to the start point, and time for short halts and for 
movement; average rate of movement; and control signals. The 
combat mission is communicated to subordinates by operation 
order. 
  In the operation order for the march the company 
(battalion) commander indicates the following: 
  First paragraph--information on the enemy. 
  Second paragraph--missions of adjacent subunits. 
  Third paragraph--company (battalion) mission; 
movement route (direction of battalion operations in forward 
detachment); place of battalion (regiment) in march formation; 
concentration (rest) area or line; time of arrival at (movement 
to) designated area or indicated line and for what actions to be 
ready; start point, control points and time of crossing them; 
places and time of short halts; concept of the march. 
  Fourth paragraph--after the words "I 
order"--missions for subunits: 

  -  point (forward security element) and patrol squads 
(tanks)- -makeup, combat mission, time for crossing start point 
and control points and situation report procedure; 
  -  motorized rifle and tank platoons (companies)--means of 
reinforcement, mission, place in march column, procedure for 
commencing and conducting fire against airborne targets, and 
procedure for operations when making the march in anticipation 
of engagement with the enemy; 
  -  artillery subunits and other weapons--missions for the march 
and when engaging the enemy, place in march column and in 
formation; 
  -  air defense subunit--missions for covering-force subunits in 
movement, at short halts, in rest areas and in concentration 
area, place in march column, duty weapons (subunits) and their 
firing (launch) positions, time and degree of readiness; 
  -  other company (battalion) subunits and reinforcing subunits-- 
place in march column and missions which they must be ready to 
perform. 


    Fifth paragraph--places and procedure for 
refueling vehicles in the course of the march and, in 
anticipation of engagement in addition, ammunition and fuel 
consumption for mission performance. 
  Sixth paragraph--readiness time for the march. 
  Seventh paragraph--procedure for observation and 
communications in the course of the march, place of the company 
(battalion) commander's COP in the column, and deputies. 
  Having issued the operation order, he organizes 
coordination. Coordination instructions must reflect the 
following matters: procedure for extending the company 
(battalion) column and crossing the start point; procedure for 
movement, for observing march discipline and negotiating 
obstacles and destructive damage on the route; procedure for 
operations in an enemy air raid, when the enemy employs raiding 
and reconnaissance parties, airborne assault forces and 
airmobile subunits, and in an encounter with the enemy by the 
point (forward security element) and main body; warning, control 
and coordination signals and signals for recognition of friendly 
aircraft and helicopters, as well as methods for marking one's 
position in the course of the march and when conducting battle. 
  After organizing coordination the company (battalion) 
commander issues instructions on comprehensive support. He 
specifies the following in addition to the usual matters: 
procedure for negotiating obstacles, including those laid by the 
remote method, and areas of destructive damage on the route; 
extent of and procedure for engineer preparation of the day 
(night) rest halt (concentration) area; measures for protection 
against precision and incendiary weapons; procedure for using 
night vision (illumination) devices and for maskirovka, and also 
safety measures and procedures for maintaining march discipline. 
  Before the beginning of the march the company (battalion) 
commander organizes preparation of the subunits. At the 
prescribed time he reports readiness for the march to the 
battalion (regimental) commander. 
  Execution of the march. By the beginning of 
movement, at the commander's signal company (battalion) subunits 
and means of reinforcement take their places in the march 
formation in accordance with the issued order. The forward 
security element is first to move out. It advances at a rate so 
as to cross the start point at the prescribed time. Then comes 
the main body, the head of whose column crosses exactly at the 
designated time. The company (battalion) commander proceeds at 
the head of this column, compares the movement route with the 
map, maintains the prescribed march order and controls 
operations of march security. 
  Movement is made only on the right side of the road with 
observance of the prescribed rate of movement, distances between 
vehicles and safety measures. The company (battalion) column 
passes through chokepoints and tunnels and over bridges nonstop 
at maximum possible speed. 
  Radar dead ground formed by terrain folds and local 
features; 
built-up areas; and roadside vegetation are used for protection 
against enemy precision weapons. When moving along open, 
unconcealed route sectors, vehicles are not permitted to bunch 
up or columns to halt, and rate of movement and distances 
between vehicles are increased. 
  Vehicles move at night using night vision or blackout 
devices, and movement is made with external illumination devices 
completely off in sectors where terrain is viewed by the enemy 
and on a bright night. 
  Enemy air strikes on the march are repelled by fire in 
movement or from short halts by forces of air defense subunits 
and by fire of weapons of motorized rifle (tank) subunits 
assigned for this. Hatches of BMP's, BTR's and tanks, except 
those from which fire will be conducted, are closed. Subunit 
personnel shift protective masks to the ready position. 
  The company (battalion) continues movement in response to 
signals warning of NBC contamination. Before crossing a zone of 
contamination the hatches, doors, firing ports and louvers in 
BMP's, BTR's and tanks are closed and the system of protection 
against mass destruction weapons is turned on. When it is 
impossible to bypass zones with high radiation levels and areas 
of destructive damage, fires and floods, the company (battalion) 
crosses them at maximum speed using individual protective gear 
and systems of protection against mass destruction weapons 
present in the fighting vehicles. 
  Partial decontamination is performed after emerging from 
zones of radioactive contamination, and immediately when the 
enemy employs chemical agents. Complete decontamination is 
performed as a rule in the day (night) rest halt area or on 
arriving in the designated area. 
  In case the enemy delivers nuclear and chemical strikes 
against the column, the company (battalion) commander takes 
steps to restore combat effectiveness, mop up in the aftermath 
of the strikes and continue movement. 
  The hatches, firing ports and louvers of tanks, BMP's and 
BTR's are closed when the enemy employs incendiary weapons and 
also when forced to cross an area of fire. The company 
(battalion) commander quickly leads the column forward or toward 
the windward side out of the area of the fire, halts it by 
permission of the battalion (regimental) commander and organizes 
the extinguishing of centers of fire on combat and other 
vehicles, rescue of personnel, and first aid to victims. Then 
the column continues movement. 
  In the course of executing a march, raiding and 
reconnaissance parties are destroyed by march security and by 
subunits of the main body especially assigned for this purpose. 
Enemy tactical airborne assault forces or airmobile parties are 
destroyed by march security subunits or by the main body of a 
battalion operating in the advance guard or in a forward 
detachment. 
  Minefields laid by enemy remote minelaying systems are 
bypassed, and if impossible to bypass are crossed through 
passages made by attached engineer subunits, mineclearing teams 
of companies and the battalion obstacle clearing party. 
  Column alignment is not disrupted at short halts and 
vehicles 
stop on the right shoulder of the road no closer than 10 m from 
each other or at distances established by the commander. BMP's, 
BTR's and tanks are placed beneath crowns of trees and in the 
radar shadow of local features, and on open terrain are 
camouflaged by organic camouflage nets and local materials. 
  Observers, duty machinegunners (gunners) and radiotelephone 
operators (radio operator/loaders) of command vehicles remain in 
the vehicles. The duty air defense subunit takes up a firing 
(launch) position indicated by the commander in readiness to 
destroy enemy air targets. At their commanders' command, the 
remaining personnel exit the vehicles and dispose themselves to 
the right of the road. Vehicle crews (teams, drivers) perform a 
visual inspection of weapons and vehicles and perform servicing 
and maintenance together with personnel assigned to assist them. 
  Vehicles which became disabled during the march stop on the 
right shoulder of the road or are moved aside. Vehicle crews 
(drivers) determine the reasons for the malfunctions and take 
steps to remedy them. After malfunctions have been remedied the 
vehicles continue movement, joining a passing column, and take 
their places in their own subunit columns at short halts. 
  The battalion technical maintenance echelon assists crews 
(drivers) in remedying malfunctions, arranges for transfer of 
vehicles not subject to repair with their own resources and 
stuck vehicles to regimental recovery vehicle assets, and 
supports the arrival of remaining battalion vehicles in the 
designated area. The deputy company (battalion) commander for 
weapons (company senior technician) and subunit commanders 
personally report vehicles left en route to the company 
(battalion) commander. 
  Communications on the march is accomplished by mobile means, 
and in subunits in addition by prearranged signals. Radio 
equipment operates only on receive. During the march the 
battalion commander reports the number of his column and 
information on the status of the route sector that was covered 
and the situation on it via commandant's posts and dispatcher 
points, and receives instructions and orders which have arrived 
for him and information on the status of the next route sector 
and about detours from the senior member of the commandant's 
post (duty dispatcher). 
  A battalion is disposed by company in a day (night) rest 
halt 
area, dispersed with consideration for rapidly extending the 
march column. Companies are in columns along the route of 
forward movement. 
  Crews perform daily routine servicing and maintenance on 
vehicles, arrange for their refueling and remedy malfunctions 
which have been discovered under the direction of subunit 
commanders and their deputies for weapons (senior company 
technicians). The personnel are given a hot meal and a rest. 
  On receiving a new mission in the course of the march, the 
battalion commander halts the forward security element and 
indicates the procedure for further operations to it. The 
battalion is moved onto the new route by the shortest path in 
the previous march column or after a necessary change in 
formation and performs the assigned mission. 
  On encountering the enemy, the forward security element 
inflicts damage on his security. Employing decisive actions, the 
battalion main body immobilizes the enemy by battle, inflicts 
damage, and supports deployment and engagement of the regiment 
by stubbornly holding a favorable line. 
<H5>  3. March Under Special Conditions </H5>
  Preparation and execution of a march under special 
conditions 
are accomplished according to general rules, but with 
consideration of conditions typical of mountainous and desert 
terrain and the winter. 
  In decisionmaking for a march in the mountains, 
special attention is given to studying route sectors difficult 
to negotiate, determining the procedure for negotiating them and 
organizing traffic control in them. Measures are planned for 
covering flanks and rear and destroying enemy enveloping 
detachments, airborne assault forces and raiding and 
reconnaissance parties. Measures are envisaged which facilitate 
orientation and maintaining a direction of movement along routes 
at night and under other conditions of limited visibility. 
  Serviceability of vehicle running gear and steering gear is 
checked during routine servicing and maintenance of weapons and 
vehicles. For movement in high-mountain areas, personnel are 
provided with warm clothing, heating devices and sunglasses and 
vehicles are equipped with devices to increase offroad 
capability and special devices to keep them from rolling during 
stops on upgrades and downgrades. Each vehicle and the battalion 
technical maintenance echelon must have a reserve of coolant and 
distilled water. 
  As a rule, a motorized rifle subunit is assigned to march 
security. It operates at a lesser distance than under ordinary 
conditions. A security element up to a platoon in strength is 
assigned to guard the battalion column from the rear. Local 
security usually is sent out and observers are posted when 
moving along route sectors affording concealment, in places of 
possible landslides, rockfalls and talus, and in sectors where 
enemy emplacement of obstacles is possible. After the company 
(battalion) column passes, they continue moving behind it and 
join their own subunits at the next short halt. 
  Passes, gorges, mountain gaps, canyons and tunnels are 
crossed by subunits nonstop; if it is impossible to cross them 
from the move, subunits halt in a sheltered place without 
bunching up, camouflage themselves and prepare to make the 
passage in turn while preserving heightened vigilance. Personnel 
of motorized rifle subunits may dismount when crossing 
especially dangerous road sectors. 
  The battalion commander may halt the battalion column by 
authorization of the regimental commander to cool vehicle 
engines. Level roads sectors safe from rockfalls and avalanches 
are chosen for this. 
  In connection with a reduced range of radio operation in the 
mountains, it is necessary to provide for using march security 
radio equipment as an intermediate station to maintain 
communications with the reconnaissance patrol. 
  In making the decision for the march in the 
desert, the company (battalion) commander studies the 
movement route and trafficability conditions in its individual 
sectors in detail and clarifies the location of oases, hydraulic 
engineering works, water sources and fuel reserves. The azimuth 
of the direction of movement is calculated and the procedure is 
outlined for marking the route in sectors where orientation 
based on local features is hampered. The most likely avenues of 
enemy operations, lines of possible encounter with him, and 
measures to secure flanks and rear of the moving column are 
determined. Wide use of close and deep envelopments of exposed 
enemy flanks and operations along axes leading to vital enemy 
objectives are envisaged at lines of possible encounter with the 
enemy. 
  Before a march special attention is given to thorough 
preparation of weapons and vehicles for moving under conditions 
of high temperatures, no roads and sandy terrain, provision of 
additional containers, canteens and the necessary reserve of 
water and fuel to subunits, and measures for protecting 
personnel against heat stroke. 
  Distances between vehicles are increased to 100-150 m to 
ensure traffic safety during a march in a head wind and heavy 
dust content of the air. Under conditions of heavy dust 
formation, tanks move behind wheeled vehicles or to the leeward 
side of the movement route. The route axis is constantly shifted 
as soil on the movement route is destroyed. Movement may be 
stopped during sandstorms by permission of the battalion 
(regimental) commander. Steps are taken to protect personnel and 
vehicles, and observation and column security are beefed up. 
Movement is renewed by order of the commander who stopped the 
column. 
  In making a decision for a march in winter the 
company (battalion) commander thoroughly estimates the nature of 
terrain for the full depth of the march, clarifies route sectors 
difficult to negotiate and outlines the procedure for bypassing 
or negotiating them and places to prepare turnoffs from the road 
and detours of natural barriers. Measures are specified for 
supporting the movement of subunits in a snowstorm, blizzard, 
dense fog, bitter cold, deep snow cover and thaw. 
  Before the march weapons and vehicles are prepared for 
operation under lowtemperature conditions and steps are taken to 
prevent personnel frostbite and to supply vehicles with devices 
to improve their off-road capability. Additional reserves of 
ammunition, fuel and food are established. Vehicles equipped 
with bulldozer attachments are included in the march security if 
a march is being made under conditions of deep snow cover. 
  Movement may be suspended by permission of the battalion 
(regimental) commander in a heavy snowstorm, a blizzard and snow 
flurries. Under these conditions the company (battalion) 
commander brings up the remaining vehicles, arranges perimeter 
security, beefs up observation, and takes steps to warm the 
personnel. 
  Under all the most difficult situation conditions, the 
success of a march depends largely on skills and ability of the 
company (battalion) commander and the battalion staff to ready 
subunits for the march and control them during its execution. 
<H5>  4. Company Commander's Work To Organize the March and March </H5>
Security 
  [Begin side line] Organization and execution of the march of 
a company in march security have features stemming from the 
specifics of missions which it is performing: ensure unhindered 
movement of the protected column, preclude an enemy surprise 
attack and penetration of his ground reconnaissance, and create 
favorable conditions for engagement of the main body. 
  On receiving the mission the company commander analyzes it, 
determines measures for preparing the company to perform the 
mission and performs a time calculation. [End side line] 
  Mission analysis 
  1st MRC (TC), the forward security element, marches along 
the 
route Gorki, Nagornoye, Nikulino, Lipki, Gerasimovo and by 0600 
hours 23 August arrives at the line Tomino, north slopes of 
Kruglaya Hill with the mission of providing favorable conditions 
for battalion deployment and engagement. Length of route is 170 
km. 
  The company marches basically at night in anticipation of 
engaging the enemy. 
  In an encounter with the enemy the company has the mission 
of 
inflicting damage on his security elements, immobilizing the 
main body from the front and supporting deployment and 
commitment of the advance guard. 
  To perform the combat mission the company is reinforced by 
an 
artillery battery, TP (MRP), combat engineer squad and 
radiological and chemical reconnaissance squad. Reinforcing 
subunits will arrive in the vicinity of the forester's house by 
1000 22 August. 
  The company crosses the start point at 2000 22 August, 
control point No 1 at 2350 22 August, and control point No 2 at 
0440 hours 23 August. 
  Short halts: first from 2300 to 2340 22 August; second from 
0230 to 0430 23 August. 
  There are no subunits on the right. 1st/5th MRR is marching 
on the left with the mission of taking the line of west 
outskirts of Astakhovo, Tomino (excluded) by 0600 23 August. 
  The regimental reconnaissance detachment is conducting 
reconnaissance ahead along the company's movement route. 
  Time calculation 
  The mission for the march was received at 0900 hours 22 
August. Readiness for the march is at 1900 22 August. Cross 
start point at 2000 22 August. The company has 10 hours to 
prepare for the march. Allocate time as follows: 

  -  familiarization of subordinates with the mission received 
and issue of instructions for preparing for the march--30 
minutes (from 0930 to 1000); 
  -  situation estimate and march 
calculation--40 minutes (from 1000 to 1040); 
  -  decisionmaking and 
report to battalion commander--60 minutes (from 1040 to 1140); 
  -  issue operation order, organize coordination and 
C[.sup]2[/]- -20 minutes (from 1140 to 1200); 
  -  issue 
instructions on supporting the march and on political work--30 
minutes (from 1200 to 1230); 
  -  monitor and assist subunits in 
preparing for the march--390 minutes (from 1230 to 1900); 
  -  report readiness for march to battalion commander--1900. 


    [Begin side line] After calculating the time, the company 
commander issues instructions to subordinates for preparing for 
the march and estimates the situation. [End side line] 
  Instructions on preparing for the march 
  Organize fueling of vehicles in the following order: 1st MRP 
(TP), 2nd MRP (TP), 3rd MRP (TP). Refueling assets will arrive 
in the company disposition by 1000. 
  Replenish and load ammunition in the following sequence: 1st 
MRP (TP), 2nd MRP (TP), 3rd MRP (TP). Ammunition transport will 
arrive by 1200. 
  Check presence and stowage of protective and decontamination 
gear, clothing and related gear, and medical equipment and 
supplies and bring up to norm by 1330. 
  Check serviceability of weapons and combat vehicles and 
complete vehicle servicing and maintenance to the extent of 
daily routine servicing and maintenance by 1500 hours. 
  Hot meals will be brought to the company disposition by 
1630. 
Bring emergency rations up to norm. They will be delivered to 
company with delivery of hot meals. 
  Platoon commanders are to submit working maps with decision 
for the march by 1800. 
  Report readiness for the march at 1850. 
  Situation estimate (conclusions) 
  Align march formation with consideration for conducting 
meeting battle: point, COP, TP (MRP), 1st MRP (TP), 3rd MRP 
(TP), SP artillery battery. Execute march with measures of 
protection against mass destruction and precision weapons. 
  Have the following march security: point consisting of MRP 
(TP) and reinforced combat engineer squad. 
  On arriving at Nagornoye, send out patrol squad (patrol 
tank) 
in direction of Nagornoye, Nikulino, Lipki, Gerasimovo. 
  During the march receive data on the enemy from the senior 
commander, the point and by observation. During the march 
maintain communications with regimental reconnaissance 
detachment No 1. On approaching a line of likely encounter with 
the enemy establish communications with adjacent subunits for 
maintaining coordination during the conduct of battle. On 
discovering a zone of contamination, assign march security to 
reconnoiter a detour route. 
  Condition of the route permits moving in the Gorki, Nikulino 
sector at a speed of 25 km/hr, and in the Nikulino, Lipki sector 
at 20 km/hr. The march to Lipki is made in hours of darkness. 
  Favorable lines for deployment and assault of the enemy are 
the north edge of the grove (700 m north of Gerasimovo) and 
north slopes of Kruglaya Hill. Deploy company at these lines 
from behind the right (left) flank of the point. Bypass 
demolished (contaminated) route sectors in a column, and if it 
is necessary to cross them increase the rate of movement and 
distances between vehicles. 
  Then the company commander makes the decision, formalizes it 
on the map and reports to the battalion commander. After this he 
summons commanders of subordinate and attached subunits, issues 
the operation order, organizes coordination and gives 
instructions for organizing comprehensive support of the march, 
C[.sup]2[/] and political work. 
  Operation order 
  1. Having suffered defeat, the enemy is withdrawing to the 
west and at the same time moving up reserves from the depth. An 
encounter with his forward detachments is possible when moving 
toward Lipki. 
  2. Our units in front are holding the line along the 
Lazurnaya River. The regimental reconnaissance 
detachment is operating on the movement axis. On the left 2nd 
MRC (TC)--the forward security element of 1st MRB (TB), 5th MRR 
(TR)--is marching along the route Ilino, Dvorovoye, 
Tuzhilovo, Bugry and by 0600 23 August takes the line of 
the west outskirts of Astakhovo, Tomino (excluded). 
  3. 1st MRC (TC), an SP artillery battery, a TP (MRP), a 
combat engineer squad and a radiological and chemical 
reconnaissance squad are the forward security element. It 
marches along the route Gorki, Nagornoye, Nikulino, Lipki, 
Gerasimovo with the mission of supporting unhindered 
movement of the advance guard main body and by 0600 23 August 
taking the line Tomino, north slopes of 
Kruglaya Hill, supporting deployment and engagement 
of the battalion main body. It crosses the following points: 
start, 3 km south of Gorki, at 2000 hours; control 
point No 1, 1.5 km west of Nikulino, at 2350; control 
point No 2, 1 km north of Lipki, at 0440 hours. 
  Short halts: first, 2 km south of Nikulino--from 
2300 to 2340; second, 1 km south of Lipki--from 0230 
to 0430 23 August. 
  Form company main body column in following order: COP, TP 
(MRP), 1st MRP (TP), 3rd MRP (TP), SP artillery battery. 
  Have point consisting of 2nd MRP (TP) with combat engineer 
squad 3 km ahead along the movement route to support unhindered 
movement of forward security element main body. 
  Rate of movement: in Gorki, Nikulino sector--25 
km/hr, in Nikulino, Lipki sector--20 km/hr; distances 
between vehicles 25-50 m. 
  Commence fire against air enemy at my command and at 
commands 
of subunit commanders. If the point encounters the ground enemy, 
seize a favorable line, defeat enemy security in a meeting 
battle and support battalion deployment and engagement by a 
determined assault of the forward security element main body 
from behind the point's right flank. 
  4. I order: 

  -  2nd MRP (TP) with combat engineer squad, the point, is to 
march along the forward security element's route, prevent an 
enemy surprise attack and by 0550 23 August take the line 
Tomino, Gerasimovo (excluded), ensuring favorable 
conditions for deployment and engagement of the forward security 
element main body. Cross the points: start at 1950, control 
point No 1 at 2350, control point No 2 at 0440. Report passing 
of each line, condition of route and situation by prearranged 
signals, and immediately on encountering the enemy; 
  -  TP (MRP) is 
to march at head of company column and arrive on north slopes of 
Kruglaya Hill by 0600 23 August, having supported 
performance of company mission. Subsequently be ready to attack. 
On encountering the enemy assault him from behind the point's 
right (left) flank. On arriving at Nagornoye send out 
patrol tank (patrol squad) in the direction Nagornoye, 
Nikulino, Lipki; 
  -  1st MRP (TP) is to march behind TP (MRP) and arrive on west 
slopes of Kruglaya Hill by 0600 23 August, having 
supported performance of company mission. Subsequently be ready 
to attack. On encountering enemy, assault him from behind 
point's right (left) flank; 
  -  3rd MRP (TP) is to march behind 1st MRP (TP) and arrive at 
west 
outskirts of Gerasimovo by 0600 23 August, having 
supported performance of company mission. Subsequently be ready 
to attack. On encountering the enemy, assault him, operating on 
the right (left) flank of the company; 
  -  SP artillery battery is to march along company route behind 
3rd 
MRP (TP) and occupy firing positions in vicinity of southwest 
outskirts of Gerasimovo by 0600 23 August. On 
encountering enemy be ready to support battle of point and 
support the deployment and engagement of forward security 
element main body by fire. 


    5. Refuel fighting vehicles at second short halt in 
following 
order: point, TP (MRP), 1st and 3rd MRP's (TP's). Receive hot 
meals on completion of fueling. Ammunition consumption for 
performance of assigned mission is 0.5 unit of fire, and fuel 
consumption is 0.7 fueling. 
  6. Readiness for march 1900 hours. 
  7. Commanders of platoons and squads (crews) are to conduct 
observation during the march up to the line of likely encounter 
with the enemy, and after crossing it all personnel are to do 
so. Communications on the march: with point by radio using brief 
signals, with platoons in main body column by signaling devices, 
and by radio on engaging. 
  I am at the head of the main body column on the march, and 
behind 1st MRP (TP) on encountering the enemy. Deputy is 1st MRP 
(TP) commander. 
  Coordination instructions 
  Extend the company [column] to the start point in accordance 
with the march calculation at my signal. Cross start point as 
follows: point at 1950, main body at 2000. 
  During the march observe prescribed distances and rate of 
movement. Stop disabled vehicles on right shoulder of road and 
observe security and defense measures when remedying 
malfunctions. After restoration, vehicles take their places in 
the march formation only at short halts (stops); have distances 
of at least 10 m between vehicles at short halts. 
  Receive hot meals at the end of fueling. At night, march 
using night vision devices. 
  1st MRP (TP) is to be ready to destroy enemy raiding and 
reconnaissance parties during the march. 
  When the enemy employs nuclear weapons and with detection of 
radioactive (chemical) contamination, turn on the system of 
protection against mass destruction weapons, and personnel are 
to put on individual protective gear and continue performing the 
assigned mission. Bypass zones of contamination and areas of 
destructive damage, fires and floods along axes marked by the 
point; if it is impossible to bypass the zones, cross them in 
the shortest direction with an increase in rate of movement and 
distances between vehicles. Perform partial decontamination and 
extinguish centers of fire on combat vehicles at my command and 
at commands of platoon commanders. 
  In case it encounters the enemy the point is to inflict 
damage on his local security, take a favorable line and support 
deployment and engagement of the company main body. The forward 
security element is to assault the enemy swiftly, destroy him 
and continue movement. On encountering an enemy of superior 
force the forward security element is to assault him decisively 
in the flank, inflict damage on him and take a line providing 
favorable conditions for deployment and engagement of the 
battalion main body. 
  Warning, control and coordination signals are in accordance 
with the signal table. 
  Instructions on combat support of the march 
  Conduct reconnaissance of the air and ground enemy during 
the 
march as follows: in the direction of movement--point; to the 
sides--by observers from 1st and 3rd MRP's (TP's); to the rear 
by an observer from the SP artillery battery. Each squad (crew) 
is to conduct observation of the air enemy. Report immediately 
on encountering the enemy. 
  2nd MRS (crew) of 2nd MRP (TP) is to conduct radiological, 
chemical and nonspecific biological (bacteriological) 
reconnaissance on the march using onboard devices, and observers 
are to do so visually. In response to signals warning of NBC 
contamination, close firing ports and doors, on tanks close 
hatches and louvers, and turn on the system for protection 
against mass destruction weapons. 
  By 1300 check the presence, serviceability, working capacity 
and state of supply of radiological and chemical reconnaissance 
devices and individual protective gear and the airtightness of 
protective masks. Go to the battalion CW instructor to replace 
unserviceable ones. 
  Perform partial decontamination at my command. 
  Carry out radiological monitoring using dosimeters and 
radiological monitoring and survey devices. 
  Observe a regime of radio silence during the march. Turn off 
night vision devices when there is a warning about the threat of 
an enemy air attack and after passing Lipki. Prohibit starting 
bonfires and limit personnel movement at short halts. 
  Breach obstacles, destructive damage and barriers with your 
own forces together with the combat engineer squad using 
bulldozer attachments, built-in equipment and local materials. 
  In the course of the march accomplish security using the 
point, and in the area of short halts using patrols from 3rd MRP 
(TP). Be ready to combat enemy raiding and reconnaissance 
parties. 
  Instructions on technical and logistic support 
  By 1500 perform daily routine servicing and maintenance on 
weapons and vehicles, paying special attention to condition of 
running gear, steering gear and storage batteries. 
  Assemble weapons and vehicles not restored by the time of 
readiness for the march in the battalion rear disposition area 
by 1800 hours for turnover to the regimental maintenance company. 
  Vehicles which become disabled during the march and cannot 
be 
repaired by crew efforts are to await battalion repair assets. 
Organize their security and defense at the points where they 
stop. Continue movement after remedying the malfunction. They 
are to take their place in the company column at a short halt 
(stop). 
  Refuel in the company disposition area by 1100 and at the 
second short halt. 
  By 1300 bring reserves of ammunition and other supplies up 
to 
the norm. Transport with reserves will arrive in company 
disposition area. 
  Complete evacuating wounded and sick to battalion aid 
station 
by 1500. During the march give first aid in the form of self- 
administered and buddyadministered emergency first aid by 
platoon riflemen-medics and by the company medical corpsman 
NCOIC. 
  During the march hot food will be issued at the second short 
halt. 
  Company operations in march security on the 
march 
  The company begins the march by direction of the battalion 
commander. At the prescribed time the point crosses the start 
point and moves along the route at the indicated speed 3-5 km 
from the company main body. Proceeding at the head of the 
column, the company commander compares the movement route with 
the map and maintains the established march order. 
  A company assigned to a flank security element moves on line 
with the head of the protected column and up to 5 km away with 
the mission of preventing an enemy surprise attack from the 
flank. 
  In performing a mission as a stationary flank guard, the 
company moves to the line indicated for it to cover the flank of 
the protected column, deploys into battle formation fully or 
with a portion of the forces, organizes a defense and is at the 
line until the prescribed time. 
  A company assigned to a rear security element proceeds up to 
5 km behind the protected column in readiness to repel a 
possible enemy attack from the rear. 
  The forward security element passes through chokepoints and 
tunnels and across bridges nonstop, moving behind the point. 
Company personnel conduct continuous all-around observation for 
the ground and air enemy and of adjoining terrain. 
  The point bypasses demolished road sectors, bridges and 
abatis on the movement route and mined sectors, using markers to 
denote places of destructive damage (mining) and the direction 
for going around. The forward security element makes a passage 
if it is impossible to go around or when making a passage in 
destructive damage (abatis) requires less time than going 
around. With remote mining of the movement route, the forward 
security element exits the minefield as one column along a 
passage which has been made in the shortest direction. 
  The commander of the point (forward security element) 
reports 
contaminated sectors, obstacles, destructive damage, directions 
for their bypass, and an encounter with the enemy to the 
commander who sent him out. 
  At short halts the point (forward security element) stops on 
a favorable line, organizes observation and is in constant 
readiness to repel an enemy attack. On arriving in the rest area 
the forward security element takes up a designated line and 
performs the mission of security at the halt. In this area the 
security element may be replaced by security at the halt. 
  With a change in movement direction, the company column is 
moved to the new route by the shortest path in the previous 
march formation or after a necessary change of formation and 
performs the assigned mission. 
  On encountering the enemy the company immobilizes him by 
battle and, stubbornly holding a favorable line, supports the 
protected column's deployment and engagement. 
<H5>  5. Transport Movement of Subunits </H5>
  A battalion is moved by rail or sea (river) transport as one 
or two troop echelons [voinskiy eshelon], by air transport as 
several military teams [voinskaya komanda], and on heavy 
multiple truck-trailer rigs as a single column. 
  To shorten the time for organizing transport movement, the 
battalion commander must constantly have prepared variants of 
calculations for moving the battalion by various kinds of 
transport. The transport movement calculation is put together 
with consideration for preserving subunits' organizational 
integrity and ensuring their readiness for battle after 
unloading (disembarking). 
  A troop echelon is understood to mean a military 
unit, subunit, establishment as well as separate teams and 
groups of combat vehicles organized for transport movement in 
one train or on one vessel (self-propelled or nonself- 
propelled). A train with ten cars or more (in a two-axle 
calculation) occupied by subunits, teams or military cargoes is 
considered to be a troop train. 
  An echelon is given an appropriate number which it retains 
throughout the journey. An echelon must have necessary forces 
and assets for loading (unloading) vehicles and cargoes; for 
organizing air defense, communications, and NBC reconnaissance; 
for security and defense; and for providing personnel with hot 
meals and medical aid. 
  A battalion is given a loading (boarding) and unloading 
(disembarking) station, port (wharf) or airfield (site) for 
loading (boarding) flatcars (railcars), vessels and aircraft 
(helicopters) and unloading (disembarking) from them. Subunits 
are in a waiting area before loading (boarding) and they move to 
an assembly area after unloading (disembarking) (Diagram 22). 
  The distance of the waiting area and assembly area from the 
loading (boarding) and unloading (disembarking) site 
respectively is determined by terrain conditions providing for 
concealed disposition of subunits and protection against mass 
destruction and precision weapons, and may be 3-5 km (usually 10 
15 km with movement by air transport). 
  Final preparation of the company (battalion) for loading 
(boarding) occurs in waiting areas. Weapons and vehicles are 
prepared for transport movement and subsequent operations: 
refueling, usually daily routine servicing and maintenance, and 
if necessary repairs are carried out. The personnel's state of 
supply of individual protective gear is checked. 
  A chief, his deputy for political affairs, assistant for 
combat support, assistant for supply, chief of communications 
and physician (paramedic) are assigned in each troop echelon. A 
daily detail is appointed for performing routine garrison and 
guard duty. A senior person is appointed for the entire journey 
in each railcar (cabin, crew quarters and so on) from among 
junior officers or NCO's, and in addition stokers also are 
appointed from among the privates during movement by rail 
transport in winter. 
  Special teams are formed to perform the main tasks of 
supporting company (battalion) subunits and the echelon as a 
whole during loading (unloading) and en route: loading-unloading 
teams, communications teams, teams for mopping up in the 
aftermath of enemy use of mass destruction, precision and 
incendiary weapons and so on. 
  Loading-unloading teams are intended for loading tracked, 
wheeled and trailer equipment onto flatcars (into railcars) and 
for loading various cargoes in boxcars. The number of these 
teams is determined basically by the number of loading sites. In 
addition to loading (unloading), the loading-unloading team 
(teams) also is obligated to assemble and disassemble various 
gear and devices necessary for loading (unloading). 
  Weapons and combat and other vehicles are loaded and 
personnel put aboard strictly at the designated time, covertly, 
with observance of safety measures precluding a breakdown of 
weapons, vehicles and transportation assets. Weapons, combat and 
other vehicles, and reserves of ammunition, fuel and other 
supplies are loaded first. 
  As a rule, ammunition and fuel are loaded in different 
railcars (on different ships, in different aircraft and 
helicopters). Combat vehicles and air defense weapons assigned 
to cover the loading point area and also prime movers intended 
for supporting the rapid loading (unloading) of tracked 
equipment are loaded on flatcars (ships) last. 
  Equipment is fastened down on railcars by the vehicle crews, 
for which they prepare chocks and pads for vehicle rollers, 
tracks and wheels; wire; chocks and blocks; and metal stops in 
advance. 
  In forming a troop train, boxcars occupied by people and 
operating kitchens are placed in the middle of the train and 
flatcars and open cars in the front and rear. Railcars with 
dangerous cargoes are separated from the locomotive, the rear of 
the train, cars with personnel, cars with operating kitchens, 
and if necessary also one from another by a special protective 
cover. Flatcars with air defense weapons are placed at the front 
and rear of the train and, for convenience of conducting fire, 
they are separated from the diesel (electric) locomotive, 
boxcars or open cars by one or more flatcars with low cargo. 
  Personnel board railcars (ships, aircraft or helicopters) on 
completion of loading of weapons, combat and other vehicles, and 
property, usually immediately before departure of the troop 
echelon (team) or before the ship puts to sea, but no later than 
10 minutes before departure. 
  During movement by rail transport, personnel as a rule are 
carried in fouraxle boxcars figuring 64-72 persons in each. It 
is prohibited to use cars which have been used for acids, toxic 
agents and animals. A passenger car may be provided for officers 
of the echelon. As part of the train it is desirable to have an 
isolation car prepared, like the car for personnel, with 
removable military equipment. 
  Weapons, combat and other vehicles, and supplies loaded on 
rolling stock (on ships, aircraft, helicopters) are reliably 
fastened down, and in addition vehicles are braked and put in 
low gear. Rotating devices of turrets of fighting vehicles and 
guns are locked and hatches sealed. 
  Responsibility for loading, accommodating and fastening down 
of weapons, combat and other vehicles and for boarding personnel 
rests with the chief of the troop echelon, and with commanders 
of crews and of aircraft (helicopters) for movement by air 
transport. 
  A battalion being moved by rail or sea (river) transport is 
supported for the entire journey with en route and destination 
supplies of food in addition to unit-level supplies. A battalion 
aid station is set up for prompt medical aid during movement in 
a troop echelon (on a ship). Wounded and sick are evacuated from 
a troop echelon (ship) to the nearest medical facilities. 
  To preserve the personnel's strength and fighting vehicles' 
engine time and to reduce their wear (especially tracks) when 
making a march over great distances, it is advisable to 
transport tanks of a TC (TB) on heavy multiple truck-trailer 
rigs, which represent transportation complexes of wheeled prime 
movers and heavy-freight trailers. 
  A company (battalion) is assigned a primary and alternate 
loading point area for loading on heavy multiple truck- 
trailer rigs. The TC (TB) commander together with the motor 
transport subunit commander directs loading of tanks on 
trailers. A trained crew can load and secure a tank on a trailer 
in 10-15 minutes. With simultaneous loading a TC loads in 15-20 
minutes and a TB in 30-40 minutes; with successive loading a 
company will require one hour. Unloading a company may take an 
average of around 30 minutes and the battalion 45 minutes. 
  With the route in good condition, a column of trailers can 
develop a speed of 45-50 km/hr, but it is inadvisable to develop 
a column speed of over 30 km/hr because of the difficulty of 
controlling a trailer when transporting heavy equipment (the 
trailer with vehicles swerves with fast driving). Railroad 
crossings are crossed at a speed of no more than 15 km/hr. 
Distances between trailers can reach 50 m, and they increase on 
upgrades and downgrades. 
  Organization of transport movement depends on the specific 
situation, mission received and time available. On receipt of an 
operation order (operational instructions) for movement by rail 
(sea, river) transport the battalion commander (troop echelon 
commander) issues instructions on preparing for the transport 
movement; together with the military commandant of the rail 
(water) sector and station (port), he updates the calculation 
for transportation of subunit personnel, weapons, vehicles and 
property by railcars, flatcars, ships or ship spaces; draws up a 
plan for loading the troop echelon; establishes the sequence of 
loading (boarding) subunits and the time of its beginning and 
completion; determines the procedure for subunits to move up to 
loading (boarding) points; performs ground reconnaissance of the 
waiting area, the station (port, wharf), and forward movement 
routes of subunits to them and to loading (boarding) points, and 
assigns missions to subunits. 
  The battalion staff prepares calculations in advance for 
transport movement of the battalion, which permits the commander 
to reduce time for organizing it. 
  On receiving the order (operational instructions) for 
movement by air transport the MRC (MRB) commander issues 
instructions for preparing for the movement; together with the 
military transport (army) aviation subunit (unit) commander or 
civil aviation group (detachment) commander and airport military 
commandant, he updates the loading (boarding) order, ramp 
parking areas and side numbers of aircraft (helicopters); 
compiles the calculation for movement of subunit personnel, 
weapons, vehicles, missiles, ammunition, fuel and other supplies 
by aircraft (helicopters), the loading (boarding) plan and 
personnel rosters of the military teams for each aircraft 
(helicopter); determines the sequence and procedure for loading 
(boarding) and arrival of the subunits and the time of their 
beginning and completion; performs ground reconnaissance of the 
waiting area, airfield (landing sites), forward movement routes 
of subunits to them and to aircraft (helicopter) ramp parking 
areas, and assigns missions to subunits. 
  In the transport movement order the battalion 
commander indicates the following: 
  First paragraph--information on the enemy. 
  Second paragraph--battalion mission; number 
(numbers) of the troop echelon (team, teams); name of ship 
(ships) and side numbers of aircraft (helicopters); loading 
(boarding) station (port, wharf, airfield or landing site) and 
waiting area and forward movement routes to them; time for 
beginning and completion of loading. 
  Third paragraph, the transport movement concept-- 
distribution of subunits, personnel, weapons and vehicles by 
troop echelons (teams), railcars, flatcars (ships, ship spaces, 
aircraft or helicopters); sequence and procedure for subunit 
loading; organization of air defense (duty subunits, procedure 
for alert duty, for observation, and for commencing and 
conducting fire against airborne targets); and the number and 
makeup of the daily detail and loadingunloading teams. 
  Fourth paragraph--after the words I 
order, missions for subunits--places (quantity of railcars 
and flatcars, numbers of aircraft, helicopters, cabins, decks, 
holds and other spaces, numbers of military teams) for 
accommodating personnel, weapons and vehicles; sequence and 
procedure for loading (boarding); place in battalion march 
column when moving up from waiting area to loading (boarding) 
points and procedure for actions after unloading; for the air 
defense subunit in addition, missions for providing cover during 
loading, en route, and when unloading; and for subunits from 
which loading- unloading teams and the daily detail are 
assigned, makeup of the teams (detail), their missions and 
readiness time. 
  Fifth paragraph--readiness time for moving out of 
the waiting area and for loading. 
  Sixth paragraph--appointed persons of the echelon, 
their place in the echelon (aboard the ship) or the number of 
the aircraft (helicopter) in which they are proceeding, and 
warning and control signals. 
  The company commander issues the transport movement order in 
the very same sequence as the battalion commander, but in 
the fourth paragraph he usually indicates the following: 
places for accommodating platoon personnel, weapons and vehicles 
on rolling stock (on the ship, in the aircraft or helicopter); 
sequence and procedure for their loading (boarding); platoon 
places in the company column when moving up from the waiting 
area to the loading point, and to the assembly area after 
unloading; makeup of loadingunloading teams, who is senior, 
their missions, and time and procedure for them to perform 
missions; from whom and in what makeup to assign the daily 
detail and procedure for its preparation; safety measures during 
loading (boarding), en route and when unloading (disembarking). 
In addition, in the sixth paragraph of the order, instead of 
appointed persons of the echelon, he indicates senior persons of 
railcars and his own place in the train (on the ship) or the 
number of the aircraft (helicopter) in which he is proceeding. 
  Battalion commander's instructions on preparing 
for transport movement 
  (Variant) 
  Organize filling of vehicles with POL and coolant from 0930 
to 1130 20 June. 
  Receive and load ammunition from 1130 to 1330 in the 
following sequence--1st, 2nd, 3rd TC. 
  Complete loading of supplies on motor transport by 1400. 
  Deputy battalion commander for weapons is to organize 
routine 
servicing and maintenance of vehicles. Restore unserviceable 
equipment by 1630. By 1700 draw catwalks, clamps and nails at 
the loading station. 
  Subunit commanders prepare and check the presence of 
fastening materials and necessary devices for loading by 1630. 
  From 1330 to 1530 hold practical classes with personnel on 
rules for loading equipment on rolling stock and communicate 
safety measures and rules for the journey. 
  Readiness for transport movement is 1730. Issue hot food to 
personnel at 1600. 
  Departure for ground reconnaissance at 1230 from battalion 
COP. Deputies and commanders of companies and separate platoons 
are involved in ground reconnaissance. 
  TC commander's operation order for transport 
movement 
  (Variant) 
  1. Employing precision weapons, the enemy has halted the 
attack of our troops by operations of reserves which have come 
up and shifted to a defense along west bank of the Shirokaya 
River on the morning of 17 June. 
  Enemy aircraft are conducting aerial reconnaissance and 
delivering strikes against reserves and rear installations. 
  2. 2nd TC is moving by rail transport as part of the 
battalion and by 2000 hours 21 June assembles in the vicinity of 
Ternovskoye terrain feature. The troop echelon number is 12345. 
Boarding station is Sineglazovo. Waiting area is forest north of 
Voznesenskoye. Route of forward movement: Shumaki, Timofeyevka. 
Beginning of loading at 1800. Completion of loading at 1930. 
Departure at 2000. 
  3. Transport the personnel in second railcar. 
  Load equipment on 13th through 22nd flatcars in the 
following 
sequence: 1st, 2nd, 3rd TP. Assign lookouts for the air enemy 
and a duty tank from 1st TP. Commence fire against air enemy at 
the command of the echelon chief, or independently in a surprise 
attack. 
  Assign daily detail from 3rd TP. Have a loading-unloading 
team of six persons, two from each platoon. 
  4. I order: transport the company personnel in 
second railcar. 
  Accommodate equipment on the following flatcars: company 
commander's tank and 1st TP from 13th through 16th, 2nd TP from 
17th through 19th, 3rd TP from 20th through 22nd. Load from end 
(side) ramp. Move out of waiting area to loading point and to 
assembly area after unloading in the following order: company 
commander's tank, 1st, 2nd, 3rd TP. 
  Platoon commanders are to assign two persons each to the 
loading- unloading team. Senior person of team is a tank 
commander from 2nd TP. Mission: from 1730 to 1750 open sides of 
13th through 22nd flatcar for movement of combat vehicles along 
them. With beginning of loading of battalion wheeled vehicles, 
support their movement along the railcars (transfer connecting 
ramps to flatcar junctions). 
  Assign daily detail from 3rd TP made up of duty NCO--a 
sergeant, 
  and orderlies--two privates. 
  Observe prescribed safety measures when loading, en route, 
and 
  when unloading. 5. Readiness for moving out of waiting area 
  1630, and for loading 1730. 
  6. Senior person in car is company 1st sergeant. I am in 
15th 
  car. 
  Warning and control signals--according to signal table. 
  After issuing the transport movement order the battalion 
commander (chief of troop echelon) gives instructions on the 
procedure for preparing rolling stock for loading the echelon, 
on methods of accommodating and fastening weapons and vehicles 
on the rolling stock (ship), on organizing security in the 
echelon or on the ship (updates the makeup of the daily detail, 
time and procedure of its relief, post locations, duties of 
sentries and procedure for communications with them), on safety 
measures during loading (boarding) and transport movement, and 
on the procedure for actions in response to warning and control 
signals; he also gives instructions on organizing combat, 
technical and logistic support, fire protection (emergency 
rescue work) and political work for the period of the transport 
movement. 
  Before the beginning of forward movement from the waiting 
area for loading (boarding), the company (battalion) commander 
checks the personnel's knowledge of loading (boarding) rules and 
safety measures; of the procedure for accommodating and 
fastening weapons and vehicles in railcars and on flatcars (on 
ships, in aircraft and helicopters); of rules for their 
unloading and of rules of personnel conduct during the transport 
movement. A check is made of the readiness of weapons, vehicles, 
missiles, ammunition, fuel and other supplies for loading as 
well as the alignment of the company (battalion) column in 
accordance with the loading plan. Before loading, the battalion 
commander (chief of troop echelon) arrives at the loading point 
with appointed persons of the echelon, where he checks the 
presence of rolling stock; organizes receipt of railcars (ship 
spaces) and removable military equipment and preparation of 
rolling stock for loading the echelon; if necessary, he makes 
changes to the loading (boarding) plan and to the transport 
movement calculation and gives the command (signal) for subunits 
to move out to the loading (boarding) point. En route the 
battalion commander and staff (chief of troop echelon) as a rule 
are accommodated in the middle of the echelon during movement by 
rail transport. He must have telephone communications with the 
officer of the guard, with observation posts and with the diesel 
(electric) locomotive engineer. During movement by sea (river) 
transport the battalion commander is in one of the cabins or a 
separate ship space. 
  C[.sup]2[/] in a troop echelon (on a ship) is exercised 
using wire means of communication, by personal contact, by 
messengers and by light and sound signals. 
  Battalion subunits begin moving out of the waiting area in 
company columns (subunit columns) in accordance with the 
prescribed loading order. As a rule, their movement out of the 
area is directed by the battalion chief of staff. 
  The battalion commander meets subunits on the approach, 
gives instructions to commanders on the procedure for 
disposition near the loading point and reports readiness for 
loading to the military commandant. 
  The deputy company (battalion) commander for weapons 
(company senior technician) is responsible for overall direction 
of loading the equipment. The subunit commander is responsible 
for the loading of each subunit. He personally directs each 
vehicle's run onto the rolling stock. Further movement of the 
vehicle along the flatcars is directed by the vehicle commander, 
who has constant visual contact with the driver and observes 
safety measures. 
  During loading under nighttime conditions it is necessary to 
take advantage of fixed illumination, and in its absence one 
should organize illumination with headlights of specially 
assigned vehicles. 
  After loading, the loading-unloading devices are collected 
and piled in a place specified by the commander. 
  Subunit commanders with their deputies for weapons (company 
senior technicians) check the reliability and correctness of 
securing the equipment, that vehicles are braked and in low 
gear, and that fighting vehicle turrets and guns are locked; 
they seal vehicle hatches (doors); and report completion of 
loading through channels. 
  In case the enemy delivers nuclear strikes or employs 
precision, chemical and incendiary weapons during loading, 
subunits are led out of areas of bursts (fires, contamination) 
and subsequently continue loading at the previous place or move 
to another loading point depending on the situation. 
  After completion of loading the battalion commander, 
military 
commandant and the station chief check readiness of the echelon 
for movement. Special attention is given to firmness and 
correctness of fastening the sides of flatcars and the vehicles. 
  In the course of transport movement the company (battalion) 
commander receives data on the situation in the direction of 
movement via military commandants, the general warning network 
and senior commanders (chiefs), constantly keeps an eye on 
compliance with transport movement rules, and monitors the 
condition of subunits and observance of discipline and safety 
measures. 
  At a signal warning of the air enemy, the troop echelon 
(ship) continues movement. Doors, windows (portholes) and 
hatches of railcars (ship spaces) are closed and protective gear 
placed in the "ready" position. Air defense and other weapons 
assigned to repel an enemy air raid commence fire on command of 
the echelon chief (ship captain), and in a surprise attack they 
do so independently in accordance with instructions on the 
procedure for conducting fire. 
  In response to signals warning of NBC contamination, 
personnel put on protective masks (breathing masks) and other 
individual protective gear as well if necessary by order of 
subunit commanders. 
  During movement by rail and sea (river) transport, personnel 
cross zones of radioactive contamination of terrain and water 
areas contaminated by radioactive substances wearing individual 
protective gear. When a troop echelon passes through a zone of 
radioactive contamination, tank and other armored vehicle crews 
may be disposed in vehicles by instruction of the echelon chief 
(ship captain). After crossing the zone of contamination, 
partial decontamination of personnel, vehicles and means of 
transportation is performed if necessary. Complete 
decontamination of subunits and personnel is performed after 
unloading. 
  Depending on the situation at hand, the company (battalion) 
always must be ready en route for unloading at unprepared 
locations, proceeding to the destination by march, bypassing 
zones of contamination and areas of destructive damage, fires 
and floods, and engaging. 
  On arriving at the transport movement destination the 
company 
(battalion) quickly unloads and, observing combat support 
measures, moves into the assembly area in readiness to move out 
to the battalion (regimental) concentration area or for 
performing the combat mission. 
  Under present conditions subunits and units may make a 
combination movement. This is the movement of troops from one 
area to another in which different methods of movement are 
combined. A combination transport movement and a combination of 
a march and transport movement may be accomplished depending on 
distance of the movement, nature of lines of communication and 
presence and kinds of transportation assets used for movement. 
  The combination transport movement as a rule presumes a 
successive and sometimes also simultaneous combination of 
transport movement of subunits by different kinds of transport-- 
rail, water (sea, river), motor, air. 
  The simultaneous or successive combination of the march and 
transport movement may become widespread under present 
conditions. With simultaneous combination of the march and 
transport movement, one part of the subunits proceeds under its 
own power, and another (tanks, prime movers, heavy engineer 
vehicles, vehicles with little range and slow speed) is moved by 
rail or water (sea, river) transport. The advantage of that 
movement method is that capabilities of each kind of transport 
are used to the maximum. Its principal shortcomings are 
disruption of organizational integrity of subunits and 
difficulty of C[.sup]2[/]. In a successive combination, a 
march may precede transport movement or be employed after 
completion of transport movement. 
  Success of combination movement of subunits depends largely 
on the ability of the battalion commander and staff to provide 
in advance for measures ensuring a rapid transfer from movement 
by one kind of transport to movement by another kind of 
transport or to the march. With the simultaneous combination of 
march and transport movement, the art of the battalion commander 
and staff to coordinate actions of those subunits moving under 
their own power and those being conveyed acquires special 
importance. 
  Calculations for movement of subunits by different methods 
are coordinated with each other so that in case transport 
movement stops, all subunits can link up quickly and arrive 
simultaneously in the designated concentration area if possible. 
  If an abrupt situation change gives rise to an interruption 
in transport movement in the course of subunit movement by the 
combination method, subunits being moved by rail or water 
transport quickly unload from rolling stock or ships and proceed 
to a new loading point by march for continuing the transport 
movement. If the situation requires cessation of transport 
movement, subunits which have unloaded from transportation 
assets proceed independently under their own power to the 
designated concentration area or join subunits moving by march. 
<H5>  Chapter IX - Disposition at the Halt </H5>
<H5>  1. Company (Battalion) Disposition at the Halt </H5>
  A company (battalion) may be disposed at the halt in a 
concentration area, assembly area, waiting area and other areas. 
The disposition area as a rule is designated on terrain 
favorable for protection against mass destruction and precision 
weapons and for maskirovka of subunits. A subunit disposition 
area should not be designated near important installations 
(plants, rail junctions, railroad stations, bridges and so on) 
or built-up areas against which the enemy may deliver massed 
fire and nuclear strikes. 
  But we resort to disposing subunits in built-up areas under 
conditions of a severe winter or protracted bad weather when 
there is no time to perform laborious work of making shelters. 
  One should make skilled use of the nature and protective 
properties of terrain in disposing subunits. Thus, on wooded 
terrain it is more advisable to place subunits along forest 
roads, openings and treelines. Since COP's and technical support 
and rear subunits are most vulnerable to the shock wave and 
penetrating radiation of a nuclear burst, they should be located 
in ravines and deep cuts. On mountainous terrain it is advisable 
to take advantage of terrain folds, tunnels, mines, caves and 
areas not subject to avalanches, landslides or floods. In 
deserts and steppe, subunits should be disposed in a more 
dispersed manner, where possible near water sources and as a 
rule away from clear- cut reference points. 
  The duration of a company's (battalion's) disposition at the 
halt may be from several hours to several days depending on 
upcoming operations and situation conditions. 
  The long range of modern weapons and presence of a real 
possibility of enemy use of nuclear and precision weapons, 
airmobile troops and airborne assault forces to a considerable 
depth force subunits disposed at the halt to be in constant 
readiness to repel an attack by the air and ground enemy. 
  To provide protection for the company (battalion) against 
mass destruction weapons and consequently also for its 
survivability in the disposition area, it must be disposed in a 
dispersed manner and in an alignment supporting the execution of 
a maneuver and conduct of battle. Optimum limits of dispersal 
are set depending on the nature of upcoming operations, strength 
level of subunits and terrain conditions. Thus, according to 
existing views, the size of disposition areas may be 1.5-2 
km[.sup]2[/] for the company and up to 10 km[.sup]2[/] for 
the battalion. 
  Studies that have been performed and the experience of field 
training exercises show that the mutual distance between 
companies (batteries) must be 1-1.5 km, between platoons 300-400 
m, and between tanks and BMP's (BTR's) on open terrain 100-150 
m. With that dispersal of subunits a low (very low) yield 
nuclear weapon can put no more than one company (platoon) out of 
commission. 
  The configuration of the battalion disposition area depends 
on the nature of terrain, purpose of the disposition and nature 
of upcoming operations. For example, to occupy an assembly area 
during a hasty attack or a concentration area when disposed in 
the depth of the defense, it is advisable to designate an area 
corresponding to the zone of advance or the defense area. The 
configuration of day (night) or 24-hour rest halt areas should 
correspond approximately to the alignment of the march formation. 
  The order of placement of battalion subunits (Diagram 23) 
when disposed at the halt depends on upcoming operations, length 
of stay in the area, situation conditions and nature of terrain. 
Thus, when disposed at the halt for preparing to conduct battle 
involving forward movement, the disposition of subunits should 
correspond to their alignment for movement and engagement from 
the move. 
  Therefore subunits intended for operations in the first 
echelon of the battle formation are disposed in that part of the 
assembly area (concentration area) nearest the enemy and other 
subunits are disposed in its depth, and the company (battalion) 
is so disposed that subunits have an opportunity to deploy 
quickly and act together. The mortar (artillery) battery is 
disposed at full strength or by platoon on threatened axes, 
being in constant readiness to commence fire, and its COP is 
prepared together with the battalion COP. Air defense subunits 
take up launch (firing) positions in places convenient for 
conducting fire against enemy aircraft and helicopters and other 
airborne targets. A portion of air defense subunits may be 
attached to subunits of the security at the halt. The GLP and 
ATP usually are disposed with MRC's and the reconnaissance 
platoon near the COP. 
  The battalion support platoon is disposed with consideration 
for convenience of preparing battalion subunits for battle. The 
area of the platoon location may reach 1 km[.sup]2[/] and 
that of the squad 0.3 km[.sup]2[/]. Squads are disposed in a 
dispersed manner and distances between them should be 150200 m. 
  The battalion COP is prepared with consideration for 
ensuring 
continuous C[.sup]2[/] of subunits while in and when moving 
out of the disposition area. Communications with subunits 
usually is accomplished by mobile and wire means. Operation of 
radio equipment on transmit is permitted only for warning and 
for controlling the fire of air defense weapons. 
  A duty subunit consisting of a reinforced MRP is assigned in 
the battalion. As a rule, it is located near the COP in constant 
readiness to destroy enemy raiding and reconnaissance parties, 
perform other missions that arise suddenly and fight fires. 
  During disposition at the halt, troops are protected by 
local 
security, and also by security at the halt when there is a 
threat of enemy attack. Security at the halt must be all-around 
and intercept all main roads and approaches to the disposition 
area. 
  Security, communications between COP's, and warning of the 
air and ground enemy, NBC contamination, use of incendiary 
weapons and an immediate threat and beginning of enemy use of 
mass destruction and precision weapons are organized; maskirovka 
measures are conducted; and the movement of personnel and 
vehicles is restricted in the company (battalion). 
  In case the enemy uses mass destruction, precision and 
incendiary weapons or remote minelaying systems against the 
company (battalion) disposition area, the company (battalion) 
will be forced to change the area by direction or permission of 
the senior commander according to a previously developed plan, 
covertly, and in a short time. As a rule, subunits make the 
change of areas as part of their own units. The change of area 
also may be done by decision of the company (battalion) 
commander with surprise enemy use of mass destruction or 
incendiary weapons and the absence of an opportunity to report 
this promptly to the senior commander. Alternate areas and 
movement routes to them should be prepared in advance to support 
a subunit change of disposition areas. The advisability of a 
change in a battalion disposition area located in zones of 
contamination, fires and flooding is determined by the degree of 
danger of the situation at hand to personnel, weapons and 
vehicles. If their decontamination is required, it is done 
outside of new disposition areas. 
  With a change in area, one should pay attention to 
covertness 
of exiting the area, to movement and to occupation of the new 
one. As a rule, the change should be made at night or under 
other conditions of limited visibility. Allaround reconnaissance 
(observation) should be conducted in subunits and air defense 
weapons must be ready to repel a strike by enemy aircraft and 
helicopters. 
  Ground reconnaissance of the designated area is organized 
before the battalion moves out to it. Usually one of the 
battalion staff officers and one officer (warrant officer) or 
NCO from each company are included in the ground reconnaissance 
party. They clarify locations of companies, other organic and 
attached subunits, and COP's; the air defense subunit launch 
(firing) positions; and locations of technical support and rear 
subunits. They reconnoiter and mark access routes, meet their 
subunits and lead them to the designated places. Subunit columns 
are not permitted to halt on roads while awaiting disposition in 
the allotted area. 
  It is forbidden to make signs or put up markers with the 
name 
and numbering of subunits and their commanders' last names. 
  If it is proposed to dispose subunits in an area free of the 
enemy, first enemy raiding and reconnaissance parties and his 
reconnaissance-signaling devices are detected and destroyed, 
mined and contaminated terrain sectors are discovered and 
marked, and suitability of using water and the food remaining 
after the enemy's departure and the possibility of using other 
supplies is determined. 
  Areas with residual radiation as well as areas mined by the 
enemy as a rule are not occupied by troops. 
  The chief of staff prepares proposals for the battalion 
commander in advance for decisionmaking on disposition at the 
halt and draws up a report on the effective combat and numerical 
strength and a diagram of disposition area security and defense. 
The deputy commander for rear services submits a request for 
delivery of supplies, a report on battalion logistic support 
and, in addition, a diagram of the security and defense of 
disposition of battalion rear subunits; and the instructor 
(chemical warfare instructor) compiles a report on personnel 
radiation doses. 
  On receiving a mission for disposition at the halt the 
company (battalion) commander analyzes it and 
estimates the situation. In estimating the 
enemy, one determines his distance and the 
possibility of an attack and delivery of strikes by mass 
destruction weapons, aircraft, artillery and other weapons. 
Conclusions are drawn on this basis about the place, strength 
and makeup of security at the halt and about measures for 
protection against mass destruction weapons, air defense, 
maskirovka, the area's engineer preparation, and conduct of 
reconnaissance and security when moving forward to the 
disposition area. 
  In estimating his own subunits the commander takes 
into account the effect of their situation and makeup on the 
size of disposition areas. In estimating adjacent subunits, 
their primary and alternate disposition areas are studied and 
advisable locations (disposition areas) of one's own subunits 
are planned (if they were not given) and requirements for their 
preparation are specified with consideration of requirements for 
protection against mass destruction weapons. 
  In estimating the nature of terrain, the commander 
plans the locations (areas) and procedure for disposition of 
subunits, C[.sup]2[/] facilities, rear and technical support 
subunits and security at the halt in the battalion. The 
procedure for taking advantage of terrain properties and the 
measures for engineer preparation of the area are specified. 
  In estimating the NBC situation, the possibility 
of safest disposition of subunits and necessary measures for 
protecting personnel and vehicles are determined. 
  In the decision for disposition at the halt, the 
company (battalion) commander specifies the following: locations 
(disposition areas) of subunits and the procedure for moving to 
them; makeup, missions and lines of security at the halt (in the 
battalion) and from what subunits it is assigned; missions and 
places of air defense weapon launch (firing) positions; the duty 
subunit; measures for protecting against mass destruction 
weapons, supporting combat readiness, repelling an enemy 
surprise attack and engineer preparation of areas (primary and 
alternate); and locations of C[.sup]2[/] facilities. 
  Based on the decision the company (battalion) commander 
issues the operation order, in which he indicates the 
following in assigning missions: 

  -  for motorized rifle (tank) platoons (companies) and 
other organic and attached subunits--primary and alternate 
locations (disposition areas) and procedure for their occupation 
and engineer preparation; 
  -  for security--makeup and position of security 
(movement route of patrols) and time of occupying it (beginning 
of patrolling); mission, procedure for commencing and conducting 
fire, maintaining communications and reporting the enemy; relief 
procedure, and the password and reply; 
  -  for air defense subunit--launch (firing) positions, 
mission, and time and degree of combat readiness; 
  -  for duty subunit--makeup, for what actions to be 
ready, disposition area and signals for requesting the 
subunit. 


    In organizing comprehensive support, measures are provided 
for repelling an enemy ground attack. For these purposes MRC's 
(TC's) and the ATP are given deployment lines and missions, the 
mortar battery, GLP and attached artillery subunit are given 
firing positions, and the procedure for preparing firing 
positions (lines of deployment) and moving out of them and a 
possible maneuver of fire and subunits are determined. The 
company (battalion) commander determines what duty weapons to 
have in the subunits to repel an enemy air attack and indicates 
the procedure for conducting fire. 
  After assigning missions and organizing comprehensive 
support, the company (battalion) commander supervises 
preparation of the disposition area, servicing and maintenance 
of weapons and vehicles, replenishment of subunits' missiles, 
ammunition and other supplies, and maintenance of subunits' 
combat readiness. 
  The following documents are drawn up in the battalion for 
disposition at the halt: operation order for the disposition, 
diagram of battalion disposition area security and defense, 
request for logistic support of subunits, report on effective 
combat and numerical strength, report on logistic support, and 
report on radiation doses. 
  A company organizes local security, performed by patrols and 
by constant alert duty of observers at the company COP. Patrols 
perform duty by making the rounds of the company disposition. In 
addition, a daily detail is assigned for guarding personnel, 
weapons and military vehicles. 
  Battalion security at the halt is accomplished by security 
posts consisting of a squad (tank) put out at a distance of up 
to 1,500 m on threatened axes where necessary; on concealed 
approaches by listening posts of 2-3 persons put out up to 400 m 
from the battalion disposition area; and within the disposition 
area by local security, including two-man patrols and constant 
alert duty of observers at the battalion COP. 
  Subunits are disposed nearer the outskirts in built-up 
areas. 
Basement rooms of buildings, local bunkers and other sturdy 
structures are used as shelters. 
  Radio-frequency and heat emitting objects are camouflaged by 
special covers (screens), and dummy objects (decoy flares) are 
prepared near them. Routes for subunits' forward movement from 
the area and for maneuver in repelling an enemy attack are 
reconnoitered and prepared in and on approaches to the area. 
  A company (battalion) in a disposition area must be in 
constant readiness to repel an enemy ground and air attack and 
destroy his airborne and raiding and reconnaissance parties. 
<H5>  2. MRC or TC (MRB or TB) in a Security Detachment at the Halt </H5>
  Security at the halt usually is accomplished by security 
detachments at the halt and outposts. 
  The following are missions of a company (battalion) in a 
security detachment at the halt: promptly detect the appearance 
of the ground enemy and warn the protected regiment of this; 
prevent penetration of enemy reconnaissance in the designated 
security zone; not allow servicemen and subunits of their 
regiment who do not know the password, as well as all civilians, 
to travel (walk) across the line of security at the halt; in 
case of enemy attack, support the protected regiment's 
deployment and organized engagement. 
  To perform these missions an MRC (MRB) is reinforced by an 
artillery battery, AT weapon subunits, grenade launchers, air 
defense subunit, and combat engineer subunit; and a TC is 
reinforced by an artillery battery, motorized rifle subunit and 
combat engineer subunit. In all cases the company (battalion) is 
provided with the necessary number of radios, and telephone 
communications is established with it. 
  A security detachment at the halt is given a defense line 
and 
zone of responsibility [polosa okhraneniya i vedeniya razvedki] 
(diagrams 24 and 25). The zone of responsibility may reach up to 
5 km in frontage for a company and up to 10 km for a battalion. 
  The distance from the unit of a company assigned to security 
at the halt should ensure its execution of a maneuver and 
organized engagement and may be up to 10 km, and that of a 
battalion up to 15 km. 
  A security detachment at the halt occupies and prepares its 
indicated line for defense, covering the most important axes 
with outposts. The line must favor defense, provide a good field 
of view toward the enemy, be prepared with emplacements and 
covered by obstacles; emplacements are connected into a 
continuous trench when there is lengthy performance of security 
duty. 
  Primary positions, and alternate positions if time is 
available, are prepared in the zone of responsibility. Based on 
combat training experience, a company may prepare a defense 
position of up to 2.5 km in frontage and a battalion up to 7.5 
km on the main axis of its zone of responsibility. Gaps between 
outposts and likely avenues of tank approach are under 
continuous observation and covered by fire of artillery and 
other weapons. Tanks attached to an MRC also may be used in 
operations from ambushes. The artillery subunit is disposed in 
the depth of the company defense, as a rule on a likely avenue 
of tank approach, and prepares several lines for conducting 
creeping and standing barrier fire and direct fire. Security 
posts are put out for observing the terrain and warning of the 
enemy's appearance ahead and to the sides in the company zone of 
responsibility, and listening posts are put out on concealed 
approaches. Reconnaissance is accomplished by observation from 
all COP's. In addition, patrol squads (tanks) and sometimes also 
a combat reconnaissance patrol are sent out. 
  The security post position is selected so it provides good 
observation and enables its stubborn defense until the security 
detachment is ready for battle. 
  Patrols are sent out to inspect the terrain, check vigilance 
of duty performance by security posts and outposts, and for 
contact with adjacent subunits of security at the halt. 
Observers assigned for this keep a lookout for signals of 
security posts and outposts. 
  The company (battalion) reserve of up to a motorized rifle 
(tank) platoon (company) is disposed in the depth in readiness 
to maneuver to threatened axes. 
  A moving ground target radar reconnaissance post may be 
deployed in the company for prompt detection of an advancing 
enemy, especially from the direction of concealed approaches. 
  On receiving the mission, the company (battalion) commander 
analyzes it, estimates the situation, makes a decision from the 
map, communicates missions to subordinates, moves the company to 
the vicinity of the indicated line, organizes observation and 
security, performs ground reconnaissance, updates the decision, 
issues the operation order and organizes occupation of the 
indicated line. 
  In assigning missions the company (battalion) commander 
indicates the following in the operation order: 

  -  for outposts--means of reinforcement, zone of 
responsibility, positions and extent of their engineer 
preparation, where to place security posts, patrols and 
listening posts, the line up to which to conduct reconnaissance, 
and the procedure for actions in repelling an enemy attack; 
  -  for reserve--disposition area and for what actions 
to be ready; 
  -  for artillery subunits--firing 
positions and missions for supporting the battle of outposts; 
  -  for air defense subunit--launch (firing) positions, 
mission, time and degree of readiness; and for motorized rifle 
(tank) subunits--procedure for conducting fire against enemy 
airborne targets. 


    In the sixth paragraph of the operation order, in 
addition to time of readiness to perform the mission, the 
company (battalion) commander indicates the time for occupying 
positions and for readiness of the system of fire, and the 
sequence and time periods for engineer preparation of positions. 
  After assigning missions to subunits the company (battalion) 
commander organizes coordination; gives them instructions on 
comprehensive support to battle and protection against precision 
weapons; and specifies the procedure for maintaining 
communications with subunits. In addition, the reply also is 
given to commanders of outposts and of subunits assigned for 
conducting reconnaissance. 
  Missions for outposts and attached means of reinforcement as 
well as locations of observers (observation posts) are updated 
on the terrain during ground reconnaissance. 
  On receipt of data on the enemy's appearance, the company 
(battalion) commander reports this to the commander who sent out 
the security element and informs adjacent subunits. Small enemy 
groups attempting to penetrate to protected subunits are 
captured or destroyed by the security detachment. With an attack 
by superior enemy forces the company (battalion) stubbornly 
holds the line and supports the regiment's deployment and 
engagement. 
  In case of an enemy airborne assault force landing in the 
zone of responsibility, the company (battalion) commander takes 
steps to destroy it and reports to the commander who sent out 
the security element. 
<H5>  Chapter X - Combat Support </H5>
<H5>  1. General Provisions </H5>
  Combat support holds an important place among factors 
determining achievement of success in modern combined arms 
battle. It consists of the organization and accomplishment of 
measures aimed at precluding an enemy surprise attack, reducing 
the effectiveness of his fire and strikes against subunits, and 
creating favorable conditions for their organized, timely 
engagement and successful conduct of battle. 
  Reconnaissance, security, protection against mass 
destruction 
weapons, maskirovka, and engineer and chemical support are the 
basic kinds of combat support. In addition, electronic warfare 
is conducted in the battalion. Measures of protection against 
enemy precision weapons are accomplished in performing combat 
support measures. 
  The subunit (battalion, company and so on) commander 
organizes combat support in accordance with the decision which 
has been made and instructions of the higher staff (commander). 
Combat support in the battalion is organized directly by the 
chief of staff in accordance with the battalion commander's 
instructions. 
  The content of combat support measures is determined in the 
course of the situation estimate based on conclusions about the 
effect of particular situation conditions and features on 
upcoming subunit operations in order to take maximum advantage 
of favorable circumstances on the one hand and to reduce and 
neutralize negative circumstances on the other hand. 
Requirements for particular kinds of combat support and their 
elements are determined and their quantitative-qualitative data 
are established, and then a decision is made on the specific 
content of each kind of combat support based on an estimate of 
existing capabilities to satisfy these requirements: goal, 
missions, forces and assets, methods of operations, time, place, 
expected result, and procedure for reporting fulfillment of 
missions. 
  Missions in terms of kinds of combat support are 
communicated 
in the form of directions (instructions). This usually is done 
after assigning the combat mission and at the conclusion of 
organizing coordination. 
  Performance of assigned missions is monitored. In case of 
abrupt situation changes, missions in terms of kinds of combat 
support are promptly updated and new forces and assets assigned 
if necessary. Successful resolution of this matter is 
facilitated by foresight of commanders at all levels of possible 
situation changes and preparation of appropriate combat support 
measures in advance on this basis. 
<H5>  2. Reconnaissance </H5>
  Reconnaissance is one of the most important conditions for 
achieving success in all kinds of battle. It is difficult to 
make substantiated decisions for battle and for accomplishing 
planned operations without knowing the enemy and features of the 
real nature of terrain in an area of operations. Its purpose is 
to collect information on the enemy and terrain in a timely 
manner. 
  Ignorance and especially underestimation of the enemy as a 
rule leads to incorrect conclusions about him, his possible 
concept of operations and the methods, time and place of their 
accomplishment, and consequently also to unsubstantiated 
operations of friendly forces and assets both in terms of 
methods as well as in terms of goal, place and time. The result 
is failure. "The most dangerous thing in war . . .," Lenin 
pointed out, "is to underestimate the enemy and be content with 
the fact that we are stronger. This is the most dangerous thing 
that can cause defeat..."[.sup]1[/] 
  The content of reconnaissance missions is determined by the 
nature of subunit operations. In the defense, reconnaissance 
must uncover enemy preparation for an attack and the possible 
time of his readiness to attack, establish the makeup of the 
enemy grouping, and identify the axis of his main attack and 
nature of maneuver for a close or deep envelopment or for 
building up efforts. It is especially important to determine the 
possible time of an assault, locations of firing positions of 
artillery and other weapons, locations of C[.sup]2[/] 
facilities, the combat effectiveness of enemy troops and their 
affiliation. 
  In the attack, reconnaissance must establish the effective 
combat strength, affiliation, combat effectiveness, situation, 
possible concept of enemy operations, and whether or not he has 
nuclear and precision weapons; and discover firing positions of 
weapons, strongpoints and the system of fire in them, gaps, and 
the nature of engineer preparation of positions. It is 
especially important to precisely establish locations of AT 
missile systems and other AT weapons, tanks, and machinegun 
emplacements and the nature of engineer obstacles. It is 
important to identify features of terrain on the FEBA and in the 
depth from the standpoint of its passability by subunits and 
convenience of employing tanks and other vehicles; establish the 
presence on it of sectors which cannot be viewed visually or by 
radar devices and the presence of natural barriers; and 
determine possibilities of negotiating them. 
  The main demands place on reconnaissance are purposefulness, 
continuity, activeness, promptness, concealment, reliability, 
and accuracy in determining coordinates of reconnoitered 
objectives (targets). Attention should be given to timeliness of 
collecting data and transmitting it to the appropriate echelon. 
The transmission of data must conform to its importance. 
Especially important information is reported immediately. 
  Intelligence is collected by various methods. The 
main ones are observation, listening, reconnaissance ambushes 
and raids, questioning local residents, interrogating prisoners 
and defectors, and studying captured enemy documents. 
Information on the enemy also may be received from higher 
headquarters and adjacent subunits. 
  Reconnaissance in the company and in subunits below company 
is conducted ahead of one's frontage to the depth of the combat 
mission (reach of weapons). 
  A general [obzornaya] reconnaissance zone to a depth up to 
10 
km and a detailed [detalnaya] reconnaissance zone to a depth up 
to 5 km are designated in the battalion for conducting 
reconnaissance. The width of reconnaissance zones usually 
coincides with the frontage of battalion operations. 
  A company (battalion) may conduct reconnaissance in 
force, which is organized and conducted just as in an 
attack on a defending enemy from a position of direct contact. 
At this time reconnaissance of all kinds is conducted actively. 
Subunit commanders in a sector where reconnaissance in force is 
conducted observe the battle and study the enemy. 
  Subunits are prepared for a reconnaissance in force in a 
most 
thorough manner. As a rule, they are reinforced by additional 
weapons. 
  Tactical reconnaissance is conducted by reconnaissance 
patrols, combat reconnaissance patrols, patrol squads (tanks) 
and observation posts. A company (battalion) may be assigned to 
a reconnaissance detachment. Radar reconnaissance is conducted 
by moving ground target radar reconnaissance posts. Engineer 
reconnaissance is performed by tactical reconnaissance entities 
and attached subunits of engineer troops. Radiological and 
chemical reconnaissance is performed by specially trained 
squads, crews and teams. Artillery reconnaissance is conducted 
by organic and attached artillery subunits. 
  A reconnaissance patrol as a rule is sent out at 
reconnaissance platoon strength; in addition, it is also sent 
out at MRP (TP) strength from a reconnaissance detachment. Such 
a patrol operates up to 15 km from its subunits, and up to 10 km 
when assigned from a reconnaissance detachment. 
  The combat reconnaissance patrol is sent out at 
MRP (TP) strength to a distance ensuring observation of it and 
its support by fire. Out of contact with the enemy, the distance 
of a combat reconnaissance patrol may reach 10 km. 
  Patrols conduct reconnaissance by patrol squads (tanks), 
observers and foot patrols. They collect intelligence by 
observation, listening, reconnaissance ambushes, raids, 
questioning local residents, interrogating prisoners, and 
studying enemy documents, weapons and vehicles. In addition, a 
combat reconnaissance patrol collects information by battle. 
  A reconnaissance patrol is sent out in all kinds of battle, 
and a combat reconnaissance patrol as a rule in the attack. In 
the defense, for example, a combat reconnaissance patrol may be 
assigned both to flanks as well as to the rear of the defense 
area during a battle when there is a threat of an airborne 
assault force landing or penetration of airmobile and 
maneuvering parties. During movement they displace by bounds, 
from cover to cover. They perform reconnaissance by all 
personnel, basically by observation. A combat reconnaissance 
patrol employs fire if necessary, destroying enemy weapons and 
personnel hampering its operations. Operations of patrols must 
be distinguished by concealment on the one hand and by speed on 
the other. Their personnel are chosen and trained especially 
thoroughly, taking into account that the enemy also conducts 
reconnaissance and attempts to mislead the other side's 
reconnaissance. Data collected must be valid, and so it is 
rechecked. By the way, this also goes for other methods of 
obtaining reconnaissance information. 
  The reconnaissance ambush is conducted to capture 
prisoners, documents and models of enemy weapons and vehicles, 
and a raid in addition is conducted to destroy (disable) an 
installation. Usually a reconnaissance or motorized rifle (tank) 
subunit up to a platoon in strength or a team of specially 
chosen privates and NCO's is assigned to an ambush. The 
raid is conducted by subunits performing 
reconnaissance. 
  The ambush and raid are a very effective reconnaissance 
method, but they must be thoroughly prepared and supported, 
especially from the standpoint of achieving surprise and speed 
in performing the mission. In the Great Patriotic War an ambush 
was prepared based on careful observation of the enemy to 
determine the most advantageous place where it was possible to 
capture prisoners without losses. Such ambushes often were used 
to intercept enemy scouts. 
  The patrol squad (tank) is sent out from a subunit 
conducting reconnaissance or from a platoon (company) performing 
a combat mission in isolation from the main body in order to 
detect the enemy promptly and reconnoiter terrain. It operates 
at a distance ensuring observation of it and its support by 
fire. A patrol squad performs the mission by moving in a BMP 
(BTR) or motor vehicle or in dismounted formation, and in winter 
also on skis. Reconnaissance is conducted by observation and by 
foot patrols. A patrol tank conducts reconnaissance by 
observation. Patrol squads (a tank) may be assigned to set up a 
reconnaissance ambush. 
  A patrol squad (tank) usually operates off the road, moving 
from one point favorable (convenient) for concealed observation 
to another (structure, bushes, edge of grove, reverse slopes of 
hill or elevation, haystack and so on). 
  In case of an encounter with a small enemy group, the patrol 
squad (tank) lets it go by or, by direction of the commander who 
sent it out, organizes an ambush and captures prisoners, 
documents and models of weapons. When there is a surprise 
encounter and it is impossible to evade, the squad (tank) opens 
fire and thereby warns of the enemy's unexpected appearance. 
  Observation is the principal method of reconnaissance in 
subunits in all kinds of battle. It is conducted continuously by 
commanders personally, by observation posts, by observers of 
tanks, squads, platoons and companies and by duty weapon crews. 
  Observation is organized so as to ensure the best view of 
the 
enemy and terrain ahead of the front, on the flanks and in the 
rear to the greatest possible depth. Special attention must be 
given to sectors difficult to view and to conducting observation 
of their approaches. 
  For the most thorough observation, it should be conducted 
systematically, in a certain sequence of actions. Thus, it is 
advisable to have observers conduct it in sectors and to divide 
a sector conditionally into zones: near, middle and far. 
  First it is desirable to inspect each zone rapidly so as not 
to miss prominent objects which may disappear in time. Then 
observation continues in the zones-first the near, then the 
middle and so on. Objects in zones should be inspected from 
right to left with consideration of terrain relief and the 
presence of local features, where disposition of particular 
enemy forces, installations and assets is possible. 
  Observation is conducted at night and under other conditions 
of limited visibility using night vision device, moving ground 
target reconnaissance radars, and terrain illumination assets 
and is supplemented by listening. 
  Observation of the air enemy is conducted by air observation 
posts of air defense subunits, by the company (battalion) 
recognition and identification point (post), and by observers 
and observation posts. Radiological and chemical observation is 
conducted by chemical observers of companies and by battalion 
observation posts. 
  In the defense (Diagram 25) the company posts one or two 
observers and a chemical observer and the battalion posts one or 
two observation posts and one chemical observation post when 
preparing the attack and during disposition at the halt. 
Observers and a chemical observer are assigned in the company 
(battalion) during an attack, meeting battle, withdrawal and on 
the march. An observer is assigned in the platoon in all cases. 
  An observation (chemical observation) post 
consists of 2-3 observers (chemical observers). They are 
equipped with observation devices, a map or terrain diagram, 
observation log, means of communication, and means of giving 
warning signals, and the chemical observation post in addition 
is equipped with chemical and radiological reconnaissance 
devices. 
  The moving ground target radar reconnaissance post 
usually is deployed together with the company (battalion) 
observer (observation post). It is attended by a specially 
trained company operator or by one assigned from the 
reconnaissance platoon. 
  The observation (chemical observation) post and moving 
ground 
target radar reconnaissance post conduct continuous observation 
and register detected instances of enemy activity right down to 
what are at first glance phenomena of little significance, which 
with subsequent comparison with each other and with other data 
may lead to important conclusions about enemy actions being 
taken or prepared. One should adhere to the rule that there are 
no trifles in reconnaissance. 
  A company (battalion) may operate as a reconnaissance 
detachment. In a reconnaissance detachment, reconnaissance 
is conducted by observation, reconnaissance ambushes, raids and 
if necessary also in force. Reconnaissance patrols and patrol 
squads (tanks) are sent out from a reconnaissance detachment. 
  A reconnaissance detachment is formed in the defense and 
offense. In the defense it is sent out in the absence of direct 
contact with the enemy for timely detection of his forward 
movement and deployment and for determining the makeup and 
direction of operations of the main enemy grouping, firing 
positions of weapons and locations of C[.sup]2[/] facilities. 
In the attack a reconnaissance detachment takes advantage of 
gaps and exposed enemy flanks to penetrate into the depth of his 
defense, reconnoiters positions and strongpoints, determines 
locations and directions of forward movement of reserves, 
uncovers the system of obstacles and fortification, and 
determines firing positions of weapons and locations of 
C[.sup]2[/] facilities. 
  A reconnaissance detachment also may perform an active 
mission such as seizure of crossings, passes, road junctions and 
other important objectives. 
  In an encounter with the enemy a reconnaissance detachment 
goes around his reconnaissance and security elements and 
covertly moves up to the main body to reconnoiter its makeup, 
direction of operations, time of passing important lines, 
deployment locations, and occupation of firing positions by 
weapons. 
  On approaching a water obstacle a reconnaissance detachment 
operates broadly and covertly, attempts to detect the enemy's 
presence on it, determines favorable sectors for operations of 
friendly forces, and determines the actual characteristics of 
the obstacle (width, depth), current velocity, steepness of 
banks, presence of fords and other crossings, presence of 
obstacles and so on. 
  In performing missions at night, in a built-up area, in the 
mountains and in the forest, a reconnaissance detachment should 
take into account features of situation conditions and employ 
advisable reconnaissance methods in accordance with them. 
  Under present conditions special attention must be given to 
the preparation and support of personnel of reconnaissance 
subunits and entities when they perform combat missions at 
night. The following is necessary in this connection: thorough 
outfitting with personal gear and equipping of reconnaissance 
entities with moving ground target reconnaissance radars and 
night vision devices; a check of their serviceability; and the 
ability of scouts to conduct observation at night, competently 
select a place for observers and posts, and have a good 
knowledge of revealing signs of targets and other objectives. 
  For example, at night the terrain is better viewed from a 
hollow inasmuch as in this case the object of observation is 
projected against the background of the sky. It is possible to 
determine the distance to it based on a light source. 
  But at night it is possible to have an error of 50 percent 
or 
more in determining a specific distance to a light source. 
  Sounds can be a good source of information at night. For 
example, a conversation is audible at 200-300 m, the sound of 
axe blows at 300-400 m, small arms being loaded up to 500 m, 
operation of a tank engine in place up to 1,000 m, a rifle shot 
up to 2-3 km and a round from an artillery piece up to 5 km. 
  The ability to orient oneself well in the darkness and use 
of 
various methods for this--azimuth, relief, roads, edges of 
groves, outskirts of built-up areas, high-voltage transmission 
lines, telegraph poles, streams and stars-play an exceptionally 
important role for successful performance of night 
reconnaissance missions. 
<H5>  3. Security </H5>
  Security is organized and accomplished in all forms of 
combat 
activity. It has the purpose of preventing penetration of enemy 
reconnaissance into the operating (disposition) area of friendly 
subunits, precluding a surprise attack of the ground enemy and 
of his airborne assault forces (airmobile groups) on them, and 
giving protected subunits time and favorable conditions for 
deployment (placing themselves in combat readiness) and 
engagement. 
  Depending on the nature of missions performed, subunits are 
secured as follows: in battle by combat security 
outposts, on the march by march security, during 
disposition at the halt by security at the halt. In 
addition, local security is organized in all cases. 
  A combat security outpost is sent out by direction 
of the senior commander or by decision of the company 
(battalion) commander. March security and security at the halt 
is sent out by direction of the senior commander, or 
independently during operations in isolation from the main body. 
Local security is organized by subunit commanders depending on 
the mission being performed, situation conditions and the senior 
commander's instructions. It is performed by sentries, patrols 
and listening posts with consideration of the organization of 
alert duty of weapons, observation, and commandant's service. 
  In organizing security it is necessary to indicate the 
following: axes on which special attention must be concentrated; 
place to have security and its makeup; time for sending it out 
(posting it) and missions; password and reply. 
  Constant combat readiness, strict observance of the 
prescribed procedure for alert duty and actions, observance of 
maskirovka measures, and a display of high vigilance as well as 
decisiveness and staunchness are required of security personnel. 
All security personnel must know the password. The reply is 
given to commanders of security subunits. 
  Usually a platoon is assigned to a combat security outpost 
from a battalion in the defense. This platoon is given a 
position up to 2 km from the FEBA. The platoon establishes a 
strongpoint at this position and conducts defense in accordance 
with requirements and provisions of the tactics of defensive 
battle. Missions of the combat security outpost are to secure 
the battalion main body against an enemy surprise attack and 
prohibit him from conducting reconnaissance. 
  In the attack, combat security outpost missions are assigned 
basically to combat reconnaissance patrols. 
  March security is an element of the march 
formation. In addition to security, it also performs the task of 
reconnaissance. A battalion usually sends out a combat 
reconnaissance patrol. In an encounter with the enemy, march 
security destroys his security element and reconnaissance, moves 
to the enemy main body and immobilizes it, providing favorable 
conditions for operations of the battalion (company) main body. 
  Security at the halt is intended for security of 
subunits during their disposition at the halt. In the battalion 
it is accomplished by security posts and listening posts. In a 
company assigned to an outpost it is accomplished by security 
posts. Obstacles are emplaced, listening posts, observation 
posts and two-man patrols are sent out and technical signaling 
devices are used ahead of the FEBA and in gaps between positions 
of security at the halt. 
  Local security is organized and accomplished 
constantly under all conditions regardless of the nature of 
actions being performed, how far off the enemy is, and the time 
of year and day. 
<H5>  4. Protection Against Mass Destruction Weapons </H5>
  Armies of the United States and other NATO countries 
continue 
to rely on use of nuclear and chemical weapons in war. Both the 
munitions as well as their delivery vehicles are constantly 
being improved. All this makes protection of troops against 
these weapons especially important. 
  Protection against mass destruction weapons is organized and 
accomplished for maximum weakening of the effect of enemy NBC 
weapons and results of destruction of enterprises of the nuclear 
and chemical industry, and for preserving combat effectiveness 
and ensuring successful performance of combat missions by 
subunits. It should be organized to the full extent in 
conducting battle both with and without the use of mass 
destruction weapons. 
  It includes the following: dispersal of subunits and a 
periodic change of the areas they occupy, and sometimes also of 
their positions; fortification of one's areas (positions) and 
preparation of maneuver routes; warning subunits about the 
immediate threat and beginning of enemy use of mass destruction 
weapons, about destruction of enterprises of the nuclear power 
and chemical industry, and about friendly nuclear strikes, and 
also warning the personnel about NBC contamination. It also 
includes accomplishment of antiepidemic, sanitary-hygienic, and 
special preventive medicine measures, identifying and mopping up 
the consequences of enemy use of mass destruction weapons, and 
assurance of personnel security and protection during operations 
in zones of contamination and areas of destructive damage, fires 
and flooding. 
  Protection against mass destruction weapons is organized and 
accomplished based on the subunit commander's decision and 
senior commander's instructions with consideration of the nature 
of the mission being performed and actions being accomplished. 
The commander usually indicates: procedure for 
dispersal of subunits, change of disposition areas, and use of 
protective properties of terrain and equipment; procedure for 
warning of the immediate threat and beginning of enemy use of 
mass destruction weapons; signals warning of NBC contamination 
and procedure of actions in response to them; time periods for 
conducting antiepidemic, sanitary-hygienic and special 
preventive medicine measures; procedure for mopping up in the 
aftermath of enemy use of mass destruction weapons; safety 
measures during operations in zones of contamination and areas 
of destructive damage, fires and flooding. 
  The specific content of each of the indicated measures 
depends on situation conditions, and particularly on missions 
being performed, the subunit's situation and makeup, missions 
and operations of adjacent subunits, nature of terrain, weather 
and time of year. 
  Dispersal, a change of areas (positions) and their 
fortification are among the most important measures of 
protection. Thus, dispersal should reduce losses of subunits and 
simultaneously ensure firm C[.sup]2[/], coordination and 
successful conduct of battle. 
  Platoons (companies) are the elements to be dispersed in the 
company (battalion). In the defense gaps may be up to 300 m 
between platoon strongpoints and up to 1,000 m between company 
strongpoints. Dispersal in depth is achieved by disposing a 
portion of the forces behind subunits defending in the first and 
second trenches. For example, the second echelon company in the 
battalion may be up to 400-600 m from first echelon companies. 
In the attack, lateral dispersal is ensured by an interval of 
50-100 m or more between vehicles and platoons (in the 
assaulting line). Dispersal in depth is achieved by the position 
of platoons (companies) in the battle formation as an echelon or 
wedge, and in the battalion in addition by the distance of the 
second echelon (reserve) and artillery from the assaulting line. 
  A change of areas (positions) is envisaged and carried out 
under the outlined plan and by direction of the senior 
commander. It is accomplished covertly and in a short time. 
Subunits usually change areas successively so a high degree of 
combat readiness is preserved on the one hand and maskirovka 
both of the portion of forces remaining in the occupied area as 
well as of subunits moving into another area is ensured on the 
other hand. The other part of subunit forces does not begin 
moving until completion of the move to the new area, 
consolidation in it, and full maskirovka. Areas left by the 
subunit should be maintained as real ones by simulating 
occupation, i.e., they become dummy ones. 
  Positions and areas are fortified and maneuver routes 
prepared in accordance with directions of company (battalion) 
commanders on engineer support. In particular, in the defense 
emplacements, trenches, communication trenches, dugouts and 
bunkers for personnel and emplacements and shelters for weapons 
and vehicles are prepared at positions and in strongpoints and 
areas. Bunkers with special equipment should support the safe 
presence of personnel in them without individual protective gear. 
  Fortification should begin immediately on subunits' arrival 
at the position or in the designated area. Fortification 
structures reduce penetrating radiation by tens of times, 
protect against thermal radiation of nuclear bursts, and protect 
against liquid-droplet chemical agents. Thus, with an air burst 
of a 20 KT nuclear weapon, the radius of the combined casualty 
zone for personnel in the open is around 1,500 m and the area of 
the zone is around 8 km[.sup]2[/]. But if personnel are in 
emplacements, slit trenches or trenches during the burst, then 
the radius of the combined casualty zone is reduced to 1,000 m 
and the area of the zone to 3 km[.sup]2[/]. Consequently, 
even very simple fortification structures reduce the area of the 
personnel casualty zone from a nuclear strike by approximately 
2.8 times. With respect to protection by such structures as 
dugouts, the casualty area of personnel in this case is reduced 
by 25 times compared with their being in the open. 
  In all cases, especially with a shortage of time, it is 
necessary to take advantage of protective and concealing 
properties of terrain--forest tracts, ravines, hollows, caves, 
mines (quarries) and other natural cover. But taking into 
account that woods, hollows and ravines facilitate persistence 
of chemical agent vapors and biological aerosols, it is also 
necessary to check such terrain features carefully. 
  With the appearance of the immediate threat and beginning of 
enemy use of mass destruction weapons or delivery of friendly 
nuclear strikes, subunits are warned by the company (battalion) 
commander by direction of (at a signal from) the battalion 
(regimental) staff based on intelligence. Subunits are notified 
immediately over all means of communication by unified signals 
constantly in effect. 
  Steps are taken ensuring protection of subunits on receiving 
a signal warning of NBC contamination. Personnel in the open put 
on individual protective gear and those in closed fighting 
vehicles (BTR's) put on breathing masks (protective masks). 
  Hatches, doors and firing ports in fighting vehicles and 
tanks are closed and the system of protection against mass 
destruction weapons is turned on. Personnel in protective 
shelters turn on the collective protection system. 
  For antiepidemic, sanitary-hygienic and preventive purposes, 
protective inoculations are given, careful monitoring of all 
servicemen's observance of rules of personal and social hygiene 
is organized, and special protective drugs (antidotes, 
antibiotics, antiradiation and other drugs) are used based on a 
comprehensive estimate of the possible situation in case of the 
use of mass destruction weapons. These measures are carried out 
by direction of the senior commander or independently when there 
is immediate danger. 
  In case of enemy use of mass destruction weapons it is 
necessary to identify the consequences without delay: determine 
losses, the personnel's morale and the scale and nature of 
contamination, destructive damages, fires and flooding. This is 
done based on subunit commanders' personal observation, reports 
from subunits and the data of various kinds of reconnaissance 
and of radiological and chemical monitoring. Based on the data 
received and their estimate, the subunit commander makes a 
decision in which he determines the procedure for moving 
subunits out of the danger area, restoring combat effectiveness, 
mopping up in the aftermath of enemy use of mass destruction 
weapons, as well as further actions. And it is important 
initially to determine the combat-effective subunits and methods 
of their actions in the situation at hand, and then the specific 
content of measures for mopping up in the aftermath of the use 
of mass destruction weapons and the procedure for carrying them 
out. 
  In mopping up in the aftermath of enemy use of mass 
destruction weapons it is necessary to reconnoiter the stricken 
area, organize rescue operations, give first aid to victims, 
transport or carry them out of the casualty (contamination) 
zone, evacuate them to aid stations and perform emergency 
prevention. Then perform decontamination of subunits and 
personnel. Simultaneously with this, one should clear rubble, 
organize the extinguishing of fires and perform restrictive 
isolation measures. 
  Partial decontamination of subunits and personnel should be 
carried out by order of the commander without ceasing to perform 
the combat mission. Complete decontamination is performed by 
order of the senior commander. 
  In connection with the vastness of zones of contamination 
and 
destructive damage, a subunit often may end up in them at full 
strength. Under these conditions it is necessary to take steps 
to ensure safety and protect personnel. For this it is necessary 
to constantly keep an eye on the NBC situation in the area of 
operations, changes on the terrain and the degree of personnel 
exposure. In case the danger of personnel injuries appears, 
promptly use protective gear, clarify the method of actions and 
strictly monitor the personnel's observance of rules of conduct 
on contaminated terrain. 
  In a situation where a subunit has to cross a zone with a 
high level of contamination, it is advisable to go around it. 
But if that is impossible, such a zone should be crossed at 
maximum speed along axes ensuring least injury and contamination 
of personnel and vehicles. In all cases reconnaissance should be 
carried out for this purpose, such as sending out a specially 
trained patrol squad (tank). 
  Maintaining direct contact with the enemy is an indirect 
measure of ensuring personnel safety from injury by mass 
destruction weapons; this will hamper him in employing his 
weapons because of the threat of injury to his own troops. 
Therefore in the attack, for example, one should close quickly 
with the enemy and pursue him relentlessly. 
  In all cases, increased safety of friendly subunits is 
ensured by thorough measures of maskirovka, use of natural 
cover, and rapid execution of a maneuver. 
  Under present conditions not only weapons of mass 
destruction, but also conventional precision weapons have begun 
to possess great casualty and damage effect. According to 
foreign specialists' views, to a certain extent their combat 
effectiveness is even becoming comparable with low-yield 
tactical nuclear weapons. Thus, just one T-22 or T-16 rocket of 
the J-SAK reconnaissance-strike complex (of the Assault Breaker 
type) is capable of killing around ten armored targets with high 
probability (0.7-0.8). Accordingly, just one salvo of a 
battalion of such rockets (6 launchers) potentially can disable 
almost up to two tank battalions. Aviation and field artillery 
presently have precision guided homing weapons. AT precision 
weapons (AT guided missiles) have become especially numerous in 
combat arms subunits and units. 
  It is obvious that without taking effective steps to counter 
enemy use of such weapons and to reduce their effectiveness 
against a subunit, it is difficult to ensure preservation of 
combat effectiveness on the modern battlefield even when nuclear 
weapons are not used. Therefore along with measures of 
protection against mass destruction weapons there also has to be 
protection against precision weapons. 
  In principle, some of the measures of protection against 
mass 
destruction weapons as well as measures of electronic warfare 
and maskirovka also provide protection against precision 
weapons. In all cases capable use of protective properties of 
terrain and combat vehicles, skilled use of maneuver and 
thorough air defense organization also serve the purposes of 
effective protection against mass destruction and precision 
weapons. 
<H5>  5. Electronic Warfare </H5>
  Various electronic equipment is playing an ever larger role 
in development of means of warfare, especially systems and 
methods of C[.sup]2[/] of subunits and units in battle. Under 
present conditions C[.sup]2[/] of subunits and weapons 
essentially is based completely on the use of various electronic 
equipment. These are the radios of command and staff vehicles, 
tanks and BMP's (BTR's) and the electronic equipment of AT 
missile systems, air defense subunits, aircraft, helicopters, 
and artillery, reconnaissance and other subunits. The use of 
electronic equipment for reconnaissance, C[.sup]2[/] and 
precise guidance in particular permitted realizing modern 
precision weapons systems. Such systems include the J-SAK 
reconnaissance-strike complex (Assault Breaker program), which 
uses an airborne radar system for reconnaissance and weapon 
guidance, an automated system for transmitting commands to 
weapons, and homing submunitions of the Skeet or Gem type 
delivered to the target by ground or air-launched missiles with 
cluster warheads. ATGM's also are included among precision 
weapons. Thus, the TOW ATGM has a semiactive opto-electronic 
guidance system and a range of fire up to 4 km and the Hellfire 
ATGM has a laser active guidance system and a range up to 6 km 
(in the future 8-10 km or more). The electronic guidance system 
permits having a hit probability on an armored target by an 
artillery projectile of 0.5-0.6 or more at a range around 16 km 
(Copperhead projectile and so on). 
  The use of electronic equipment in modern battle took on a 
broad character and began to characterize the so-called 
electronic environment. 
  In connection with the fact that use of electronic equipment 
led to a considerable increase in quality and reliability of 
C[.sup]2[/] and to a sharp growth in effectiveness of 
weapons, it is possible to substantially hamper reconnaissance 
and C[.sup]2[/] and reduce the effectiveness of weapons and 
other combat assets by affecting electronic equipment. Therefore 
along with inflicting direct damage on the enemy by fire and 
strikes, in accomplishing the most varied combat missions each 
of the opposing sides also will attempt to disrupt or hamper the 
operation of enemy electronic equipment and systems while 
simultaneously taking all steps to ensure stable operation of 
his similar equipment. As a result a new phenomenon arises in 
conduct of modern combat operations-- electronic warfare [EW] 
[radioelektronnaya borba]. 
  EW represents a complex of subunits' measures and actions 
interrelated by goal, missions, place and time and directed 
toward detection and subsequent destruction and electronic 
suppression [radioelektronnoye podavleniye] of enemy electronic 
equipment, and also electronic protection [radioelektronnaya 
zashchita] of friendly means of C[.sup]2[/] and fire control, 
and opposition [protivodeystviye] to enemy technical 
reconnaissance equipment. Its importance received special 
confirmation during local wars in Southeast Asia and in the Near 
East, where successful performance of EW missions had a very 
direct influence on the course and outcome of combat operations. 
  EW is organized and conducted in the battalion to 
disorganize 
C[.sup]2[/] of opposing enemy subunits, degrade the 
effectiveness of employment of his weapons and technical 
reconnaissance equipment, and also ensure stable operation of 
means of C[.sup]2[/] of friendly subunits and of fire 
control. It is accomplished in close combination with fire 
damage and destruction of the principal enemy means of 
C[.sup]2[/] of subunits and weapons. It is conducted by 
fulfilling certain measures of electronic suppression, 
electronic protection of friendly means of C[.sup]2[/] of 
subunits and weapons, and opposition to enemy technical 
reconnaissance equipment. It is also conducted in coordination 
with performance of reconnaissance and maskirovka missions. 
  The battalion commander organizes conduct of EW in subunits. 
He should provide for and organize fulfillment of such measures 
as detection (reconnaissance) of enemy electronic targets and 
their engagement by fire of available weapons, electronic 
suppression of enemy electronic equipment, opposition to his 
technical reconnaissance equipment, and protection of friendly 
electronic equipment and other installations. 
  To resolve these matters back when analyzing the mission 
that 
was received it is necessary to understand the following: what 
EW measures are being planned by the senior commander and what 
is the mission of one's own subunit in their fulfillment; and 
what is to be done in what time periods, by what means, and by 
what methods. 
  In the course of the situation estimate, along with other 
matters the battalion commander also should determine whether or 
not the enemy has guided weapons, what their strong and weak 
points are under given conditions, locations of C[.sup]2[/] 
facilities and observation posts, and locations of his 
electronic equipment and, based on this, outline conditions and 
the advisable method and procedure of combating that equipment. 
  It is especially important to correctly estimate the terrain 
and the effect of weather and time of year and day and to 
determine on what lines and at what time it is advisable to lay 
smoke screens and turn on IR searchlights, and at what places it 
is advantageous to use concealing and camouflaging properties of 
terrain for protection against enemy technical reconnaissance 
equipment. 
  In estimating friendly subunits, one should determine the 
vulnerability of friendly guided weapon systems and necessary 
measures for their electronic protection and for ensuring stable 
C[.sup]2[/] of friendly subunits under conditions of enemy 
ECM [radioelektronnoye protivodeystviye]. It is necessary to 
take into account the operation of electronic equipment of 
adjacent subunits and of friendly troops and determine how to 
avoid mutual interference with that equipment during 
simultaneous operation. 
  In organizing EW the battalion commander indicates 
the following: what enemy C[.sup]2[/] facilities and 
installations are to be destroyed by fire or captured (disabled) 
and at what time, and the forces and assets to be used for this; 
procedure for employing electronic suppression assets; missions 
for electronic protection and for opposition to enemy technical 
reconnaissance equipment; and readiness times. 
  EW measures are reflected on working maps of subunit 
commanders, where one should indicate fire damage of enemy 
electronic targets, the lines, time and methods of laying smoke 
screens, lines and time for turning on IR searchlights, areas 
and lines for radar and thermal maskirovka, dummy C[.sup]2[/] 
facilities and positions, and places for setting up decoy flares. 
  In conducting EW in the battle of motorized rifle and tank 
subunits, the primary targets for fire engagement should be 
considered the electronic equipment of C[.sup]2[/] facilities 
of enemy mechanized infantry (tank) companies and battalions, 
artillery battalions (batteries) and air defense subunits with 
their electronic equipment, reconnaissance subunits (entities) 
employing electronic equipment for surveillance (detection, 
intersection) and communications, AT subunits as a whole, 
individual ATGM systems on an armor base, portable ATGM systems, 
as well as facilities for C[.sup]2[/] of aviation (forward 
air controller points). 
  An electronic target [radioelektronnyy obyekt] is understood 
to mean one of the elements of the system for C[.sup]2[/] of 
troops (subunits) and weapons outfitted with electronic 
equipment. Thus, in the battalion C[.sup]2[/] system of 
armies of the United States and FRG the primary electronic 
targets are the communications center of the battalion command 
(observation) post and the moving ground target reconnaissance 
radar (AN/PPS-5), as well as communications centers of command 
posts of artillery battalion C[.sup]2[/], mortar locating 
radars (AN/TPQ-36) and artillery locating radars (AN/TPQ-37) 
included in the Firefinder non-visual target acquisition system, 
which in turn operate as part of the TACFIRE field artillery 
automated C[.sup]2[/] system (USA). 
  In the course of battle those targets are disposed as 
follows: battalion (mechanized infantry battalion, tank 
battalion) CP 2-4 km from forward subunits in the defense and 
0.5-1.5 km in the offense; 155-mm SP howitzer artillery 
battalion CP 3-8 km from the FEBA; and field artillery radar 
positions are selected within 3-10 km from the FEBA. 
  In addition, three radio nets are established in battalions 
for C[.sup]2[/] of subunits: command, intelligence and rear. 
Communications with subordinate subunits is accomplished only 
with radios in the UHF frequency band (30-76 MHz). With 
introduction of the TACFIRE and Adler automated field artillery 
fire control systems in armies of the United States and FRG, the 
electronics of these systems accommodated at battery CP's and 
firing positions and at forward observation posts also should be 
regarded as electronic targets to be affected at the company 
(battalion) level. As we know, the TACFIRE (Adler) system 
enables rapid computer-assisted processing of target data and 
calculation of firing data at the battery-artillery group level 
in a matter of seconds. Therefore timely detection and 
destruction of its electronic targets is an important condition 
for sharply degrading the effectiveness of enemy field artillery 
fire. 
  Forward air controllers are in battle formations of first 
echelon battalions (1-2 km from the line of forward subunits, 
including at CP's of these battalions). They help aircraft 
locate targets and vector them to targets. Forward control posts 
equipped with radios for communicating with ground air control 
facilities and with aircraft are technical air control entities 
usually disposed in operation areas of first echelon battalions 
(brigades). Laser target designation devices for illuminating 
ground targets also are installed at the forward control posts 
in support of aimed strikes by aircraft using aircraft weapons 
with laser guidance systems. 
  CP's of Chaparral-Vulcan and Stinger batteries located 2-4 
km 
from the FEBA should be considered electronic targets in the 
enemy air defense system. They have some of the elements of the 
AN/MPQ-49 radar system for acquisition of low-flying targets-- 
the AN/TPQ-32 radars. 
  MRC's (TC's) and MRB's (TB's) can successfully engage all 
the 
aforementioned targets by fire of their supporting artillery 
subunits (batteries, battalions). Performing EW missions by fire 
damage of enemy electronic targets is part of overall fire 
damage of the enemy carried out in accordance with the 
commander's concept. 
  In determining the procedure for fire damage of a target, it 
should be taken into account that a battalion CP usually is 
disposed in an area of around 1.52 hectares and up to 300 rounds 
(6 artillery pieces) are necessary for its destruction in 
shelters. At the same time it should be taken into account that 
the fire of one battery with that ammunition expenditure 
sometimes will require a time of several tens of minutes, and in 
this interval the CP may change places (move out from under the 
strike). Therefore in a number of cases it is more advantageous 
to deliver a fire strike against a CP not with a battery, but 
with a battalion. The mission will be executed faster and the 
target will not manage to get out from under the strike. 
  Engaging an artillery battalion CP (the area is the very 
same-- 1.5-2 hectares) requires around 500 rounds and conduct of 
fire by a battery or battalion. Engaging the CP of a 
Chaparral-Vulcan or Stinger battery, forward air controllers and 
radars requires around 200-220 rounds and conduct of fire by a 
battery (six pieces). Engaging those targets disposed in the 
open requires an ammunition expenditure approximately 3-4 times 
less. 
  Electronic suppression is conducted in the 
battalion to disrupt operation of enemy infrared and laser 
reconnaissance and weapon control equipment by using active and 
passive jammers mounted on the vehicles (objects) being 
protected. To perform missions of electronic suppression of 
enemy electronic equipment in the company (battalion), it is 
necessary to use tank and BMP thermal smoke apparatus, the smoke 
grenade launching system, IR searchlights and smoke hand 
grenades (smokepots) and also employ artillery smoke ammunition 
of supporting artillery subunits. Use of these assets is 
especially effective in combating enemy AT weapons such as 
ATGM's. 
  It is common knowledge that it is typical of the ATGM 
control 
system that the missile is tracked automatically during flight 
using the infrared coordinator of a device guiding on signals of 
the missile's onboard tracking flare. Based on data of the IR 
coordinator, the guidance device computer automatically produces 
commands transmitted to the missile over a wire communication 
line (at the present time) and which adjust its flight along the 
line of sight with the target. 
  Such a control system has three basic functional channels: 
target sighting (tracking), missile tracking, and transmission 
of signals--guidance commands. The first two channels are the 
most vulnerable: they have an open atmospheric sector and by 
affecting it with smoke it is possible to disrupt or hamper 
control of the missile and thereby sharply degrade its hit 
probability. Another vulnerable element of the sighting channel 
is the optical sightoperator link, which can be affected by 
blinding-type interference (such as flashes of firing or a 
shellburst) and by creating heat-emitting decoys in case a 
thermal-imaging night sight is used. Creation of interference 
using an IR searchlight which simulates missile tracking flare 
emissions is an effective form of jamming the guidance device's 
IR coordinator. 
  Interference with the new Hellfire ATGM with semiactive 
laser 
homing head also can be created successfully by electronic 
suppression assets. Vulnerable spots of this system are channels 
for laser illumination and for target tracking from aboard a 
helicopter and by the missile homing head. Operation of these 
channels can be disrupted by remote laying of smoke screens by 
artillery rounds and by creating smoke screens near the target 
using thermal smoke apparatus of tanks and BMP's. It is also 
advisable to create heatemitting decoys inasmuch as this may 
help reduce the effectiveness of Hellfire missiles and of homing 
submunitions of cluster warheads on the missiles of 
reconnaissance-strike complexes. Infrared pyrotechnic cartridges 
and smoke grenades fired from tanks (BMP's) as well as burning 
smokepots, which are a source of thermal emissions, can be such 
heat-emitting decoys. 
  Protection of friendly electronic equipment 
against damage by enemy munitions which home on emissions, 
against enemy electronic suppression, and against the effect of 
ionizing and electromagnetic emissions of nuclear bursts is an 
important component of EW. 
  The principal method of protecting company (battalion) 
electronic equipment against damage by enemy munitions which 
home on emissions is by rigid regulation of their operation. 
This is achieved, for example, by turning on electronic 
equipment only for the time necessary for performing the combat 
mission, by using intermittent emission modes, by changing 
operating frequencies and by employing diversionary (imitative) 
sources of electromagnetic emissions. Using directional 
antennas, selecting frequencies favorable (stable) for given 
conditions, maneuvering operating frequencies and radio 
operating data in a timely manner, operating radio equipment on 
reduced power, and siting operating radio equipment with 
consideration of the terrain's screening properties and of the 
location and power of adjacent radios and other sources of 
electromagnetic emissions also are advisable. 
  One should pay attention to the following in considering 
questions of protecting friendly electronic equipment. In 
conducting EW support measures [radiotekhnicheskaya razvedka] 
and in jamming, NATO armies attach great importance to 
"compelling" radio operators of the net being reconnoitered to 
shift to clear-text transmissions. it is believed that along 
with a terrain relief analysis, intercepting the names of built- 
up areas, reference points and directions mentioned in such 
transmissions can substantially facilitate reconnaissance 
missions. 
  It is obvious that one of the simplest but very important 
requirements for ensuring good protection of friendly electronic 
equipment against enemy jamming is strict observance of rules of 
radio traffic and maximum reduction of the time of going on the 
air to transmit, basically by using brief signals and commands. 
The use of redundant communication channels and signaling 
devices was a very effective measure based on the past war's 
experience. 
  Opposition to enemy technical reconnaissance 
assets is one of the most important components of 
electronic warfare. The essence of such opposition is the 
elimination (weakening) of revealing signs of friendly subunits, 
installations, weapons and measures being carried out, and also 
special protection for technical means of data processing and 
transmission. 
  The enemy can conduct space, aerial and ground 
reconnaissance 
using technical means. Radiotechnical, radar, photographic, 
television, thermal, infrared, laser, radiation, acoustic, 
magnetometric, seismic and other means are used for this. 
  Subunits and weapons are concealed and revealing signs of 
their installations and measures being carried out are 
eliminated or weakened by using means of maskirovka and 
simulation of military vehicles, by using the terrain's 
concealing properties, by fulfilling requirements of secure 
C[.sup]2[/], by creating interference to technical means of 
reconnaissance using smoke, by reducing the level of combat 
vehicle thermal emissions, and by other maskirovka measures. 
  The use of radio signaling gear (REMBASS) by the enemy may 
become widespread. He can emplace radio signaling devices on 
probable movement routes and in concentration areas. Subunits 
must constantly observe the surrounding terrain to detect and 
destroy them promptly. 
  The measures for conducting EW examined above are carried 
out 
in all kinds of battle and in other operations to the full 
extent, but with emphasis on those most essential for specific 
situation conditions. Thus, the entire enumerated set of EW 
measures may be used in the defense. In accordance with senior 
commanders' instructions, it is necessary to set up vertical 
screen camouflage nets [maska-ekran], decoy flares, and corner 
reflectors at the places planned for this. Concealing properties 
of terrain are used to the maximum extent. Radar, optical and 
thermal maskirovka measures are carried out to the full extent 
in preparing emplacements and positions in addition to 
maskirovka using improvised materials. It is advisable to create 
a low-density concealing area smoke screen ("smoke haze") and to 
create dummy installations and thermal emission sources. 
  Electronic targets detected in the course of battle should 
be 
destroyed quickly by fire of supporting artillery and mortars 
and also by fire of organic weapons, and smoke screens should be 
used to blind them (in the disposition area of the targets). 
  The necessary maneuver, a change of positions, movement to a 
line of firing positions or launching of a counterattack should 
be carried out using terrain sectors sheltered from observation 
from the enemy's direction, edges of groves, embankments, dams 
and ravines. Use smoke screens in open sectors. 
  In addition to general measures in the attack, the following 
are specific measures: moving to the line of departure using 
terrain sectors sheltered from the enemy's direction, edges of 
groves, hollows and reverse slopes; firing smoke grenades 
against terrain in the direction of enemy EW support and 
surveillance equipment, including helicopters employing ATGM's; 
and deploying and assaulting under cover of smoke screens 
(placed by supporting artillery and organic assets) ahead of the 
FEBA and on flanks. 
  It is advisable to carry out an assault of the enemy FEBA 
and 
penetration of his defense with IR searchlights switched on. 
During the assault and battle in the depth it is advisable to 
make wide use of smoke to blind the enemy and cover friendly 
subunits. It is desirable to create smoke screens in the depth 
at 2-3 lines successively 600-800 m from each other using 
organic equipment of tanks and BMP's. Smoke screens also should 
be created actively during counterattacks of the enemy and when 
going around his strongpoints on the flanks. In assigning 
missions to subunits for operations in the depth, especially for 
the pursuit, it is also necessary to assign them the mission of 
destroying enemy CP's, OP's and radars by a surprise assault, 
and assign some of the subunits (a squad, a platoon) to destroy 
detected targets (electronic equipment) by an assault. 
  When the battalion or company is in the attack position or 
disposition area, and also for countering technical means of 
reconnaissance, subunits should be placed covertly and the 
conduct of radio conversations should be completely precluded. 
Corner reflectors and thermal decoys are set up to simulate 
targets by direction of senior commanders. If the situation 
permits, smoke may be used, but on condition that it not reveal 
yourself or adjacent subunits. 
<H5>  6. Tactical Maskirovka </H5>
  The purpose of maskirovka is to achieve surprise of subunit 
operations and preserve their combat effectiveness. Maskirovka 
missions consist of ensuring concealment of friendly subunits 
and misleading the enemy regarding their makeup, situation and 
the commander's concept. The most important requirements for 
maskirovka are continuity, persuasiveness, variety and 
activeness. Maskirovka measures are carried out immediately by 
subunits when they take up a particular position and are 
accomplished in all kinds of battle and in other operations. 
  Maskirovka missions are performed by a set of measures for 
concealing the simulation and by decoy actions. The set of these 
measures includes the following: use of concealing properties of 
terrain and conditions of limited visibility; use of authorized 
means of maskirovka, local materials and aerosols (smoke); 
modifying the appearance (shape) of weapons and vehicles (by 
setting up various structures on them which change the object's 
external appearance); painting weapons and vehicles to resemble 
the background of surrounding terrain; and preparing (erecting) 
dummy installations, structures, emplacements and so on. 
  Goals of maskirovka also are served by a timely warning to 
subunits about operations of enemy reconnaissance assets and by 
observance of rules of secure C[.sup]2[/], especially of the 
previously established regime of activity in an area or at a 
position. An important role is played by strictly fulfilling 
measures and rules of light, thermal, sound, radio, 
radiotechnical and radar discipline and requirements of 
maskirovka discipline, and by promptly detecting and eliminating 
revealing signs. 
  The subunit commander organizes maskirovka. In so doing he 
indicates basic maskirovka measures; the extent, time 
periods and procedure of fulfilling them; forces and assets for 
accomplishing maskirovka measures; and procedure for observing 
maskirovka discipline in the subunit. 
  Adopting maskirovka measures to protect weapons and military 
vehicles against precision weapons plays an important role. For 
this one should use ravines, reverse hillslopes, radar dead 
ground and other concealing properties of terrain and should 
carry out measures for reducing the radar, thermal and optical 
signature of fighting vehicles with respect to the surrounding 
terrain background. It is advisable to install heat-dissipating 
screens (covers) over heat-emitting surfaces (places) of 
fighting vehicles (tanks, BMP's and so on). There should be wide 
use of thermal simulators (decoy flares) and radar and laser 
reflectors. 
  In the interests of concealment, in organizing for battle it 
is necessary to keep preparatory measures secret and preclude a 
leak of information about upcoming operations--place, times, 
methods, and especially measures for deceiving the enemy. It is 
important that maskirovka measures in turn not draw enemy 
attention (for example, by their simultaneous active 
accomplishment in certain areas). 
  In this connection, to mislead the enemy one should carry 
out 
all maskirovka measures considering the likelihood of their 
perception by the enemy, i.e., one should conjecture what he may 
take to be simulation or a dummy installation and what he may 
take to be real. Decoy actions, a deliberate display of activity 
of real forces and assets on a dummy axis or in a dummy area, 
and simulation of real installations, positions and emplacements 
by creating dummy ones, where the alleged presence and 
functioning of particular assets or subunits is shown by 
recreating appropriate revealing signs, are especially effective 
in this regard. These measures must be determined and carried 
out in accordance with the commander's concept and with the idea 
of deceiving the enemy. 
  It should be borne in mind that decoy actions, simulation, 
and creation of dummy installations of some one subunit should 
not disrupt another subunit's similar measures and not come into 
contradiction with corresponding measures under the senior 
commander's plan. Therefore they must be carried out with his 
authorization. 
  Conducting measures which would create a distorted 
impression 
on the enemy's part about the system of fire and obstacles, 
FEBA, trench trace, location of emplacements of main weapons, 
and about boundaries and flanks is of special significance in 
the defense. To this end an appropriate procedure should be 
thought out for conduct of fire by various weapons before the 
beginning of battle, their maneuver, a change of locations, and 
a change of concealing devices to change the shape of the 
general background at the position, in the defense area, in the 
strongpoint and in gaps between them. One must ensure that the 
enemy forms a distorted impression of the defense alignment or 
is constantly uncertain about its particular status. It is 
especially important to carefully conceal main forces and 
assets, fire sacks, fire ambushes and reserves. 
  In choosing maskirovka methods and means, one should 
consider 
the feature of specific situation conditions: nature of relief, 
coloration of vegetation, and color background of grass. On open 
terrain, for example, it is advisable to camouflage emplacements 
and shelters to resemble spots of bare soil. Open sectors 
unoccupied by subunits are spotted for purposes of maskirovka. 
The number of spots on the terrain should be greater than the 
number of installations being concealed. 
  Camouflage painting of equipment and structures--protective, 
imitative and disruptive--presently is widely used. For example, 
tricolor camouflage painting (black, brown, green) of combat 
vehicles almost doubles the time it takes to detect the object 
and reduces the likelihood of its visual detection by one and 
one- half times compared with single-color painting.[.sup]2[/] 
  Strictest observance of maskirovka discipline is necessary 
in 
all kinds of battle. For example, one must constantly watch to 
prevent revealing signs when on defense, especially in direct 
contact with the enemy. One should not allow excessive 
movements, preclude them in open places, not give commands in a 
loud voice and not light fires at night. In this case even a 
smoldering cigarette can be noticed at a distance up to 500 m, 
and a lit match up to 1.5 km. 
  Disturbed maskirovka should be restored without delay in the 
course of defensive battle. Carry out movements and change 
positions using sheltered routes. Simultaneously with this, 
leave either some assets or a simulation of them at previous 
positions so as not to cause the enemy to suspect a possible 
maneuver. 
  Creating dummy strongpoints, positions, installations and 
movement routes is especially effective in the defense for 
maskirovka of its true alignment. One always should bear in mind 
that dummy installations should not differ from real ones and 
their number must be such that they reliably mislead the enemy. 
  In the attack it is important to conceal preparation for it 
and the place and time of the assault and ensure its surprise. 
For this it is necessary to take advantage of natural concealing 
properties and, where they are insufficient, to employ smoke 
screening and installation of camouflage nets. Smoke screening 
and installation of camouflage nets also should be used 
especially actively on a dummy axis, where an assault also is 
possible. Moreover, it is on such a dummy axis that one must 
show it is the primary axis by means of intensive firing, engine 
noise, movements, radio conversations, conduct of reconnaissance 
and so on. 
<H5>  7. Engineer Support </H5>
  The purpose of engineer support is to create necessary 
conditions for subunits' prompt, concealed forward movement, 
deployment and maneuver; for increased protection of personnel, 
weapons and vehicles against all weapons; and for inflicting 
losses on the enemy and hampering his operations. Engineer 
support in the company (battalion) includes engineer 
reconnaissance, fortification, engineer measures for maskirovka 
and protection against precision weapons, emplacing engineer 
obstacles, breaching obstacles and rubble, making crossings over 
barriers, preparing and maintaining crossings, obtaining and 
purifying water, and preparing water supply points. 
  Successful performance of engineer support missions is 
achieved by having them properly understood by all subunit 
commanders and personnel, by a high level of the personnel's 
engineer training, by skillful use of available means of 
performing engineer work (authorized and improvised equipment 
and material), and by continuous conduct of engineer 
reconnaissance of the enemy and terrain. 
  The subunit commander organizes engineer support. To this 
end, in organizing the defense he indicates the 
following: nature and time periods of fortification and 
maskirovka of positions, strongpoints and disposition areas; 
main axes which must be covered by obstacles; what installations 
must be demolished (prepared for demolition) and the time and 
methods of performing these tasks; and what maneuver routes to 
prepare. The commander of an engineer subunit (if it is 
attached) is told the procedure for using engineer vehicles and 
explosives, places and times for laying minefields and the 
procedure for the engineer subunit's coordination with motorized 
rifle (tank) and other subunits. 
  Positions, strongpoints and defense (disposition) areas are 
fortified by efforts of the subunits themselves with maximum use 
of heavy equipment, with use of explosive charges, local 
materials, constructions and factory-made structures, and with 
consideration of protective properties of terrain. The procedure 
for fortifying strongpoints (positions, areas) and the sequence, 
time periods and extent should be determined based on the 
requirement of the subunit's constant readiness for battle and a 
build-up of the protection of personnel, weapons and vehicles 
against all weapons. 
  Fortification increases survivability of a subunit in the 
defense severalfold. The more time there is, naturally the 
higher the degree of preparation of a position or area. 
  The increase in subunit survivability is determined by the 
fact that as fortification of positions and areas is upgraded, 
personnel will be disposed in ever stronger structures. 
  Engineer measures of maskirovka and protection against 
precision weapons are carried out with consideration of the time 
of year and in accordance with situation conditions, basically 
by using authorized camouflage gear and means of simulation and 
the installation of overhead cover and heat-dissipating screens 
and covers over heat-emitting surfaces of armored equipment. 
  Engineer obstacles are arranged ahead of the FEBA, on 
flanks, 
around weapon emplacements and sometimes also in the depth. 
Subunits emplace mainly explosive obstacles (minefields, mine 
clusters, mined abatis and so on) and nonexplosive obstacles 
(wire fences and entanglements, knife rests, hedgehogs and so 
on). They should be emplaced with consideration of the system of 
fire so that each minefield and other barrier or obstacle is 
covered by fire, especially fire of AT weapons. 
  In organizing the attack the subunit commander indicates the 
following: nature, sequence and time periods for fortification 
and maskirovka of subunit disposition areas in the attack 
position (assembly area); number, places, time and methods of 
breaching passages in enemy obstacles and obstacles ahead of the 
friendly FEBA, and the procedure for marking and maintaining 
them and passing subunits through them; procedure and methods 
for crossing minefields laid by remote minelaying equipment and 
for negotiating difficult sectors; places, kinds and readiness 
time of crossings over water obstacles; forces and assets for 
performing engineer support missions; and the procedure for 
using engineer subunits and their vehicles if they are attached. 
  In the attack it is especially important to organize and 
support the breaching of obstacles and destructive damage and 
the arrangement of crossings over barriers. This mission is 
performed by the subunits themselves and by attached subunits of 
engineer troops. 
  Remotely laid minefields are bypassed along reconnoitered 
axes or, when impossible to bypass, they are crossed through 
breached passages. 
  Non-T/O mineclearing teams at squad (crew) strength usually 
are formed in companies for breaching minefields laid by remote 
minelaying equipment. The team must be trained in mineclearing 
methods. It is provided with a transportable mineclearing set 
and explosive charges. In particular, the team should have a 
mine detector, probe, grappling hook, 10-15 TNT blocks, 10-15 
safety fuze detonator sets and 8-10 standard markers. 
  An obstacle clearing party is formed in the battalion. For 
this the party may be reinforced by a combat engineer platoon, 
bridgelayer (MTU-20), mineclearing unit (UR-77), obstacle 
clearing engineer vehicle (BAT-2 route clearance vehicle), and 
tank with KMT-6 [type of tank mineclearing attachment]. If 
necessary the obstacle clearing party is reinforced by a combat 
arms subunit. Based on experience, such a party advances 400-600 
m behind battalion first echelon battle formations. 
  The preparation and maintenance of crossings in authorized 
amphibious combat vehicles by fording and crossings of tanks 
fully submerged consist of determining and marking sectors 
convenient for forcing a water obstacle, preparing descents into 
and exits from the water, maskirovka and security of crossings, 
commandant's service there, and breaching of obstacles on banks 
and in the water. Existing bridges on a water obstacle often 
will be partially or fully demolished. In the first case it will 
be necessary to strengthen and reinforce them. In the second 
case, if it is a major bridge, reconnaissance is conducted to 
locate and prepare a ford or another accessible method of 
crossing the water obstacle is prepared. Most often in this case 
subunits cross over crossings prepared by the senior commander's 
forces and assets. 
  Engineer subunits also are assigned the task of demolishing 
installations on water obstacles if they may be used by the 
enemy for his own purposes. 
  The battalion obtains and purifies water and prepares water 
supply points by its own efforts using authorized field water 
supply equipment. 
<H5>  8. Chemical Support </H5>
  Chemical support is organized and carried out in motorized 
rifle (tank) subunits to preclude or minimize losses from NBC 
contamination, provide maskirovka by aerosols (smoke), and 
inflict losses on the enemy by incendiary weapons. Chemical 
support includes the following: radiological and chemical 
reconnaissance; prompt use of individual and collective 
protective gear; radiological and chemical monitoring; 
decontamination of subunits; and use of aerosols (smoke) and 
incendiary weapons. Chemical support measures are performed by 
forces and assets of company (battalion) subunits, but its most 
difficult and specific measures are performed by subunits of 
chemical troops. 
  In resolving problems of chemical support the company 
(battalion) commander determines and issues 
instructions on the procedure for performing radiological 
and chemical reconnaissance and on the place, time and procedure 
for conducting decontamination of subunits. He also indicates 
the procedure and time periods for conducting measures for 
maskirovka of subunits by aerosols (smoke) and the forces and 
assets to be assigned for this, procedure for using attached 
flamethrower subunits, and the procedure for technical 
inspection of protective masks and for providing subunits with 
protective gear. 
  Radiological and chemical reconnaissance is organized to 
provide the commander with prompt data on the radiation and 
chemical situation and warn subunits of terrain contamination. 
It is conducted continuously. A chemical observer is appointed 
for this in the company and a chemical observation post in the 
battalion. Radiological and chemical reconnaissance devices 
which are in combat vehicles (tanks, BMP's and so on) also are 
used. 
  When there is a threat of injury, personnel make use of 
protective gear at the subunit commander's command based on 
reconnaissance data and an estimate of the chemical and 
radiation situation. For prompt use, protective masks and 
breathing masks must be constantly in a traveling position (on 
the person), protective ponchos, footwear and gloves should be 
in vehicles when operating in vehicles and should be with the 
person when operating outside the vehicles. 
  Skilled use of individual and collective protective gear 
plays an important role in protecting personnel against NBC 
contamination. This is achieved by constantly drilling personnel 
in its use and by properly determining the lines and time for 
transferring it to a particular position. 
  Radiological and chemical monitoring also must be constant 
and regular, inasmuch as a conclusion is drawn on its basis 
about combat effectiveness of personnel and the subunit as a 
whole, the possibility of removing individual protective gear, 
and the extent of decontamination. Radiological and chemical 
monitoring is performed by the CW instructor and specially 
trained servicemen. A dose rate meter (ID-1) is issued during 
operations by officers, NCO's and privates performing missions 
apart from the subunit. 
  The subunit keeps a record of the personnel's radiation 
exposure levels: in the company for all personnel, and in the 
battalion an average for the platoon. Chemical monitoring is 
performed in the automatic mode using radiological and chemical 
reconnaissance devices installed in tanks and BMP's. 
  Partial or complete decontamination is performed in 
subunits. 
It consists of NBC decontamination of weapons, equipment, 
clothing, gear, protective gear and supplies. 
  Partial decontamination is organized by order of the company 
(battalion) commander. It is performed by the personnel during 
performance of the mission using authorized means. The 
appropriate chemical decontamination devices and sets (TDP [tank 
decontamination device], DK-4 and so on) available on tanks, 
BMP's, BTR's and trucks are used. Individual chemical 
decontamination devices (of the IDPS-69 type) issued to each 
serviceman are used for decontaminating personal weapons. 
Decontamination is performed immediately when contaminated by 
chemical agents. 
  Complete decontamination of subunits is done by order of the 
senior commander in areas occupied by the subunits or in 
decontamination areas, as a rule after performance of the combat 
mission. Subunits of chemical troops with special vehicles-- 
spray trucks (ARS-14, ARS-15) and chemical decontamination sets 
(DKV)--usually are used to perform it. Crews of tanks (BMP's, 
BTR's) perform the decontamination. Several objects (usually 
four) are processed simultaneously using the spray truck. 
  Use of aerosols (smoke) is organized for maskirovka of 
friendly subunits and also for countering enemy technical means 
of reconnaissance and his means of weapon guidance (homing). The 
following smoke producing munitions and equipment are used for 
smoke generation: white and black smoke grenades, incendiary 
smoke cartridges, thermal smoke apparatus, and an armored 
vehicle smoke grenade launching system. With an oblique wind it 
is advisable to carry out smoke maskirovka by turning on the 
thermal smoke apparatus, and with a head wind toward the enemy 
by using the smoke grenade launching system. With consideration 
of the flight range of smoke grenades (around 300 m), it is 
possible to create a "smoke barrier" for supporting (covering) a 
forward dash to assault the enemy or to execute a maneuver. 
  Thermal smoke apparatus is turned on by the driver and smoke 
grenades are launched by the tank (BMP) gunner on command when 
it is necessary to conceal a crew exit from the vehicle, 
simulate a burning vehicle or cover its maneuver to another 
position. 
  Incendiary weapons are used to engage enemy personnel, 
weapons, vehicles and supplies and create centers of fire in his 
operations area. They are employed in the company (battalion) by 
attached flamethrower subunits. 
Footnotes 
  1. V. I. Lenin, "Polnoye sobraniye sochineniy" [Complete 
Collected Works], Vol 41, p 144. 
  2. See "Inzhenernoye obespecheniye boya" [Engineer Support 
to 
Battle], Moscow, Voyenizdat, 1988, p 239. 
<H5>  Chapter XI - Technical and Logistic Support </H5>
<H5>  1. Technical Support </H5>
  Uninterrupted technical support is one of the basic 
conditions for successful conduct of battle. It consists of the 
organization and accomplishment of technically correct use of 
weapons and vehicles, providing subunits with weapons, vehicles, 
missiles, ammunition and military-technical property, promptly 
replenishing their expenditure and losses, and rapidly restoring 
disabled weapons and vehicles. 
  The scope and content of technical support to subunits 
depend 
on many factors: nature of combat operations, mission being 
performed, subunit's place in the unit battle formation, nature 
of terrain, time of year and day, and so on. But there are 
general principles which are the basis for organizing and 
accomplishing technical support. 
  The following are such general principles: performance of 
technical support missions directly in the course of battle; 
priority performance of primary missions; bringing technical 
support forces and assets as close to subunits as possible and 
their broad maneuver in the course of battle. 
  Technical support missions are performed in the company 
(battery) by vehicle crews (teams, drivers) using spare parts, 
tools and accessories available in each tank, BMP, BTR and motor 
vehicle, with the artillery piece, and in the battery. 
  The battalion has a servicing and maintenance platoon for 
performing technical support missions. The MRB maintenance 
platoon consists of an armored equipment servicing and 
maintenance squad and a motor transport vehicles servicing and 
maintenance squad. The TB servicing and maintenance platoon has 
a servicing and maintenance squad and recovery squad with an 
armored recovery vehicle. 
  Maintenance squads are intended for helping crews (drivers) 
perform servicing and maintenance, remedying minor malfunctions 
and performing nonlaborintensive routine maintenance on weapons, 
vehicles and communications equipment. Equipment of the 
maintenance and service shop permits performing the operations 
of washing filters; checking and adjusting assemblies, machine 
units and mechanisms; remedying failures and malfunctions; 
replacing assemblies and machine units; and touch-up painting, 
external washing and filling vehicles with POL. 
  A battalion may be reinforced by regimental recovery and 
repair assets when operating on a separate axis. 
  The company (battalion) commander is responsible for timely 
technical support of subordinate subunits. He is obligated to 
take steps to keep weapons and vehicles in constant readiness 
for combat use, rapidly restore them when disabled, and provide 
subunits with missiles, ammunition and other militarytechnical 
property. 
  In organizing for battle, in questions of technical support 
the company (battalion) commander usually indicates 
the following: time, place and extent of servicing and 
maintenance; procedure for recovery and repair of weapons and 
vehicles during preparation for and in the course of battle; 
size of reserves of missiles, ammunition and military-technical 
property, time periods for establishing them, their expenditure 
rates and supply procedure; places for deploying the battalion 
servicing and maintenance subunit and procedure for its 
displacement in the course of battle (march); place, time and 
procedure for replenishing subunits' missiles and ammunition; 
procedure for security and defense and for maintaining 
communications with technical support subunits; and he also 
announces disposition areas of maintenance company subunits, 
location of the disabled vehicle collecting point, and the 
regimental evacuation route. 
  In determining the time, procedure and extent of servicing 
and maintenance, the battalion commander proceeds from the 
nature of upcoming battle, his own decision, and the technical 
condition, types and makes of vehicles. 
  Four kinds of servicing and maintenance are established for 
armored equipment and motor vehicles: visual inspection, daily 
routine servicing and maintenance, TO [periodic servicing and 
maintenance inspection] No 1 and TO No 2. 
  The visual inspection is performed at short halts (stops) in 
the course of a march and sometimes also in battle. It averages 
15- 30 minutes for all makes and types of vehicles. 
  As a rule, TO No 1 or 2 is performed depending on engine use 
in preparing for battle to ensure reliable operation of armament 
and vehicles under conditions of lengthy, intensive operation in 
a combat situation. 
  The periodicity and duration of servicing and maintenance of 
armored equipment and motor transport vehicles are given in 
Table 5. 


Table 5 - Periodicity and Duration of Servicing and Maintenance of Weapons and 
Vehicles 

