             Maintenance 

Duration,    Periodicity,    Duration,      Periodicity,    Duration, 
hrs          km              hrs            km              hrs 

T-72         1.5             1,600-1,800    4.5-5.5         3,300-3,500    10-12 

T-64         3.5             2,500          9-10            5,000          13-14 

T-62         2.5-3.5         1,000          5-6.5           2,000          8-12 

BMP          2-3             2,500- 2,600   5-6             4,800-5,000    8-10 


BTR-80       1.1- 1.6        2,000          1.8-2           6,000          6.4-6.6 

BTR- 70      3               2,000          7-8             6,000          14 

Motor        1-2             1,200-1,800    5-6             6,000-9,000    14 
vehicles 


  Experience of the Great Patriotic War and postwar field 
training exercises permitted developing principles of servicing 
and maintenance and of recovery and repair of weapons and 
vehicles under combat conditions. The main ones are the 
following: routine servicing and maintenance of vehicles is 
performed directly in battle formations without removing them to 
the rear, servicing and maintenance assets are brought to the 
vehicles to be serviced, and servicing and maintenance is 
performed by the crews (drivers) using the vehicles' spare 
parts, tools and accessories and with involvement of battalion 
and sometimes also regimental servicing and maintenance 
personnel and assets; vehicles requiring the least amount of 
repair work are evacuated first from under enemy fire to the 
nearest shelters and help is given to lightly stuck vehicles; 
vehicles intended for C[.sup]2[/] of subunits and for 
conducting fire (command and staff vehicles, tanks, BMP's) and 
requiring the least volume of work are repaired initially; 
repair assets are brought to vehicles to be repaired. 
  Technical reconnaissance and control of battalion technical 
support in the course of battle are accomplished from the 
technical observation post, which is headed by the deputy 
battalion commander for weapons. Reserve crew members may be at 
the technical observation post in addition to deputy company 
commanders for weapons (company senior technicians). A technical 
observation post also may be established in a company when it 
operates on a separate axis. The technical observation post is 
located behind battle formations of first echelon companies near 
the battalion (company) COP. Technical reconnaissance is 
performed for prompt detection of disabled weapons and vehicles; 
determination of the causes, nature and degree of their damages; 
determination of the extent of restoration work and necessary 
amount of forces and assets for this; determination of locations 
of the recovery and repair team or repair party. The technical 
observation post maintains constant communications with the 
battalion (company) COP, the recovery and repair team (repair 
party), fighting vehicle commanders, the regimental recovery and 
repair team and the deputy regimental (battalion) commander for 
weapons. 
  A battalion recovery and repair team or repair party is 
established for the time of combat operations from battalion 
servicing and maintenance assets. They perform routine 
maintenance on damaged weapons and vehicles at the places they 
are disabled or in the nearest shelters. 
  In determining the size of and time periods for establishing 
ammunition reserves, its expenditure rates and delivery 
procedure, the battalion commander is guided by the order 
establishing norms of unit-level supplies in the battalion and 
the regimental commander's instructions on ammunition supply and 
consumption norms in a given kind of battle and the procedure 
for their delivery. 
  An ammunition supply point is deployed in the battalion and 
company (during operations in defense) for replenishing tank, 
BMP and BTR ammunition in the course of battle. 
  Local security and defense of disposition areas (locations) 
of technical support subunits and protection against mass 
destruction and precision weapons are accomplished with their 
own forces and assets and within the regiment's overall system. 
  Technical support is organized by the deputy company 
(battalion) commander for weapons (company senior technician) 
based on the commander's decision for battle, his instructions 
on technical support, and instructions of the senior commander 
(chief). 
  The deputy company (battalion) commander for weapons 
(company 
senior technician) is obligated to do the following: constantly 
know the company (battalion) mission, its strength level in 
weapons and vehicles and their technical condition, and state of 
supply of missiles, ammunition and militarytechnical property; 
direct preparation of weapons and vehicles for battle (march) 
and their servicing and maintenance; organize and conduct 
observation of fighting vehicles in battle and determine the 
reasons for their being out of commission; organize the recovery 
and repair of weapons and vehicles, their timely return to duty 
and the transfer of disabled vehicles to the senior commander's 
assets; maintain constant communications with the deputy 
battalion (regimental) commander for weapons and the recovery 
and repair team (repair party), and report to them and his 
commander about the number, location and technical condition of 
disabled weapons and vehicles and steps taken for their 
restoration. 
  In the course of battle the company (battalion) commander 
personally (through the chief of staff, deputy for weapons and 
commanders of platoons or companies) monitors the technical 
condition and combat readiness of weapons and vehicles and the 
expenditure of missiles and ammunition and their timely delivery 
to the subunits, reports on this to the battalion (regimental) 
commander or his deputy for weapons and submits requests for 
replenishing subunits with necessary supplies. 
  Technical support in main forms of battle. In the 
defense the conditions of subunits' shift to the defense exert a 
substantial effect on organization and accomplishment of their 
technical support. 
  The most favorable conditions are created with the advance 
shift of a company (battalion) to the defense or when it is in 
the regimental reserve. In this case there is more time for 
performing technical support measures (Diagram 26). 
  Shifting to a defense in direct contact with the enemy 
hampers the resolution of matters of organizing and 
accomplishing servicing and maintenance. In this situation the 
time for servicing and maintenance of weapons and vehicles will 
be limited and many vehicles will have a considerable 
expenditure of engine time. In addition, vehicle crews (drivers) 
will be engaged in organizing the system of fire and engineer 
preparation of firing positions, shelters and emplacements for 
vehicles and will not be able to take part at full strength in 
the work of servicing and maintenance of weapons and vehicles. 
  The following factors basically influence organization of 
servicing and maintenance under the conditions in question: a 
subunit's defense frontage, nature of terrain, technical 
condition of vehicles, level of training of crews (drivers) and 
the presence of servicing and maintenance and of recovery and 
repair assets. 
  Servicing and maintenance of tanks, BMP's and BTR's when 
shifting to the defense begins with their fueling and 
replenishment of ammunition, performance of visual inspection 
and remedying of detected malfunctions. The procedure for 
fueling vehicles and replenishing ammunition is established by 
the company (battalion) commander and the procedure for using 
means of refueling and ammunition supply by the deputy for 
weapons. 
  Servicing and maintenance is accomplished basically by 
vehicle crews (drivers) with the involvement of the battalion 
maintenance platoon. Sometimes motorized riflemen also may be 
used to assist BMP (BTR) drivers by direction of the company 
commander. 
  The procedure for using the servicing and maintenance 
platoon 
by companies and other subunits is established by the deputy 
battalion commander for weapons, and within companies by the 
commanders and their deputies for weapons (company senior 
technicians). Assets are assigned first to subunits which are 
shifting to defense in the first echelon. 
  Vehicles usually are serviced and maintained directly in 
subunit battle formations. The sequence of servicing and 
maintenance and time allocated are established by the company 
(battalion) commander depending on the situation. The extent of 
servicing and maintenance is determined by the deputy company 
(battalion) commander for weapons (company senior technician). 
  Work connected with partial disassembly of vehicles and 
their 
loss of mobility as well as with moving them to the nearest 
shelters for servicing and maintenance is done only by 
permission of the company (battalion) commander. In all cases, 
at least two- thirds of the vehicles must be in full combat 
readiness when performing servicing and maintenance. 
  Additional ammunition reserves are established in organizing 
defense in subunits and at tank and BMP firing positions. It is 
replenished as expended. Ammunition reserves in subunits are 
immediately replenished after repelling enemy assaults. 
  Recovery and repair of weapons and vehicles in the course of 
battle are done by the battalion recovery and repair team, which 
is located behind the first echelon. Damaged vehicles with 
serviceable weapons capable of fighting are left in the battle 
formation and recovered only by permission of the battalion 
commander. 
  The recovery of damaged tanks, BMP's and BTR's within the 
battalion defense area is done by organic prime movers, and 
recovery to the regimental disabled vehicle collecting point by 
regimental recovery assets. Motor vehicles are recovered by 
battalion assets and also by incidental regimental transport 
delivering supplies, and by vehicles specially assigned for this. 
  With enemy penetration, damaged fighting vehicles are 
evacuated from under fire under cover of the regimental second 
echelon or reserve. In this case fighting vehicles also may be 
used for recovery by permission of the battalion (regimental) 
commander. 
  The procedure for work of commanders and their deputies for 
weapons and the extent of technical support measures taken 
depend on the time allotted for preparing subunits for battle. 
  The following basic measures usually are carried out before 
the beginning of an attack: technical preparation of personnel, 
servicing and maintenance of weapons and vehicles to ensure 
reliable operation in the course of battle, their repair, 
replenishment of ammunition and replenishment of vehicle spare 
parts, tools and accessories. If there is to be a forcing, tanks 
are prepared for a fully submerged crossing of water obstacles 
and the seal of hulls and operation of water jets are checked on 
amphibious BTR's. 
  If the attack is made from a position of direct contact with 
the enemy and tank subunits are moving forward from assembly 
positions, a visual inspection of weapons and vehicles usually 
is made before battle. In a hasty attack, their servicing and 
maintenance is performed in the assembly area, as a rule to the 
extent of daily routine servicing and maintenance. Unserviceable 
fighting vehicles and weapons which cannot be repaired in the 
company and battalion are transferred to assets of the senior 
commander (chief) for repair. 
  A battalion's hasty attack begins with forward movement to 
the line of departure. At this time the support platoon makes up 
the battalion technical maintenance echelon and performs the 
following missions: establishes the places and causes of vehicle 
halts; determines methods of remedying malfunctions; provides 
technical assistance to crews (drivers) of damaged vehicles and 
issues spare parts to them; recovers unserviceable vehicles and 
lightly stuck vehicles from movement routes. 
  Battalion technical maintenance echelon assets are not used 
for repairing vehicles on the march, but move up to the line of 
departure together with the subunits. The technical support 
procedure in the course of battle is shown in Diagram 27. 
  With the beginning of an assault the technical maintenance 
echelon begins performing missions of a recovery and repair team 
or repair party. In the course of battle the recovery and repair 
team recovers damaged vehicles out from under enemy fire, 
performs routine maintenance on them, and extracts lightly stuck 
vehicles. If it is impossible to repair vehicles with one's own 
assets, they are transferred to the regimental disabled vehicle 
collecting point. After repair, weapons and combat and other 
vehicles are immediately returned to their subunits. 
  The duration of work by the recovery and repair team is 
established so as to ensure its arrival at the battalion battle 
formation by the moment the battalion is performing the next 
mission. Duration of the battalion recovery and repair team work 
may be 2-3 hours depending on depth of the mission and planned 
rates of advance. 
  When an MRC attacks in dismounted formation or is on 
defense, 
i.e., when a company ammunition supply point has been 
established, ammunition goes directly to the point and then is 
delivered by ammunition bearers to battle formations of platoons 
and squads and to the BMP's (BTR's). 
  In tank subunits in all cases and in motorized rifle 
subunits 
when attacking in BMP's (BTR's), combat vehicles are replenished 
with ammunition in the course of battle by platoon or by 
vehicle, usually in battle formations and also in breaks between 
battles. 
  After mission accomplishment the battalion commander reports 
the presence and technical condition of weapons and vehicles and 
the state of ammunition supply to the regimental commander and 
gives instructions on the procedure for repairing vehicles for 
the next day of combat operations. 
  Daily routine servicing and maintenance usually is conducted 
on all equipment and weapons of the battalion by day's end. As a 
rule, fighting vehicles are replenished with ammunition and 
filled with fuel and lubricants first. 
  Technical support on the march. Maximum exertion 
of personnel efforts and a large expenditure of engine time will 
be required in a relatively short time interval during a march. 
During 10-12 hours of movement at a speed of 20-25 km/hr, the 
average daily engine expenditure may be 200-250 km or more. 
Therefore technical support during preparation for and in the 
course of the march is one of the deciding factors on which 
company (battalion) combat effectiveness largely depends at the 
line of probable encounter with the enemy or in the 
concentration area. 
  When preparing for the march, reserves of ammunition, fuel 
and technical property are replenished to prescribed norms, 
weapons and vehicles are serviced and maintained and 
unserviceable vehicles which cannot be repaired by the beginning 
of the march are evacuated. Subunits intended for operating in 
reconnaissance and security are serviced first. 
  Before making a march under conditions of difficult terrain, 
special attention is given to preparing devices to increase 
vehicle off-road capability and to the presence and 
serviceability of devices and entrenching tools. The servicing 
and maintenance platoon and vehicles with spare parts and fuel 
are assigned to the technical maintenance echelon. 
  In questions of technical support the deputy commander for 
weapons indicates the following: extent of work of servicing and 
maintenance of weapons and vehicles on the march, methods and 
places for conducting it and assets used; makeup and missions of 
the technical maintenance echelon, its place en route, procedure 
for transferring vehicles not being repaired by one's own 
resources to the senior chief's assets. The makeup and missions 
of the recovery and repair team and the battalion technical 
observation post, their possible locations by the beginning of a 
meeting battle, and direction of displacement in battle are 
determined in addition under conditions of a probable encounter 
with the enemy. 
  In the course of a march the company (battalion) commander 
proceeds at the head of the column and his deputy for weapons in 
the last vehicle in the company or with the technical 
maintenance echelon at the tail of the battalion column. 
  Technical support on the march (Diagram 28) is performed 
directly on the route, at short halts and in the day (night) 
rest halt area. Weapons and vehicles are serviced and maintained 
every 3-4 hours of movement at short halts to the extent of a 
visual inspection; in addition, vehicles are refueled in the 
second half of a day's march and they are serviced and 
maintained to the extent of daily routine servicing and 
maintenance in day (night) rest halt areas. 
  Combat and other vehicles disabled during the march stop on 
the right shoulder of the road. The crew (driver) determines the 
cause of the malfunction and takes steps to remedy it. The 
deputy company (battalion) commander for weapons estimates the 
extent and nature of repair work. If the crew is capable of 
remedying the malfunction, it is issued spare parts and briefed 
on the procedure for performing the work. If necessary, one or 
more specialists are left for the repair. The duration of 
vehicle repair by the technical maintenance echelon on the route 
usually should not exceed the time necessary for the next 
battalion column to approach. 
  In the day (night) rest halt area the deputy company 
(battalion) commander for weapons organizes preparation of 
vehicles for the next day's march or for battle. Fighting 
vehicles which cannot be restored by the technical maintenance 
echelon are transferred to regimental repair assets or recovered 
from the route to shelters. After repair, vehicles continue 
moving and join a passing column. They take their place in the 
subunit at short halts. It is prohibited to overtake columns in 
movement. 
  The deputy company (battalion) commander for weapons reports 
vehicles left en route, steps taken, and the presence and 
technical condition of weapons and vehicles to the company 
(battalion) commander and senior chief. 
<H5>  2. Logistic Support </H5>
  Logistic support is one of the main conditions for 
successful 
battle by a company (battalion). It includes the delivery of all 
kinds of supplies and satisfaction of subunits' needs for them; 
organization and accomplishment of fueling of combat and other 
vehicles; meals for personnel; and medical support. To perform 
these missions the battalion has a support platoon with reserves 
of supplies and an aid station. Logistic support in the company 
is performed by the first sergeant, and in the MRC in addition 
also by the medical party NCOIC. 
  The support platoon consists of a motor transport squad and 
supply squad. The motor transport squad is intended for receipt, 
upkeep and delivery of battalion ammunition and fuel reserves 
and the fueling of vehicles. The supply squad receives and 
maintains reserves of food, delivers and issues it to subunits, 
prepares hot meals and safeguards servicemen's personal articles. 
  The following are deployed to perform logistic support 
missions in battle: in the company during operations 
in defense--ammunition supply point and aid station; 
in the battalion-ammunition supply point, 
refueling point, ration distribution point, and in the 
defense in addition an aid station. 
  Ammunition supply points are intended for replenishing 
subunit ammunition, the refueling point for refueling vehicles, 
and the ration distribution point for preparing hot meals and 
supplying personnel with water. The company aid station and 
battalion aid station determine the sick, search for wounded, 
collect and carry or transport them from the battlefield and 
from stricken areas, give first aid to the wounded and sick and 
prepare them for further evacuation. In addition, where possible 
the battalion aid station gives paramedic assistance and 
accomplishes sanitary-hygienic and anti-epidemic measures, 
medical reconnaissance, and the receipt, storage and issue of 
medical equipment and supplies to subunits. 
  Unit-level reserves are established in prescribed amounts 
for 
uninterrupted support of the company (battalion) with supplies. 
They are kept in fighting vehicles, with the weapons and 
personnel, and in battalion transport. 
  Reserves are divided into expendable supplies and emergency 
reserve (for fuel, a minimum level of supply), which is used by 
authorization of the regimental commander or, in a case brooking 
no delay, by authorization of the battalion commander with a 
subsequent report about this to the senior commander. 
  The requirement for missiles, ammunition, fuel and other 
supplies, their state of supply to subunits and expenditure 
rates are figured in supply units (units of fire, fuelings, 
rations, sets) and other measurement units. The requirement for 
supplies for battle is determined with consideration of their 
established expenditure and the presence of reserves in 
necessary amounts by the end of battle. 
  The amount of missiles and ammunition established per weapon 
or per fighting vehicle is called the unit of fire. 
  The amount of fuel contained in a vehicle (generator) fuel 
system or ensuring its prescribed range (time of operation) is 
called a fueling. 
  A ration is the amount of food prescribed under 
established norms for feeding one person in a 24-hour period. It 
is figured for the roster strength of a subunit. 
  A set of spare parts, tools and accessories for 
weapons and vehicles as well as of clothing, medical and other 
property consists of a set of items according to a specific list 
and in an established amount. 
  Company and battalion needs for supplies are met through 
their own unit-level reserves and by delivery from unit depots. 
If necessary, additional reserves of ammunition, fuel and other 
supplies may be established in the battalion by authorization of 
the senior commander. They are established in battalion 
transport by compact stowage or by freeing up a portion of the 
transport, and before battle also at firing positions of 
artillery and mortars participating in artillery preparation of 
the assault. 
  In the course of battle the expenditure of supplies is 
strictly limited by the having the senior commander (chief) 
establish their consumption rates, especially for ammunition and 
fuel. If it is necessary to replenish subunit ammunition in the 
course of battle the chief of the battalion ammunition supply 
point arranges for delivery (issue) of missiles and ammunition 
by order of the battalion commander (chief of staff). The 
delivery of missiles and ammunition to platoons and to fighting 
vehicles in the company is arranged by the first sergeant by 
direction of the company commander and is carried out by 
appointed ammunition bearers. 
  Replenishment of ammunition and refueling of tanks and BMP's 
(BTR's) in the course of battle is done directly in battle 
formations. If it is impossible to deliver supplies to combat 
vehicles, transportation assets with ammunition and fuel come as 
close to them as possible. Tanks and BMP's (BTR's) take turns 
moving covertly to locations of the transportation assets, 
replenish ammunition and refuel. The support platoon commander 
is responsible for delivering supplies to battalion subunits, 
and subunit commanders are responsible for replenishing 
ammunition and refueling vehicles. 
  Supply delivery usually is by regimental transport to the 
support platoon and from the latter to companies by battalion 
transport. In some cases battalion transportation assets are 
used for delivering supplies from the logistic support company 
to subunits. Missiles, ammunition and fuel are delivered based 
on verbal requests of commanders of companies and separate 
platoons and by order of the battalion commander (chief of 
staff). Stockpiles in subunits should be replenished to unit- 
level norms by the end of the day (or the battle). 
  Personnel are supplied with hot meals through the ration 
point, as a rule three times a day. If it is impossible to 
arrange three meals, personnel are provided with hot meals twice 
a day and a portion of the daily food norm is issued in dry form 
by permission of the battalion (regimental) commander. 
Preparation, delivery and issue of food to subunits is organized 
by the chief of the ration point in accordance with instructions 
of the deputy battalion commander for rear, who determines for 
what number of personnel, for which subunits and by what time to 
prepare food and the procedure for delivering (issuing) it to 
battalion subunits. The first sergeant receives and issues food 
to personnel in accordance with the company commander's 
instructions. 
  With forced organization of meals in zones of radioactive 
contamination the preparation, issue and eating of food is 
accomplished as follows: with a radiation up to 1 rad/hr, in the 
usual manner; from 1 to 5 rads/hr, in radiologically 
decontaminated covered structures. Under these conditions, only 
canned and concentrated food in protected containers and 
packaging is used to prepare meals. In areas contaminated by 
chemical agents it is permitted to prepare and eat food only in 
special structures equipped with air filtration and ventilation 
systems. On terrain contaminated by biological (bacterial) 
agents, meals are prepared and eaten after thorough biological 
decontamination of the grounds, field kitchens and equipment as 
well as complete decontamination of personnel. 
  Subunits are supplied with water from the battalion water 
supply (diversion) point. Delivery of water is organized as a 
rule by the deputy battalion commander for rear. Water for 
preparing food in zones of contamination is delivered in sealed 
containers. 
  Medical support is organized directly in the battalion by 
the 
paramedic; in MRC's (MRP's) by the medical party NCOIC (by 
riflemen-medics); and in TC's and other subunits by their 
commanders. 
  First aid is given to wounded and sick in the form of self- 
administered and buddy-administered emergency first aid, by 
riflemen-medics of platoons and by company medical party NCOIC's 
at the spot of the wound, in the nearest shelter or at the 
company aid station, and also by personnel of subunits assigned 
for rescue operations and for treatment and evacuation measures 
in stricken areas. Paramedic assistance is given at the 
battalion aid station and emergency medical treatment at the 
regimental aid station and at battalion aid stations headed by 
physicians. 
  The wounded are collected and carried or transported from 
the 
battlefield (from stricken areas) with their personal weapons 
and protective masks by battalion aid station forces and assets, 
and if necessary by personnel and transportation assets 
additionally assigned by the battalion (company) commander. When 
there is a significant number of wounded and sick in the 
battalion, the seriously-wounded and seriously-ill are subject 
to evacuation first. Lightly-wounded persons not requiring 
hospitalization are sent to their subunits after being given 
medical aid. 
  The company commander organizes logistic support personally, 
through the first sergeant and through platoon commanders; the 
battalion commander does so through the deputy for rear and the 
company commanders. 
  In questions of logistic support the company (battalion) 
commander usually indicates: size and times for 
establishing reserves of fuel, food, medical equipment and 
supplies, and other supplies, their consumption rates and 
delivery procedure; procedure for searching for, collecting and 
evacuating wounded and sick; places for deployment of battalion 
rear subunits and procedure for their displacement in the course 
of battle (or march); places, time and sequence for refueling 
equipment and vehicles; organization of meals for personnel; 
procedure for security and defense and for maintaining 
communications with rear subunits; and he also announces the 
disposition areas of the regimental logistic support company and 
maneuver, delivery and evacuation routes. 
  During battle the company (battalion) commander monitors 
fuel 
and food consumption and its timely delivery to subunits; 
reports to the battalion commander (regimental commander or his 
deputy for rear) on the supply of fuel and other supplies and on 
the presence of wounded and sick; and submits requests for 
replenishing subunits with necessary supplies. 
  Logistic support in principal forms of battle. The 
scope, times and procedure for carrying out measures for 
preparing the battalion rear depend on the nature of the combat 
mission, status of rear subunits, time available for preparation 
and other factors. When disposed in a defense area, rear 
subunits are reliably sheltered and carefully camouflaged and 
their protection against mass destruction and precision weapons 
and their security and defense are organized. 
  In the period of preparation for battle, reserves of 
supplies 
are built up to prescribed norms in battalion transport, in 
companies and in separate platoons. Battalion subunits and the 
aid station are cleared of wounded and sick. 
  The location of the battalion rear must ensure the 
following: 
rapid, effective use of its forces and assets; possibility of 
executing a flexible maneuver; close coordination of battalion 
rear subunits with each other and with corresponding regimental 
rear subunits; firm C[.sup]2[/]; and a decrease in losses 
from enemy effect. The procedure for battalion logistic support 
in the defense is shown in Diagram 29. Battalion rear subunits, 
including the aid station, are disposed behind its battle 
formation. This is dictated by the need for creating favorable 
conditions for their operation in case the enemy penetrates. 
  Tanks, BMP's (BTR's) and other vehicles are fueled directly 
in battle formations in lulls between battles, as a rule at 
night and under other conditions of limited visibility. 
  In both defensive as well as offensive battle meals are 
organized for personnel so the principal messing falls in hours 
of a drop in combat intensity. The issue to personnel of 
prepared food that has been checked by the paramedic is done by 
permission of the battalion commander or his deputy for rear. 
For this the truck-mounted field kitchen moves to the company, 
where it is met by a guide and directed to cover nearest the 
battle formation. The company first sergeant organizes the issue 
of food by bearers assigned from platoons, who receive it in 
insulated food containers and deliver it directly to the 
personnel. 
  Artillery and mortar subunits attached to the company as a 
rule are fed through their own subunit ration points and the 
others are fed together with the company. 
  Water usually is delivered from the battalion ration point 
simultaneously with hot food. 
  Organization of medical support depends chiefly on 
conditions 
in which subunits shift to the defense and the sanitary 
condition of terrain. 
  When shifting to a defense in direct contact with the enemy, 
evacuation of wounded and sick is organized above all from 
subunits actively fighting the enemy. Trenches and communication 
trenches are widely used in evacuation. 
  An aid station with reserves of means for giving first aid 
and of potable water is prepared in each company for temporary 
shelter of wounded and sick. It usually is located in a 
sheltered spot with consideration of the possibility of 
concealed carrying (transporting) of wounded and sick from 
platoons, evacuating them to the battalion aid station and 
maintaining stable communications with the company commander. As 
a rule, the battalion aid station is deployed near the rear 
boundary of the battalion defense area. 
  After enemy conduct of fire preparation and the beginning of 
the assault, subunit commanders, riflemen-medics, medical party 
NCOIC's and the paramedic clarify the sick and wounded and 
arrange for their first aid, for carrying (transporting) them 
from the battlefield and for evacuation to aid stations. Self- 
administered and buddy-administered emergency first aid is given 
where the wound was received. Then riflemen-medics and medical 
party NCOIC's supplement the first aid, shelter the wounded and 
sick from getting wounded again and evacuate them to the 
battalion and regimental aid station at the first opportunity. 
  At the battalion aid station the wounded and sick are 
examined directly in the motor vehicles where possible and those 
in acute need are given assistance and sent to the regimental 
aid station. 
  The battalion rear proceeds behind the combat subunits in a 
hasty attack when moving up to the line of deployment into 
company columns. It is advisable to align its column in the 
following sequence: aid station, motor vehicles with ammunition 
and fuel, and supply squad motor vehicles. The procedure for 
logistic support of the battalion in the attack is shown in 
Diagram 30. 
  By the beginning of the assault the battalion aid station is 
disposed directly behind battle formations of first echelon 
companies on the axis of the presumed greatest casualties of 
assaulting subunit personnel at a distance ensuring protection 
against small arms fire. The ammunition supply point, ration 
distribution point and refueling point displace behind battalion 
second echelon subunits. 
  Before an attack from a position of direct contact with the 
enemy, vehicles usually are refueled in the assembly area (at 
the assembly position), using the senior chief's assets as a 
rule. During the attack refueling is accomplished if necessary 
directly in battle formations of companies (in places not viewed 
by the enemy), with refueling assets coming up to the vehicles. 
The most favorable conditions for refueling fighting vehicles 
may be when the company (battalion) is in the second echelon or 
reserve. All vehicles must be fully refueled by the end of the 
day (battle). 
  In organizing medical support in the attack, main attention 
is devoted to giving first aid to wounded and sick, collecting 
them, and carrying (transporting) and evacuating them from the 
battlefield, especially at the dismount line and during the 
battle to take enemy strongpoints on the FEBA and in the depth 
of his defense. 
  In the course of an attack the wounded and sick are given 
first aid directly on vehicles in the form of self-administered 
and buddy-administered emergency first aid. If necessary they 
are transferred to battalion (regimental) medical transport or 
evacuated to the nearest deployed aid stations. 
  During operations in dismounted formation, riflemen-medics 
of 
platoons and medical party NCOIC's of companies who are 
advancing behind their subunits observe the battlefield, note 
places where personnel have become casualties, locate the 
wounded, give them first aid and concentrate them in the nearest 
shelter for subsequent evacuation to the battalion and 
regimental aid station. 
  As a rule battalion rear subunits displace during an attack 
as combat subunits advance so the uninterrupted nature of their 
logistic and medical support is not disturbed. 
  With beginning of pursuit of a withdrawing enemy the 
battalion rear comes closer to the subunits and steps are taken 
to clear the battalion aid station of wounded and sick. During a 
pursuit it is advisable to displace the rear at full strength in 
a column immediately behind combat subunits. 
  Logistic support on the march. In preparing for 
the march, special attention is given to establishing additional 
reserves of fuel and to accomplishing measures for improving 
off- road capability of transport. 
  On the march, logistic subunits usually proceed at the rear 
of the battalion main body column. When movement of motor 
transport behind tanks and BMP's will be difficult, the rear can 
proceed as a separate column where possible, in constant 
readiness to move forward rapidly onto the main body's route. 
  When making a march the ammunition of tanks and BMP's 
(BTR's) 
is replenished and they are refueled in areas of short halts and 
the day (night) rest halt area and on arrival in the designated 
area. 
  Organization of refueling of vehicles on the march is 
determined by the length of the march and conditions for making 
it, the number of vehicles in the company (battalion), and 
availability of refueling equipment. At short halts it is 
advisable to perform refueling with the senior chief's assets. 
Regimental and division fuel tanker trucks are included in the 
battalion column for this. Subsequently all vehicles are 
refueled in day (night) rest halt areas and on arrival in the 
designated area using all refueling assets. 
  Refueling on the march may be done by various methods. The 
most characteristic ones are when refueling assets approach 
subunit vehicles or visa versa. A mixed method also may be used, 
where some fighting vehicles are fueled by the first method and 
others by the second. The procedure for refueling a company at a 
short halt is shown in Diagram 28. 
  During a march being made over a great distance, by 
direction 
of the regimental commander, refueling of all or some groups of 
battalion vehicles may be done at field fueling points deployed 
along the movement route by forces and assets of senior chiefs. 
Characteristics of field fueling points and the duration of 
subunit refueling are shown in tables 6 and 7. 


Table 6 - Basic Tactical-Technical Characteristics of Field Fueling Points 

Characteristics            PZP-10            PZP-10A            PZP- 20 

